{ Hello and Welcome to the Lifetime Repertoires: Triangle Slav! } 1. d4 d5
{ This opening course provides a full repertoire for Black against 1.d4, based on the so-called 'Triangle' formation. The chapter you are currently reading is the Introduction, giving you an overview of the course and providing you with the basic information about it.   Your authors:  1. Erwin l'Ami from the Netherlands became a grandmaster in 2005 and a professional chess player shortly thereafter. His most notable tournament victory was the 2015 edition of the Reykjavik Open and he has been a member of the Dutch Olympic team since 2006. Erwin is perhaps best known for his work as a second. A second helps another player come to the game as best prepared as possible. That means opening work and a lot of it!  For about three years Erwin was part of Veselin Topalov’s team, and also helped him during the World Championship match against Vishy Anand. These days, Erwin regularly helps Anish Giri who is arguably the best-prepared player in the world. Without a doubt, the work for this course greatly corresponds with the work he has been doing as a second. This is Erwin's fifth course on Chessable.  2. Christof Sielecki is an International Master from Germany and has been creating courses since the early times of Chessable. He has authored more than a dozen courses and has been involved in several milestone projects.  In 2018, Keep It Simple 1.e4 was Chessable's first course with video instruction. In 2019, Fight like Magnus was the first course to include a Quickstarter Guide, which has become a must ever since. One year later, Christof was involved in the creation of Magnus Touch, the first Chessable course that was presented by the World Champion, Magnus Carlsen. Christof's latest course, Keep it Simple for Black, won the Chessable Awards 2021 for 'Course of the Year' and 'Opening Course of the Year'.  How did the team cooperation start:  Erwin and Christof got in touch exchanging ideas on courses that they had written – both have featured the Caro-Kann prominently, for example. Quickly, the idea of a joint project was born. Let's explain how the course was written as a team.  After selecting the topic @@StartBracket@@more on that later in the intro@@EndBracket@@, we created a chapter structure and discussed all major variation choices for each chapter. After having a repertoire roadmap, so to say, it was time to get into details and analyze. It's impractical to discuss each detail as it pops up, of course. Therefore, each chapter has a 'head author', who would make a detailed analysis and write the first draft of the text. These drafts were the foundation of further checks and adjustments until the final, reconciled version of the course was completed.  All chapters are written in 'we'-form, as both of us have extensively worked on all chapters. The video presentation is assigned to the respective 'head author' of each chapter, though. We considered presenting all chapters together as a duo but decided that a single presenter is the best option for an opening course.  About the Triangle and the scope of the course:  There are various ways to name chess openings or certain variations. You'll meet connections to places, countries, and persons, and sometimes it is descriptive. The 'Dragon' formation in the Sicilian Defense is supposed to 'look like a Dragon', which requires some imagination. However, in the case of the 'Triangle', the situation is a lot more clear-cut.   Let's have a look at the first moves: @@StartFEN@@rnbqkbnr/pppppppp/8/8/8/8/PPPPPPPP/RNBQKBNR w KQkq - 0 1@@EndFEN@@  1.d4  d5  2.c4  e6  3.Nc3  c6  or @@StartFEN@@rnbqkbnr/pppppppp/8/8/8/8/PPPPPPPP/RNBQKBNR w KQkq - 0 1@@EndFEN@@  1.d4  d5  2.c4  e6  3.Nf3  c6  . Black's pawn  formation e6-d5-c6 or even f7-e6-d5-c6-b7 looks like a triangle, no questions asked! Once White has decided to go for the Queen's Gambit with 2.c4, the 'Triangle' is our weapon and comprises the majority of this course.   An important move order issue to talk about: @@StartFEN@@rnbqkbnr/pppppppp/8/8/8/8/PPPPPPPP/RNBQKBNR w KQkq - 0 1@@EndFEN@@  1.d4  d5  2.c4  we play  2...e6  first. It's also possible to start with  2...c6  and continue with  3.--  e6  to set up the Triangle, but there is a crucial difference. After @@StartFEN@@rnbqkbnr/ppp1pppp/8/3p4/2PP4/8/PP2PPPP/RNBQKBNR b KQkq - 0 2@@EndFEN@@  2...c6  , White may play the Exchange Variation  3.cxd5  cxd5  , which leads to a rather stale, symmetrical position. Black gets equal chances, but it's tough to play for a win.  In the 2006 Bundesliga game Sielecki-l'Ami, Christof played the Exchange variation with White and made an easy draw, even though Erwin was about 200 points higher rated. Therefore, we prefer the move order @@StartFEN@@rnbqkbnr/ppp1pppp/8/3p4/2PP4/8/PP2PPPP/RNBQKBNR b KQkq - 0 2@@EndFEN@@  2...e6  , avoiding the somewhat annoying Exchange Variation. After  2...e6  White can still take on d5, but the resulting  positions after  3.cxd5  exd5  are not symmetrical and offer good chances to play for a win. The main branches of the Triangle are:  The Noteboom: @@StartFEN@@rnbqkbnr/pppppppp/8/8/8/8/PPPPPPPP/RNBQKBNR w KQkq - 0 1@@EndFEN@@  1.d4  d5  2.c4  e6  3.Nc3  c6  4.Nf3  dxc4  .  We capture the c-pawn and intend ...b5, trying to hold on to the pawn. Taking and keeping the c-pawn is a key idea of the Triangle. In many lines, White needs to be precise and knowledgeable to gain proper compensation for the pawn. In the main continuation of the Noteboom White regains the pawn, but at the cost of entering a fantastically unbalanced position  after  5.e3  b5  6.a4  Bb4  7.Bd2  a5  8.axb5  Bxc3  9.Bxc3  cxb5  10.b3  Bb7  11.bxc4  b4  12.Bb2  Nf6  . White has an excellent center, but we have two outside passed pawns! This leads to great complications.  Often White is playing for an attack in the center and our king, while we need to weather the storm and promote our pawns. Black's practical chances are excellent here, as proved by the scores. Black has a positive score in the Noteboom, highlighting the difficulties our opponents will face.  The Marshall Gambit: @@StartFEN@@rnbqkbnr/pppppppp/8/8/8/8/PPPPPPPP/RNBQKBNR w KQkq - 0 1@@EndFEN@@  1.d4  d5  2.c4  e6  3.Nc3  c6  4.e4  is White's sharpest attempt against the Triangle. It's called 'Gambit' because in the almost forced main line  4...dxe4  5.Nxe4  Bb4+  6.Bd2  Qxd4  7.Bxb4  Qxe4+  , White sacrifices a central pawn for the bishop pair and a lead in development. Black needs to be careful and know the best defensive setups. We provide you with this information, showing that White has compensation for the pawn, but no advantage.  Stonewalls: @@StartFEN@@rnbqkbnr/pppppppp/8/8/8/8/PPPPPPPP/RNBQKBNR w KQkq - 0 1@@EndFEN@@  1.d4  d5  2.c4  e6  3.Nc3  c6  4.e3  f5  | @@StartFEN@@rnbqkbnr/ppp2ppp/4p3/3p4/2PP4/8/PP2PPPP/RNBQKBNR w KQkq - 0 3@@EndFEN@@  3.Nf3  c6  4.e3  f5  | @@StartFEN@@rnbqkbnr/ppp2ppp/4p3/3p4/2PP4/8/PP2PPPP/RNBQKBNR w KQkq - 0 3@@EndFEN@@  3.Nf3  c6  4.Nbd2  f5  .  If White decides to cover the c-pawn by blocking the bishop with e3 or Nbd2, we recommend setting up a Stonewall formation. The move ...f5 completes the Stonewall, which is an aggressive attempt to grab as much central space as possible.   There are various versions of the Stonewall that have a dubious reputation, but we only employ it under favorable circumstances. We think that Black gets good chances to unbalance the game and often surprise the opponent early on.  Triangle Sidelines: White has a range of sidelines in reserve. We cover all these attempts in detail, showing that Black gets a good game against the harmless ones. White has some more serious tries, like @@StartFEN@@rnbqkbnr/ppp2ppp/4p3/3p4/2PP4/8/PP2PPPP/RNBQKBNR w KQkq - 0 3@@EndFEN@@  3.Nf3  c6  4.g3  or  4.Qc2  . These require some knowledge on our part, so make sure to not neglect these lines. This is particularly relevant if you play higher-rated opposition. Stronger players often like to avoid the Marshall or Noteboom and look for new ideas in these areas.  White avoids the Queen's Gambit: White may also opt to avoid the most critical option @@StartFEN@@rnbqkbnr/ppp1pppp/8/3p4/3P4/8/PPP1PPPP/RNBQKBNR w KQkq - 0 2@@EndFEN@@  2.c4  and choose a sideline instead. We also include suggestions against all the sidelines that White may play on move two, which makes this course a comprehensive repertoire for Black against 1.d4. The most important options for White are the flexible  2.Nf3  and  2.Bf4  , the London System. Against both moves, we suggest the interesting reply  2...Bf5  , which leads to less explored positions.  Black is playing ambitiously and tries to prove that White's second move was slow, compared to the Queen's Gambit. After @@StartFEN@@rnbqkbnr/pppppppp/8/8/8/8/PPPPPPPP/RNBQKBNR w KQkq - 0 1@@EndFEN@@  1.d4  d5  2.c4  , Black is under immediate  pressure on d5, which makes it impossible to develop our bishop to f5 early on.  Besides  2.Nf3  and  2.Bf4  , White has more offbeat lines. They don't pose serious problems for Black but contain some tricks that you should know. The chapter on these sidelines provides you with enough information to face them with confidence.  How to start?  Go for the Quickstarters! Our course consists of 20 chapters and 3 Quickstarter Guides. The Quickstarters give you an introduction and overview of the most important and common lines of the repertoire. After studying the Quickstarters, you are able to employ the repertoire in your games.  We split the coverage into three Quickstarters. One about the Noteboom and Marshall Gambit, one about other Triangle lines and the Stonewall, and one about non-Queen's Gambit lines. Once you have mastered the Quickstarters, you can start learning single chapters. This gives you some flexibility. You may focus on chapters that interest you the most or study in-depth the lines that you experienced problems in your games.  Thanks a lot for reading the Intro − let's get started with the repertoire now! }
