[White "Quickstarter Guide − Noteboom & Marshall"]
[Black "Noteboom Variation 8.axb5 − 11.d5 #1"]
[Result "*"]

1. d4 d5 2. c4 e6 3. Nf3 c6 4. Nc3 dxc4
{ The Noteboom Variation, named after Dutchman Daniel Noteboom. Noteboom died of pneumonia at just 21 years of age, but he lives on in chess history as his name is forever attached to this variation. He gained international fame at the Hamburg Olympiad of 1930, where he scored 11.5/15, defeating some leading players in the process. It is in this period that he started to experiment with the variation we are discussing in this course.  We capture the pawn on c4 and intend to hold on to it with all our might, with moves like ...b7-b5 and ...Bf8-b4. In the main variations, this will eventually lead to positions that are very unbalanced and of great complexity. If that isn't good enough news already; from a theoretical perspective, Black is in fine shape as well, meaning we have no reason to shy away from playing this line. }
5. a4
{ A standard move, making it harder for Black to hold on to the c4-pawn by preempting the move ...b7-b5. }
5... Bb4
{ Pinning the knight in order to get the move ...b7-b5 back on the cards. Here we see a major difference with the Slav @@StartFEN@@rnbqkbnr/pppppppp/8/8/8/8/PPPPPPPP/RNBQKBNR w KQkq - 0 1@@EndFEN@@  1.d4  d5  2.c4  c6  3.Nf3  Nf6  4.Nc3  dxc4  5.a4  where Black also takes on c4 but is unable to hold on to that pawn for very long.  Having played ...e7-e6 instead of ...Ng8-f6 allows us to pin the knight on c3 with 5...Bb4 and follow it up with ...b7-b5, thus making it much harder for White to regain the pawn. }
6. e3
{ 6.e4  may look more logical, taking full control of the center, but it also leaves that same center more vulnerable to attack. That shows in the line  6...b5  7.Bd2  a5  8.axb5  Bxc3  9.Bxc3?!  cxb5  10.b3  Nf6!  and Black already has an advantage because  the attack on e4 is hard to counter.  In this line, the e-pawn is much better placed on e3 instead of e4. That's why, as we have seen, 6.e4 is usually played with the idea of playing a gambit where White is not thinking about regaining the sacrificed pawn. }
6... b5 7. Bd2
{ Not only developing the bishop but once again pressuring the pawn on b5. }
7... a5
{ It is important to get the move orders right. For all the subtle nuances, please see the Informational dedicated to this topic. }
8. axb5 Bxc3 9. Bxc3 cxb5 10. b3
{ Winning back the pawn, and slowly taking us to the main position of the Noteboom Variation. }
10... Bb7 11. d5
{ This move had a short burst of popularity when Boris Gelfand used it twice in 1996. White takes the opportunity to open the long diagonal for the bishop on c3. Nowadays, reliable methods have been found to deal with this direct approach. The next few moves are forced. }
11... Nf6 12. bxc4 b4 13. Bxf6
{ Giving up the mighty bishop is a big concession, but White has no time to preserve it as the d5-pawn is under attack. }
13... Qxf6 14. Qa4+
{ The point of White's play. Our king will have to stay in the center for a while. }
14... Nd7 15. Nd4 Ke7
{ Introduced by Dutchman Nicolaas Cortlever in 1950. We immediately get out of the pin and prepare ...Rhc8. White has to play fast given the huge strategic danger there is in the position.   Both Gelfand games continued with  15...e5  16.Nb3  Ke7  and after  17.Be2  Rhc8  , Black had established a blockade on the  important c5-square and has an approximately equal game in Gelfand-Piket, Amsterdam 1996.   For some time it was thought that  15...Qe7!?  was some sort of refutation of White's setup. Black prepares to castle while  16.Qb5  Rb8  17.Qxa5  O-O  gives Black tremendous compensation. Better is @@StartFEN@@r3k2r/1b1nqppp/4p3/p2P4/QpPN4/4P3/5PPP/R3KB1R w KQkq - 4 16@@EndFEN@@  16.c5!  Qxc5  17.Bb5  Qxd5  18.f3  when White sacrifices two pawns  to activate the bishop and keep Black's king in the center. }
16. d6+ { The critical response. Our king is lured out into the open! } 16...
Kxd6 17. Rd1 Nc5
{ A very important move, with a very elegant point! Instead,  17...Rhd8  18.c5+!  Nxc5  19.Qb5  Rdc8  20.Nf5+  Ke5  21.Nd6  Qe7  22.Qc4  saw White winning in style in Spanjaard-Cortlever, Amsterdam 1950. }
18. Qb5
{ The big question to answer. How do we respond to the numerous threats? }
18... Rhc8
{ Fearless play! It turns out the discovered checks don't bring White anything. }
19. Nf5+ Ke5 { It is not often that we centralize our king in the middlegame! }
20. Nd6 Qe7 21. Nxc8 Bxc8
{ Time to take stock. Black's king is untouchable on e5, not because it's the best square on the board for the king, but mostly because of the inactivity of White's forces. The queen is stuck on b5 and the other pieces are mostly dormant. Next up for Black is to send the queenside pawns forward. Supported by the rook on a8 and the knight on c5, they will prove an unstoppable force. }
*

