{ Pinning the knight in order to get the move ...b7-b5 back on the cards. Here we see a major difference with the Slav @@StartFEN@@rnbqkbnr/pppppppp/8/8/8/8/PPPPPPPP/RNBQKBNR w KQkq - 0 1@@EndFEN@@  1.d4  d5  2.c4  c6  3.Nf3  Nf6  4.Nc3  dxc4  5.a4  where Black also takes on c4 but is unable to hold on to that pawn for very long.  Having played ...e7-e6 instead of ...Ng8-f6 allows us to pin the knight on c3 with 5...Bb4 and follow it up with ...b7-b5, thus making it much harder for White to regain the pawn. }
6. e3
{ 6.e4  may look more logical, taking full control of the center, but it also leaves that same center more vulnerable to attack. That shows in the line  6...b5  7.Bd2  a5  8.axb5  Bxc3  9.Bxc3?!  cxb5  10.b3  Nf6!  and Black already has an advantage because  the attack on e4 is hard to counter.  In this line, the e-pawn is much better placed on e3 instead of e4. That's why, as we have seen, 6.e4 is usually played with the idea of playing a gambit where White is not thinking about regaining the sacrificed pawn. }
6... b5 7. Bd2
{ Not only developing the bishop but once again pressuring the pawn on b5. }
7... a5
{ It is important to get the move orders right. For all the subtle nuances, please see the Informational dedicated to this topic. }
8. axb5 Bxc3 9. Bxc3 cxb5 10. b3
{ Winning back the pawn and slowly taking us to the main position of the Noteboom Variation. }
10... Bb7 11. bxc4
{ White can also start with  11.Bb2  transposing after  11...Nf6  12.bxc4  b4  . }
11... b4
{ Here we get to see the point behind Black's 7th move. While White has won back the sacrificed pawn, Black has managed to get connected passed pawns on the queenside. }
12. Bb2
{ The correct square for the bishop. Right now it is hiding behind the d4-pawn, but it only takes the d-pawn one move to turn that b2-bishop into a monster on the long diagonal. }
12... Nf6 13. c5
{ Despite Erwin having played this move against Polish Grandmaster Krasenkov, we don't quite like the look of it. There is some point to it though. Generally speaking, White always plays Bf1-d3 in order to control the e4-square and perhaps aim for an e3-e4 push in the future.  The text move takes a fundamentally different course, giving up on the light squares in the center in order to blockade the queenside pawns by playing Bf1-b5 next. In combination with a future Qd1-c2, Nf3-e5 and the advance of the c-pawn, this plan could be dangerous for Black. }
13... O-O 14. Bb5 Qd5
{ 14...Nc6  15.O-O  Qd5  transposes to 14...Qd5.   A decent alternative is  14...Bc6  15.Ba4  Bxa4  16.Qxa4  which is also how that game with Krasenkow continued. Here  16...Qc8!?  with the idea to meet  17.O-O  with  17...Nc6  18.Nd2  Nd5  19.Nc4  f5  is a good improvement over that game.  White can aim for a break in the center with f2-f3 followed by e3-e4 but the resulting positions are very double-edged. }
15. O-O Nc6
{ The knight is destined to move to e7 next, from where it has the flexibility to either jump to d5 or g6. }
16. Qc2 Ne7
{ Black has managed to get the perfect setup. We are following a 2017 correspondence game and will continue to do so for a few more moves. }
17. Bc4 Qc6 { 17...Qh5!?  is not out of the question either. } 18. Bb3 Rfd8 19.
Rfc1 { In case of  19.Rfd1  the waiting move  19...h6  looks fine. } 19... Qe4
20. Qe2
{ 20.Qxe4  Nxe4  is not worrisome for Black.  All the pieces have great squares on the h1-a8 diagonal. }
20... Bc6
{ One of the reasons we move the queen to e4 is to place our bishop on c6. We are now set to push the queenside passers. }
21. Bc2 Qg4 22. h3 Qh5
{ The queen is fine on the kingside, where it can sometimes participate in an attack against the king on g1. }
23. e4 a4
{ Time to cut the line short. In Nekhaev-Lebedev, ICCF 2017 the players drew on move 39, but it's obvious that there is a very sharp position on the board. As usual, we find our game easier − we have plans including ...Ne7-g6, ...Rd8-b8 and, as always, pushing the pawns. }
*

[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "Quickstarter Guide − Noteboom & Marshall"]
[Black "Noteboom Variation 11.bxc4 b4 12.Bb2 − Main Line #2"]
[Result "*"]

1. d4 d5 2. c4 e6 3. Nf3 c6 4. Nc3 dxc4
{ The Noteboom Variation, named after Dutchman Daniel Noteboom. Noteboom died of pneumonia at just 21 years of age, but he lives on in chess history as his name is forever attached to this variation. He gained international fame at the Hamburg Olympiad of 1930, where he scored 11.5/15, defeating some leading players in the process. It is in this period that he started to experiment with the variation we are discussing in this course.  We capture the pawn on c4 and intend to hold on to it with all our might, with moves like ...b7-b5 and ...Bf8-b4. In the main variations, this will eventually lead to positions that are very unbalanced and of great complexity. If that isn't good enough news already; from a theoretical perspective, Black is in fine shape as well, meaning we have no reason to shy away from playing this line. }
5. a4
{ A standard move, making it harder for Black to hold on to the c4-pawn by preempting the move ...b7-b5. }
5... Bb4
{ Pinning the knight in order to get the move ...b7-b5 back on the cards. Here we see a major difference with the Slav @@StartFEN@@rnbqkbnr/pppppppp/8/8/8/8/PPPPPPPP/RNBQKBNR w KQkq - 0 1@@EndFEN@@  1.d4  d5  2.c4  c6  3.Nf3  Nf6  4.Nc3  dxc4  5.a4  where Black also takes on c4 but is unable to hold on to that pawn for very long.  Having played ...e7-e6 instead of ...Ng8-f6 allows us to pin the knight on c3 with 5...Bb4 and follow it up with ...b7-b5, thus making it much harder for White to regain the pawn. }
6. e3
{ 6.e4  may look more logical, taking full control of the center, but it also leaves that same center more vulnerable to attack. That shows in the line  6...b5  7.Bd2  a5  8.axb5  Bxc3  9.Bxc3?!  cxb5  10.b3  Nf6!  and Black already has an advantage because  the attack on e4 is hard to counter.  In this line, the e-pawn is much better placed on e3 instead of e4. That's why, as we have seen, 6.e4 is usually played with the idea of playing a gambit where White is not thinking about regaining the sacrificed pawn. }
6... b5 7. Bd2
{ Not only developing the bishop but once again pressuring the pawn on b5. }
7... a5
{ It is important to get the move orders right. For all the subtle nuances, please see the Informational dedicated to this topic. }
8. axb5 Bxc3 9. Bxc3 cxb5 10. b3
{ Winning back the pawn and slowly taking us to the main position of the Noteboom Variation. }
10... Bb7 11. bxc4
{ White can also start with  11.Bb2  transposing after  11...Nf6  12.bxc4  b4  . }
11... b4
{ Here we get to see the point behind Black's 7th move. While White has won back the sacrificed pawn, Black has managed to get connected passed pawns on the queenside. }
12. Bb2
{ The correct square for the bishop. Right now it is hiding behind the d4-pawn, but it only takes the d-pawn one move to turn that b2-bishop into a monster on the long diagonal. }
12... Nf6 13. Bd3
{ Developing the bishop and preparing to castle. The bishop is best placed on d3 where it has an influence on the important e4-square. It is this unbalanced position that has mesmerized generations for decades. }
13... O-O
{ 13...Be4  is a move we will see a lot more of, but here it comes too early. White replies  14.Bxe4  Nxe4  15.Qa4+!  Qd7  16.Qc2  with the double threat of  taking the knight on e4 and Nf3-e5. Following  16...Qb7  17.O-O  O-O  18.Ra4!  White  prepares Rfa1 with huge pressure on the queenside. }
14. Qc2
{ This move is rare in this exact position, and is usually played after 14.O-O. We, however, meet  14.O-O  with  14...Be4  , and the text move prevents that idea and forces us back into one of the traditional main lines. }
14... Nbd7 15. O-O
{ Now we are back in the main line, but there is an upside to that. White has already committed to the move Qc2, which is not considered the biggest test of the Noteboom Variation.  One can still find hundreds of games in the database with this move, and the sharp nature of the position alone should already be enough reason to take it very seriously. White intends to play e3-e4 and essentially blow Black away in the center. }
15... Qc7
{ In this day and age there is no more room for dogmatic thinking. The engine has shown us that we need to be flexible in our thinking and we are reminded of that in the line  15...Bxf3  16.gxf3  Qc7  . While we will not be advocating this line as our main recommendation, we do feel it's entirely playable.   To take on f3 would likely have been dismissed some time ago, but we have learned that when engines claim something is playable, we better have a look! Black's play is very simple, the next moves will be ...Rf8-b8 and ...Nd7-f8-g6 more or less regardless of what White is up to. Of course, White's bishops and center look promising, but White's slightly weakened king and Black's queenside passers should compensate for that. Definitely worth having a look at it! }
16. e4
{ The most principled follow-up, creating the immediate threat of e4-e5. }
16... e5
{ A typical counterthrust. We immediately try to get hold of the c5-square. }
17. c5 Rfc8
{ A fresh idea, put in practice by Russian Grandmaster Boris Savchenko. It should be said that there is nothing wrong with  17...exd4  either. }
18. Rfe1 exd4 19. e5 Qxc5
{ The tactical justification behind Black's last few moves. Instead of removing the knight from f6, Black creates a counterthreat. }
20. Qd2
{ The best try, avoiding the queen exchange and thereby keeping attacking options alive. }
20... Bxf3
{ Safest as both  20...Ne8  21.Nxd4  Nxe5  22.Nf5  and @@StartFEN@@r1r3k1/1b1n1ppp/5n2/p1q1P3/1p1p4/3B1N2/1B1Q1PPP/R3R1K1 b - - 1 20@@EndFEN@@  20...Nd5  21.Bxd4  are messier. }
21. Bxd4 { Using the fact there is a discovered check in the position. } 21...
Qxd4 { Falling for the trap.  21...Qd5  22.gxf3  g6!  isn't bad either. } 22.
Bxh7+ Nxh7 23. Qxd4 Bc6
{ With three pieces for the queen and two connected passed pawns, Black is in good shape. }
