[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "Quickstarter Guide − Noteboom & Marshall"]
[Black "Avoiding the Marshall Gambit 3.Nc3 c6 4.e4 − 6.Nc3"]
[Result "*"]

1. d4 d5 2. c4 e6 3. Nc3 c6 4. e4
{ Without a doubt, the most principled way of tackling our Triangle. It's good to set the stage at this point. What kind of game can we expect from here on out? We should play  4...dxe4  as it's the only way to question White's center. After  5.Nxe4  Bb4+  we then get a split.  A@@EndBracket@@  6.Nc3  is a quiet, positional, line where White aims for a small plus but we have little to worry about.  B@@EndBracket@@  6.Bd2  is the real deal. The move invites us to the complications that arise after  6...Qxd4  7.Bxb4  Qxe4+  which we will happily accept. }
4... dxe4
{ Players trying to avoid the theoretical discussion that arises after  4...dxe4  have tried to sidestep it with  4...Bb4  . It is not a great choice though, on top of the fact that it gives White additional options, after  5.Bd2  I don't think Black has anything better but to transpose back to main lines with  5...dxe4  6.Nxe4  Qxd4  . Instead @@StartFEN@@rnbqk1nr/pp3ppp/2p1p3/3p4/1bPPP3/2N5/PP1B1PPP/R2QKBNR b KQkq - 2 5@@EndFEN@@  5...dxc4  6.Bxc4  Qxd4  is a very dangerous pawn grab, as  7.Qe2  Nf6  8.Nf3  gives White a large lead in development. }
5. Nxe4 Bb4+
{ Without this check as a follow-up, White would simply be doing great, having destroyed our proud triangle structure.   In the 2018 Candidates tournament, Vladimir Kramnik shocked the chess world with the fresh  5...c5!?  which was clearly meant to be a surprise weapon. Objectively speaking, after  6.Nxc5  Nc6  7.Be3!   Caruana-Kramnik, Candidates Berlin 2018, continued  7.Nf3  Nxd4  8.Qxd4  Qxd4  9.Nxd4  Bxc5  10.Nb5  Ke7  and now  11.Nc7!  Rb8  12.Bf4  Bb4+  13.Ke2  Bd6  14.Bxd6+  Kxd6  15.Nb5+  would have given Fabiano an edge.  7...e5  8.dxe5  Qa5+  9.Qd2  Nb4  White seems to be in trouble, but there is in fact  10.Ne4!  as  10...Nc2+  11.Ke2  Qxd2+  12.Kxd2  Nxa1  13.Bd3  has the knight trapped on a1 and White already has two pawns for the exchange. That means it is actually Black who is in trouble here. }
6. Nc3
{ The positional approach, instead of the sharp pawn sacrifice  6.Bd2  . Magnus Carlsen used the text move in his World Championship match against Vishy Anand in 2013. It is often used by players who have been caught off-guard by their opponents and want to avoid the abundance of theory that arises after 6.Bd2. }
6... e5
{ Despite being a pawn sacrifice, this is in fact the most solid reply. } 7.
Be3
{ There was a time when I @@StartBracket@@Erwin@@EndBracket@@ thought this gave White something to play for. Modern engines made me rethink that earlier assessment. }
7... exd4 8. Qxd4 Qxd4 9. Bxd4 Nf6 10. Ne2
{ White is ever so slightly better, but it's not nearly enough to claim an advantage. }
10... Na6
{ 10...Be6!?  is untested, but looks very reasonable. The idea is that  11.a3  Be7  12.Nf4  Nbd7  , simply allowing  13.Nxe6  , is not bad at all. After the further  13...fxe6  14.O-O-O  Bc5  the exchange of bishops leads to an equal endgame. The isolated  pawn on e6 barely plays any role as e7 will be a nice spot for the king. }
11. O-O-O Nc5 { The endgame is equal. } 12. Bxf6
{ Instead, the immediate  12.a3  allows  12...Nb3+  and the bishop  on d4 will get exchanged. }
12... gxf6 13. a3 a5
{ 13...Bxc3  14.Nxc3  Be6  is possible too, but less pretty! } 14. axb4 axb4
15. Nb1 Bf5 16. Nd4 O-O-O
{ Threatening to take on d4 followed by a knight fork on b3. } 17. Nxf5
{ Allowing perpetual check. } 17... Nb3+ 18. Kc2 Na1+ { A curious line! } *

[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "Quickstarter Guide − Noteboom & Marshall"]
[Black "Marshall Gambit 6.Bd2 − 8.Ne2"]
[Result "*"]

1. d4 d5 2. c4 e6 3. Nc3 c6 4. e4
{ Without a doubt, the most principled way of tackling our Triangle. It's good to set the stage at this point. What kind of game can we expect from here on out? We should play  4...dxe4  as it's the only way to question White's center. After  5.Nxe4  Bb4+  we then get a split.  A@@EndBracket@@  6.Nc3  is a quiet, positional, line where White aims for a small plus but we have little to worry about.  B@@EndBracket@@  6.Bd2  is the real deal. The move invites us to the complications that arise after  6...Qxd4  7.Bxb4  Qxe4+  which we will happily accept. }
4... dxe4
{ Players trying to avoid the theoretical discussion that arises after  4...dxe4  have tried to sidestep it with  4...Bb4  . It is not a great choice though, on top of the fact that it gives White additional options, after  5.Bd2  I don't think Black has anything better but to transpose back to main lines with  5...dxe4  6.Nxe4  Qxd4  . Instead @@StartFEN@@rnbqk1nr/pp3ppp/2p1p3/3p4/1bPPP3/2N5/PP1B1PPP/R2QKBNR b KQkq - 2 5@@EndFEN@@  5...dxc4  6.Bxc4  Qxd4  is a very dangerous pawn grab, as  7.Qe2  Nf6  8.Nf3  gives White a large lead in development. }
5. Nxe4 Bb4+
{ Without this check as a follow-up, White would simply be doing great, having destroyed our proud triangle structure.   In the 2018 Candidates tournament, Vladimir Kramnik shocked the chess world with the fresh  5...c5!?  which was clearly meant to be a surprise weapon. Objectively speaking, after  6.Nxc5  Nc6  7.Be3!   Caruana-Kramnik, Candidates Berlin 2018, continued  7.Nf3  Nxd4  8.Qxd4  Qxd4  9.Nxd4  Bxc5  10.Nb5  Ke7  and now  11.Nc7!  Rb8  12.Bf4  Bb4+  13.Ke2  Bd6  14.Bxd6+  Kxd6  15.Nb5+  would have given Fabiano an edge.  7...e5  8.dxe5  Qa5+  9.Qd2  Nb4  White seems to be in trouble, but there is in fact  10.Ne4!  as  10...Nc2+  11.Ke2  Qxd2+  12.Kxd2  Nxa1  13.Bd3  has the knight trapped on a1 and White already has two pawns for the exchange. That means it is actually Black who is in trouble here. }
6. Bd2
{ Obviously, the sharpest response. White is sacrificing a pawn following  6...Qxd4  7.Bxb4  Qxe4+  and as a result Black somewhat falls back in development and will be missing the dark-squared bishop.  That is especially felt when we see the mighty bishop on b4, which makes it hard for the king on e8 to find refuge.  We are a pawn up though, and while play is less straightforward compared to the Noteboom, and concrete knowledge of variations is of the essence, the Marshall Gambit stands firm from a theoretical standpoint: Black is OK in all the lines. We need to fight the bishop on b4 @@StartBracket@@usually starting with ...Nb8-a6@@EndBracket@@ and should focus on finding a safe spot for the king. If we manage those two objectives, we are usually surviving − and, with that extra pawn in the pocket, maybe even more than that! }
6... Qxd4
{ Black has to take the bait. Worse is  6...Bxd2+  7.Qxd2  Nf6  8.Nxf6+  Qxf6  9.Nf3  with a clear and easy advantage for White. }
7. Bxb4 Qxe4+
{ The starting position of the Marshall Gambit. White has given a pawn but obviously, the strong bishop on b4 gives certain compensation as outlined on move 6. }
8. Ne2
{ This gets played approximately one out of five times and is considered less critical than  8.Be2  . }
8... Na6
{ Yes, a knight on the rim is dim, but here it does attack the bishop on b4, gaining a big tempo that can be used for further development. }
9. Bf8
{ Very flashy! The bishop can't be captured because of mate in 1, and White simply intends to take on g7 next. }
9... Ne7
{ An equally cunning reply! It takes White a lot of time to grab the pawn on g7 and that gives Black enough time to launch counterplay. }
10. Bxg7 Nb4
{ This move is responsible for making White's 8th move go out of fashion.  10...Rg8  11.Bc3  gives White a solid edge because of the bishop pair. Note that  11...Qxc4  12.Ng3  Qd5  13.Qc2  is already terrible for Black with h7 hanging and Ra1-d1 coming. }
11. Bxh8 e5
{ Without this move, none of the previous ones would have made sense. Black frees the c8-h3 diagonal for the bishop and cuts the bishop on h8 out of the game. }
12. Qd6 { With the idea of creating mating threats with Bh8-f6. } 12... Nc2+
13. Kd2 Bf5
{ Development first! Suddenly ...Ra8-d8 is a major threat. The materialistic  13...Nxa1  14.Qxe5  Qc2+  15.Ke3!  Be6  16.f3  Ng6  17.Qc3  gives White a tangible edge. }
14. Ng3 { Only move! } 14... Qf4+ 15. Kc3 Nd5+
{ Simplest. Black forces a draw by perpetual check. In order to set that up, the queen needs access to d4, which is why the text move is played.   A winning attempt is  15...Nxa1  but it's hard to believe Black can realistically play for a win after  16.Qd2  Qxd2+  17.Kxd2  O-O-O+  18.Kc3  Rxh8  19.Nxf5  Nxf5  20.Bd3  when White wins back the knight and has nothing to fear at all. }
16. cxd5 Qd4+ 17. Kb3 Nxa1+ 18. Ka3 Nc2+
{ A dozen of games have ended this way and it is currently where the variation stands. Neither side can avoid repetition. }
*

