[White "Quickstarter Guide − Stonewall & Triangle Sidelines"]
[Black "Stonewall 3.Nc3 c6 4.e3 f5 #2"]
[Result "*"]

1. d4 d5 2. c4 e6 3. Nc3 c6 4. e3
{ We thought long and hard about what to suggest against this modest pawn push. Of course  4...Nf6  is possible, but transposing to the so-called Slow-Slav, did not seem very appealing. After all, in our LTR we aim for fighting positions, while the winning chances in the Slow-Slav are slim, and the positions, though strategically not uninteresting, are rather dry. We have therefore decided to meet all the e3-setups @@StartBracket@@including the @@StartFEN@@rnbqkbnr/ppp2ppp/4p3/3p4/2PP4/8/PP2PPPP/RNBQKBNR w KQkq - 0 3@@EndFEN@@  3.Nf3  c6  4.e3  move order@@EndBracket@@ with the Stonewall. }
4... f5
{ Without a doubt, the most ambitious way of playing. As always, when a rigorous decision is made on the chessboard, there are clear up and downsides. Let's start with the obvious downside: placing the pawn on f5 means we leave ourselves with a giant hole on e5, and we weaken the dark squares as a whole. If White also manages to exchange the dark-squared bishops, which is a common strategic idea against the Stonewall we will regret having pushed the pawn to f5 in the first place.  Another small issue is the bishop on c8, which is often the problem child in the Stonewall, hidden behind all the pawns on the light squares.  Luckily, there are upsides as well. By playing ...f7-f5 we strengthen our presence in the center by controlling the e4-square a second time and set up an impressive wall of pawns behind which we can swiftly develop our pieces. As Simen Agdestein, a big exponent of the Stonewall, mentioned in his foreword to the book Win with the Stonewall Dutch, people often think that setting up a 'stone wall' means trying to stay solid and defensive, while the modern interpretation is very different.  As in many, if not all, other openings, the engines have shown that Black can play in many different ways, some of which the inventors of this opening never could have imagined! We will try to bring you up to date on all those modern ideas. }
5. f4
{ A rather annoying move to face. We are simply being copied, and on top of that, the pawn being on c4 means White is on the somewhat better side of the symmetry. On the upside, play can still get very interesting, as we found a curious method to unbalance the position. }
5... Nf6
{ 5...Qh4+!?  6.g3  Qd8  was played by Grischuk in 2001 and certainly has its merits. It could be used as a surprise weapon. }
6. Nf3 Bb4
{ A positionally well-founded move that was played three times by Gdanski in the '90s. Black intends to play ...b6, bring the bishop to a6, and, in due time, exchange on c3, thereby gaining full control of the light squares. }
7. Bd2
{ Almost universally played. Of the 14 games in the database, 12 times the bishop was moved to d2. }
7... O-O 8. Bd3 b6 9. O-O a5
{ Gdanski played  9...Ba6  twice, but we don't like the sequence  10.Nxd5!  Nxd5  11.cxd5  Bxd2  12.Qxd2  Bxd3  13.Qxd3  when Black fails to equalize, whichever  way we recapture on d5. By playing 9...a5 we protect the bishop on b4, preventing any Nxd5 trickery, and once again prepare ...Bc8-a6. }
10. Ne5 Ba6 11. b3
{ White's best bet, keeping light-squared bishops on the board. } 11... Qc7
{ We overrule the engines here that prefer  11...c5  . While that is certainly a fine move,  11...Qc7  keeps more tension in the position  and prepares ...Nb8-d7. }
12. Rc1 Nbd7
{ We could also have stepped out of the c-file first with  12...Qb7  but it's not strictly necessary. }
13. Be1 Ne4
{ At first sight, this seems to lead to trouble on the c-file, but no need to worry! }
14. cxd5 Bxd3 15. Qxd3 Bxc3 16. Nxd7 Qxd7 17. dxc6
{ This intermediate move nets White a pawn, but in the resulting position, our knight is clearly superior to the bishop. }
17... Qxc6 18. Bxc3 Qd5 { Black is in great shape. } *

[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "Quickstarter Guide − Stonewall & Triangle Sidelines"]
[Black "Stonewall 3.Nf3 c6 4.Nbd2 f5"]
[Result "*"]

1. d4 d5 2. c4 e6 3. Nf3 c6 4. Nbd2
{ Players advocating this move as White, aim for a solid game, without much risk, which makes recommending a Stonewall setup all the more pleasing. }
4... f5
{ As always, when a rigorous decision is made on the chessboard, there are clear up and downsides. Let's start with the obvious downside: placing the pawn on f5 means we leave ourselves with a giant hole on e5, and we weaken the dark squares as a whole. If White also manages to exchange the dark-squared bishops, which is a common strategic idea against the Stonewall, we will regret having pushed the pawn to f5 in the first place.   Another small issue is the bishop on c8, which is often the problem child in the Stonewall, hidden behind all the pawns on the light squares.  Luckily, there are upsides as well. By playing ...f7-f5 we strengthen our presence in the center by controlling the e4-square a second time and set up an impressive wall of pawns behind which we can swiftly develop our pieces. As Simen Agdestein, a big exponent of the Stonewall, mentioned in his foreword to the book Win with the Stonewall Dutch, people often think that setting up a 'stone wall' means trying to stay solid and defensive, while the modern interpretation is very different.  As in many, if not all, other openings, the engines have shown that Black can play in many different ways, some of which the inventors of this opening never could have imagined!   Compared to @@StartFEN@@rnbqkbnr/ppp2ppp/4p3/3p4/2PP4/8/PP2PPPP/RNBQKBNR w KQkq - 0 3@@EndFEN@@  3.Nc3  c6  4.e3  and @@StartFEN@@rnbqkbnr/ppp2ppp/4p3/3p4/2PP4/8/PP2PPPP/RNBQKBNR w KQkq - 0 3@@EndFEN@@  3.Nf3  c6  4.e3  , we believe this is the best possible version of the Stonewall. Why is that?   First of all, White has already committed the f3-knight, which is often developed to h3 in the Stonewall, so as to reach key squares f4 and d3 easier. Secondly, placing the knight on d2 makes it much harder for White to execute the typical plan of exchanging Black's dark-squared bishops on the a3-square @@StartBracket@@after preparatory moves such as b2-b3 and a2-a4 or Bc1-b2, Qd1-c1 etc.@@EndBracket@@. Last but not least, committing both knights at such an early stage makes White's position rather inflexible.   @@StartFEN@@rnbqkbnr/pp3ppp/2p1p3/3p4/2PP4/5N2/PP1NPPPP/R1BQKB1R b KQkq - 1 4@@EndFEN@@  4...Nf6  is very sound here as well, but we are advocating an LTR that is aimed at fighting chess, and for that purpose, pushing the f-pawn is more suitable. }
5. g3 Nd7 6. Bg2 Nh6
{ We follow in the footsteps of Richard Rapport, who won a brilliant game using this setup. There are just a handful of practical examples here so the position is very fresh.   More orthodox is  6...Ngf6  7.O-O  @@StartBracket@@  7.Ng5  Qe7  followed by ...h6 and ...g5 is  also reasonable.@@EndBracket@@ @@StartFEN@@r1bqkb1r/pp1n2pp/2p1pn2/3p1p2/2PP4/5NP1/PP1NPPBP/R1BQ1RK1 b kq - 4 7@@EndFEN@@  7...Bd6  8.b3  O-O  9.Bb2  b6  followed by ...Bb7, which leads to a position that has a fine reputation. }
7. O-O Nf7 8. Qc2
{ Roubaud-Pirs, ICCF 2012 was a high-level Correspondence game which continued with  8...Qf6  9.b3  g5  , but we feel there is no need to prepare Black's 9th move. }
8... g5 9. cxd5 cxd5
{ With the queen on f6, we would have been able to recapture with the e-pawn, but we know from other lines that the exchange cxd5/...cxd5 is rarely promising for White with a knight on d2 instead of c3. }
10. Nb3 h5
{ Forward! It's surprisingly difficult for White to react to our kingside aggression. }
*

[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "Quickstarter Guide − Stonewall & Triangle Sidelines"]
[Black "Stonewall 3.Nf3 c6 4.e3 f5 #1"]
[Result "*"]

1. d4 d5 2. c4 e6 3. Nf3 c6 4. e3
{ Inviting us to play a Meran type of game with  4...Nf6  , but as you probably know by now, that is not how we are going to roll in this course!  Against all the e3 setups we employ the Stonewall. }
4... f5
{ And there we go! As always, when a rigorous decision is made on the chessboard, there are clear up and downsides. Let's start with the obvious downside: placing the pawn on f5 means we leave ourselves with a giant hole on e5, and we weaken the dark squares as a whole. If White also manages to exchange the dark-squared bishops, which is a common strategic idea against the Stonewall, we will regret having pushed the pawn to f5 in the first place.   Another small issue is the bishop on c8, which is often the problem child in the Stonewall, hidden behind all the pawns on the light squares.  Luckily, there are upsides as well. By playing ...f7-f5 we strengthen our presence in the center by controlling the e4-square a second time and set up an impressive wall of pawns behind which we can swiftly develop our pieces. As Simen Agdestein, a big exponent of the Stonewall, mentioned very nicely in his foreword to the book Win with the Stonewall Dutch, people often think that setting up a 'stone wall' means trying to stay solid and defensive, while the modern interpretation is very different.  As in many other openings, the engines have shown that Black can play this opening in many different ways, some of which the inventors of this opening never could have imagined! We will try to bring you up to date on all those ideas. }
5. Be2
{ Not the most popular move in the position but a very solid one indeed. It is here that Black has most difficulties getting a fighting game. }
5... Nf6
{ With the bishop on d3, we are happy to play @@StartFEN@@rnbqkbnr/pp4pp/2p1p3/3p1p2/2PP4/3BPN2/PP3PPP/RNBQK2R b KQkq - 0 5@@EndFEN@@  5...Nd7  6.O-O  Nh6  here, but with the bishop on e2, @@StartFEN@@r1bqkb1r/pp1n2pp/2p1p2n/3p1p2/2PP4/4PN2/PP2BPPP/RNBQ1RK1 w kq - 0 7@@EndFEN@@  7.b3  g5  8.e4!  is a giant difference. Though it should be mentioned that even without this direct refutation, the standard  8.Ba3  would also have led to an  improved version of the 5.Bd3 line since the bishop is better placed on e2 in this case: it is not in the way of a future Nf3-e1-d3 @@StartBracket@@after Black plays ...g5-g4@@EndBracket@@ and does a better job protecting White against Black's aggression on the kingside.   5...Bb4+!?  is a very original idea, though not new, but rather 'borrowed' from the Queen's Indian and Catalan where this maneuver is very common. The idea is to lure either the bishop or the  knight to d2, to prevent White from trading bishops on a3. The reason we aren't recommending it is  6.Bd2  Bd6  7.a3!  Threatening Bd2-b4.  7...a5  8.Ne5  Nf6  9.Nc3  O-O  10.f4  followed by castling kingside, when our position is cramped and it's hard to come up with an active plan. }
6. O-O Bd6
{ It's probably best to fall in line with common theory at this point. We tried to make  6...Ne4  7.b3  Nd7  8.Ba3  Bxa3  9.Nxa3  work,  when Black can try to go for ...g5 or even ...h5 first, but it's all rather dubious.   Not very ambitious but perhaps playable is  6...Be7  with the idea that after  7.b3  O-O  8.Ba3  , we can play  8...Bd7  and recapture  on e7 with the queen followed by ...Be8 and ...Nbd7. White is a bit better, but Black's position is certainly solid. }
7. b3 Qe7
{ It's important to make White work a little for the exchange of bishops. Instead,  7...O-O  8.Ba3  makes things too easy for White. }
8. Bb2
{ The choice is between this move, followed by Qd1-c1 and Bb2-a3, or a2-a4 followed by Bc1-a3. The text move is the more popular option since White isn't keen on fixing the queenside structure with a2-a4 which allows ...a7-a5. }
8... O-O 9. Qc1 Nbd7
{ Less good is  9...a5  10.Ba3  Bb4  11.Bxb4  axb4  12.a3  , which is similar to  how we tackle 5.Bd3, but that's exactly the problem. With the bishop on e2 instead of d3, the concept of Stoofvlees, which was to continue  12...Nbd7  13.Qb2  e5  just makes no sense after the simple  14.dxe5  . }
10. Ba3 e5
{ The endgame after  10...Bxa3  11.Qxa3  Qxa3  12.Nxa3  certainly isn't going to be much fun.  In these types of positions, we'd love to make the move ...f5-f7. }
11. dxe5 Nxe5 12. Bxd6 Qxd6
{ The ...e6-e5 push has significantly altered the nature of the position. The c8-bishop is no longer a pawn and is about to go on active duty on e6. }
13. cxd5 Nxd5 14. Nc3 Be6 15. Rd1 Rad8
{ Play is approximately equal as we plan to exchange some more pieces with ...Ne5xf3 followed by ...Qd6-e5. We could also hold off on that for now and await developments with small improving moves such as ...h7-h6 or ...Be6-f7. }
*

[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "Quickstarter Guide − Stonewall & Triangle Sidelines"]
[Black "Stonewall 3.Nf3 c6 4.e3 f5 #2"]
[Result "*"]

1. d4 d5 2. c4 e6 3. Nf3 c6 4. e3
{ Inviting us to play a Meran type of game with  4...Nf6  , but as you probably know by now, that is not how we are going to roll in this course!  Against all the e3 setups we employ the Stonewall. }
4... f5
{ And there we go! As always, when a rigorous decision is made on the chessboard, there are clear up and downsides. Let's start with the obvious downside: placing the pawn on f5 means we leave ourselves with a giant hole on e5, and we weaken the dark squares as a whole. If White also manages to exchange the dark-squared bishops, which is a common strategic idea against the Stonewall, we will regret having pushed the pawn to f5 in the first place.   Another small issue is the bishop on c8, which is often the problem child in the Stonewall, hidden behind all the pawns on the light squares.  Luckily, there are upsides as well. By playing ...f7-f5 we strengthen our presence in the center by controlling the e4-square a second time and set up an impressive wall of pawns behind which we can swiftly develop our pieces. As Simen Agdestein, a big exponent of the Stonewall, mentioned very nicely in his foreword to the book Win with the Stonewall Dutch, people often think that setting up a 'stone wall' means trying to stay solid and defensive, while the modern interpretation is very different.  As in many other openings, the engines have shown that Black can play this opening in many different ways, some of which the inventors of this opening never could have imagined! We will try to bring you up to date on all those ideas. }
5. Bd3 { By far the main move in the position. } 5... Nf6
{ And the most usual reply. A game analyzed by Matthew Sadler in The Silicon Road to Chess Improvement recently caught our eye. In that game, the engine Stoofvlees came up with the most remarkable concept. Many of the lines that now follow are taken from the book as well. }
6. O-O Bd6 7. b3
{ We are faced with the usual plan of exchanging bishops on a3. } 7... Qe7 8.
Bb2
{ With the bishop on d3, the plan connected to  8.a4  is less attractive. The reason for that becomes apparent after  8...a5  9.Ba3  Bxa3  10.Nxa3  O-O  ,  when we have reached the same position as in Chapter 12, except for the fact that White's light-squared bishop was on e2 in that line. As it is, the plan of going Na3-c2-e1-d3 is now much harder to achieve, as the bishop is in the way, making this a less favorable version for White. }
8... O-O 9. Qc1 a5
{ Surprise, surprise! Magnus Carlsen faced Black here in 2021 in the MC-tour on chess24, against Vidit, and that game continued  9...b6  10.Ba3  Bb7  11.Bxd6  Qxd6  12.Qa3  Qxa3  13.Nxa3  and Carlsen, being Carlsen, managed to win this endgame, which, objectively speaking, gave White a risk-free edge. 9...a5 is the move advocated by Stoofvlees and a whole lot more fun! }
10. Ba3 Bb4 { Agreeing to the exchange of bishops, but on our terms. } 11. Qb2
Nbd7 12. Bxb4 axb4 13. a3 e5
{ The point! Of course, Black did not intend to suffer for the remainder of the game after  13...bxa3  14.Rxa3  Rxa3  15.Qxa3  when White holds all trumps. As Sadler points out, Stoofvlees' idea is not to fight for the a-file, but rather to use the whole queenside operation as a diversion for play on the other side of the board. }
14. Bxf5 { The critical reply. } 14... exd4
{ Definitely not the only move! Very playable as well is  14...e4  , which is given as an alternative. }
15. exd4
{ 15.Qxd4  is not very critical and gives us a good game after the simple  15...bxa3  . }
15... Ne4
{ Releasing the f8-rook, reminding White we really don't miss the f-pawn! } 16.
Bxe4 { The start of a highly tactical variation. } 16... dxe4 17. Re1 Rxf3
{ The only way to proceed, and a good one. White's king position is breached. }
18. gxf3 Qg5+ 19. Kh1 exf3 20. Rg1
{ It looks like our attack has been repelled, but a second wave is incoming. }
20... Qh4 21. axb4 Nf6
{ No time to be thinking about rooks! It's about the king on h1. } 22. Rxa8
{ 22.Nd2!  is the only move to stay in the game. } 22... Ng4 23. Rxc8+ Kf7 24.
Rc7+ Ke8
{ Two rooks up, White will be running out of checks, after which mate is imminent. }
*

[Event "?"]
