{ White castles first and only later decide how to combine moves like Ne5, a4 or b3. }
6... Nf6
{ We suggest starting with this move, instead of  6...Bb7  . The difference between the two moves is small, but we believe playing  6...Nf6  is slightly more flexible due to one particular line @@StartBracket@@see C below@@EndBracket@@. After  6...Nf6  , we focus on three moves, which are all standard ideas in White's arsenal.  A@@EndBracket@@  7.a4  is very popular and the line we examine in the Quickstarter.   B@@EndBracket@@  7.Ne5  is also frequently seen. In many cases,  a later a4 will transpose into lines that we cover under A though. Lines without a4 are possible and interesting  like  7.Ne5  Bb7  8.b3  or  8.Nc3  a6  9.b3  b4  10.Na4  − they lead to complex play that gives White compensation for the pawn.   C@@EndBracket@@  7.b3  is an interesting sideline. White immediately changes the queenside pawn structure and intends to play without  a quick a4. We  suggest  7...cxb3  8.Qxb3  Bd6  , delaying the  development of the c8-bishop, as it often can be employed effectively on a6 later.  This is the reason for @@StartFEN@@rnbqkbnr/p4ppp/2p1p3/1p6/2pP4/5NP1/PP2PPBP/RNBQ1RK1 b kq - 1 6@@EndFEN@@  6...Nf6  , instead of starting with  6...Bb7  . In the Quickstarter, we'll focus on 7.a4, while White other ideas are examined in the dedicated chapter. }
7. a4 Bb7
{ After this natural reply, there are two options. White can play  8.b3  immediately or prefer  8.Ne5  , opening up the diagonal of the bishop and provoking  8...a6  this way. }
8. Ne5
{ This knight jump looks attractive. White opens the diagonal for the bishop and threatens axb5 now, which more or less forces us to play 8...a6. White sometimes tries  8.b3  , when both  8...cxb3  and  8...b4!?  are fine for Black. }
8... a6
{ We support the b-pawn, there is no fully satisfactory alternative. After  8...a6  , White's most frequently played lines are  9.Nc3  Be7  10.axb5  axb5  11.Rxa8  Bxa8  or @@StartFEN@@rn1qkb1r/1b3ppp/p1p1pn2/1p2N3/P1pP4/6P1/1P2PPBP/RNBQ1RK1 w kq - 0 9@@EndFEN@@  9.axb5  axb5  10.Rxa8  Bxa8  11.Nc3  Be7  , which lead to the same position and pose no problem. More dangerous is @@StartFEN@@rn1qkb1r/1b3ppp/p1p1pn2/1p2N3/P1pP4/6P1/1P2PPBP/RNBQ1RK1 w kq - 0 9@@EndFEN@@  9.b3  , trying to open the queenside as quickly as possible. }
9. b3 { This move looks to be the most dangerous for Black. } 9... cxb3
{ Let's take the pawn. White now has a choice.  A@@EndBracket@@  10.Bb2  looks like White's best bet. We are fine with precise play, though. This is the line we'll examine in the Quickstarter.   B@@EndBracket@@  10.Qxb3  Qxd4  sacrifices a second pawn. White gets enough compensation, but 'two pawns are two pawns'. After  11.Bb2  Qb4  12.Qc2  Qc5  we offer a queen trade  and protect c6.   C@@EndBracket@@  10.axb5  axb5  11.Rxa8  Bxa8  is an alternative for White, after which they can decide between the two concepts of  12.Qxb3  or  12.Bb2  again. Our play against both is similar to A and B above. }
10. Bb2
{ White covers the d-pawn first and intends to capture the b-pawn later. GM Srinath Narayanan recommended this line in his Chessable course Lifetime Repertoires: The Catalan − a good choice as Black needs to be precise against it. }
10... Nbd7
{ The first important moment. We don't mind returning a pawn to coordinate our forces. Now we'll take a closer look at  11.Nxc6  and Narayanan's suggestion  11.Nd2  . Please note that  11.Qxb3  will likely lead to the same positions as  11.Nd2  , as we'll examine shortly. }
11. Nd2
{ This move is recommended by Narayanan. White can also try  11.Nxc6  , but  11...Qc7  is fine for Black. The following sequence after 11.Nd2 looks like the best play from both sides. }
11... Nxe5 12. dxe5 Nd7
{ We prefer this move over  12...Nd5  . You'll see that our knight is well placed after the following moves. }
13. Ne4 { White is aiming at the weak d6-square. } 13... Be7 14. Nd6+ Bxd6 15.
exd6
{ White managed to establish a strong pawn on d6, but our knight is an excellent blockading piece. Note that  16.Qxd6?!  Qb8  leads nowhere for White. }
15... O-O 16. Qxb3
{ White finally takes the b-pawn. Narayanan concludes his analysis here and correctly assesses that White has good compensation for the pawn. We'll look closer once our suggested reply is on the board. A small side note: it's fascinating to see that @@StartFEN@@r2qkb1r/1b1n1ppp/p1p1pn2/1p2N3/P2P4/1p4P1/1B2PPBP/RN1Q1RK1 w kq - 2 11@@EndFEN@@  11.Qxb3  Nxe5  12.dxe5  Nd7  13.Nd2  Be7  14.Ne4  O-O  15.Nd6  Bxd6  16.exd6  leads to the same position. }
16... Qb6
{ A logical move. We cover the bishop and thus threaten ...c5 now. White has to address this threat, so slow development is not enough. Therefore we don't have to examine many moves.   A@@EndBracket@@  17.a5  Qa7  18.Bxc6  Bxc6  19.Qc3  e5  20.Qxc6  Rac8  leads to equal chances.   B@@EndBracket@@  17.Qf3  b4  18.h4  Rad8!  is strong, protecting the knight. This allows answering  19.Qg4?  with  19...e5!  These fascinating complications are analyzed more in the dedicated chapter on the Catalan Triangle, of course. }
*

[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "Quickstarter Guide − Stonewall & Triangle Sidelines"]
[Black "Triangle 3.Nf3 c6 4.Qc2 #1"]
[Result "*"]

1. d4 d5 2. c4 e6
{ After  2...e6  , White's most popular and best moves are the two natural knight jumps,  3.Nc3  and  3.Nf3  . Even if White intends to avoid the most critical paths @@StartBracket@@Noteboom/Marshall Gambit@@EndBracket@@, they usually start with a knight move. Playing one of the knights makes a lot of sense.  They are well-positioned on c3/f3 and White does not yet determine the pawn structure.  This leads us to possible White alternatives to  3.Nf3  or  3.Nc3  − let's have a look.   A@@EndBracket@@  3.cxd5  exd5  White  immediately exchanges on d5, aiming for the famous 'Carlsbad Structure' that arises after our natural recapture. If White intends to go for this pawn structure, they usually play 3.Nc3 first, and only trade on move four. We'll examine this version of the Carlsbad in the Quickstarter, as it is the most frequently seen move order. The trade on move three has no independent value, as playing the move pair Nc3 and ...c6 is very natural and will happen rather sooner than later.   B@@EndBracket@@  3.e3  c6  White covers the c4-pawn but commits to e3 relatively early. If White intends to play with e3, they usually decide to play lines  like @@StartFEN@@rnbqkbnr/ppp2ppp/4p3/3p4/2PP4/8/PP2PPPP/RNBQKBNR w KQkq - 0 3@@EndFEN@@  3.Nc3  c6  4.e3  or @@StartFEN@@rnbqkbnr/ppp2ppp/4p3/3p4/2PP4/8/PP2PPPP/RNBQKBNR w KQkq - 0 3@@EndFEN@@  3.Nf3  c6  4.e3  . Now, after @@StartFEN@@rnbqkbnr/ppp2ppp/4p3/3p4/2PP4/8/PP2PPPP/RNBQKBNR w KQkq - 0 3@@EndFEN@@  3.e3  c6  , White will likely play a knight  to c3 or f3, transposing to these mentioned lines.   C@@EndBracket@@  3.g3  dxc4  . The move 3.g3 is similar to the line @@StartFEN@@rnbqkbnr/ppp2ppp/4p3/3p4/2PP4/8/PP2PPPP/RNBQKBNR w KQkq - 0 3@@EndFEN@@  3.Nf3  c6  4.g3  , when we suggest playing  4...dxc4  .  Against 3.g3, the capture on c4 is a fine solution, as well.  After @@StartFEN@@rnbqkbnr/ppp2ppp/4p3/3p4/2PP4/8/PP2PPPP/RNBQKBNR w KQkq - 0 3@@EndFEN@@  3.g3  dxc4  4.Bg2  c6  5.Nf3  b5  we have transposed to the main line of the mentioned @@StartFEN@@rnbqkbnr/ppp2ppp/4p3/3p4/2PP4/8/PP2PPPP/RNBQKBNR w KQkq - 0 3@@EndFEN@@  3.Nf3  c6  4.g3  variation @@StartBracket@@The Catalan Triangle@@EndBracket@@.   D@@EndBracket@@  3.Bf4?!  dxc4!  is very similar @@StartFEN@@rnbqkbnr/ppp2ppp/4p3/3p4/2PP4/8/PP2PPPP/RNBQKBNR w KQkq - 0 3@@EndFEN@@ to  3.Nc3  c6  4.Bf4?!  dxc4!  , which we examine in this Quickstarter Guide. A transposition to this line is very likely, as a sequence like @@StartFEN@@rnbqkbnr/ppp2ppp/4p3/8/2pP1B2/8/PP2PPPP/RN1QKBNR w KQkq - 0 4@@EndFEN@@  4.e3  b5  5.a4  c6  6.Nc3  Qb6  is very natural.   E@@EndBracket@@  3.c5?  is just a mistake. After  3...b6  Black is already much better, as  4.b4  a5  fails for White. The queenside is falling apart. As you see, the 'non-knight' moves are at best a transposition and therefore don't merit any detailed coverage here. }
3. Nf3 c6
{ Our triangle move. Now White has a range of options.  A@@EndBracket@@  4.Nc3  dxc4  is the Noteboom.   B@@EndBracket@@  4.e3  f5  or @@StartFEN@@rnbqkbnr/pp3ppp/2p1p3/3p4/2PP4/5N2/PP2PPPP/RNBQKB1R w KQkq - 0 4@@EndFEN@@  4.Nbd2  f5  leads to the Stonewall formation.   C@@EndBracket@@  4.Qc2  dxc4  or @@StartFEN@@rnbqkbnr/pp3ppp/2p1p3/3p4/2PP4/5N2/PP2PPPP/RNBQKB1R w KQkq - 0 4@@EndFEN@@  4.Qb3  dxc4  is not without venom and needs to be handled with care by Black. We cover the main points here in the Quickstarter.   D@@EndBracket@@  4.g3  dxc4  leads to the Catalan Triangle, an interesting continuation for White. Very frequently, we'll grab and hold the c-pawn, but White has compensation for the material deficit. This line is covered in this Quickstarter too.   E@@EndBracket@@  4.cxd5  exd5  leads to a Carlsbad pawn structure. We examine @@StartFEN@@rnbqkbnr/ppp2ppp/4p3/3p4/2PP4/8/PP2PPPP/RNBQKBNR w KQkq - 0 3@@EndFEN@@  3.Nc3  c6  4.cxd5  exd5  in the Quickstarter to illustrate the main ideas of this popular formation.   F@@EndBracket@@ @@StartFEN@@rnbqkbnr/pp3ppp/2p1p3/3p4/2PP4/5N2/PP2PPPP/RNBQKB1R w KQkq - 0 4@@EndFEN@@  4.Bg5  is a solid line for White. After  4...Be7  5.Bxe7  Qxe7  Black  has no problems, though. We'll develop with ...Nf6 and ...O-O, followed by a quick ...dxc4 and ...c5 idea, opening the center. }
4. Qc2
{ White covers the c4-pawn with the queen but remains flexible regarding further action. In many cases, White intends to fianchetto the f1-bishop but wants to avoid the line  4.g3  dxc4  , which often amounts to a 'real' pawn sacrifice.  White is not committed to a kingside fianchetto, though. White may still develop with Bf4 or Bg5, followed by e3, when the king's bishop will be placed on e2 or d3 later. }
4... dxc4
{ The immediate capture is most in spirit with the Triangle/Noteboom. In most cases, we plan a queenside expansion with ...b5 after White has recovered the c4-pawn.   A quick word about alternatives: Black has to avoid  4...f5?  , which is a dreadful version of the Stonewall after  5.Bf4  . We only want to enter a Stonewall after White has committed to the  move e3, for example,  after @@StartFEN@@rnbqkbnr/pppppppp/8/8/8/8/PPPPPPPP/RNBQKBNR w KQkq - 0 1@@EndFEN@@  1.d4  d5  2.c4  e6  3.Nc3  c6  4.e3  Bd6  5.Nf3  f5  ,  or an early Nbd2 after  @@StartFEN@@rnbqkbnr/pppppppp/8/8/8/8/PPPPPPPP/RNBQKBNR w KQkq - 0 1@@EndFEN@@  1.d4  d5  2.c4  e6  3.Nf3  c6  4.Nbd2  f5  .  Black is in terrible shape after @@StartFEN@@rnbqkbnr/pp3ppp/2p1p3/3p4/2PP4/5N2/PPQ1PPPP/RNB1KB1R b KQkq - 1 4@@EndFEN@@  4...f5?  5.Bf4  , when  5...Nf6  6.e3  Be7  7.Nc3  O-O  8.Bd3  Ne4  9.g4  scores about 75% for White.  A much better alternative is @@StartFEN@@rnbqkbnr/pp3ppp/2p1p3/3p4/2PP4/5N2/PPQ1PPPP/RNB1KB1R b KQkq - 1 4@@EndFEN@@  4...Nf6  ,  intending to capture on c4 after  5.Bg5  dxc4  or @@StartFEN@@rnbqkb1r/pp3ppp/2p1pn2/3p4/2PP4/5N2/PPQ1PPPP/RNB1KB1R w KQkq - 2 5@@EndFEN@@  5.g3  dxc4  . These sequences would transpose to our recommendation, but @@StartFEN@@rnbqkb1r/pp3ppp/2p1pn2/3p4/2PP4/5N2/PPQ1PPPP/RNB1KB1R w KQkq - 2 5@@EndFEN@@  5.e3  or  5.Nbd2  give White additional options that we can sidestep by taking on c4 immediately. }
5. Qxc4
{ After the natural 5.Qxc4, we reach an important moment early in the game. }
5... Nf6
{ It is essential to play  5...Nf6  here and avoid the most natural move,  5...b5  . Somewhat surprisingly, the immediate pawn push is a serious inaccuracy after  6.Qc2  Bb7  7.e4  , when Black  does not manage to play ...c6-c5 under fully satisfactory circumstances.  We need to play @@StartFEN@@rnbqkbnr/pp3ppp/2p1p3/8/2QP4/5N2/PP2PPPP/RNB1KB1R b KQkq - 0 5@@EndFEN@@  5...Nf6  first and wait for a moment until White gives us more information about the intended setup. Now White has some options − here's an overview:  A@@EndBracket@@  6.g3  is the most popular move, playing in the style of the Catalan. We'll play  6...b5  , intending to oppose White's bishop on the long diagonal  after a later ...Bb7 and ...c6-c5.   B@@EndBracket@@  6.Bg5  White pins our knight and usually intends  to develop with a later e2-e3 or e2-e4. It is important NOT to play  6...b5  here, but go for  6...Nbd7!  instead. We'll discuss the reasoning in the notes to this line.   C@@EndBracket@@  6.Qc2  is a tricky move, hoping for  6...b5?!  7.e4  , when White is better @@StartBracket@@a transposition to @@StartFEN@@rnbqkbnr/pp3ppp/2p1p3/8/2QP4/5N2/PP2PPPP/RNB1KB1R b KQkq - 0 5@@EndFEN@@  5...b5?!  6.Qc2  , essentially@@EndBracket@@. The way to equalize is @@StartFEN@@rnbqkb1r/pp3ppp/2p1pn2/8/3P4/5N2/PPQ1PPPP/RNB1KB1R b KQkq - 2 6@@EndFEN@@  6...c5!  , using the fact that 6.Qc2 is relatively slow. After  7.dxc5  Qc7  we will regain the pawn, as  8.b4?  a5  is fine for Black.   D@@EndBracket@@ @@StartFEN@@rnbqkb1r/pp3ppp/2p1pn2/8/2QP4/5N2/PP2PPPP/RNB1KB1R w KQkq - 1 6@@EndFEN@@  6.Nc3  is not very popular here but leads to a well-explored line that more often arises via @@StartFEN@@rnbqkbnr/pppppppp/8/8/8/8/PPPPPPPP/RNBQKBNR w KQkq - 0 1@@EndFEN@@  1.d4  d5  2.c4  c6  3.Nf3  Nf6  4.Nc3  e6  5.Qb3  @@StartBracket@@or 5.Qd3@@EndBracket@@  5...dxc4  6.Qxc4  . Black is fine after  6...b5  ,  when both queen moves will be answered with ...a6, playing for ...c5.  The lines A and B are the most popular and the ones we will focus on in the Quickstarter. C and D are covered in the dedicated chapter. As you see, we need to be very flexible here. There is no 'standard' setup that we can go for, but we need to adjust to the various subtleties. A good rule of thumb about whether to play ...b5 or not is: we play ...b5 against the fianchetto @@StartBracket@@we answer a fianchetto with an extended fianchetto, so to say@@EndBracket@@ and when White plays Nc3, giving the b-pawn a target to attack @@StartBracket@@...b5-b4@@EndBracket@@. It's not about playing ...b5 just for the tempo, but the move needs to serve a definite purpose in reply to White's decision on move six. }
6. Bg5
{ White scores well with this pinning move, but Black is fine if we play precisely. }
6... Nbd7
{ The far more popular option for Black is the more obvious  6...b5  , but it is surprisingly difficult for Black to play. Instead, the move  6...Nbd7  is less explored but looks fully satisfactory for Black.  We prepare ...c6-c5 and also get the ...Nd7xf6 option if White decides to capture on f6.   We'll have a look at the reply @@StartFEN@@r1bqkb1r/pp1n1ppp/2p1pn2/6B1/2QP4/5N2/PP2PPPP/RN2KB1R w KQkq - 3 7@@EndFEN@@  7.e3  now. White could also go for  7.e4  , when  7...h6  8.Bxf6  Nxf6  9.Nc3  Qb6  looks best.  Black is attacking the b-pawn and is preparing ...c5 at the same time. }
7. e3
{ White remains flexible about the knight development but allows a tricky reply that we are happy to go for. }
7... Qa5+
{ Black should also equalize with  7...c5  , but the queen check sets more problems. }
8. Nbd2
{ White recognizes that 8.Nc3 Ne4 is uncomfortable and prefers the more conservative knight move. After  8.Nc3  Ne4  9.Bh4  Nb6  10.Qd3  we have the fine move  10...Na4!  ,  putting pressure on c3. }
8... Ne4
{ We are going for concrete play with 7...Qa5+ and have to continue in this fashion. The knight jump attacks the bishop and starts the following sequence, which equalizes comfortably. }
9. Bf4
{ White can't play  9.Bh4??  g5  10.Bg3  g4  , which wins a full piece for Black! }
9... e5
{ This looks a bit cooler than  9...Nxd2  10.Nxd2  e5  , but both will lead to the same positions.   9...g5  would be excellent, if not for  10.Bc7!  Qxc7  11.Nxe4  , with a pleasant  edge for White. The g5-pawn is now a weakness. }
10. dxe5
{ The only move for White. After  10.Bxe5?  Bb4  11.Qc2  Nxd2  12.Nxd2  Nxe5  13.dxe5  Be6  White is in terrible shape as ...O-O-O is hard to stop. }
10... Nxd2 11. Nxd2 Nxe5
{ We have regained the pawn and managed to open the position for our bishops. After  12.Qe4  f6  or @@StartFEN@@r1b1kb1r/pp3ppp/2p5/q3n3/2Q2B2/4P3/PP1N1PPP/R3KB1R w KQkq - 0 12@@EndFEN@@  12.Qd4  Ng6  Black has equal chances. }
