6. g3 { Preparing the kingside fianchetto is White's most popular move. } 6...
b5
{ Playing ...b5 makes a lot of sense against 6.g3. We free the b7-square for our bishop and intend to play ...Bb7 and ...c5 as soon as possible. Often this pawn break needs to be supported with ...Nbd7 and ...a6, depending on White's setup.   Now  7.Qc2  is the most popular move, but it seems that  7.Qd3  or  7.Qb3  pose more problems for Black. In the Quickstarter, we'll have a closer look at  7.Qc2  and  7.Qb3  . }
7. Qc2
{ This queen retreat is White's most popular move, but it's very easy to handle for Black. The white queen does not have an eye on b5, making it easier for us to accomplish ...c5. In addition, the queen may prove to be vulnerable on the c-file to a later ...Rc8. }
7... Bb7
{ Our plan of ...Bb7, ...Nbd7 and ...c5 is simple and straightforward. } 8. Bg2
Nbd7
{ We are ready for ...c5 now. The only move that stops the pawn push now is  9.Ne5  , otherwise, we'd  play ...c5, for example, after  9.O-O  c5  , @@StartFEN@@r2qkb1r/pb1n1ppp/2p1pn2/1p6/3P4/5NP1/PPQ1PPBP/RNB1K2R w KQkq - 4 9@@EndFEN@@  9.Nc3  c5  or @@StartFEN@@r2qkb1r/pb1n1ppp/2p1pn2/1p6/3P4/5NP1/PPQ1PPBP/RNB1K2R w KQkq - 4 9@@EndFEN@@  9.a4  c5  . }
9. Ne5
{ The knight jump to e5 is White's key resource in the lines with 7.Qb3 and 7.Qd3. Black has to be precise in these variations to obtain chances. Here, Black's job is easier.   If White does not play  9.Ne5  ,  we'll manage ...c5 and have a good game.  You'll often meet  9.O-O  c5  , when Black is in good shape. Note that White's queen is not ideal on the c-file,  as ...Rc8 will be annoying soon. }
9... Nxe5 10. dxe5 Nd5
{ Much better than  10...Nd7?  11.a4  , which gives White the better chances. }
11. O-O
{ White also plays  11.Nc3  , when  11...Be7  12.O-O  is a common transposition to the same line that we reach via @@StartFEN@@r2qkb1r/pb3ppp/2p1p3/1p1nP3/8/6P1/PPQ1PPBP/RNB1K2R w KQkq - 1 11@@EndFEN@@  11.O-O  Be7  12.Nc3  . }
11... Be7
{ The exclamation mark is a bit strong, but it is crucial to remember that we want to complete kingside castling first and only then aim for ...c6-c5. The pawn move is the main element of our strategy, but timing is essential.   After  11...c5?!  12.Nc3  White  has pressure on b5 and d5. Black is worse after  12...Qb6  13.Nxd5  Bxd5  14.Bxd5  exd5  15.Rd1  , which is a scenario that we can easily avoid by delaying  the ...c5 move for a while. We want to play ...Be7 and ...O-O first, maybe ...Qb8 if White goes for Rd1. }
12. Nc3 { Or  12.Rd1  Qb8  , which will likely lead to the same thing. } 12...
O-O 13. Rd1 Qb8
{ A much better move than  13...Qc7?  when  14.Nxd5  exd5  15.Rxd5  exploits the unfavorable position of the queen. }
14. f4
{ Lines like  14.Qe4  b4  @@StartBracket@@a good moment to play ...b4, as Ne4 is impossible@@EndBracket@@  or @@StartFEN@@rq3rk1/pb2bppp/2p1p3/1p1nP3/8/2N3P1/PPQ1PPBP/R1BR2K1 w - - 7 14@@EndFEN@@  14.Nxd5  cxd5  give Black equal chances without any hassle. The move 14.f4 is also fine for Black, but there is an interesting point to examine. }
14... Rc8
{ We can't play  14...c5  as White would win a pawn after multiple captures on d5. After the alternative  14...Nxc3  15.Qxc3  c5  White has  16.Rd7  , though. This leads to equal play, but 14... Rc8! is a bit more ambitious. We wait for a moment and play a useful move first, without committing to a pawn advance yet. }
15. Nxd5
{ The only good move, according to Stockfish. Black is definitely in good shape after  15.Ne4  c5  or @@StartFEN@@rqr3k1/pb2bppp/2p1p3/1p1nP3/5P2/2N3P1/PPQ1P1BP/R1BR2K1 w - - 1 15@@EndFEN@@  15.a4  b4  16.Ne4  Ba6  ,  when ...Qb6+ is looming. }
15... cxd5 16. Qd3 b4
{ We'll play ...a5 and ...Ba6 next, with good chances for Black. It still should be equal, but Black's job is easy. }
*

[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "Quickstarter Guide − Stonewall & Triangle Sidelines"]
[Black "Triangle Sidelines 3.Nc3 c6 4.Bf4"]
[Result "*"]

1. d4 d5 2. c4 e6
{ After  2...e6  , White's most popular and best moves are the two natural knight jumps,  3.Nc3  and  3.Nf3  . Even if White intends to avoid the most critical paths @@StartBracket@@Noteboom/Marshall Gambit@@EndBracket@@, they usually start with a knight move. Playing one of the knights makes a lot of sense.  They are well-positioned on c3/f3 and White does not yet determine the pawn structure.  This leads us to possible White alternatives to  3.Nf3  or  3.Nc3  − let's have a look.   A@@EndBracket@@  3.cxd5  exd5  White  immediately exchanges on d5, aiming for the famous 'Carlsbad Structure' that arises after our natural recapture. If White intends to go for this pawn structure, they usually play 3.Nc3 first, and only trade on move four. We'll examine this version of the Carlsbad in the Quickstarter, as it is the most frequently seen move order. The trade on move three has no independent value, as playing the move pair Nc3 and ...c6 is very natural and will happen rather sooner than later.   B@@EndBracket@@  3.e3  c6  White covers the c4-pawn but commits to e3 relatively early. If White intends to play with e3, they usually decide to play lines  like @@StartFEN@@rnbqkbnr/ppp2ppp/4p3/3p4/2PP4/8/PP2PPPP/RNBQKBNR w KQkq - 0 3@@EndFEN@@  3.Nc3  c6  4.e3  or @@StartFEN@@rnbqkbnr/ppp2ppp/4p3/3p4/2PP4/8/PP2PPPP/RNBQKBNR w KQkq - 0 3@@EndFEN@@  3.Nf3  c6  4.e3  . Now, after @@StartFEN@@rnbqkbnr/ppp2ppp/4p3/3p4/2PP4/8/PP2PPPP/RNBQKBNR w KQkq - 0 3@@EndFEN@@  3.e3  c6  , White will likely play a knight  to c3 or f3, transposing to these mentioned lines.   C@@EndBracket@@  3.g3  dxc4  . The move 3.g3 is similar to the line @@StartFEN@@rnbqkbnr/ppp2ppp/4p3/3p4/2PP4/8/PP2PPPP/RNBQKBNR w KQkq - 0 3@@EndFEN@@  3.Nf3  c6  4.g3  , when we suggest playing  4...dxc4  .  Against 3.g3, the capture on c4 is a fine solution, as well.  After @@StartFEN@@rnbqkbnr/ppp2ppp/4p3/3p4/2PP4/8/PP2PPPP/RNBQKBNR w KQkq - 0 3@@EndFEN@@  3.g3  dxc4  4.Bg2  c6  5.Nf3  b5  we have transposed to the main line of the mentioned @@StartFEN@@rnbqkbnr/ppp2ppp/4p3/3p4/2PP4/8/PP2PPPP/RNBQKBNR w KQkq - 0 3@@EndFEN@@  3.Nf3  c6  4.g3  variation @@StartBracket@@The Catalan Triangle@@EndBracket@@.   D@@EndBracket@@  3.Bf4?!  dxc4!  is very similar @@StartFEN@@rnbqkbnr/ppp2ppp/4p3/3p4/2PP4/8/PP2PPPP/RNBQKBNR w KQkq - 0 3@@EndFEN@@ to  3.Nc3  c6  4.Bf4?!  dxc4!  , which we examine in this Quickstarter Guide. A transposition to this line is very likely, as a sequence like @@StartFEN@@rnbqkbnr/ppp2ppp/4p3/8/2pP1B2/8/PP2PPPP/RN1QKBNR w KQkq - 0 4@@EndFEN@@  4.e3  b5  5.a4  c6  6.Nc3  Qb6  is very natural.   E@@EndBracket@@  3.c5?  is just a mistake. After  3...b6  Black is already much better, as  4.b4  a5  fails for White. The queenside is falling apart. As you see, the 'non-knight' moves are at best a transposition and therefore don't merit any detailed coverage here. }
3. Nc3 c6
{ The starting position of the Triangle. Now White's main options are covered in other chapters:  A@@EndBracket@@  4.e4  − The Marshall Gambit.   B@@EndBracket@@  4.Nf3  dxc4  − The Noteboom.   C@@EndBracket@@  4.e3  − We'll answer in Stonewall style with  4...f5  .   The most important option that we'll examine is  4.cxd5  exd5  , leading to a Carlsbad pawn structure. You'll frequently meet this variation, as many opponents prefer this simple but objectively toothless exchange. The second move that we'll examine is  4.Bf4  , which is dubious for White but requires a precise reply. }
4. Bf4
{ A very natural move, White wants to play Bf4 first, then continue with e3 to start development of the kingside. All the lines after 4.Bf4 are promising for White, except the one we will play! }
4... dxc4
{ Very much in the spirit of the Noteboom. We grab the c-pawn and have ...b5 ready to cover it. As we will see, White must fight for equality after  4...dxc4  . White's only move to do that is  5.a4!  Black is already much better after  5.e3  , as  5...b5  6.a4  Qb6!  keeps the extra pawn without any problems. Black has to avoid  6...Bb4?  though, because  7.axb5  cxb5  8.Qf3  Qd5  9.Qg3  and all of a sudden White wins due to the double attack on b8 and g7. This idea/line is also relevant  after @@StartFEN@@rnbqkbnr/pp3ppp/2p1p3/8/2pP1B2/2N5/PP2PPPP/R2QKBNR w KQkq - 0 5@@EndFEN@@  5.a4!  as we will see. }
5. a4
{ White's best move and the only one that fights for equality. It also sets a trap that we need to avoid. In the Noteboom, we often play a combination of the moves ...b5 and ...Bb4 to secure the b5-pawn.   Now  5...Bb4?!  6.e3  b5??  is a huge mistake due to  7.axb5  cxb5  8.Qf3  Qd5  9.Qg3  and White wins! This point was already mentioned in the context of @@StartFEN@@rnbqkbnr/pp3ppp/2p1p3/8/2pP1B2/2N5/PP2PPPP/R2QKBNR w KQkq - 0 5@@EndFEN@@  5.e3  b5  6.a4  Bb4?  , which leads to exactly the same trap. }
5... Nf6
{ This looks best for Black. As mentioned, you need to avoid  5...Bb4?!  at this point. }
6. e3
{ White has tried  6.e4?  in some games, but  6...Bb4  puts too much pressure on White's center. Neither  7.f3  b5  nor @@StartFEN@@rnbqk2r/pp3ppp/2p1pn2/8/PbpPPB2/2N5/1P3PPP/R2QKBNR w KQkq - 1 7@@EndFEN@@  7.e5  Nd5  are desirable for White, showing that  the combination of Bf4 and e4 is ill-advised. }
6... b5
{ We like this dynamic approach. Here the move  6...Nd5?!  is quite popular, but after  7.Bxc4  Nxf4  8.exf4  White has a good game despite the weakened pawn structure. It's challenging for Black to activate  the c8-bishop in these structures. Some classic games by Alekhine and Rubinstein demonstrated Black's issues about a century ago. Our solution 6...b5! starts a forced sequence that wins Black tempi for development. }
7. axb5
{ White has to regain the pawn before we cover it with ...Qb6 or ...Bb4. } 7...
cxb5 8. Nxb5
{ Here,  8.Qf3?  is very naive and easily dispatched by  8...Nd5  9.Nxb5  Bb4+  10.Nc3  Bb7  , when Black has a winning attack. }
8... Bb4+ 9. Nc3 Nd5 { This position is more or less forced after 5.a4 Nf6. }
10. Ne2
{ White plays this move most of the time, but Black has a considerable advantage now. Understandably, White wants to cover both f4 and c3, but how to develop the kingside?   Stockfish suggests  10.Qc2  instead, which is not an intuitive solution. After  10...Bxc3+  11.bxc3  Nxf4  12.exf4  Qc7  chances are about equal. }
10... O-O 11. Bg3 { White prepares the move e4. } 11... Nc6 12. e4 Nb6
{ Black is much better in this position. In the online Blitz game A. Tang - S. Nihal, the move  13.f3  was played, when  13...f5  would have been even better than Nihal's  13...Na5  . Black can start an attack on White's king in the center, exploiting its awkward position. }
