1. d4 d5 2. c4 e6
{ After  2...e6  , White's most popular and best moves are the two natural knight jumps,  3.Nc3  and  3.Nf3  . Even if White intends to avoid the most critical paths @@StartBracket@@Noteboom/Marshall Gambit@@EndBracket@@, they usually start with a knight move. Playing one of the knights makes a lot of sense.  They are well-positioned on c3/f3 and White does not yet determine the pawn structure.  This leads us to possible White alternatives to  3.Nf3  or  3.Nc3  − let's have a look.   A@@EndBracket@@  3.cxd5  exd5  White  immediately exchanges on d5, aiming for the famous 'Carlsbad Structure' that arises after our natural recapture. If White intends to go for this pawn structure, they usually play 3.Nc3 first, and only trade on move four. We'll examine this version of the Carlsbad in the Quickstarter, as it is the most frequently seen move order. The trade on move three has no independent value, as playing the move pair Nc3 and ...c6 is very natural and will happen rather sooner than later.   B@@EndBracket@@  3.e3  c6  White covers the c4-pawn but commits to e3 relatively early. If White intends to play with e3, they usually decide to play lines  like @@StartFEN@@rnbqkbnr/ppp2ppp/4p3/3p4/2PP4/8/PP2PPPP/RNBQKBNR w KQkq - 0 3@@EndFEN@@  3.Nc3  c6  4.e3  or @@StartFEN@@rnbqkbnr/ppp2ppp/4p3/3p4/2PP4/8/PP2PPPP/RNBQKBNR w KQkq - 0 3@@EndFEN@@  3.Nf3  c6  4.e3  . Now, after @@StartFEN@@rnbqkbnr/ppp2ppp/4p3/3p4/2PP4/8/PP2PPPP/RNBQKBNR w KQkq - 0 3@@EndFEN@@  3.e3  c6  , White will likely play a knight  to c3 or f3, transposing to these mentioned lines.   C@@EndBracket@@  3.g3  dxc4  . The move 3.g3 is similar to the line @@StartFEN@@rnbqkbnr/ppp2ppp/4p3/3p4/2PP4/8/PP2PPPP/RNBQKBNR w KQkq - 0 3@@EndFEN@@  3.Nf3  c6  4.g3  , when we suggest playing  4...dxc4  .  Against 3.g3, the capture on c4 is a fine solution, as well.  After @@StartFEN@@rnbqkbnr/ppp2ppp/4p3/3p4/2PP4/8/PP2PPPP/RNBQKBNR w KQkq - 0 3@@EndFEN@@  3.g3  dxc4  4.Bg2  c6  5.Nf3  b5  we have transposed to the main line of the mentioned @@StartFEN@@rnbqkbnr/ppp2ppp/4p3/3p4/2PP4/8/PP2PPPP/RNBQKBNR w KQkq - 0 3@@EndFEN@@  3.Nf3  c6  4.g3  variation @@StartBracket@@The Catalan Triangle@@EndBracket@@.   D@@EndBracket@@  3.Bf4?!  dxc4!  is very similar @@StartFEN@@rnbqkbnr/ppp2ppp/4p3/3p4/2PP4/8/PP2PPPP/RNBQKBNR w KQkq - 0 3@@EndFEN@@ to  3.Nc3  c6  4.Bf4?!  dxc4!  , which we examine in this Quickstarter Guide. A transposition to this line is very likely, as a sequence like @@StartFEN@@rnbqkbnr/ppp2ppp/4p3/8/2pP1B2/8/PP2PPPP/RN1QKBNR w KQkq - 0 4@@EndFEN@@  4.e3  b5  5.a4  c6  6.Nc3  Qb6  is very natural.   E@@EndBracket@@  3.c5?  is just a mistake. After  3...b6  Black is already much better, as  4.b4  a5  fails for White. The queenside is falling apart. As you see, the 'non-knight' moves are at best a transposition and therefore don't merit any detailed coverage here. }
3. Nc3 c6
{ The starting position of the Triangle. Now White's main options are covered in other chapters:  A@@EndBracket@@  4.e4  − The Marshall Gambit.   B@@EndBracket@@  4.Nf3  dxc4  − The Noteboom.   C@@EndBracket@@  4.e3  − We'll answer in Stonewall style with  4...f5  .   The most important option that we'll examine is  4.cxd5  exd5  , leading to a Carlsbad pawn structure. You'll frequently meet this variation, as many opponents prefer this simple but objectively toothless exchange. The second move that we'll examine is  4.Bf4  , which is dubious for White but requires a precise reply. }
4. cxd5
{ White captures on d5 and changes the pawn structure. We'll talk about this more after our natural reply. }
4... exd5
{ This pawn formation, characterized by White's trade of the c-pawn for the e-pawn, is a very regular scenario in various Queen's Gambit lines. We may face the exchange on d5 after @@StartFEN@@rnbqkbnr/pppppppp/8/8/8/8/PPPPPPPP/RNBQKBNR w KQkq - 0 1@@EndFEN@@  1.d4  d5  2.c4  e6  3.cxd5  exd5  , or after @@StartFEN@@rnbqkbnr/ppp2ppp/4p3/3p4/2PP4/8/PP2PPPP/RNBQKBNR w KQkq - 0 3@@EndFEN@@  3.Nc3  c6  4.cxd5  / @@StartFEN@@rnbqkbnr/ppp2ppp/4p3/3p4/2PP4/8/PP2PPPP/RNBQKBNR w KQkq - 0 3@@EndFEN@@  3.Nf3  c6  4.cxd5  .  We will reach the same positions because after @@StartFEN@@rnbqkbnr/ppp2ppp/4p3/3p4/2PP4/8/PP2PPPP/RNBQKBNR w KQkq - 0 3@@EndFEN@@  3.cxd5  exd5  , White has nothing better than  4.Nc3  or  4.Nf3  when, in both cases,  4...c6  is the best move and our suggested reply.   In the Carlsbad structure, Black's ideal development scheme involves playing the bishops to d6 and f5, going for the most active squares possible. This setup can only be reached if you play ...c6 first. Black needs to cover d5, to allow ...Bd6, and also prepares ...Bf5.  Without the move ...c6, the reply Qb3 is often a problem, hitting d5 and b7 simultaneously. Once ...c6 is on the board, the move ...Bf5 is easier to play, as Qb3 can quickly be answered with ...Qb6.  It is helpful to compare our specific version of the exchange with two similar lines.  A@@EndBracket@@ @@StartFEN@@rnbqkbnr/pppppppp/8/8/8/8/PPPPPPPP/RNBQKBNR w KQkq - 0 1@@EndFEN@@  1.d4  d5  2.c4  e6  3.cxd5  exd5  4.Nc3  c6  or @@StartFEN@@rnbqkbnr/ppp2ppp/4p3/3p4/2PP4/8/PP2PPPP/RNBQKBNR w KQkq - 0 3@@EndFEN@@  3.Nc3  c6  4.cxd5  exd5  .  B@@EndBracket@@ @@StartFEN@@rnbqkbnr/pppppppp/8/8/8/8/PPPPPPPP/RNBQKBNR w KQkq - 0 1@@EndFEN@@  1.d4  d5  2.c4  e6  3.Nc3  Nf6  4.cxd5  exd5  .  C@@EndBracket@@ @@StartFEN@@rnbqkbnr/pppppppp/8/8/8/8/PPPPPPPP/RNBQKBNR w KQkq - 0 1@@EndFEN@@  1.d4  d5  2.c4  e6  3.Nc3  Be7  4.cxd5  exd5  .  While lines B and C are considered main lines and good tries for an advantage, line A @@StartBracket@@our version@@EndBracket@@ is not. Why? In line B, White continues with @@StartFEN@@rnbqkb1r/ppp2ppp/5n2/3p4/3P4/2N5/PP2PPPP/R1BQKBNR w KQkq - 0 5@@EndFEN@@  5.Bg5  , pinning the knight @@StartBracket@@not possible in A@@EndBracket@@.  As mentioned, Black would like to employ an active piece setup with ...Bd6 and ...Bf5.  It turns out that it is impossible to achieve both moves under favorable circumstances. If Black  decides to play  5...Be7  to break the pin,  the ...Bd6-formation is off.  So  5...c6  is the best try to shoot for it. After  6.e3  Bd6  7.Bd3  ,  you won't manage ...Bf5, though. You could start  with @@StartFEN@@rnbqkb1r/pp3ppp/2p2n2/3p2B1/3P4/2N1P3/PP3PPP/R2QKBNR b KQkq - 0 6@@EndFEN@@  6...Bf5  , but this is met with the annoying move  7.Qf3!  when Black needs to accept a doubled f-pawn.  These lines are not entirely bad for Black, but they show that reaching the optimal/most active setup is not possible against best play.  In line C,  Black has already played the bishop to e7 and avoided the move ...Nf6. This way, the pin on the knight is not possible, but playing ...Be7 is not ideal if you'd like to place the bishop on d6.  One main continuation in line C  is: @@StartFEN@@rnbqk1nr/ppp1bppp/8/3p4/3P4/2N5/PP2PPPP/R1BQKBNR w KQkq - 0 5@@EndFEN@@  5.Bf4  c6  6.e3  Bd6  , when Black accepts a tempo loss with the bishop. We'll save a full tempo on this line: @@StartFEN@@rnbqkbnr/ppp2ppp/4p3/3p4/2PP4/8/PP2PPPP/RNBQKBNR w KQkq - 0 3@@EndFEN@@  3.cxd5  exd5  4.Nc3  c6  5.Bf4  Bd6  . This tempo is very relevant,  as White uses it to play Bd3 and Qc2, making our ...Bf5 move more difficult to realize. White has a small advantage in this line, while in our version, we easily play ...Bf5 soon and have no problems.  The conclusion is: of all the early exchange lines that aim for the Carlsbad, our version is the most comfortable for Black to handle. In many lines, Black even reaches a positive score.  Let's talk about plans and ideas for both sides now. We'll start with White's options. White has two main plans in the Carlsbad structure:  1. The Minority Attack on the queenside. White's idea is based on the advance of b4-b5, weakening Black's pawn structure. After b4-b5, White intends to capture c6 and create a backward pawn on the half-open c-file after Black recaptures with the pawn on b7. Alternatively, Black could take on b5 or decide to capture with a piece after White's capture on c6. In this case, the d5-pawn would be isolated.  We'll see that Black has good options against the minority attack in our version of the Carlsbad. One key argument in Black's favour is that usually we manage to trade the light-squared bishops. This exchange improves our option to answer b2-b4 with ...b7-b5! and stops the minority attack in its tracks.  This reply is less attractive with the light-squared bishops on the board. In this case, we'd be reluctant to place more pawns on light squares. After the trade, this is not a relevant point anymore. An additional idea after ...b7-b5 is the knight tour to c4, which is an attractive square. We'll examine these points in more detail later.  2. White plays for a central expansion with the moves f2-f3 and e2-e3-e4. After the trade on d5, White has an extra pawn in the center. Advancing in the center to gain more space certainly makes sense. This idea is often associated with the sixth World Champion Mikhail Botvinnik, and was later often adopted by his student, Garry Kasparov,  the 13th World Champion.  They used this plan in the line @@StartFEN@@rnbqkbnr/pppppppp/8/8/8/8/PPPPPPPP/RNBQKBNR w KQkq - 0 1@@EndFEN@@  1.d4  d5  2.c4  e6  3.Nc3  Nf6  4.cxd5  exd5  5.Bg5  c6  6.e3  Be7  7.Bd3  O-O  8.Qc2  Nbd7  9.Nge2  Re8  10.O-O  Nf8  11.f3  . A key issue for Black in this line is the lack of space. Black still has all the minor pieces on the board.  White's expansion with f3 and e4, possibly even e4-e5 next, gains a lot of ground, and Black often does not have enough space for the pieces.  In our version of the Carlsbad, this is usually not the case, as we quickly gain active positions for the bishops @@StartBracket@@compared to the bishops in the Botvinnik/Kasparov line@@EndBracket@@ and often trade them quickly @@StartBracket@@...Bd6 in response to Bf4 or ... Bf5 against a bishop on d3@@EndBracket@@.  What about Black's ideas? Our play depends to some extent on White's choice of plan. In some cases, correctly answering White's approach is perfectly fine to equalize and gain slightly better chances. This is often the case if we manage to answer the 'Minority Attack' with ...b7-b5, for example. A general idea for Black is to play for an attack on the kingside.  We can often make good use of the e4-square with a knight, supported by piece play and sometimes the advance of pawns. Pushing f5-f4 is our version of the 'Minority Attack', just on the other side of the board. Another common idea is to use a rook on the sixth rank @@StartBracket@@...Re8-e6-g6 or h6@@EndBracket@@.  We'd also like to mention that the square d6 is often an excellent spot for a knight. On d6, it has a very versatile role. It helps to address a possible White 'Minority Attack', maybe stopping it altogether or allowing ...Nc4 at an opportune moment. At the same time, it is ready to switch to the kingside @@StartBracket@@e4 and f5@@EndBracket@@. This also explains why we frequently develop our knight to e7 early on. The knight supports ...Bf5 in many cases, but it is also ready to be transferred to the ideal d6-square via f5 or c8.  Let's return to concrete moves now. What  does White play after @@StartFEN@@rnbqkbnr/pp3ppp/2p1p3/3P4/3P4/2N5/PP2PPPP/R1BQKBNR b KQkq - 0 4@@EndFEN@@  4...exd5?  They usually continue with a combination of the moves Bf4, Nf3, or Qc2. We suggest answering with ...Bd6 in all cases, making it easier to remember.  We'll have a look @@StartFEN@@rnbqkbnr/pp3ppp/2p5/3p4/3P4/2N5/PP2PPPP/R1BQKBNR w KQkq - 0 5@@EndFEN@@  5.Qc2  Bd6  and  5.Bf4  Bd6  , showing some typical ideas. }
5. Qc2
{ An interesting move order − White stops ...Bf5 and hopes for  5...Nf6  6.Bg5  , but we have better options. }
5... Bd6 { We not only develop our bishop but at the same prevent Bf4. } 6. Nf3
{ A logical choice. White is unable to play Bf4, so Bg5 is prepared. } 6... h6
{ Again pointing at the c1-bishop: how is this piece being developed now? We like  6...h6  , as it poses more problems, but there is a fine alternative in  6...Ne7  .  Black prepares ...Bf5 and follows a similar concept as in the  line @@StartFEN@@rnbqkbnr/pp3ppp/2p5/3p4/3P4/2N5/PP2PPPP/R1BQKBNR w KQkq - 0 5@@EndFEN@@  5.Nf3  Bd6  6.Bg5  Ne7  . }
7. e4
{ This looks like the most exciting try for White. Moves like  7.e3  or  7.g3  aren't challenging and are easily met with simple development  like ...Nf6, ...Bd6, and ...O-O. }
7... dxe4 8. Nxe4 Nf6
{ This looks better than  8...Bb4+  .  We don't mind the capture on d6, as we retain excellent control of the light squares in exchange for the bishop pair. It's interesting to compare this approach to the following  line: @@StartFEN@@rnbqkbnr/pppppppp/8/8/8/8/PPPPPPPP/RNBQKBNR w KQkq - 0 1@@EndFEN@@  1.e4  c6  2.d4  d5  3.exd5  cxd5  4.Bd3  Nc6  5.c3  Nf6  6.h3  e5  7.dxe5  Nxe5  8.Nf3  , which leads to equal chances. White has the extra  move Qc2 in our version, which is not particularly useful, as we will see. }
9. Nxd6+ Qxd6 10. h3
{ Not exactly a dynamic move, but White needs to worry about ...Bg4 ideas. Black is clearly in good shape after  10.Bd3  Bg4  . }
10... O-O 11. Be2 Re8
{ Or  11...Be6  , which is just as good. We like Black's position, as we have a good grip on the light squares, and White does not have much dynamic play. However, White has the bishop pair, which is enough to have equal chances.  After  11...Re8  ,  we'll continue with ...Be6 and ...Nbd7. After these natural moves, it's interesting to decide between playing ...Nd5 or ...Bd5. Placing the bishop on d5 might be a good idea, as a later ...Nd7-f8-e6 could nicely increase the pressure on the IQP. }
*

[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "Quickstarter Guide − Stonewall & Triangle Sidelines"]
[Black "Triangle Sidelines 3.Nc3 c6 4.cxd5 #2"]
[Result "*"]

1. d4 d5 2. c4 e6
{ After  2...e6  , White's most popular and best moves are the two natural knight jumps,  3.Nc3  and  3.Nf3  . Even if White intends to avoid the most critical paths @@StartBracket@@Noteboom/Marshall Gambit@@EndBracket@@, they usually start with a knight move. Playing one of the knights makes a lot of sense.  They are well-positioned on c3/f3 and White does not yet determine the pawn structure.  This leads us to possible White alternatives to  3.Nf3  or  3.Nc3  − let's have a look.   A@@EndBracket@@  3.cxd5  exd5  White  immediately exchanges on d5, aiming for the famous 'Carlsbad Structure' that arises after our natural recapture. If White intends to go for this pawn structure, they usually play 3.Nc3 first, and only trade on move four. We'll examine this version of the Carlsbad in the Quickstarter, as it is the most frequently seen move order. The trade on move three has no independent value, as playing the move pair Nc3 and ...c6 is very natural and will happen rather sooner than later.   B@@EndBracket@@  3.e3  c6  White covers the c4-pawn but commits to e3 relatively early. If White intends to play with e3, they usually decide to play lines  like @@StartFEN@@rnbqkbnr/ppp2ppp/4p3/3p4/2PP4/8/PP2PPPP/RNBQKBNR w KQkq - 0 3@@EndFEN@@  3.Nc3  c6  4.e3  or @@StartFEN@@rnbqkbnr/ppp2ppp/4p3/3p4/2PP4/8/PP2PPPP/RNBQKBNR w KQkq - 0 3@@EndFEN@@  3.Nf3  c6  4.e3  . Now, after @@StartFEN@@rnbqkbnr/ppp2ppp/4p3/3p4/2PP4/8/PP2PPPP/RNBQKBNR w KQkq - 0 3@@EndFEN@@  3.e3  c6  , White will likely play a knight  to c3 or f3, transposing to these mentioned lines.   C@@EndBracket@@  3.g3  dxc4  . The move 3.g3 is similar to the line @@StartFEN@@rnbqkbnr/ppp2ppp/4p3/3p4/2PP4/8/PP2PPPP/RNBQKBNR w KQkq - 0 3@@EndFEN@@  3.Nf3  c6  4.g3  , when we suggest playing  4...dxc4  .  Against 3.g3, the capture on c4 is a fine solution, as well.  After @@StartFEN@@rnbqkbnr/ppp2ppp/4p3/3p4/2PP4/8/PP2PPPP/RNBQKBNR w KQkq - 0 3@@EndFEN@@  3.g3  dxc4  4.Bg2  c6  5.Nf3  b5  we have transposed to the main line of the mentioned @@StartFEN@@rnbqkbnr/ppp2ppp/4p3/3p4/2PP4/8/PP2PPPP/RNBQKBNR w KQkq - 0 3@@EndFEN@@  3.Nf3  c6  4.g3  variation @@StartBracket@@The Catalan Triangle@@EndBracket@@.   D@@EndBracket@@  3.Bf4?!  dxc4!  is very similar @@StartFEN@@rnbqkbnr/ppp2ppp/4p3/3p4/2PP4/8/PP2PPPP/RNBQKBNR w KQkq - 0 3@@EndFEN@@ to  3.Nc3  c6  4.Bf4?!  dxc4!  , which we examine in this Quickstarter Guide. A transposition to this line is very likely, as a sequence like @@StartFEN@@rnbqkbnr/ppp2ppp/4p3/8/2pP1B2/8/PP2PPPP/RN1QKBNR w KQkq - 0 4@@EndFEN@@  4.e3  b5  5.a4  c6  6.Nc3  Qb6  is very natural.   E@@EndBracket@@  3.c5?  is just a mistake. After  3...b6  Black is already much better, as  4.b4  a5  fails for White. The queenside is falling apart. As you see, the 'non-knight' moves are at best a transposition and therefore don't merit any detailed coverage here. }
3. Nc3 c6
{ The starting position of the Triangle. Now White's main options are covered in other chapters:  A@@EndBracket@@  4.e4  − The Marshall Gambit.   B@@EndBracket@@  4.Nf3  dxc4  − The Noteboom.   C@@EndBracket@@  4.e3  − We'll answer in Stonewall style with  4...f5  .   The most important option that we'll examine is  4.cxd5  exd5  , leading to a Carlsbad pawn structure. You'll frequently meet this variation, as many opponents prefer this simple but objectively toothless exchange. The second move that we'll examine is  4.Bf4  , which is dubious for White but requires a precise reply. }
4. cxd5
{ White captures on d5 and changes the pawn structure. We'll talk about this more after our natural reply. }
4... exd5
{ This pawn formation, characterized by White's trade of the c-pawn for the e-pawn, is a very regular scenario in various Queen's Gambit lines. We may face the exchange on d5 after @@StartFEN@@rnbqkbnr/pppppppp/8/8/8/8/PPPPPPPP/RNBQKBNR w KQkq - 0 1@@EndFEN@@  1.d4  d5  2.c4  e6  3.cxd5  exd5  , or after @@StartFEN@@rnbqkbnr/ppp2ppp/4p3/3p4/2PP4/8/PP2PPPP/RNBQKBNR w KQkq - 0 3@@EndFEN@@  3.Nc3  c6  4.cxd5  / @@StartFEN@@rnbqkbnr/ppp2ppp/4p3/3p4/2PP4/8/PP2PPPP/RNBQKBNR w KQkq - 0 3@@EndFEN@@  3.Nf3  c6  4.cxd5  .  We will reach the same positions because after @@StartFEN@@rnbqkbnr/ppp2ppp/4p3/3p4/2PP4/8/PP2PPPP/RNBQKBNR w KQkq - 0 3@@EndFEN@@  3.cxd5  exd5  , White has nothing better than  4.Nc3  or  4.Nf3  when, in both cases,  4...c6  is the best move and our suggested reply.   In the Carlsbad structure, Black's ideal development scheme involves playing the bishops to d6 and f5, going for the most active squares possible. This setup can only be reached if you play ...c6 first. Black needs to cover d5, to allow ...Bd6, and also prepares ...Bf5.  Without the move ...c6, the reply Qb3 is often a problem, hitting d5 and b7 simultaneously. Once ...c6 is on the board, the move ...Bf5 is easier to play, as Qb3 can quickly be answered with ...Qb6.  It is helpful to compare our specific version of the exchange with two similar lines.  A@@EndBracket@@ @@StartFEN@@rnbqkbnr/pppppppp/8/8/8/8/PPPPPPPP/RNBQKBNR w KQkq - 0 1@@EndFEN@@  1.d4  d5  2.c4  e6  3.cxd5  exd5  4.Nc3  c6  or @@StartFEN@@rnbqkbnr/ppp2ppp/4p3/3p4/2PP4/8/PP2PPPP/RNBQKBNR w KQkq - 0 3@@EndFEN@@  3.Nc3  c6  4.cxd5  exd5  .  B@@EndBracket@@ @@StartFEN@@rnbqkbnr/pppppppp/8/8/8/8/PPPPPPPP/RNBQKBNR w KQkq - 0 1@@EndFEN@@  1.d4  d5  2.c4  e6  3.Nc3  Nf6  4.cxd5  exd5  .  C@@EndBracket@@ @@StartFEN@@rnbqkbnr/pppppppp/8/8/8/8/PPPPPPPP/RNBQKBNR w KQkq - 0 1@@EndFEN@@  1.d4  d5  2.c4  e6  3.Nc3  Be7  4.cxd5  exd5  .  While lines B and C are considered main lines and good tries for an advantage, line A @@StartBracket@@our version@@EndBracket@@ is not. Why? In line B, White continues with @@StartFEN@@rnbqkb1r/ppp2ppp/5n2/3p4/3P4/2N5/PP2PPPP/R1BQKBNR w KQkq - 0 5@@EndFEN@@  5.Bg5  , pinning the knight @@StartBracket@@not possible in A@@EndBracket@@.  As mentioned, Black would like to employ an active piece setup with ...Bd6 and ...Bf5.  It turns out that it is impossible to achieve both moves under favorable circumstances. If Black  decides to play  5...Be7  to break the pin,  the ...Bd6-formation is off.  So  5...c6  is the best try to shoot for it. After  6.e3  Bd6  7.Bd3  ,  you won't manage ...Bf5, though. You could start  with @@StartFEN@@rnbqkb1r/pp3ppp/2p2n2/3p2B1/3P4/2N1P3/PP3PPP/R2QKBNR b KQkq - 0 6@@EndFEN@@  6...Bf5  , but this is met with the annoying move  7.Qf3!  when Black needs to accept a doubled f-pawn.  These lines are not entirely bad for Black, but they show that reaching the optimal/most active setup is not possible against best play.  In line C,  Black has already played the bishop to e7 and avoided the move ...Nf6. This way, the pin on the knight is not possible, but playing ...Be7 is not ideal if you'd like to place the bishop on d6.  One main continuation in line C  is: @@StartFEN@@rnbqk1nr/ppp1bppp/8/3p4/3P4/2N5/PP2PPPP/R1BQKBNR w KQkq - 0 5@@EndFEN@@  5.Bf4  c6  6.e3  Bd6  , when Black accepts a tempo loss with the bishop. We'll save a full tempo on this line: @@StartFEN@@rnbqkbnr/ppp2ppp/4p3/3p4/2PP4/8/PP2PPPP/RNBQKBNR w KQkq - 0 3@@EndFEN@@  3.cxd5  exd5  4.Nc3  c6  5.Bf4  Bd6  . This tempo is very relevant,  as White uses it to play Bd3 and Qc2, making our ...Bf5 move more difficult to realize. White has a small advantage in this line, while in our version, we easily play ...Bf5 soon and have no problems.  The conclusion is: of all the early exchange lines that aim for the Carlsbad, our version is the most comfortable for Black to handle. In many lines, Black even reaches a positive score.  Let's talk about plans and ideas for both sides now. We'll start with White's options. White has two main plans in the Carlsbad structure:  1. The Minority Attack on the queenside. White's idea is based on the advance of b4-b5, weakening Black's pawn structure. After b4-b5, White intends to capture c6 and create a backward pawn on the half-open c-file after Black recaptures with the pawn on b7. Alternatively, Black could take on b5 or decide to capture with a piece after White's capture on c6. In this case, the d5-pawn would be isolated.  We'll see that Black has good options against the minority attack in our version of the Carlsbad. One key argument in Black's favour is that usually we manage to trade the light-squared bishops. This exchange improves our option to answer b2-b4 with ...b7-b5! and stops the minority attack in its tracks.  This reply is less attractive with the light-squared bishops on the board. In this case, we'd be reluctant to place more pawns on light squares. After the trade, this is not a relevant point anymore. An additional idea after ...b7-b5 is the knight tour to c4, which is an attractive square. We'll examine these points in more detail later.  2. White plays for a central expansion with the moves f2-f3 and e2-e3-e4. After the trade on d5, White has an extra pawn in the center. Advancing in the center to gain more space certainly makes sense. This idea is often associated with the sixth World Champion Mikhail Botvinnik, and was later often adopted by his student, Garry Kasparov,  the 13th World Champion.  They used this plan in the line @@StartFEN@@rnbqkbnr/pppppppp/8/8/8/8/PPPPPPPP/RNBQKBNR w KQkq - 0 1@@EndFEN@@  1.d4  d5  2.c4  e6  3.Nc3  Nf6  4.cxd5  exd5  5.Bg5  c6  6.e3  Be7  7.Bd3  O-O  8.Qc2  Nbd7  9.Nge2  Re8  10.O-O  Nf8  11.f3  . A key issue for Black in this line is the lack of space. Black still has all the minor pieces on the board.  White's expansion with f3 and e4, possibly even e4-e5 next, gains a lot of ground, and Black often does not have enough space for the pieces.  In our version of the Carlsbad, this is usually not the case, as we quickly gain active positions for the bishops @@StartBracket@@compared to the bishops in the Botvinnik/Kasparov line@@EndBracket@@ and often trade them quickly @@StartBracket@@...Bd6 in response to Bf4 or ... Bf5 against a bishop on d3@@EndBracket@@.  What about Black's ideas? Our play depends to some extent on White's choice of plan. In some cases, correctly answering White's approach is perfectly fine to equalize and gain slightly better chances. This is often the case if we manage to answer the 'Minority Attack' with ...b7-b5, for example. A general idea for Black is to play for an attack on the kingside.  We can often make good use of the e4-square with a knight, supported by piece play and sometimes the advance of pawns. Pushing f5-f4 is our version of the 'Minority Attack', just on the other side of the board. Another common idea is to use a rook on the sixth rank @@StartBracket@@...Re8-e6-g6 or h6@@EndBracket@@.  We'd also like to mention that the square d6 is often an excellent spot for a knight. On d6, it has a very versatile role. It helps to address a possible White 'Minority Attack', maybe stopping it altogether or allowing ...Nc4 at an opportune moment. At the same time, it is ready to switch to the kingside @@StartBracket@@e4 and f5@@EndBracket@@. This also explains why we frequently develop our knight to e7 early on. The knight supports ...Bf5 in many cases, but it is also ready to be transferred to the ideal d6-square via f5 or c8.  Let's return to concrete moves now. What  does White play after @@StartFEN@@rnbqkbnr/pp3ppp/2p1p3/3P4/3P4/2N5/PP2PPPP/R1BQKBNR b KQkq - 0 4@@EndFEN@@  4...exd5?  They usually continue with a combination of the moves Bf4, Nf3, or Qc2. We suggest answering with ...Bd6 in all cases, making it easier to remember.  We'll have a look @@StartFEN@@rnbqkbnr/pp3ppp/2p5/3p4/3P4/2N5/PP2PPPP/R1BQKBNR w KQkq - 0 5@@EndFEN@@  5.Qc2  Bd6  and  5.Bf4  Bd6  , showing some typical ideas. }
5. Bf4
{ White develops the bishop first, keeping some flexibility in regards to the kingside setup. }
5... Bd6
{ We suggest immediately offering the bishop trade with  5...Bd6  . The other move fitting to our concept would be  5...Bf5  . This is a popular option for Black and can't be wrong. However, we found the engine suggestion  6.f3!?  to be surprisingly tricky to handle for Black. This move is extremely rare, but it could be something a well-prepared opponent has in mind.  Long story short: we play 5...Bd6, as we usually do − we play the same move against @@StartFEN@@rnbqkbnr/pp3ppp/2p5/3p4/3P4/2N5/PP2PPPP/R1BQKBNR w KQkq - 0 5@@EndFEN@@  5.Qc2  and  5.Nf3  too. }
6. Bxd6
{ This simple move looks best for White. White can try  6.Bg3  , but  6...Ne7  ,  intending ...Nf5, is a good reply. We might even manage to get the bishop pair if White allows ...Nf5xg3. }
6... Qxd6 7. e3
{ White's usual choice.  7.Qc2  can also be played, but after  7...Ne7  ,  we'll manage ...Bf5 anyway. }
7... Bf5
{ The natural move. There is nothing wrong with  7...Ne7  8.Bd3  Bf5  , either. Now, after @@StartFEN@@rnb1k1nr/pp3ppp/2pq4/3p4/3P4/2N1P3/PP3PPP/R2QKBNR b KQkq - 0 7@@EndFEN@@  7...Bf5  , White plays the harmless  8.Bd3  most of the time. A bit more interesting is  8.Nge2  , but it does not promise White an advantage either. }
8. Bd3
{ Or  8.Nge2  , when  8...Ne7  is again a good response. After  9.Ng3  Bg6  ,  our bishop and knight control the f5-square, which takes the sting out of the Nge2-plan. The resulting positions are similar to 8.Bd3 and share the same general ideas. }
8... Bxd3 { Or  8...Ne7  , which is just as good. } 9. Qxd3 Ne7
{ Placing the knight on e7 looks very flexible. In some cases, we can still play the f-pawn if White continues with an f3&e4 idea. In many cases, the squares d6 or b6 are excellent for a knight, looking at important squares like c4 or e4. From e7, our knight has the route via c8 to d6 or b6, reaching these good posts quickly. }
10. Nf3
{ Or  10.Nge2  O-O  11.O-O  Nd7  12.f3  f5!  showing one idea of the knight placement on e7. }
10... Nd7 { Castling first is also fine, of course. } 11. O-O O-O 12. Rab1
{ White prepares the move b2-b4, starting the 'Minority Attack' on the queenside. In White's ideal world, they manage b2-b4-b5 and trade on c6, when Black would have an inferior pawn structure.   To illustrate what to avoid, please see the following move sequence. It features bad play on Black's part, basically ignoring White's intentions completely:  12...Rfe8  13.b4  a6  14.a4  Nf6  15.b5  axb5  16.axb5  Ng6  17.bxc6  bxc6  . This is White's dream scenario: the c-pawn is weak and an easy target, while Black has no counterplay.   How to counter White's 'Minority Attack'? The key idea is to stop the further advance of the b-pawn by playing ...b5. In such a pawn structure, the knight on e7 is ready to be improved via c8-b6-c4, reaching a dream square. }
12... a5
{ Stopping b4 for the moment, so White needs to invest a bit of time for the move a3. }
13. a3 Rfe8
{ A good waiting move. White now has a hard time making any headway, as the planned advance b4 leads nowhere. }
14. b4
{ White should probably play a slow waiting move instead. After such a move, like  14.h3  , we can play  14...Nc8  ,  heading towards b6. With a knight on b6, the advance b4 would also be difficult to achieve, as we'd have ...Nc4 in reply. }
14... b5
{ That's the key idea for Black. We already have better chances because of ...Nb6-c4 next. White has some weaknesses on the queenside and nothing to show for it. }
*

