 Black's light-squared bishop is passive for the moment. Of course,  2...e6  is an excellent move and our  repertoire choice, but the c8-bishop is a cause for concern for the foreseeable future.   Now, consider what happens if White does not play @@StartFEN@@rnbqkbnr/ppp1pppp/8/3p4/3P4/8/PPP1PPPP/RNBQKBNR w KQkq - 0 2@@EndFEN@@  2.c4  but instead goes for a slower move. We wondered if it is possible to 'punish' White for not playing  2.c4  by  developing our c8-bishop to f5 on move two, and only then playing the move ...e6.  We examined  2.Nf3  Bf5  , and @@StartFEN@@rnbqkbnr/ppp1pppp/8/3p4/3P4/8/PPP1PPPP/RNBQKBNR w KQkq - 0 2@@EndFEN@@  2.Bf4  Bf5  , and concluded that Black's concept is perfectly viable. These lines have the practical advantage of being relatively unexplored and, therefore, will likely not be prepared as thoroughly by your opponents. }
2. Nf3
{ Developing the knight is a popular move for White. It is a flexible choice. White may still play c2-c4 on the next move, entering a Queen's Gambit, or opt for a slower development. As already discussed, we answer  2.Nf3  with  2...Bf5  , which leads to less explored and interesting positions. }
2... Bf5
{ After  2...Bf5  , the only critical move must be  3.c4  , which we will focus on. White's calmer alternatives on move three,  3.g3  and  3.e3  , are rather harmless or will transpose to lines that we examine via  3.c4  . An important option for White is the move  3.Bf4  , but  3...e6  4.e3  immediately leads to a position that is covered via 2.Bf4 in this Quickstarter Guide. }
3. c4
{ White's most principled and best move. It puts pressure on d5 and prepares the move Qb3 in many situations, looking at the tender b7-pawn. }
3... e6
{ We always play  3...e6  first in this line, preparing the kingside development. The move  3...c6?  is worse, as  4.cxd5  cxd5  5.Qb3  is awkward for Black. Black's resources are much better after the better choice, @@StartFEN@@rn1qkbnr/ppp1pppp/8/3p1b2/2PP4/5N2/PP2PPPP/RNBQKB1R b KQkq - 0 3@@EndFEN@@  3...e6  . In some cases,  we might be able to play ...c7-c5, fighting for the center with the c-pawn. Another common scenario is answering Qb3 with ...Nb8-c6, which leads to sharp play. Let's have a look at White's options after  3...e6  . By far, the most popular are A and B, which we will focus on in the Quickstarter.  A@@EndBracket@@ White's main move is  4.Nc3  , when we suggest  4...Nf6!  This move is much better than the old-fashioned  4...c6?!  when Black's position is too passive. We cover this main line in a dedicated chapter of the course and examine it in this Quickstarter.   B@@EndBracket@@ A critical option for White is  4.Qb3  , which immediately puts  pressure on b7. We have the strong reply  4...Nc6!  , which leads to sharp play that we'll examine here too.   C@@EndBracket@@ White has the quiet move  4.e3  , preparing kingside development and covering the c-pawn. We suggest  4...c6  , intending to play  5.Bd3  Bxd3  6.Qxd3  f5!?  , and reach a Stonewall formation without the potential worry of a bad  bishop on c8.   D@@EndBracket@@ The move  4.g3  is rare at this particular point, but White sometimes  combines the moves d4, c4, Nf3, and g3 in other move orders,  like @@StartFEN@@rnbqkbnr/pppppppp/8/8/8/8/PPPPPPPP/RNBQKBNR w KQkq - 0 1@@EndFEN@@  1.d4  d5  2.g3  or @@StartFEN@@rnbqkbnr/pppppppp/8/8/8/8/PPPPPPPP/RNBQKBNR w KQkq - 0 1@@EndFEN@@  1.d4  d5  2.Nf3  Bf5  3.g3  . We suggest a setup  with ...Nf6, ...c6, and ...h6 against it.   E@@EndBracket@@ The exchange  4.cxd5  exd5  , leading to a Carlsbad pawn structure. We'll examine the Carlsbad structure in the Quickstarter via the move order @@StartFEN@@rn1qkbnr/ppp2ppp/4p3/3p1b2/2PP4/5N2/PP2PPPP/RNBQKB1R w KQkq - 0 4@@EndFEN@@  4.Nc3  Nf6  5.cxd5  exd5  , which is quite similar.  In both cases, it's crucial to answer Qb3 with the active ...Nc6, as usual. }
4. Nc3
{ By far, White's most popular move. Developing the knight while increasing the pressure on d5 is undoubtedly a natural choice. }
4... Nf6
{ The exclamation mark is a bit strong, but it's essential to play this move instead of the old-fashioned one  4...c6  . The move  4...Nf6  is more flexible and allows much sharper play. The critical difference is that after  4...c6  , White is better in the line  5.Qb3  Qb6  6.c5  Qc7  7.Bf4!  Qc8  8.Nh4  Bg6  9.Nxg6  hxg6  10.e4  , which we avoid by playing 4...Nf6.   After  4...Nf6  , White can still play  5.Qb3  , but now we have the dynamic reply  5...Nc6!  , which is much more active. After our move @@StartFEN@@rn1qkbnr/ppp2ppp/4p3/3p1b2/2PP4/2N2N2/PP2PPPP/R1BQKB1R b KQkq - 1 4@@EndFEN@@  4...Nf6  , White has many options. Let's make an overview.  A@@EndBracket@@  5.Qb3  ,  attacking b7, always needs to be checked. We answer, as usual, with 5...Nc6, defending actively.   B@@EndBracket@@  5.Bg5  is the most popular line, pinning the knight. We suggest  5...c6  , which is a much better moment for this move than one move earlier.   C@@EndBracket@@  5.Nh4  attacks the bishop and is considered a critical try. We advise playing  5...Bg6  , which gives Black fair chances. As 5.Nh4 is unlikely to happen in your games, we decided not to include it in the Quickstarter. It is analyzed in detail in the dedicated chapter on the 2.Nf3 Bf5 main line.   D@@EndBracket@@  5.cxd5  exd5  leads to a harmless version of a Carlsbad structure.   E@@EndBracket@@  5.e3  is a quiet continuation. Our suggestion against it is  5...Bb4  , again going for the most active choice.   F@@EndBracket@@  5.Bf4  is a healthy development move but does not pressure Black. After  5...Bb4  , we transpose to a line of the London System that we examine via a different move order. Please refer to the dedicated chapter on the London for more information.   G@@EndBracket@@  5.g3  h6!  immediately transposes to the line @@StartFEN@@rn1qkbnr/ppp2ppp/4p3/3p1b2/2PP4/5N2/PP2PPPP/RNBQKB1R w KQkq - 0 4@@EndFEN@@  4.g3  Nf6  5.Nc3  h6  ,  with ...c6 to follow soon. }
5. e3
{ White covers the c4-pawn but locks in the c1-bishop. This is a solid line for White that looks similar to 4.e3, but there is a key difference.   After @@StartFEN@@rnbqkbnr/pppppppp/8/8/8/8/PPPPPPPP/RNBQKBNR w KQkq - 0 1@@EndFEN@@  1.d4  d5  2.Nf3  Bf5  3.c4  e6  4.e3  , we suggest  4...c6  ,  when White can't play Nh4, because our queen still has an eye on this square.   Now, after @@StartFEN@@rn1qkbnr/ppp2ppp/4p3/3p1b2/2PP4/5N2/PP2PPPP/RNBQKB1R w KQkq - 0 4@@EndFEN@@  4.Nc3  Nf6  5.e3  , the situation is different, as  5...c6  6.Nh4  is possible. This would not be terrible at all because we'd just transpose to a line of the Slav Defense that usually arises after @@StartFEN@@rnbqkbnr/pppppppp/8/8/8/8/PPPPPPPP/RNBQKBNR w KQkq - 0 1@@EndFEN@@  1.d4  d5  2.c4  c6  3.Nf3  Nf6  4.e3  Bf5  5.Nc3  e6  6.Nh4  , when Black has good chances to equalize. We'd still like to suggest a different approach that is more dynamic and in the spirit of our line. }
5... Bb4
{ This move is a frequent guest in the current chapter. Black plays in the style of the Nimzo-Indian or the Ragozin Defense of the Queen's Gambit, both featuring the pinning move ...Bb4.   Now, after  5...Bb4  , White usually chooses between  6.Qb3  ,  6.Qa4  or  6.Bd2  , which is the most frequently played but rather harmless move. The whole 5...Bb4 is still rather unexplored and offers many possibilities for both sides. In the Quickstarter, we'll have a look at  6.Qa4+  Nc6  7.Ne5  , which is White's most aggressive idea. }
6. Qa4+
{ The critical move. White forces our knight to c6 and may continue with a quick Ne5, applying more pressure on the knight. The alternatives, like  6.Bd2  O-O  7.Qb3  c5!?  or @@StartFEN@@rn1qk2r/ppp2ppp/4pn2/3p1b2/1bPP4/2N1PN2/PP3PPP/R1BQKB1R w KQkq - 1 6@@EndFEN@@  6.Qb3  Nc6  , don't look scary. }
6... Nc6 7. Ne5
{ The logical follow-up to the queen check. White puts more pressure on our knight. }
7... O-O
{ It's also possible to play  7...Bxc3+  8.bxc3  O-O  , when  9.Nxc6  bxc6  leads to the same position that we will examine in a minute. }
8. Nxc6 Bxc3+ 9. bxc3 bxc6
{ White has managed to weaken our pawn structure and can now capture the c6-pawn if desired. White is far behind in development, though, which nicely balances the chances. We want to open the game as fast as possible, trying to generate an attack against White's still uncastled king.   Now we need to check the pawn grab  10.Qxc6  @@StartBracket@@very risky and dubious@@EndBracket@@ and the better move,  10.f3  , which takes control  of the vital e4-square. We don't need to worry about  10.Ba3?!  , as  10...Re8  is a valuable move  for us @@StartBracket@@...e5 is the idea@@EndBracket@@, while the a3-bishop is severely misplaced on a3. }
10. Qxc6
{ White grabs the pawn most of the time, but it is a dubious decision. We get too much of an attack for the small material deficit. It looks like White should prefer  10.f3  , which takes control  of the e4-square but still does not contribute to White's piece development.  We suggest  10...e5!  in reply, opening up the position immediately. It leads to fun complications, for example after  11.dxe5  Nd7  12.cxd5  cxd5  13.Qf4  Be6  , when we'll continue with ideas  like ...c5 and ...Qa5 and have excellent compensation for the pawn. }
10... Ne4
{ That's the best-attacking move, centralizing the knight. White can't attack it with  11.f3??  now, as  11...Qh4+  shows. }
11. cxd5 { White's almost universal choice here. } 11... exd5
{ Black's game is so easy to play from here on. We have ...Re8-e6 or ...Rb8-b6 ideas, gaining more time on the queen. To put it mildly, White's defensive task is unenviable. }
12. Be2
{ That's the only move that does not immediately lose@@StartBracket@@!@@EndBracket@@, according to Stockfish. We don't think it is necessary to check alternatives to  12.Be2  , as it's clear that our job is much simpler than White's. }
12... Re8
{ Here, the other obvious move,  12...Rb8  , is of about equal strength. Now White can't castle as @@StartFEN@@r2qr1k1/p1p2ppp/2Q5/3p1b2/3Pn3/2P1P3/P3BPPP/R1B1K2R w KQ - 2 13@@EndFEN@@  13.O-O?  Re6  already leads to a deadly attack on our opponent's king. }
13. c4
{ The best defense. As mentioned already,  13.O-O?  Re6  14.Qb5  Rg6  already starts a devastating attack on White's king. The point of @@StartFEN@@r2qr1k1/p1p2ppp/2Q5/3p1b2/3Pn3/2P1P3/P3BPPP/R1B1K2R w KQ - 2 13@@EndFEN@@  13.c4  is to answer  13...Re6??  with  14.Qxd5  . }
13... Bd7
{ A powerful and important move! The great point is that White now can't grab the d5-pawn. }
14. Qa6
{ The only move, as White can't take the pawn. After  14.Qxd5?  c6  15.Qh5  g6  16.Qh6  Qa5+  17.Kf1  Qc3  , Black is invading with decisive effect. }
14... Rb8
{ We activate our final piece and don't care about the a-pawn. Our attack is powerful, but it's tough to say how much of an advantage Black has. Clearly, we have all the fun! Stockfish now wants to continue with  15.Qxa7  Re6  16.Bf3  Ra8  17.Qb7  Bc6  18.Qb2  dxc4  , when we have a fantastic position for just an unimportant pawn. }
