[Result "*"]

1. d4 d5
{ In this Quickstarter chapter, we will examine White's most popular alternatives to the Queen's Gambit move,  2.c4  . If White decides to avoid this main path, the most important options are  2.Nf3  , which is a flexible development move, and  2.Bf4  , the London System.  In the Quickstarter, we will focus on these two moves and have a brief look at  2.Nc3  , which enjoys some popularity. White has some offbeat alternatives, but they don't pose a theoretical challenge or are dubious. Please refer to the dedicated chapter on 1.d4 d5 sidelines for more information about White's 'odds and ends'.   Now let's examine our concept against  2.Nf3  and  2.Bf4  − we'll use a similar approach against both moves. Let's return to some opening basics to better understand our line of thinking. Our answer to the Queen's Gambit is the Triangle Variation, @@StartFEN@@rnbqkbnr/pppppppp/8/8/8/8/PPPPPPPP/RNBQKBNR w KQkq - 0 1@@EndFEN@@  1.d4  d5  2.c4  e6  3.Nc3  c6  or @@StartFEN@@rnbqkbnr/ppp2ppp/4p3/3p4/2PP4/8/PP2PPPP/RNBQKBNR w KQkq - 0 3@@EndFEN@@  3.Nf3  c6  , which is the namesake of the course.  However, White is not obliged to play @@StartFEN@@rnbqkbnr/ppp1pppp/8/3p4/3P4/8/PPP1PPPP/RNBQKBNR w KQkq - 0 2@@EndFEN@@  2.c4  but may opt for a different path. The two most important alternatives are the flexible  2.Nf3  and  2.Bf4  , the popular London System. Black has a range of possible replies to these moves.  We play the moves ...e6 and ...c6 @@StartBracket@@the Triangle@@EndBracket@@  against  2.c4  , so why not go for the same setup against White's arguably less aggressive options? We considered this approach but wondered if Black might have a more ambitious response.  Let's go back to the basic position after @@StartFEN@@rnbqkbnr/pppppppp/8/8/8/8/PPPPPPPP/RNBQKBNR w KQkq - 0 1@@EndFEN@@  1.d4  d5  2.c4  .  White threatens cxd5, so our options are limited if we want to keep the central pawn on d5. Black has to play  2...e6  or  2...c6  to accomplish this goal. After  2...e6  , Black's light-squared bishop is passive for the moment. Of course,  2...e6  is an excellent move and our  repertoire choice, but the c8-bishop is a cause for concern for the foreseeable future.   Now, consider what happens if White does not play @@StartFEN@@rnbqkbnr/ppp1pppp/8/3p4/3P4/8/PPP1PPPP/RNBQKBNR w KQkq - 0 2@@EndFEN@@  2.c4  but instead goes for a slower move. We wondered if it is possible to 'punish' White for not playing  2.c4  by  developing our c8-bishop to f5 on move two, and only then playing the move ...e6.  We examined  2.Nf3  Bf5  , and @@StartFEN@@rnbqkbnr/ppp1pppp/8/3p4/3P4/8/PPP1PPPP/RNBQKBNR w KQkq - 0 2@@EndFEN@@  2.Bf4  Bf5  , and concluded that Black's concept is perfectly viable. These lines have the practical advantage of being relatively unexplored and, therefore, will likely not be prepared as thoroughly by your opponents. }
2. Nf3
{ Developing the knight is a popular move for White. It is a flexible choice. White may still play c2-c4 on the next move, entering a Queen's Gambit, or opt for a slower development. As already discussed, we answer  2.Nf3  with  2...Bf5  , which leads to less explored and interesting positions. }
2... Bf5
{ After  2...Bf5  , the only critical move must be  3.c4  , which we will focus on. White's calmer alternatives on move three,  3.g3  and  3.e3  , are rather harmless or will transpose to lines that we examine via  3.c4  . An important option for White is the move  3.Bf4  , but  3...e6  4.e3  immediately leads to a position that is covered via 2.Bf4 in this Quickstarter Guide. }
3. c4
{ White's most principled and best move. It puts pressure on d5 and prepares the move Qb3 in many situations, looking at the tender b7-pawn. }
3... e6
{ We always play  3...e6  first in this line, preparing the kingside development. The move  3...c6?  is worse, as  4.cxd5  cxd5  5.Qb3  is awkward for Black. Black's resources are much better after the better choice, @@StartFEN@@rn1qkbnr/ppp1pppp/8/3p1b2/2PP4/5N2/PP2PPPP/RNBQKB1R b KQkq - 0 3@@EndFEN@@  3...e6  . In some cases,  we might be able to play ...c7-c5, fighting for the center with the c-pawn. Another common scenario is answering Qb3 with ...Nb8-c6, which leads to sharp play. Let's have a look at White's options after  3...e6  . By far, the most popular are A and B, which we will focus on in the Quickstarter.  A@@EndBracket@@ White's main move is  4.Nc3  , when we suggest  4...Nf6!  This move is much better than the old-fashioned  4...c6?!  when Black's position is too passive. We cover this main line in a dedicated chapter of the course and examine it in this Quickstarter.   B@@EndBracket@@ A critical option for White is  4.Qb3  , which immediately puts  pressure on b7. We have the strong reply  4...Nc6!  , which leads to sharp play that we'll examine here too.   C@@EndBracket@@ White has the quiet move  4.e3  , preparing kingside development and covering the c-pawn. We suggest  4...c6  , intending to play  5.Bd3  Bxd3  6.Qxd3  f5!?  , and reach a Stonewall formation without the potential worry of a bad  bishop on c8.   D@@EndBracket@@ The move  4.g3  is rare at this particular point, but White sometimes  combines the moves d4, c4, Nf3, and g3 in other move orders,  like @@StartFEN@@rnbqkbnr/pppppppp/8/8/8/8/PPPPPPPP/RNBQKBNR w KQkq - 0 1@@EndFEN@@  1.d4  d5  2.g3  or @@StartFEN@@rnbqkbnr/pppppppp/8/8/8/8/PPPPPPPP/RNBQKBNR w KQkq - 0 1@@EndFEN@@  1.d4  d5  2.Nf3  Bf5  3.g3  . We suggest a setup  with ...Nf6, ...c6, and ...h6 against it.   E@@EndBracket@@ The exchange  4.cxd5  exd5  , leading to a Carlsbad pawn structure. We'll examine the Carlsbad structure in the Quickstarter via the move order @@StartFEN@@rn1qkbnr/ppp2ppp/4p3/3p1b2/2PP4/5N2/PP2PPPP/RNBQKB1R w KQkq - 0 4@@EndFEN@@  4.Nc3  Nf6  5.cxd5  exd5  , which is quite similar.  In both cases, it's crucial to answer Qb3 with the active ...Nc6, as usual. }
4. Nc3
{ By far, White's most popular move. Developing the knight while increasing the pressure on d5 is undoubtedly a natural choice. }
4... Nf6
{ The exclamation mark is a bit strong, but it's essential to play this move instead of the old-fashioned one  4...c6  . The move  4...Nf6  is more flexible and allows much sharper play. The critical difference is that after  4...c6  , White is better in the line  5.Qb3  Qb6  6.c5  Qc7  7.Bf4!  Qc8  8.Nh4  Bg6  9.Nxg6  hxg6  10.e4  , which we avoid by playing 4...Nf6.   After  4...Nf6  , White can still play  5.Qb3  , but now we have the dynamic reply  5...Nc6!  , which is much more active. After our move @@StartFEN@@rn1qkbnr/ppp2ppp/4p3/3p1b2/2PP4/2N2N2/PP2PPPP/R1BQKB1R b KQkq - 1 4@@EndFEN@@  4...Nf6  , White has many options. Let's make an overview.  A@@EndBracket@@  5.Qb3  ,  attacking b7, always needs to be checked. We answer, as usual, with 5...Nc6, defending actively.   B@@EndBracket@@  5.Bg5  is the most popular line, pinning the knight. We suggest  5...c6  , which is a much better moment for this move than one move earlier.   C@@EndBracket@@  5.Nh4  attacks the bishop and is considered a critical try. We advise playing  5...Bg6  , which gives Black fair chances. As 5.Nh4 is unlikely to happen in your games, we decided not to include it in the Quickstarter. It is analyzed in detail in the dedicated chapter on the 2.Nf3 Bf5 main line.   D@@EndBracket@@  5.cxd5  exd5  leads to a harmless version of a Carlsbad structure.   E@@EndBracket@@  5.e3  is a quiet continuation. Our suggestion against it is  5...Bb4  , again going for the most active choice.   F@@EndBracket@@  5.Bf4  is a healthy development move but does not pressure Black. After  5...Bb4  , we transpose to a line of the London System that we examine via a different move order. Please refer to the dedicated chapter on the London for more information.   G@@EndBracket@@  5.g3  h6!  immediately transposes to the line @@StartFEN@@rn1qkbnr/ppp2ppp/4p3/3p1b2/2PP4/5N2/PP2PPPP/RNBQKB1R w KQkq - 0 4@@EndFEN@@  4.g3  Nf6  5.Nc3  h6  ,  with ...c6 to follow soon. }
5. cxd5 { White opts for the trade on d5, heading to a Carlsbad structure. }
5... exd5
{ After our natural reply, White has three moves worth checking. The first one is  6.Bf4  , when  6...c6  looks best, completing  the b7-c6-d5 pawn chain. We don't need to analyze this line here, as it leads to position types that we examine via the move  order @@StartFEN@@rnbqkbnr/pppppppp/8/8/8/8/PPPPPPPP/RNBQKBNR w KQkq - 0 1@@EndFEN@@  1.d4  d5  2.c4  e6  3.Nc3  c6  4.cxd5  exd5  .  If Black manages ...Bf5 in a Carlsbad structure, chances are even already.  A bit more interesting is @@StartFEN@@rn1qkb1r/ppp2ppp/5n2/3p1b2/3P4/2N2N2/PP2PPPP/R1BQKB1R w KQkq - 0 6@@EndFEN@@  6.Bg5  and, in particular,  6.Qb3  , which forces  6...Nc6  . We'll examine these moves now. }
6. Bg5 { Pinning the knight is a very natural move. } 6... c6
{ This looks the best. We lend additional protection to the d5-pawn and prepare the move ...Qb6 in reply to Qb3. The position we currently have on the board has been reached quite frequently in practice, because @@StartFEN@@rnbqkbnr/pppppppp/8/8/8/8/PPPPPPPP/RNBQKBNR w KQkq - 0 1@@EndFEN@@  1.d4  d5  2.c4  e6  3.Nf3  Nf6  4.Nc3  c6  5.cxd5  exd5  6.Bg5  Bf5  is a common move order to reach it. }
7. Qb3
{ The only interesting move for White. After  7.e3  Nbd7  8.Bd3  Bxd3  9.Qxd3  Bd6  , we'd reach a comfortable Carlsbad structure. We often reach this pawn formation via @@StartFEN@@rnbqkbnr/pppppppp/8/8/8/8/PPPPPPPP/RNBQKBNR w KQkq - 0 1@@EndFEN@@  1.d4  d5  2.c4  e6  3.Nc3  c6  4.cxd5  exd5  − please see the notes to this line for more information about the general strategy that we should employ.  In Carlsbad, knowing the ideas is more important than concrete moves. This is why we don't advise learning more moves by heart in the version here, after @@StartFEN@@rn1qkb1r/pp3ppp/2p2n2/3p1bB1/3P4/2N2N2/PP2PPPP/R2QKB1R w KQkq - 0 7@@EndFEN@@  7.e3  . The move  7.Qb3  is a different story,  though: White attacks b7, what to do? }
7... Qb6
{ We suggest playing this move, which is the main line and the simplest solution. Black has two interesting alternatives that are worth mentioning, though.  A@@EndBracket@@  7...Nbd7  offers the b-pawn. It looks like  8.Qxb7  Rb8  9.Qxc6  Rxb2  is fine for Black. A practical drawback is that  10.Bxf6  gxf6  11.Nxd5  Qa5+  12.Kd1  Bc2+  13.Kc1  Ba3  14.Qc8+  Qd8  15.Nc7+  Ke7  16.Nd5+  can lead to a draw in this line. White can also react with  8.e4!?  , when  8...Bxe4  9.Nxe4  Qe7  leads to a wild position.   B@@EndBracket@@  7...b5  was played multiple times by the ever-creative genius Evgeny Shveshnikov. White usually replies  8.e3  , when a sequence like  8...Nbd7  9.Rc1  Bd6  10.Be2  O-O  11.O-O  Qb8  is likely to happen. It looks interesting, as the c-pawn is backward, but this looks difficult to exploit. On the other hand, Black has some space on the queenside.  Stockfish evaluates  8.e3  as equal and suggest  8.a4  b4  9.e4!?  instead, which leads to crazy complications. After  9...dxe4  10.Ne5  Be6  11.Bc4  bxc3  12.Bxe6  fxe6  13.Qxe6+  Qe7  , White could force a draw with  14.Qc8  Qd8  15.Qe6+  , or continue with  15.Qb7  , which looks about equal. We don't think it's sensible to study these lines in detail, given that 7...Qb6 is a good solution for Black. Still, these alternatives are rather unexplored and could be fun to try. }
8. Bxf6
{ White should damage our pawn structure before we can play ...Nbd7. White sometimes takes on b6 first; we'll check this option on the next move. }
8... gxf6
{ It's possible to take on b3, of course. We suggest not taking just yet, as White might still capture on b6, which is very much welcome. Better seems to be  9.e3  , though. For more information, see the corresponding variation. }
9. Qxb6
{ The queen trade on b6 is a strategically dubious decision. We are happy about the open a-file and the doubled pawns, which allow a quick advance of the b6-pawn. It looks better for White to play  9.e3  Nd7  10.Be2  , when we should opt for  10...Qxb3  11.axb3  a6  , which leads to an endgame with about equal chances. }
9... axb6 10. e3 b5
{ We not only plan ...b5-b4, but ...Nd7-b6-c4 as well. Let's have a look at a possible sequence to illustrate these ideas. }
11. Kd2 { White prepares Bd3. } 11... b4
{ This gains a bit of time.  11...Nd7  12.Bd3  looks a bit easier for White to defend. }
12. Ne2 Nd7 13. Ng3 Be6 14. Bd3 Nb6
{ Black has the better chances already. We can also follow the idea of ...Nc8-d6, followed by ...f5 and ...Ne4. A long maneuver, but White is hard-pressed to come up with anything active. }
*

