{ The exclamation mark is a bit strong, but it's essential to play this move instead of the old-fashioned one  4...c6  . The move  4...Nf6  is more flexible and allows much sharper play. The critical difference is that after  4...c6  , White is better in the line  5.Qb3  Qb6  6.c5  Qc7  7.Bf4!  Qc8  8.Nh4  Bg6  9.Nxg6  hxg6  10.e4  , which we avoid by playing 4...Nf6.   After  4...Nf6  , White can still play  5.Qb3  , but now we have the dynamic reply  5...Nc6!  , which is much more active. After our move @@StartFEN@@rn1qkbnr/ppp2ppp/4p3/3p1b2/2PP4/2N2N2/PP2PPPP/R1BQKB1R b KQkq - 1 4@@EndFEN@@  4...Nf6  , White has many options. Let's make an overview.  A@@EndBracket@@  5.Qb3  ,  attacking b7, always needs to be checked. We answer, as usual, with 5...Nc6, defending actively.   B@@EndBracket@@  5.Bg5  is the most popular line, pinning the knight. We suggest  5...c6  , which is a much better moment for this move than one move earlier.   C@@EndBracket@@  5.Nh4  attacks the bishop and is considered a critical try. We advise playing  5...Bg6  , which gives Black fair chances. As 5.Nh4 is unlikely to happen in your games, we decided not to include it in the Quickstarter. It is analyzed in detail in the dedicated chapter on the 2.Nf3 Bf5 main line.   D@@EndBracket@@  5.cxd5  exd5  leads to a harmless version of a Carlsbad structure.   E@@EndBracket@@  5.e3  is a quiet continuation. Our suggestion against it is  5...Bb4  , again going for the most active choice.   F@@EndBracket@@  5.Bf4  is a healthy development move but does not pressure Black. After  5...Bb4  , we transpose to a line of the London System that we examine via a different move order. Please refer to the dedicated chapter on the London for more information.   G@@EndBracket@@  5.g3  h6!  immediately transposes to the line @@StartFEN@@rn1qkbnr/ppp2ppp/4p3/3p1b2/2PP4/5N2/PP2PPPP/RNBQKB1R w KQkq - 0 4@@EndFEN@@  4.g3  Nf6  5.Nc3  h6  ,  with ...c6 to follow soon. }
5. Bg5 { White's most popular move at this point, pinning our knight. } 5... c6
{ Here Black has two playable moves:  5...c6  and  5...Bb4  . Deciding between the two is not trivial, but  5...c6  looks slightly more reliable. The critical replies against  5...Bb4  are the lines  6.Qa4+  or  6.cxd5  exd5  7.Qa4+  , when White seems to keep a small edge.   Still, playing  5...Bb4  is certainly a good alternative if you are interested in expanding the repertoire. The move  5...c6  adds some stability to the center and prepares  the move ...Qb6 in response to White's Qb3 sortie.  An important point to recognize is that we only play ...c6 after White is committed to the move Bg5,  which is a difference to the line @@StartFEN@@rn1qkbnr/ppp2ppp/4p3/3p1b2/2PP4/2N2N2/PP2PPPP/R1BQKB1R b KQkq - 1 4@@EndFEN@@  4...c6?!  , when  5.Qb3  Qb6  6.c5  Qc7  7.Bf4!  is the critical reply. White can employ a similar idea after @@StartFEN@@rn1qkb1r/ppp2ppp/4pn2/3p1b2/2PP4/2N2N2/PP2PPPP/R1BQKB1R w KQkq - 2 5@@EndFEN@@  5.Bg5  c6  , but would lose a full tempo, as the bishop is  already on g5 − this is a substantial difference.  White has some choices after  5...c6  . Here is an overview:  A@@EndBracket@@  6.cxd5  exd5  leads to @@StartFEN@@rn1qkb1r/ppp2ppp/4pn2/3p1b2/2PP4/2N2N2/PP2PPPP/R1BQKB1R w KQkq - 2 5@@EndFEN@@  5.cxd5  exd5  6.Bg5  c6  .  B@@EndBracket@@ @@StartFEN@@rn1qkb1r/pp3ppp/2p1pn2/3p1bB1/2PP4/2N2N2/PP2PPPP/R2QKB1R w KQkq - 0 6@@EndFEN@@  6.e3  is the most frequently played move but rather harmless.  C@@EndBracket@@  6.Qb3  and  6.Nh4  are more concrete approaches and look like the most dangerous continuations. We have a look at  6.Qb3  in the Quickstarter, while  6.Nh4  Bg6  is examined more in the dedicated chapter. }
6. Qb3
{ Probably the move Qb3 is the most frequently played one in the whole chapter. White can go for it in countless cases. Here our reply has been prepared by ...c6. }
6... Qb6 7. c5
{ The logical and popular move. White plays in the same fashion after @@StartFEN@@rn1qkbnr/ppp2ppp/4p3/3p1b2/2PP4/2N2N2/PP2PPPP/R1BQKB1R b KQkq - 1 4@@EndFEN@@  4...c6?!  5.Qb3  Qb6  6.c5  , which is a better version for White as  6...Qc7  7.Bf4!  Qc8  8.Nh4  Bg6  9.Nxg6  hxg6  10.e4!  shows.  Instead of @@StartFEN@@rn2kb1r/pp3ppp/1qp1pn2/3p1bB1/2PP4/1QN2N2/PP2PPPP/R3KB1R w KQkq - 2 7@@EndFEN@@  7.c5  , White could also play  7.e3  Nbd7  , which we examine via the move order @@StartFEN@@rn1qkb1r/pp3ppp/2p1pn2/3p1bB1/2PP4/2N2N2/PP2PPPP/R2QKB1R w KQkq - 0 6@@EndFEN@@  6.e3  Nbd7  7.Qb3  Qb6  . }
7... Qc7 8. e3
{ White prepares the move Bf4, but it's possible to play it right away too.  8.Bf4  Qc8  9.e3  Nbd7  would lead to a position that we will examine shortly. White could also play @@StartFEN@@rnq1kb1r/pp3ppp/2p1pn2/2Pp1b2/3P1B2/1QN2N2/PP2PPPP/R3KB1R w KQkq - 3 9@@EndFEN@@  9.Nh4  Bg6  10.Nxg6  hxg6  11.e3  Nbd7  , again leading to a position that we'll reach via 8.e3 in a moment. }
8... Nbd7 9. Bf4
{ White may also start with  9.Nh4  Bg6  and then play  10.Bf4  Qc8  , leading to the same positions. }
9... Qc8 10. Nh4
{ White is after our strong bishop. We need to give up the pair of bishops, but in compensation, we gain some time and additional control of e5, which are key accomplishments for us. }
10... Bg6 11. Nxg6 hxg6
{ Black's position makes a solid impression. We have no weaknesses, and ...Be7-d8-c7 is a logical plan to challenge White's control of e5. We also have the idea ...b6, attacking White's pawn chain, but this is less of a priority. Let's continue with some moves to illustrate the bishop regrouping. }
12. h3 Be7
{ Here  12...e5!?  is a tactical alternative, as  13.dxe5  Nxc5  leads to interesting complications. We prefer the bishop maneuver, as we know it may prove useful in this structure in general. }
13. Be2 Bd8 14. Qc2 Bc7
{ We are ready for ...e5 now, and White can't stop it radically with the following line. }
15. Bxc7 Qxc7 16. f4 g5
{ A strong move, based on  17.fxg5?  Qg3+  , which is excellent for Black. } *

