1. d4 d5
{ In this Quickstarter chapter, we will examine White's most popular alternatives to the Queen's Gambit move,  2.c4  . If White decides to avoid this main path, the most important options are  2.Nf3  , which is a flexible development move, and  2.Bf4  , the London System.  In the Quickstarter, we will focus on these two moves and have a brief look at  2.Nc3  , which enjoys some popularity. White has some offbeat alternatives, but they don't pose a theoretical challenge or are dubious. Please refer to the dedicated chapter on 1.d4 d5 sidelines for more information about White's 'odds and ends'.   Now let's examine our concept against  2.Nf3  and  2.Bf4  − we'll use a similar approach against both moves. Let's return to some opening basics to better understand our line of thinking. Our answer to the Queen's Gambit is the Triangle Variation, @@StartFEN@@rnbqkbnr/pppppppp/8/8/8/8/PPPPPPPP/RNBQKBNR w KQkq - 0 1@@EndFEN@@  1.d4  d5  2.c4  e6  3.Nc3  c6  or @@StartFEN@@rnbqkbnr/ppp2ppp/4p3/3p4/2PP4/8/PP2PPPP/RNBQKBNR w KQkq - 0 3@@EndFEN@@  3.Nf3  c6  , which is the namesake of the course.  However, White is not obliged to play @@StartFEN@@rnbqkbnr/ppp1pppp/8/3p4/3P4/8/PPP1PPPP/RNBQKBNR w KQkq - 0 2@@EndFEN@@  2.c4  but may opt for a different path. The two most important alternatives are the flexible  2.Nf3  and  2.Bf4  , the popular London System. Black has a range of possible replies to these moves.  We play the moves ...e6 and ...c6 @@StartBracket@@the Triangle@@EndBracket@@  against  2.c4  , so why not go for the same setup against White's arguably less aggressive options? We considered this approach but wondered if Black might have a more ambitious response.  Let's go back to the basic position after @@StartFEN@@rnbqkbnr/pppppppp/8/8/8/8/PPPPPPPP/RNBQKBNR w KQkq - 0 1@@EndFEN@@  1.d4  d5  2.c4  .  White threatens cxd5, so our options are limited if we want to keep the central pawn on d5. Black has to play  2...e6  or  2...c6  to accomplish this goal. After  2...e6  , Black's light-squared bishop is passive for the moment. Of course,  2...e6  is an excellent move and our  repertoire choice, but the c8-bishop is a cause for concern for the foreseeable future.   Now, consider what happens if White does not play @@StartFEN@@rnbqkbnr/ppp1pppp/8/3p4/3P4/8/PPP1PPPP/RNBQKBNR w KQkq - 0 2@@EndFEN@@  2.c4  but instead goes for a slower move. We wondered if it is possible to 'punish' White for not playing  2.c4  by  developing our c8-bishop to f5 on move two, and only then playing the move ...e6.  We examined  2.Nf3  Bf5  , and @@StartFEN@@rnbqkbnr/ppp1pppp/8/3p4/3P4/8/PPP1PPPP/RNBQKBNR w KQkq - 0 2@@EndFEN@@  2.Bf4  Bf5  , and concluded that Black's concept is perfectly viable. These lines have the practical advantage of being relatively unexplored and, therefore, will likely not be prepared as thoroughly by your opponents. }
2. Bf4
{ Playing the bishop to f4 is the signature move of the London System. The London is White's most frequently played and challenging alternative to the Queen's Gambit. It's popular on all levels, from online games to classical time control games played in top GM events.  White's strategy after playing the bishop to f4 is not yet determined, but the pawn break c2-c4 or claiming control of the e5-square is still on the cards. Controlling this central square can be the start of a kingside initiative, often started by the move Ne5.  As we will see, against our answer, the symmetrical reply 2...Bf5, the first plan is the more challenging one.   A word about the move 2.Nf3: White often starts with  2.Nf3  and intends  to play Bf4 on the next move. We answer  2.Nf3  with  2...Bf5  , when  3.Bf4  is a possible transposition to the lines that we'll examine now. }
2... Bf5
{ After 2...Bf5 White's main choice  is between playing the move c4 soon or avoiding the pawn break favoring kingside development. This plan often involves playing for control of the e5-square, with a quick Ne5 and Nd2-f3 ideas.   White has many move orders to choose from. If c4 is intended, White can start with  3.c4  right away, but may also begin with  3.Nf3  or  3.e3  . Similarly, play can start with the kingside development scheme following  3.Nf3  or  3.e3  .   We decided to cover all c4-setups starting with the move order  3.c4  , while the kingside development plan is covered via  3.e3  . This means that in our coverage, the move order  3.Nf3  is more or less purely transpositional. Switching to our point of view, our move orders and ideas are fairly straightforward. Our next move will be  3...e6  , preparing kingside development.   One point of the  2...Bf5  move order, compared to  2...Nf6  first, is the delay  of the move ...Nf6. Not playing ...Nf6 early gives us additional options against some of White's plans, in particular against early Ne5 ideas. }
3. e3
{ The most flexible move. White can continue with c4 but also prioritize the development of the kingside. }
3... e6
{ The natural move. Of course, it's also possible to play  3...Nf6  first. It would be an almost certain transposition, as Black  needs both ...e6 and ...Nf6 to develop the kingside.  After  3...e6  , White's most active move is  4.c4  Nf6  , but this continuation transposes to lines that we examine via @@StartFEN@@rnbqkbnr/pppppppp/8/8/8/8/PPPPPPPP/RNBQKBNR w KQkq - 0 1@@EndFEN@@  1.d4  d5  2.Bf4  Bf5  3.c4  e6  4.e3  Nf6  .  This leaves the symmetrical @@StartFEN@@rn1qkbnr/ppp2ppp/4p3/3p1b2/3P1B2/4P3/PPP2PPP/RN1QKBNR w KQkq - 0 4@@EndFEN@@  4.Nf3  and  4.Bd3  to examine. In both cases, White has some very conservative options. We'll try to create some tension without taking unduly risks. In the Quickstarter, we'll focus on  4.Nf3  , while  4.Bd3  should be answered  by the capture on d3, followed by ...c5. }
4. Nf3
{ This position arises very frequently, as White can also start with move orders like @@StartFEN@@rnbqkbnr/pppppppp/8/8/8/8/PPPPPPPP/RNBQKBNR w KQkq - 0 1@@EndFEN@@  1.d4  d5  2.Bf4  Bf5  3.Nf3  e6  4.e3  , leading to the same position. Now we have a good choice between two moves: the symmetrical  4...Nf6  and  4...Bd6  . Please note that  4...c5?  is a rather big mistake, as  5.Bxb8!  is excellent for White.  We play the following variation: @@StartFEN@@rnbqkbnr/pppppppp/8/8/8/8/PPPPPPPP/RNBQKBNR w KQkq - 0 1@@EndFEN@@  1.d4  d5  2.Bf4  Bf5  3.c4  e6  4.e3  Nf6  5.Nf3  Bxb1  , which is fine for Black. A tempo up on this line is too much to bear, so we need to avoid @@StartFEN@@rn1qkbnr/ppp2ppp/4p3/3p1b2/3P1B2/4PN2/PPP2PPP/RN1QKB1R b KQkq - 1 4@@EndFEN@@  4...c5?  here. So what to play:  4...Bd6  or  4...Nf6?  We suggest  4...Nf6  , as this gives us more chances to reach a more complicated position. Still,  4...Bd6  looks perfectly fine and could be played as an alternative, without any deep theoretical knowledge needed. }
4... Nf6
{ We suggest this move, completing the symmetry. The main reason for choosing  4...Nf6  is that we have exciting replies against White's most popular continuations. Let's have a look:  A@@EndBracket@@  5.c4  Bxb1!  transposes to a critical line that we examine via the move order @@StartFEN@@rn1qkbnr/ppp1pppp/8/3p1b2/3P1B2/8/PPP1PPPP/RN1QKBNR w KQkq - 2 3@@EndFEN@@  3.c4  e6  4.e3  Nf6  5.Nf3  Bxb1!   B@@EndBracket@@ @@StartFEN@@rn1qkb1r/ppp2ppp/4pn2/3p1b2/3P1B2/4PN2/PPP2PPP/RN1QKB1R w KQkq - 2 5@@EndFEN@@  5.Bd3  is most commonly played. We suggest the aggressive move  5...Ne4!?  , trying to unbalance the game.   These two moves are the most common, important, and examined in the Quickstarter. White has also tried slow moves like  5.Be2  or  5.Nbd2  , when a symmetrical reply is a simple and good solution. }
5. Bd3
{ White wants to exchange our bishop. This move is the most popular choice at this point, in particular below the master level. Black's simplest response is  5...Bxd3  , which leads to equal play without specific problems. But we want to suggest a different move, though. }
5... Ne4
{ This quirky knight jump is more fun to play than the more obvious capture on d3. Our idea is to play for the advance ...g5, usually prepared with ...Nd7 and ...Be7. This sets White players some problems that they might not even know when they opted for their quiet opening setup.   It's interesting to compare @@StartFEN@@rn1qkb1r/ppp2ppp/4pn2/3p1b2/3P1B2/4PN2/PPP2PPP/RN1QKB1R w KQkq - 2 5@@EndFEN@@  5.Bd3  Ne4  to @@StartFEN@@rn1qkb1r/ppp2ppp/4pn2/3p1b2/3P1B2/4PN2/PPP2PPP/RN1QKB1R w KQkq - 2 5@@EndFEN@@  5.Ne5  for White. A key difference is that after  5.Ne5  Nbd7  we threaten to take on e5, while White's extra tempo  after @@StartFEN@@rn1qkb1r/ppp2ppp/4pn2/3p1b2/3P1B2/4PN2/PPP2PPP/RN1QKB1R w KQkq - 2 5@@EndFEN@@  5.Bd3  Ne4  6.Nbd2  Nd7  makes the capture impossible.  Now White's most logical replies are @@StartFEN@@rn1qkb1r/ppp2ppp/4p3/3p1b2/3PnB2/3BPN2/PPP2PPP/RN1QK2R w KQkq - 4 6@@EndFEN@@  6.Nbd2  and  6.O-O  . White should avoid  6.c4?!  when  6...Bb4+  is awkward to meet... White needs to move the king in reply. }
6. Nbd2
{ White puts some pressure on our knight immediately. There are two key differences to  6.O-O  , the second natural move that White frequently plays.  1. After  6.Nbd2  , White has a hard time playing the  c-pawn in the future, as the d3-bishop would be undefended. A sample line for this scenario  is  6.Nbd2  Nd7  7.c3??  Nxf2  , when Black wins.   2. White has the option g2-g4, which is important to consider when choosing the right move order. After  6.Nbd2  , we should avoid  6...Be7?!  as  7.g4!  is surprisingly strong. More on that later.   Before we continue examining  6.Nbd2  we should talk about  6.O-O  for a moment. After  6...Nd7  White often plays  7.Nbd2  , which transposes to  6.Nbd2  Nd7  7.O-O  − we will examine this in a moment. An independent option is @@StartFEN@@r2qkb1r/pppn1ppp/4p3/3p1b2/3PnB2/3BPN2/PPP2PPP/RN1Q1RK1 w kq - 6 7@@EndFEN@@  7.c4  , when we suggest  7...dxc4!  8.Bxc4  g5!  9.Bg3  h5  , which leads to fun complications. This continuation is analyzed a bit more in the dedicated chapter on the London. }
6... Nd7
{ This looks best, but an interesting alternative is  6...Nc6!?  , which is  toying with the idea of ...Qd7 and a later queenside castling. Our move is more flexible and still allows us to play ...c5, attacking White's central pawn.   It's important to avoid  6...Be7?!  7.g4!  Bxg4  8.Nxe4  dxe4  9.Bxe4  c6  10.Rg1  , when White is better.  The g4 idea does not work after our move,  as @@StartFEN@@rn1qkb1r/ppp2ppp/4p3/3p1b2/3PnB2/3BPN2/PPPN1PPP/R2QK2R b KQkq - 5 6@@EndFEN@@  6...Nd7  7.g4  Bxg4  8.Nxe4  dxe4  9.Bxe4  c6  10.Rg1  Bh5  is fine for Black.  Our g-pawn is protected here, as the bishop is still on f8.   We'll investigate @@StartFEN@@r2qkb1r/pppn1ppp/4p3/3p1b2/3PnB2/3BPN2/PPPN1PPP/R2QK2R w KQkq - 6 7@@EndFEN@@  7.O-O  ,  7.Bxe4  and  7.Ne5  now. White has to avoid the blunder  7.c3?  Nxf2!  , which happens quite frequently in blitz games. }
7. O-O
{ A perfectly normal-looking move, but it is just what we've been hoping for! White should prefer  7.Ne5  Nxe5  8.Bxe5  f6  9.Bf4  g5  or the fun line @@StartFEN@@r2qkb1r/pppn1ppp/4p3/3p1b2/3PnB2/3BPN2/PPPN1PPP/R2QK2R w KQkq - 6 7@@EndFEN@@  7.Bxe4  dxe4  8.Ng5  Nf6  9.Be5  Qd5  10.Bxc7  Bg4  11.f3  Qxg5  12.Bf4  exf3!  13.Bxg5  fxg2  , which leads to equal chances.  There are more possibilities for both sides in these lines, but it is clear that we'll reach some interesting positions with good fighting chances. }
7... Be7
{ The immediate  7...g5?  fails to  8.Bxe4  , but after the much better @@StartFEN@@r2qkb1r/pppn1ppp/4p3/3p1b2/3PnB2/3BPN2/PPPN1PPP/R2Q1RK1 b kq - 7 7@@EndFEN@@  7...Be7  , we are ready  for ...g5! next. Now White has a tough task... what to do about our threat? It's surprising to see that Stockfish regards  8.h3  as the only fully satisfactory move for White, which is a very tough move for a human to play. }
8. Ne5
{ This move was played most of the time in online games, so we use it as the main line. As mentioned, Stockfish suggests  8.h3  , but White's task after  8...g5  9.Bh2  h5  is certainly not enviable − Black has all the fun. The same applies to @@StartFEN@@r2qk2r/pppnbppp/4p3/3p1b2/3PnB2/3BPN2/PPPN1PPP/R2Q1RK1 w kq - 8 8@@EndFEN@@  8.Qe2  g5  or similar lines. }
8... g5 { Here we go! } 9. Bg3 Nxe5
{ This looks even a bit better than  9...h5  . } 10. dxe5
{ Or  10.Bxe5  f6  11.Bg3  Nxg3  12.fxg3  Bxd3  13.cxd3  h5  , which is great for Black. We will have a safe king on the queenside and an attack for free. }
10... h5
{ Black is in great shape here. We have a promising attacking setup on the kingside and no downsides in our position. }
*

[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "Quickstarter Guide − White avoids 2.c4"]
[Black "London System #2"]
[Result "*"]

1. d4 d5
{ In this Quickstarter chapter, we will examine White's most popular alternatives to the Queen's Gambit move,  2.c4  . If White decides to avoid this main path, the most important options are  2.Nf3  , which is a flexible development move, and  2.Bf4  , the London System.  In the Quickstarter, we will focus on these two moves and have a brief look at  2.Nc3  , which enjoys some popularity. White has some offbeat alternatives, but they don't pose a theoretical challenge or are dubious. Please refer to the dedicated chapter on 1.d4 d5 sidelines for more information about White's 'odds and ends'.   Now let's examine our concept against  2.Nf3  and  2.Bf4  − we'll use a similar approach against both moves. Let's return to some opening basics to better understand our line of thinking. Our answer to the Queen's Gambit is the Triangle Variation, @@StartFEN@@rnbqkbnr/pppppppp/8/8/8/8/PPPPPPPP/RNBQKBNR w KQkq - 0 1@@EndFEN@@  1.d4  d5  2.c4  e6  3.Nc3  c6  or @@StartFEN@@rnbqkbnr/ppp2ppp/4p3/3p4/2PP4/8/PP2PPPP/RNBQKBNR w KQkq - 0 3@@EndFEN@@  3.Nf3  c6  , which is the namesake of the course.  However, White is not obliged to play @@StartFEN@@rnbqkbnr/ppp1pppp/8/3p4/3P4/8/PPP1PPPP/RNBQKBNR w KQkq - 0 2@@EndFEN@@  2.c4  but may opt for a different path. The two most important alternatives are the flexible  2.Nf3  and  2.Bf4  , the popular London System. Black has a range of possible replies to these moves.  We play the moves ...e6 and ...c6 @@StartBracket@@the Triangle@@EndBracket@@  against  2.c4  , so why not go for the same setup against White's arguably less aggressive options? We considered this approach but wondered if Black might have a more ambitious response.  Let's go back to the basic position after @@StartFEN@@rnbqkbnr/pppppppp/8/8/8/8/PPPPPPPP/RNBQKBNR w KQkq - 0 1@@EndFEN@@  1.d4  d5  2.c4  .  White threatens cxd5, so our options are limited if we want to keep the central pawn on d5. Black has to play  2...e6  or  2...c6  to accomplish this goal. After  2...e6  , Black's light-squared bishop is passive for the moment. Of course,  2...e6  is an excellent move and our  repertoire choice, but the c8-bishop is a cause for concern for the foreseeable future.   Now, consider what happens if White does not play @@StartFEN@@rnbqkbnr/ppp1pppp/8/3p4/3P4/8/PPP1PPPP/RNBQKBNR w KQkq - 0 2@@EndFEN@@  2.c4  but instead goes for a slower move. We wondered if it is possible to 'punish' White for not playing  2.c4  by  developing our c8-bishop to f5 on move two, and only then playing the move ...e6.  We examined  2.Nf3  Bf5  , and @@StartFEN@@rnbqkbnr/ppp1pppp/8/3p4/3P4/8/PPP1PPPP/RNBQKBNR w KQkq - 0 2@@EndFEN@@  2.Bf4  Bf5  , and concluded that Black's concept is perfectly viable. These lines have the practical advantage of being relatively unexplored and, therefore, will likely not be prepared as thoroughly by your opponents. }
2. Bf4
{ Playing the bishop to f4 is the signature move of the London System. The London is White's most frequently played and challenging alternative to the Queen's Gambit. It's popular on all levels, from online games to classical time control games played in top GM events.  White's strategy after playing the bishop to f4 is not yet determined, but the pawn break c2-c4 or claiming control of the e5-square is still on the cards. Controlling this central square can be the start of a kingside initiative, often started by the move Ne5.  As we will see, against our answer, the symmetrical reply 2...Bf5, the first plan is the more challenging one.   A word about the move 2.Nf3: White often starts with  2.Nf3  and intends  to play Bf4 on the next move. We answer  2.Nf3  with  2...Bf5  , when  3.Bf4  is a possible transposition to the lines that we'll examine now. }
2... Bf5
{ After 2...Bf5 White's main choice  is between playing the move c4 soon or avoiding the pawn break favoring kingside development. This plan often involves playing for control of the e5-square, with a quick Ne5 and Nd2-f3 ideas.   White has many move orders to choose from. If c4 is intended, White can start with  3.c4  right away, but may also begin with  3.Nf3  or  3.e3  . Similarly, play can start with the kingside development scheme following  3.Nf3  or  3.e3  .   We decided to cover all c4-setups starting with the move order  3.c4  , while the kingside development plan is covered via  3.e3  . This means that in our coverage, the move order  3.Nf3  is more or less purely transpositional. Switching to our point of view, our move orders and ideas are fairly straightforward. Our next move will be  3...e6  , preparing kingside development.   One point of the  2...Bf5  move order, compared to  2...Nf6  first, is the delay  of the move ...Nf6. Not playing ...Nf6 early gives us additional options against some of White's plans, in particular against early Ne5 ideas. }
3. c4
{ White plays the typical Queen's Gambit move c4, putting pressure on the d5-pawn. This approach is possible immediately or after preparing the move with  3.e3  first. We chose the move order  3.c4  , as White has some possible options to play  without the move e3. }
3... e6
{ The natural reply. We cover the d5-pawn and prepare for kingside development. Now White has some choice − here is an overview of our opponent's options.  A@@EndBracket@@ A critical line is  4.Nf3  Nf6  5.Qb3  , which we fight with the active knight jump  5...Nc6  . This continuation is covered here, in the Quickstarter. Please note that this variation often arises via the move order @@StartFEN@@rnbqkbnr/ppp1pppp/8/3p4/3P4/8/PPP1PPPP/RNBQKBNR w KQkq - 0 2@@EndFEN@@  2.Nf3  Bf5  3.Bf4  e6  4.c4  Nf6  5.Qb3  , leading to the same position.  B@@EndBracket@@ A common and important option is @@StartFEN@@rn1qkbnr/ppp2ppp/4p3/3p1b2/2PP1B2/8/PP2PPPP/RN1QKBNR w KQkq - 0 4@@EndFEN@@  4.Nf3  Nf6  5.e3  , or @@StartFEN@@rn1qkbnr/ppp2ppp/4p3/3p1b2/2PP1B2/8/PP2PPPP/RN1QKBNR w KQkq - 0 4@@EndFEN@@  4.e3  Nf6  5.Nf3  , when it is crucial to play  5...Bxb1  to enable a powerful  check on b4 without having to reckon with the reply Nc3. We cover this line in the Quickstarter too.   C@@EndBracket@@ @@StartFEN@@rn1qkbnr/ppp2ppp/4p3/3p1b2/2PP1B2/8/PP2PPPP/RN1QKBNR w KQkq - 0 4@@EndFEN@@ White often plays the natural move  4.Nc3  , when  4...Nf6  is a logical answer. White has some options against it, like  5.e3  or  5.Nf3  . We'll examine some key ideas here in the Quickstarter.  D@@EndBracket@@ A key idea for White is the queen  sortie Qb3, which puts pressure on d5 and b7.  The immediate @@StartFEN@@rn1qkbnr/ppp2ppp/4p3/3p1b2/2PP1B2/8/PP2PPPP/RN1QKBNR w KQkq - 0 4@@EndFEN@@  4.Qb3?!  is a dubious choice, as our usual reply  4...Nc6!  is very strong.  We attack the d-pawn and threaten ...Nb4 at the same time. White is already struggling after our knight jump. We examine some more sample lines in the full chapter. Let's have a look at the most common and critical lines now, listed as A to C. }
4. Nc3
{ White's most popular move. It increases the pressure on the d5-pawn and avoids a possible capture on b1, followed by Bb4+. This idea is relevant in lines like @@StartFEN@@rn1qkbnr/ppp2ppp/4p3/3p1b2/2PP1B2/8/PP2PPPP/RN1QKBNR w KQkq - 0 4@@EndFEN@@  4.e3  Nf6  5.Nf3  Bxb1  6.Rxb1  Bb4+  , when White needs to move the king. }
4... Nf6
{ We continue to develop and get one move closer to castling. Now White's main move is the natural  5.e3  , but  5.Nf3  and  5.Qb3  are possible too. It's essential to keep in mind that we want to develop as actively as possible and avoid slow  moves like ...c6. After  5.e3  our reply is  5...Bb4!  , pinning the knight.  We'll reach similar positions after @@StartFEN@@rn1qkb1r/ppp2ppp/4pn2/3p1b2/2PP1B2/2N5/PP2PPPP/R2QKBNR w KQkq - 2 5@@EndFEN@@  5.Nf3  Bb4!  or @@StartFEN@@rn1qkb1r/ppp2ppp/4pn2/3p1b2/2PP1B2/2N5/PP2PPPP/R2QKBNR w KQkq - 2 5@@EndFEN@@  5.Qb3  Nc6!  @@StartBracket@@attacking the d-pawn@@EndBracket@@  6.e3  Bb4!  , which not only develops, but also protects the b-pawn. Check the relevant chapter for more details. }
5. e3 { The most flexible and natural move for White. } 5... Bb4
{ An important move! We want to play as actively as possible, in the style of the Nimzo-Indian @@StartFEN@@rnbqkbnr/pppppppp/8/8/8/8/PPPPPPPP/RNBQKBNR w KQkq - 0 1@@EndFEN@@  1.d4  Nf6  2.c4  e6  3.Nc3  Bb4  , or the Ragozin @@StartFEN@@rnbqkbnr/pppppppp/8/8/8/8/PPPPPPPP/RNBQKBNR w KQkq - 0 1@@EndFEN@@  1.d4  d5  2.c4  e6  3.Nf3  Nf6  4.Nc3  Bb4  , but with the  added moves Bf4 and ...Bf5. This leads to an interesting struggle that theory has not yet deeply covered.  Let's have a look at White's options.  A@@EndBracket@@ @@StartFEN@@rn1qk2r/ppp2ppp/4pn2/3p1b2/1bPP1B2/2N1P3/PP3PPP/R2QKBNR w KQkq - 1 6@@EndFEN@@  6.Qb3  is the most popular move. We suggest  6...Nc6  , which transposes to a line that we can reach via other move orders, for example, @@StartFEN@@rnbqkbnr/pppppppp/8/8/8/8/PPPPPPPP/RNBQKBNR w KQkq - 0 1@@EndFEN@@  1.d4  d5  2.Bf4  Bf5  3.c4  e6  4.Nc3  Nf6  5.Qb3  Nc6  6.e3  Bb4  , which gives Black good chances.  It also possible to answer @@StartFEN@@rn1qk2r/ppp2ppp/4pn2/3p1b2/1bPP1B2/2N1P3/PP3PPP/R2QKBNR w KQkq - 1 6@@EndFEN@@  6.Qb3  with  6...c5!?  , but it does not seem better than  6...Nc6  , so we suggest going for the transposition.  B@@EndBracket@@ @@StartFEN@@rn1qk2r/ppp2ppp/4pn2/3p1b2/1bPP1B2/2N1P3/PP3PPP/R2QKBNR w KQkq - 1 6@@EndFEN@@  6.Nf3  looks like the most natural move, besides option A. We answer  6...O-O  and stay flexible. We'll have a closer look at this line in a moment.  C@@EndBracket@@ @@StartFEN@@rn1qk2r/ppp2ppp/4pn2/3p1b2/1bPP1B2/2N1P3/PP3PPP/R2QKBNR w KQkq - 1 6@@EndFEN@@  6.a3  Bxc3+  7.bxc3  c5  is unexplored but should certainly be fine for Black. White has many pawn weaknesses that we can exploit  later with Qa5, for example.   D@@EndBracket@@ @@StartFEN@@rn1qk2r/ppp2ppp/4pn2/3p1b2/1bPP1B2/2N1P3/PP3PPP/R2QKBNR w KQkq - 1 6@@EndFEN@@  6.Qa4+  Nc6  looks like a worse version of line A,  as the queen can't be any better on a4 compared to b3. A continuation like  7.Nf3  Ne4  looks easy to play for Black. }
6. Nf3
{ This developing move looks like White's best bet. Against  6.Qb3  we have  6...Nc6  , leading to a position that may also arise via @@StartFEN@@rn1qkb1r/ppp2ppp/4pn2/3p1b2/2PP1B2/2N5/PP2PPPP/R2QKBNR w KQkq - 2 5@@EndFEN@@  5.Qb3  Nc6  6.Nf3  . }
6... O-O { We stay flexible. } 7. Qb3
{ We always have to check the queen sortie. Alternatives for White? We'd be happy about  7.a3  Bxc3+  8.bxc3  c5  , when White's queenside is weak. @@StartFEN@@rn1q1rk1/ppp2ppp/4pn2/3p1b2/1bPP1B2/2N1PN2/PP3PPP/R2QKB1R w KQ - 3 7@@EndFEN@@  7.Be2  looks reasonable, but  7...Ne4  is an attractive reply. }
7... Nc6
{ We stick with this setup instead of  7...c5  . White now has to worry  about ...Ne4 and ...a5-a4 ideas. }
8. Bg5
{ Not ideal, but it stops ...Ne4. After  8.Be2  Ne4  we'd transpose to @@StartFEN@@rn1q1rk1/ppp2ppp/4pn2/3p1b2/1bPP1B2/2N1PN2/PP3PPP/R2QKB1R w KQ - 3 7@@EndFEN@@  7.Be2  Ne4  8.Qb3  Nc6  , which is easy for Black to play. }
8... a5
{ This is the idea you need to remember. White now faces the extremely annoying threat of ...a5-a4-a3, tearing down the queenside. }
9. Qa4
{ A sad move, but probably the best. White can't ignore the a-pawn push, as  9.Be2??  a4  10.Qd1  a3  shows. We are threatening to capture  on b2, followed by ...Ra3 − Black wins!   If White tries  9.a3  , then  9...a4  10.Qa2  Bxc3+  11.bxc3  Na5  is great for Black. White has multiple weaknesses on the queenside that we are ready to exploit  with ...c5 next. }
9... h6
{ Stockfish also likes the surprising move  9...Ne7  , which  threatens ...Ne4 and thus more or less forces the capture on f6.  We suggest playing  9...h6  to do the same, as White now can't keep the bishop. }
10. Bxf6
{ White must take, as  10.Bh4?  g5  11.Bg3  Ne4  12.Rc1  h5  is more or less winning for Black. }
10... Qxf6
{ We have gained the bishop pair for the moment, but White could play a3 when we take on c3 and return it for a weakening of White's queenside. We are happy with Black's chances as we either keep the bishops or create weaknesses that we can try to exploit. }
*

[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "Quickstarter Guide − White avoids 2.c4"]
[Black "London System #3"]
[Result "*"]

1. d4 d5
{ In this Quickstarter chapter, we will examine White's most popular alternatives to the Queen's Gambit move,  2.c4  . If White decides to avoid this main path, the most important options are  2.Nf3  , which is a flexible development move, and  2.Bf4  , the London System.  In the Quickstarter, we will focus on these two moves and have a brief look at  2.Nc3  , which enjoys some popularity. White has some offbeat alternatives, but they don't pose a theoretical challenge or are dubious. Please refer to the dedicated chapter on 1.d4 d5 sidelines for more information about White's 'odds and ends'.   Now let's examine our concept against  2.Nf3  and  2.Bf4  − we'll use a similar approach against both moves. Let's return to some opening basics to better understand our line of thinking. Our answer to the Queen's Gambit is the Triangle Variation, @@StartFEN@@rnbqkbnr/pppppppp/8/8/8/8/PPPPPPPP/RNBQKBNR w KQkq - 0 1@@EndFEN@@  1.d4  d5  2.c4  e6  3.Nc3  c6  or @@StartFEN@@rnbqkbnr/ppp2ppp/4p3/3p4/2PP4/8/PP2PPPP/RNBQKBNR w KQkq - 0 3@@EndFEN@@  3.Nf3  c6  , which is the namesake of the course.  However, White is not obliged to play @@StartFEN@@rnbqkbnr/ppp1pppp/8/3p4/3P4/8/PPP1PPPP/RNBQKBNR w KQkq - 0 2@@EndFEN@@  2.c4  but may opt for a different path. The two most important alternatives are the flexible  2.Nf3  and  2.Bf4  , the popular London System. Black has a range of possible replies to these moves.  We play the moves ...e6 and ...c6 @@StartBracket@@the Triangle@@EndBracket@@  against  2.c4  , so why not go for the same setup against White's arguably less aggressive options? We considered this approach but wondered if Black might have a more ambitious response.  Let's go back to the basic position after @@StartFEN@@rnbqkbnr/pppppppp/8/8/8/8/PPPPPPPP/RNBQKBNR w KQkq - 0 1@@EndFEN@@  1.d4  d5  2.c4  .  White threatens cxd5, so our options are limited if we want to keep the central pawn on d5. Black has to play  2...e6  or  2...c6  to accomplish this goal. After  2...e6  , Black's light-squared bishop is passive for the moment. Of course,  2...e6  is an excellent move and our  repertoire choice, but the c8-bishop is a cause for concern for the foreseeable future.   Now, consider what happens if White does not play @@StartFEN@@rnbqkbnr/ppp1pppp/8/3p4/3P4/8/PPP1PPPP/RNBQKBNR w KQkq - 0 2@@EndFEN@@  2.c4  but instead goes for a slower move. We wondered if it is possible to 'punish' White for not playing  2.c4  by  developing our c8-bishop to f5 on move two, and only then playing the move ...e6.  We examined  2.Nf3  Bf5  , and @@StartFEN@@rnbqkbnr/ppp1pppp/8/3p4/3P4/8/PPP1PPPP/RNBQKBNR w KQkq - 0 2@@EndFEN@@  2.Bf4  Bf5  , and concluded that Black's concept is perfectly viable. These lines have the practical advantage of being relatively unexplored and, therefore, will likely not be prepared as thoroughly by your opponents. }
2. Bf4
{ Playing the bishop to f4 is the signature move of the London System. The London is White's most frequently played and challenging alternative to the Queen's Gambit. It's popular on all levels, from online games to classical time control games played in top GM events.  White's strategy after playing the bishop to f4 is not yet determined, but the pawn break c2-c4 or claiming control of the e5-square is still on the cards. Controlling this central square can be the start of a kingside initiative, often started by the move Ne5.  As we will see, against our answer, the symmetrical reply 2...Bf5, the first plan is the more challenging one.   A word about the move 2.Nf3: White often starts with  2.Nf3  and intends  to play Bf4 on the next move. We answer  2.Nf3  with  2...Bf5  , when  3.Bf4  is a possible transposition to the lines that we'll examine now. }
2... Bf5
{ After 2...Bf5 White's main choice  is between playing the move c4 soon or avoiding the pawn break favoring kingside development. This plan often involves playing for control of the e5-square, with a quick Ne5 and Nd2-f3 ideas.   White has many move orders to choose from. If c4 is intended, White can start with  3.c4  right away, but may also begin with  3.Nf3  or  3.e3  . Similarly, play can start with the kingside development scheme following  3.Nf3  or  3.e3  .   We decided to cover all c4-setups starting with the move order  3.c4  , while the kingside development plan is covered via  3.e3  . This means that in our coverage, the move order  3.Nf3  is more or less purely transpositional. Switching to our point of view, our move orders and ideas are fairly straightforward. Our next move will be  3...e6  , preparing kingside development.   One point of the  2...Bf5  move order, compared to  2...Nf6  first, is the delay  of the move ...Nf6. Not playing ...Nf6 early gives us additional options against some of White's plans, in particular against early Ne5 ideas. }
3. c4
{ White plays the typical Queen's Gambit move c4, putting pressure on the d5-pawn. This approach is possible immediately or after preparing the move with  3.e3  first. We chose the move order  3.c4  , as White has some possible options to play  without the move e3. }
3... e6
{ The natural reply. We cover the d5-pawn and prepare for kingside development. Now White has some choice − here is an overview of our opponent's options.  A@@EndBracket@@ A critical line is  4.Nf3  Nf6  5.Qb3  , which we fight with the active knight jump  5...Nc6  . This continuation is covered here, in the Quickstarter. Please note that this variation often arises via the move order @@StartFEN@@rnbqkbnr/ppp1pppp/8/3p4/3P4/8/PPP1PPPP/RNBQKBNR w KQkq - 0 2@@EndFEN@@  2.Nf3  Bf5  3.Bf4  e6  4.c4  Nf6  5.Qb3  , leading to the same position.  B@@EndBracket@@ A common and important option is @@StartFEN@@rn1qkbnr/ppp2ppp/4p3/3p1b2/2PP1B2/8/PP2PPPP/RN1QKBNR w KQkq - 0 4@@EndFEN@@  4.Nf3  Nf6  5.e3  , or @@StartFEN@@rn1qkbnr/ppp2ppp/4p3/3p1b2/2PP1B2/8/PP2PPPP/RN1QKBNR w KQkq - 0 4@@EndFEN@@  4.e3  Nf6  5.Nf3  , when it is crucial to play  5...Bxb1  to enable a powerful  check on b4 without having to reckon with the reply Nc3. We cover this line in the Quickstarter too.   C@@EndBracket@@ @@StartFEN@@rn1qkbnr/ppp2ppp/4p3/3p1b2/2PP1B2/8/PP2PPPP/RN1QKBNR w KQkq - 0 4@@EndFEN@@ White often plays the natural move  4.Nc3  , when  4...Nf6  is a logical answer. White has some options against it, like  5.e3  or  5.Nf3  . We'll examine some key ideas here in the Quickstarter.  D@@EndBracket@@ A key idea for White is the queen  sortie Qb3, which puts pressure on d5 and b7.  The immediate @@StartFEN@@rn1qkbnr/ppp2ppp/4p3/3p1b2/2PP1B2/8/PP2PPPP/RN1QKBNR w KQkq - 0 4@@EndFEN@@  4.Qb3?!  is a dubious choice, as our usual reply  4...Nc6!  is very strong.  We attack the d-pawn and threaten ...Nb4 at the same time. White is already struggling after our knight jump. We examine some more sample lines in the full chapter. Let's have a look at the most common and critical lines now, listed as A to C. }
4. Nf3
{ This position arises frequently via @@StartFEN@@rnbqkbnr/ppp1pppp/8/3p4/3P4/8/PPP1PPPP/RNBQKBNR w KQkq - 0 2@@EndFEN@@  2.Nf3  Bf5  3.Bf4  e6  4.c4  , which makes it particularly important. }
4... Nf6
{ A healthy development, getting one move closer to castling. Here  4...dxc4!?  is a relatively unexplored alternative worth checking.  We still opted for  4...Nf6  because the position after White's reply  5.e3  needs to be covered in any case.  White can always start with the move e3 and only then play c4, which would avoid the ...dxc4 option.   A possible move order is @@StartFEN@@rn1qkbnr/ppp1pppp/8/3p1b2/3P1B2/8/PPP1PPPP/RN1QKBNR w KQkq - 2 3@@EndFEN@@  3.e3  e6  4.c4  Nf6  5.Nf3  , reaching the same position.  Now we'll focus on @@StartFEN@@rn1qkb1r/ppp2ppp/4pn2/3p1b2/2PP1B2/5N2/PP2PPPP/RN1QKB1R w KQkq - 2 5@@EndFEN@@  5.e3  and  5.Qb3  , two critical lines. White may also play  5.Nc3  when  5...Bb4  is a good reply. We examine similar lines via the move order @@StartFEN@@rn1qkbnr/ppp2ppp/4p3/3p1b2/2PP1B2/8/PP2PPPP/RN1QKBNR w KQkq - 0 4@@EndFEN@@  4.Nc3  Nf6  5.e3  Bb4  , which will often lead to the same positions. }
5. Qb3
{ White can play the move Qb3 in various versions. There are sequences like @@StartFEN@@rn1qkbnr/ppp1pppp/8/3p1b2/3P1B2/8/PPP1PPPP/RN1QKBNR w KQkq - 2 3@@EndFEN@@  3.c4  e6  4.Qb3  ,  3.c4  e6  4.Nc3  Nf6  5.Qb3  or @@StartFEN@@rn1qkbnr/ppp1pppp/8/3p1b2/3P1B2/8/PPP1PPPP/RN1QKBNR w KQkq - 2 3@@EndFEN@@  3.e3  e6  4.c4  Nf6  5.Qb3  .   In all cases, we want to avoid a passive or weakening reply like ...Qc8 or ...b6 and instead defend actively. This is usually accomplished by ignoring the threat to the b7-pawn and developing the knight on c6.  This is the way we handle the three mentioned sample sequences, and the current position is no exception. Still, it's worth mentioning that Black has a good alternative here, the capture on c4.  After @@StartFEN@@rn1qkb1r/ppp2ppp/4pn2/3p1b2/2PP1B2/1Q3N2/PP2PPPP/RN2KB1R b KQkq - 3 5@@EndFEN@@  5...dxc4  6.Qxb7  Be4  7.Qxc7  Qxc7  8.Bxc7  Bb4+  , Black is a pawn down for a while but gets reasonable compensation.   Currently, Black's chances look okay in this line, but we see a practical drawback. It requires a substantial effort to learn, but the resulting endgames will not give Black great winning chances in many cases. On the other hand, our move 5...Nc6 leads to combative and still relatively unexplored positions. }
5... Nc6
{ The usual reply to Qb3 ideas. Now White's best moves are  6.c5  and  6.Nbd2  , which are surprisingly challenging. In the Quickstarter, we'll have a closer look at  6.Qxb7  , though. This move is too risky for White, but it is nevertheless by far the most popular in amateur and online games. Before we explore the move, a quick word about the already mentioned alternatives that White should prefer.  A@@EndBracket@@  6.c5  White  controls the b4-square this way, which makes Qxb7 a more serious threat.  A good reply is the simple  6...Rb8  ,  covering the b-pawn. A key idea for Black is ...Ne4! in the future, intending to expand on the kingside with ...g5.   B@@EndBracket@@  6.Nbd2  is a rare move, but it was recently tested on the highest level. The best seems to be  6...Be7  7.e3  O-O  ,  when we keep offering the b-pawn. White can never take it without harm, as ...Nb4 is the reply. We analyze lines A and B in some detail in the dedicated chapter. Let's now check what happens after the greedy pawn grab. }
6. Qxb7
{ The greedy capture is not bad objectively, but White has to be very careful. We get a strong initiative − the best that White can hope for is equality with perfect play. We need to check the move in detail, as taking the pawn is certainly a principled way of playing. }
6... Nb4 7. Na3 { There is nothing else, White has to cover c2. } 7... dxc4
{ The only good move. We take the pawn but, more importantly, clear the d5-square for our pieces. Our knights and the queen might use this square, but ...Be4-d5 is also an important idea. }
8. Bxc7
{ White grabs a second pawn, but this is decidedly too much. White is also on the defensive after  8.Nb5  Nfd5  , but the preicse  9.Rc1  Rb8  10.Nxc7+  Nxc7  11.Qxc7  Qxc7  12.Bxc7  Rb7  13.Rxc4  Nd5  leads to equal chances.   An alternative is  8.Qb5+  c6  9.Qxc4  , but  9...Be4!  gives Black excellent compensation.  Also, note that ...Rc8 and ...c5 is an essential part of Black's concept, opening the position quickly. }
8... Qc8
{ That's even stronger than  8...Qd5  , which is good enough for a significant advantage. }
9. Qxc8+
{ Or  9.Qb5+  Nd7  10.Qxc4  Qb7  , when White is helpless against the  threat ...Rc8. }
9... Rxc8 10. Ba5 c3
{ The important point. Black is breaking through on the queenside. } 11. bxc3
Rxc3 12. Nb5 Rc8
{ And finally, we can conclude that White is helpless against the ...Nc2+ threat. }
*

