4. Nf3
{ This position arises frequently via @@StartFEN@@rnbqkbnr/ppp1pppp/8/3p4/3P4/8/PPP1PPPP/RNBQKBNR w KQkq - 0 2@@EndFEN@@  2.Nf3  Bf5  3.Bf4  e6  4.c4  , which makes it particularly important. }
4... Nf6
{ A healthy development, getting one move closer to castling. Here  4...dxc4!?  is a relatively unexplored alternative worth checking.  We still opted for  4...Nf6  because the position after White's reply  5.e3  needs to be covered in any case.  White can always start with the move e3 and only then play c4, which would avoid the ...dxc4 option.   A possible move order is @@StartFEN@@rn1qkbnr/ppp1pppp/8/3p1b2/3P1B2/8/PPP1PPPP/RN1QKBNR w KQkq - 2 3@@EndFEN@@  3.e3  e6  4.c4  Nf6  5.Nf3  , reaching the same position.  Now we'll focus on @@StartFEN@@rn1qkb1r/ppp2ppp/4pn2/3p1b2/2PP1B2/5N2/PP2PPPP/RN1QKB1R w KQkq - 2 5@@EndFEN@@  5.e3  and  5.Qb3  , two critical lines. White may also play  5.Nc3  when  5...Bb4  is a good reply. We examine similar lines via the move order @@StartFEN@@rn1qkbnr/ppp2ppp/4p3/3p1b2/2PP1B2/8/PP2PPPP/RN1QKBNR w KQkq - 0 4@@EndFEN@@  4.Nc3  Nf6  5.e3  Bb4  , which will often lead to the same positions. }
5. e3 { The natural move, covering the c-pawn. } 5... Bxb1
{ A key move in our concept. After  5...Bb4+  , White can still play  6.Nbd2  . Our idea is to take the knight first and then give the check, forcing the white king to move. White can now insert @@StartFEN@@rn1qkb1r/ppp2ppp/4pn2/3p4/2PP1B2/4PN2/PP3PPP/Rb1QKB1R w KQkq - 0 6@@EndFEN@@  6.Qa4+  or choose between  6.Rxb1  and  6.Qxb1  , when we'd reply  6...Bb4+  to force the king to move. }
6. Rxb1
{ The recaptures on move six are about equally popular on the master level. They lead to somewhat different positions, as White's concept after  6.Rxb1  involves a quick Qa4+, which is clearly off the table after  6.Qxb1  . In the Quickstarter, we'll focus on  6.Rxb1  , as this move demands more precision from Black.  After  6.Qxb1  Bb4+  7.Kd1  we suggest  7...Bd6  ,  challenging the f4-bishop and trying to get rid of the pair of bishops. White can avoid this with  8.Bg5  , when  8...c6  9.Bd3  Nbd7  10.Ke2  dxc4  is the way to go. We open the position, seeing that White's king is in the middle of the board.  In some cases, castling queenside is an option for us. }
6... Bb4+
{ We didn't give up the bishop on b1 for nothing. This check forces  7.Ke2  , as  7.Nd2??  Ne4  wins the house. }
7. Ke2 dxc4
{ That is the most direct way to play. We make sure that the position opens up quickly. Black has also fared well with  7...Bd6  , but our suggested move is clearer. }
8. Qa4+
{ The only move that makes any sense. After  8.Qa4+  Nc6  , White wants to continue with  9.Ne5  to put pressure on our minor pieces. }
8... Nc6 9. Ne5
{ White not only attacks our c6-knight but also undermines the stability of our bishop. }
9... a5
{ This move looks like the cleanest solution, but Black has also tried  9...Nd5  with good results. }
10. Nxc6
{ White can also play  10.a3  Bd6  11.Nxc6  Qd7  , which is just a transposition to the line that we will examine in a moment. }
10... Qd7
{ This fun counter-pin is saving the day for us. We will regain the knight later − White has no way of keeping the material. It's important to note that we don't even need to take the knight on the next move. We have ideas like ...Nd5-b6 or ...Ra6, which might allow us to take it without doubling pawns.   Now we'll examine White's replies  11.a3  and  11.Rc1  . White has also tried  11.g3  , but this is very similar to  11.a3  Bd6  12.g3  . }
11. a3
{ White pushes our bishop back first.  11.Rc1  can be tried as well, but  11...Ra6!  or  11...Nd5  are good replies. }
11... Bd6
{ Now we threaten to take on f4, which would damage White's pawn structure considerably if recapturing with the e-pawn is forced. This applies to a line like  12.Qxc4?!  Bxf4  12.exf4  bxc6  , when Black is much better. }
12. g3
{ This makes a lot of sense. White is now ready to recapture with the g-pawn and at the same time prepares the bishop fianchetto. White could have played this idea even one move earlier. After @@StartFEN@@r3k2r/1ppq1ppp/2N1pn2/p7/QbpP1B2/4P3/PP2KPPP/1R3B1R w kq - 1 11@@EndFEN@@  11.g3  Ra6  12.Bg2  Nd5  , we would follow a very similar path to the line we are currently examining. }
12... Bxf4
{ This looks a bit easier for Black than  12...Qxc6  , which was played in an online rapid game between Magnus Carlsen and Anish Giri @@StartBracket@@chess24 Banter Blitz Cup Final@@EndBracket@@. Our move aims to avoid the compromised pawn structure. }
13. gxf4 Ra6 { That's the point! } 14. Bg2 Nd5
{ And finally, after all the tricks, we get the piece back. } 15. Qxc4 Rxc6
{ Black is in good shape here. We have avoided any pawn structure concessions and enjoy the strong knight on d5. White has a hard time ever playing e3-e4, as the pawn advance would weaken f4 and d4 a lot. }
*

[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "Quickstarter Guide − White avoids 2.c4"]
[Black "2.Nc3 c5 3.e4"]
[Result "*"]

1. d4 d5
{ In this Quickstarter chapter, we will examine White's most popular alternatives to the Queen's Gambit move,  2.c4  . If White decides to avoid this main path, the most important options are  2.Nf3  , which is a flexible development move, and  2.Bf4  , the London System.  In the Quickstarter, we will focus on these two moves and have a brief look at  2.Nc3  , which enjoys some popularity. White has some offbeat alternatives, but they don't pose a theoretical challenge or are dubious. Please refer to the dedicated chapter on 1.d4 d5 sidelines for more information about White's 'odds and ends'.   Now let's examine our concept against  2.Nf3  and  2.Bf4  − we'll use a similar approach against both moves. Let's return to some opening basics to better understand our line of thinking. Our answer to the Queen's Gambit is the Triangle Variation, @@StartFEN@@rnbqkbnr/pppppppp/8/8/8/8/PPPPPPPP/RNBQKBNR w KQkq - 0 1@@EndFEN@@  1.d4  d5  2.c4  e6  3.Nc3  c6  or @@StartFEN@@rnbqkbnr/ppp2ppp/4p3/3p4/2PP4/8/PP2PPPP/RNBQKBNR w KQkq - 0 3@@EndFEN@@  3.Nf3  c6  , which is the namesake of the course.  However, White is not obliged to play @@StartFEN@@rnbqkbnr/ppp1pppp/8/3p4/3P4/8/PPP1PPPP/RNBQKBNR w KQkq - 0 2@@EndFEN@@  2.c4  but may opt for a different path. The two most important alternatives are the flexible  2.Nf3  and  2.Bf4  , the popular London System. Black has a range of possible replies to these moves.  We play the moves ...e6 and ...c6 @@StartBracket@@the Triangle@@EndBracket@@  against  2.c4  , so why not go for the same setup against White's arguably less aggressive options? We considered this approach but wondered if Black might have a more ambitious response.  Let's go back to the basic position after @@StartFEN@@rnbqkbnr/pppppppp/8/8/8/8/PPPPPPPP/RNBQKBNR w KQkq - 0 1@@EndFEN@@  1.d4  d5  2.c4  .  White threatens cxd5, so our options are limited if we want to keep the central pawn on d5. Black has to play  2...e6  or  2...c6  to accomplish this goal. After  2...e6  , Black's light-squared bishop is passive for the moment. Of course,  2...e6  is an excellent move and our  repertoire choice, but the c8-bishop is a cause for concern for the foreseeable future.   Now, consider what happens if White does not play @@StartFEN@@rnbqkbnr/ppp1pppp/8/3p4/3P4/8/PPP1PPPP/RNBQKBNR w KQkq - 0 2@@EndFEN@@  2.c4  but instead goes for a slower move. We wondered if it is possible to 'punish' White for not playing  2.c4  by  developing our c8-bishop to f5 on move two, and only then playing the move ...e6.  We examined  2.Nf3  Bf5  , and @@StartFEN@@rnbqkbnr/ppp1pppp/8/3p4/3P4/8/PPP1PPPP/RNBQKBNR w KQkq - 0 2@@EndFEN@@  2.Bf4  Bf5  , and concluded that Black's concept is perfectly viable. These lines have the practical advantage of being relatively unexplored and, therefore, will likely not be prepared as thoroughly by your opponents. }
2. Nc3
{ In recent years, early combinations of d4 and Nc3 have become more popular. Lines like @@StartFEN@@rnbqkbnr/pppppppp/8/8/8/8/PPPPPPPP/RNBQKBNR w KQkq - 0 1@@EndFEN@@  1.d4  Nf6  2.Bf4  g6  3.Nc3  or @@StartFEN@@rnbqkbnr/pppppppp/8/8/8/8/PPPPPPPP/RNBQKBNR w KQkq - 0 1@@EndFEN@@  1.d4  Nf6  2.Nc3  d5  3.Bf4  , the so-called 'Jobava London' are interesting ways for White to get the game away from the mainstream while still being fundamentally sound.  The sequence @@StartFEN@@rnbqkbnr/pppppppp/8/8/8/8/PPPPPPPP/RNBQKBNR w KQkq - 0 1@@EndFEN@@  1.d4  d5  2.Nc3  is a bit less common because it gives Black some additional options than the lines mentioned before. The difference is that Black hasn't yet committed to  an early ...Nf6, which allows the  reply  2...c5  , our choice. }
2... c5
{ This is the most principled move. Black plays the desired pawn break right away and claims: 'Well, you failed to play 2.c4, then I'll go ahead and play 2...c5!'. Of course, this is not the only good move available.   2...Nf6  is a frequently seen alternative, while  2...Bf5  is an interesting option that is less explored. We often play an  early ...Bf5,  think of @@StartFEN@@rnbqkbnr/pppppppp/8/8/8/8/PPPPPPPP/RNBQKBNR w KQkq - 0 1@@EndFEN@@  1.d4  d5  2.Nf3  Bf5  , so this would fit quite well too.  Back to the position after @@StartFEN@@rnbqkbnr/ppp1pppp/8/3p4/3P4/2N5/PPP1PPPP/R1BQKBNR b KQkq - 1 2@@EndFEN@@  2...c5  . What is White's idea behind playing the knight on move two? One point is a  quick assault on the c7-square that White may go for, combining Nc3 and Bf4.  Let's have a look: one example is  3.Bf4  Nc6  4.e3  @@StartBracket@@after  4.Nb5??  Qa5+  is important!@@EndBracket@@ @@StartFEN@@r1bqkbnr/pp2pppp/2n5/2pp4/3P1B2/2N1P3/PPP2PPP/R2QKBNR b KQkq - 0 4@@EndFEN@@  4...cxd4!  @@StartBracket@@you need to avoid  4...Nf6??  5.Nb5!  , showing the basic idea  of the Nc3&Bf4  combo@@EndBracket@@ @@StartFEN@@r1bqkbnr/pp2pppp/2n5/3p4/3p1B2/2N1P3/PPP2PPP/R2QKBNR w KQkq - 0 5@@EndFEN@@  5.exd4  Bf5  , when we reach a comfortable position. Again, please note that  5...Nf6??  6.Nb5  would be a blunder.  By playing @@StartFEN@@r1bqkbnr/pp2pppp/2n5/3p4/3P1B2/2N5/PPP2PPP/R2QKBNR b KQkq - 0 5@@EndFEN@@  5...Bf5  first, we  enable ...Rc8 as a reply to the knight jump. White's knight on c3 is misplaced in this Carlsbad structure, showing a drawback of the early knight move.  This line illustrates why White is not posing any problems with slow moves like @@StartFEN@@rnbqkbnr/pp2pppp/8/2pp4/3P4/2N5/PPP1PPPP/R1BQKBNR w KQkq-6 0 3@@EndFEN@@  3.Bf4  or  3.Nf3  , which are similar. White's most interesting move is  3.e4  , which we'll focus on in the Quickstarter. }
3. e4
{ White's most aggressive move, playing the Albin's Counter-Gambit with an extra tempo. The Albin's arises after @@StartFEN@@rnbqkbnr/pppppppp/8/8/8/8/PPPPPPPP/RNBQKBNR w KQkq - 0 1@@EndFEN@@  1.d4  d5  2.c4  e5  and has a dubious reputation.  Black does not have enough compensation after  3.dxe5  d4  4.Nf3  Nc6  5.a3  or  5.Nbd2  , which both grant White a sizeable advantage. White has an extra tempo, which changes the evaluation considerably. While the Albin's is dubious, 3.e4 can lead to interesting play and equal chances if White is precise. }
3... dxe4
{ Just as in the Albin's @@StartFEN@@rnbqkbnr/pppppppp/8/8/8/8/PPPPPPPP/RNBQKBNR w KQkq - 0 1@@EndFEN@@  1.d4  d5  2.c4  e5  3.dxe5  , taking the e-pawn is best. White's usual response is @@StartFEN@@rnbqkbnr/pp2pppp/8/2p5/3Pp3/2N5/PPP2PPP/R1BQKBNR w KQkq - 0 4@@EndFEN@@  4.d5  , but we'll briefly check the alternatives  4.Nge2  and  4.Bb5+  in the 1.d4 d5 − 2nd Move Sidelines chapter. }
4. d5 { White is gaining space and controls the important squares c6 and e6. }
4... Nf6
{ We develop the knight and cover e4, the best move for sure. Now White has some choice. To get the most out of the opening, we need to react flexibly. Here's an overview.   A@@EndBracket@@  5.Bg5  is a great practical upside for Black.  5.Bg5  happens to be the most popular and ambitious move, but it's one of the worst moves that White can play, objectively speaking. The key point is that we frequently have the option of playing ...h6, intending to answer Bh4 with ...g5 and ...Bg7, speeding up our development. White often intends queenside castling, which we are happy to answer with ...a6 and ...b5, giving Black all the fun.   B@@EndBracket@@  5.Bf4  looks better than 5.Bg5 for White. We recommend immediately starting queenside play  with ...a6 and ...b5 against it.   C@@EndBracket@@  5.f3  turns White's opening into a 'real gambit'. We'll take the f-pawn and enter the complications of being a pawn up. White's compensation is insufficient.   D@@EndBracket@@  5.Nge2  seems to be the best move for White, but it is rather unpopular. This is somewhat surprising, as in the Albin's @@StartFEN@@rnbqkbnr/pppppppp/8/8/8/8/PPPPPPPP/RNBQKBNR w KQkq - 0 1@@EndFEN@@  1.d4  d5  c4  e5  3.dxe5  d4  4.Nf3  Nc6  5.a3  Nge7  or @@StartFEN@@r1bqkbnr/ppp2ppp/2n5/4P3/2Pp4/5N2/PP2PPPP/RNBQKB1R w KQkq - 2 5@@EndFEN@@  5.g3  Nge7  are well-known lines.  White's idea is simple: playing Ng3, trying to regain the e4-pawn.  We suggest replying with @@StartFEN@@rnbqkb1r/pp2pppp/5n2/2pP4/4p3/2N5/PPP1NPPP/R1BQKB1R b KQkq - 2 5@@EndFEN@@  5...g6  6.Ng3  Bg7  7.Ngxe4  Nbd7  , which leads to equal chances. }
5. Bg5
{ The bishop move is by far White's most popular move, but it is a welcome sight. With precise play, Black should get the better chances now. }
5... Nbd7
{ An important move order detail. We don't want to play ...g6 here against White's main reply,  6.Qd2  , but  rather ...h6 and ...g5! On the queenside, a quick expansion with ...a6 and ...b5 is on the agenda too.   It is interesting to compare the current position with the Albin, when @@StartFEN@@rnbqkbnr/pppppppp/8/8/8/8/PPPPPPPP/RNBQKBNR w KQkq - 0 1@@EndFEN@@  1.d4  d5  2.c4  e5  3.dxe5  d4  4.Nf3  Nc6  5.Nbd2  is a good line for White. Black should play  5...Nge7  against it, while  5...Bg4  is  assessed as more or less losing for Black, due to the expansion plans with h3 & g4 and a3 & b4. Here we play in the same way, but a tempo down − still a large advantage for us! }
6. Qd2 h6 7. Bf4
{ Slightly more resilient than  7.Bh4  g5  8.Bg3  a6  ,  intending ...b5. Black has a strong initiative and an extra pawn on top! }
7... a6
{ We start our queenside attack immediately, with ...b5 coming next. This not only gains space but undermines the position of the c3-knight, thus putting serious pressure on the d5-pawn. We see no way now for White to maintain reasonable chances. }
8. O-O-O
{ In the spirit of the opening, we certainly welcome the move. Stockfish instead suggests  8.Nge2  , but after  8...b5  9.Ng3  Bb7  10.Ngxe4  Qa5  Black is clearly better too. At least White's king is not in the direct line of fire compared to 8.O-O-O. }
8... b5 9. f3 Qa5
{ Black is also more or less winning with  9...Bb7  or  9...g5  . } 10. Kb1 Bb7
{ White's center is falling apart, as in the following line. } 11. Qe1
{ Still a tricky idea, as we should avoid  11...b4??  12.Nxe4  ,  when Nd6+ will be a cold shower. }
11... e3 12. Qxe3 { Or  12.Bxe3  b4  13.Ne4  Bxd5  ,  winning the d-pawn. }
12... g5
{ This is very strong, as is  12...O-O-O  , which strengthens  the ...b4 threat. }
13. Bg3 Bg7
{ Black has a great attack against White's king and the weak d-pawn as a target. White is in terrible shape here. }
*

[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "1. Noteboom 4.Nc3 dxc4 − 5th Moves"]
[Black "Noteboom 4.Nc3 dxc4 5.Bg5 #1"]
[Result "*"]

1. d4 d5 2. c4 e6 3. Nf3 c6 4. Nc3 dxc4
{ The Noteboom Variation, named after Dutchman Daniel Noteboom. Noteboom died of pneumonia at just 21 years of age, but he lives on in chess history as his name is forever attached to this variation. He gained international fame at the Hamburg Olympiad of 1930, where he scored 11.5/15, defeating some leading players in the process. It is in this period that he started to experiment with the variation we are discussing in this course.  We capture the pawn on c4 and intend to hold on to it with all our might, with moves like ...b7-b5 and ...Bf8-b4. In the main variations, this will eventually lead to positions that are very unbalanced and of great complexity. If that isn't good enough news already; from a theoretical perspective, Black is in fine shape as well, meaning we have no reason to shy away from playing this line. }
5. Bg5
{ I made this move myself on a couple of occasions and visually, it is certainly appealing. White already brings the third piece into the game while Black has only resorted to pawn moves. In reality though, this system is very harmless. White is yet to win back the pawn on c4 and the time that requires will allow Black to get mobilized as well. }
5... Be7
{ For people with a materialistic nature, the move  5...f6  may look promising, but it is a serious weakening of Black's position. Following  6.Bd2  b5  7.a4  b4  8.Ne4  , practice has shown that White is doing fantastic here.   More serious is  5...Qc7  ,  which has the same idea of trying to hang on to the extra pawn with ...b7-b5 but has the upside of not weakening the kingside structure. This is certainly playable, though I think the text move is simpler. }
6. Bxe7 Nxe7
{ Simplest. Black recaptures the bishop and simultaneously brings the knight into the game.   The alternative  6...Qxe7  has always had a bad reputation due to  7.e4  b5  8.e5  but this may in fact not be that clear after for instance  8...Nh6  when Black prepares to castle and is always ready to meet a future Ne4-d6 with ...Nh6-f5. White is probably better off playing the more  modest @@StartFEN@@rnb1k1nr/pp2qppp/2p1p3/8/2pP4/2N2N2/PP2PPPP/R2QKB1R w KQkq - 0 7@@EndFEN@@  7.e3  b5  8.a4  , which does seem to give good compensation for the pawn as Black experiences some discomfort on the queenside. }
7. e4 { Gambit-style play is not very effective here. } 7... b5 8. a4 Bb7
{ Black holds a pleasant advantage already. } 9. axb5 cxb5 10. Nxb5 Bxe4 11.
Bxc4 O-O { White is left with an ugly isolated pawn. } *

