[Result "*"]

1. d4 d5 2. c4 e6 3. Nf3 c6 4. Nc3 dxc4
{ The Noteboom Variation, named after Dutchman Daniel Noteboom. Noteboom died of pneumonia at just 21 years of age, but he lives on in chess history as his name is forever attached to this variation. He gained international fame at the Hamburg Olympiad of 1930, where he scored 11.5/15, defeating some leading players in the process. It is in this period that he started to experiment with the variation we are discussing in this course.  We capture the pawn on c4 and intend to hold on to it with all our might, with moves like ...b7-b5 and ...Bf8-b4. In the main variations, this will eventually lead to positions that are very unbalanced and of great complexity. If that isn't good enough news already; from a theoretical perspective, Black is in fine shape as well, meaning we have no reason to shy away from playing this line. }
5. Bg5
{ I made this move myself on a couple of occasions and visually, it is certainly appealing. White already brings the third piece into the game while Black has only resorted to pawn moves. In reality though, this system is very harmless. White is yet to win back the pawn on c4 and the time that requires will allow Black to get mobilized as well. }
5... Be7
{ For people with a materialistic nature, the move  5...f6  may look promising, but it is a serious weakening of Black's position. Following  6.Bd2  b5  7.a4  b4  8.Ne4  , practice has shown that White is doing fantastic here.   More serious is  5...Qc7  ,  which has the same idea of trying to hang on to the extra pawn with ...b7-b5 but has the upside of not weakening the kingside structure. This is certainly playable, though I think the text move is simpler. }
6. Bxe7 Nxe7
{ Simplest. Black recaptures the bishop and simultaneously brings the knight into the game.   The alternative  6...Qxe7  has always had a bad reputation due to  7.e4  b5  8.e5  but this may in fact not be that clear after for instance  8...Nh6  when Black prepares to castle and is always ready to meet a future Ne4-d6 with ...Nh6-f5. White is probably better  of playing the more modest @@StartFEN@@rnb1k1nr/pp2qppp/2p1p3/8/2pP4/2N2N2/PP2PPPP/R2QKB1R w KQkq - 0 7@@EndFEN@@  7.e3  b5  8.a4  , which does seem to give good compensation for the pawn as Black experiences some discomfort on the queenside. }
7. a4 Nd5
{ Black has other moves as well, but this one threatens to play ...b7-b5 and keep the pawn, therefore limiting White's options. }
8. e4 { Overly ambitious. } 8... Nxc3 9. bxc3 b5
{ Black has an extra pawn and with two minor pieces exchanged, White's dynamic options are limited. }
