{ I made this move myself on a couple of occasions and visually, it is certainly appealing. White already brings the third piece into the game while Black has only resorted to pawn moves. In reality though, this system is very harmless. White is yet to win back the pawn on c4 and the time that requires will allow Black to get mobilized as well. }
5... Be7
{ For people with a materialistic nature, the move  5...f6  may look promising, but it is a serious weakening of Black's position. Following  6.Bd2  b5  7.a4  b4  8.Ne4  , practice has shown that White is doing fantastic here.   More serious is  5...Qc7  ,  which has the same idea of trying to hang on to the extra pawn with ...b7-b5 but has the upside of not weakening the kingside structure. This is certainly playable, though I think the text move is simpler. }
6. Bxe7 Nxe7
{ Simplest. Black recaptures the bishop and simultaneously brings the knight into the game.   The alternative  6...Qxe7  has always had a bad reputation due to  7.e4  b5  8.e5  but this may in fact not be that clear after for instance  8...Nh6  when Black prepares to castle and is always ready to meet a future Ne4-d6 with ...Nh6-f5. White is probably better  of playing the more modest @@StartFEN@@rnb1k1nr/pp2qppp/2p1p3/8/2pP4/2N2N2/PP2PPPP/R2QKB1R w KQkq - 0 7@@EndFEN@@  7.e3  b5  8.a4  , which does seem to give good compensation for the pawn as Black experiences some discomfort on the queenside. }
7. a4 Nd5
{ Black has other moves as well, but this one threatens to play ...b7-b5 and keep the pawn, therefore limiting White's options. }
8. a5 { In order to take en passant the moment Black pushes ...b7-b5. } 8... c5
{ Black can still play  8...b5  but after  9.axb6  it is a pity that our queenside pawns have become isolated. }
9. e4 Nb4
{ Introducing the threat of capturing on d4 twice, as there will be a check on c2 in the end. Instead  9...Nxc3  10.bxc3  merely strengthens White's center. }
10. dxc5 Qxd1+ 11. Kxd1 { 11.Rxd1  N8a6  is very similar to 11.Kxd1. } 11...
N8a6
{ Black has a very comfortable endgame. The next moves are ...Na6xc5, ...Ke8-e7, ...Bc8-d7 followed by centralizing the rooks. Though the endgame is probably bordering on equality, I'd rather be Black. }
*

[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "1. Noteboom 4.Nc3 dxc4 − 5th Moves"]
[Black "Noteboom 4.Nc3 dxc4 5.e4 #1"]
[Result "*"]

1. d4 d5 2. c4 e6 3. Nf3 c6 4. Nc3 dxc4
{ The Noteboom Variation, named after Dutchman Daniel Noteboom. Noteboom died of pneumonia at just 21 years of age, but he lives on in chess history as his name is forever attached to this variation. He gained international fame at the Hamburg Olympiad of 1930, where he scored 11.5/15, defeating some leading players in the process. It is in this period that he started to experiment with the variation we are discussing in this course.  We capture the pawn on c4 and intend to hold on to it with all our might, with moves like ...b7-b5 and ...Bf8-b4. In the main variations, this will eventually lead to positions that are very unbalanced and of great complexity. If that isn't good enough news already; from a theoretical perspective, Black is in fine shape as well, meaning we have no reason to shy away from playing this line. }
5. e4 b5 6. a4 Bb4
{ 6...b4  is certainly a viable option here but we prefer to keep the burden on our memory down by transposing to another variation. After @@StartFEN@@rnbqk1nr/p4ppp/2p1p3/1p6/PbpPP3/2N2N2/1P3PPP/R1BQKB1R w KQkq - 1 7@@EndFEN@@  7.Be2  , we reach the same position as in the 5.a4 move order. }
*

[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "1. Noteboom 4.Nc3 dxc4 − 5th Moves"]
[Black "Noteboom 4.Nc3 dxc4 5.e4 #2"]
[Result "*"]

1. d4 d5 2. c4 e6 3. Nf3 c6 4. Nc3 dxc4
{ The Noteboom Variation, named after Dutchman Daniel Noteboom. Noteboom died of pneumonia at just 21 years of age, but he lives on in chess history as his name is forever attached to this variation. He gained international fame at the Hamburg Olympiad of 1930, where he scored 11.5/15, defeating some leading players in the process. It is in this period that he started to experiment with the variation we are discussing in this course.  We capture the pawn on c4 and intend to hold on to it with all our might, with moves like ...b7-b5 and ...Bf8-b4. In the main variations, this will eventually lead to positions that are very unbalanced and of great complexity. If that isn't good enough news already; from a theoretical perspective, Black is in fine shape as well, meaning we have no reason to shy away from playing this line. }
5. e4 b5 6. a3
{ While preventing ...b5-b4, this move is not advisable as it loses time and momentum. It's been played in plenty of amateur games though, which is why we briefly discuss it. }
6... Nf6 { Simple development. } 7. Bg5 Be7
{ 7...Nbd7  is fine as well since  8.e5  h6  9.Bh4  g5  10.Nxg5  hxg5  11.Bxg5  is an excellent version for Black of the Botvinnik Variation. The further  11...Qa5  12.exf6  b4!  shows one of the upsides of having a2-a3 and ...Nb8-d7 included. }
8. e5 Nd5 9. Bxe7 Nxc3
{ 9...Qxe7  10.Ne4  O-O  also gives Black a great advantage. Yes,  11.Nd6  is a great square for the knight, but after  11...Nd7  and ...f6 next, White's center is collapsing. }
10. Bxd8 { 10.bxc3  Qxe7  is a healthy extra pawn for Black. } 10... Nxd1 11.
Rxd1 Kxd8 { Black's position may be called technically winning. } *

[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "1. Noteboom 4.Nc3 dxc4 − 5th Moves"]
[Black "Noteboom 4.Nc3 dxc4 5.e4 #3"]
[Result "*"]

1. d4 d5 2. c4 e6 3. Nf3 c6 4. Nc3 dxc4
{ The Noteboom Variation, named after Dutchman Daniel Noteboom. Noteboom died of pneumonia at just 21 years of age, but he lives on in chess history as his name is forever attached to this variation. He gained international fame at the Hamburg Olympiad of 1930, where he scored 11.5/15, defeating some leading players in the process. It is in this period that he started to experiment with the variation we are discussing in this course.  We capture the pawn on c4 and intend to hold on to it with all our might, with moves like ...b7-b5 and ...Bf8-b4. In the main variations, this will eventually lead to positions that are very unbalanced and of great complexity. If that isn't good enough news already; from a theoretical perspective, Black is in fine shape as well, meaning we have no reason to shy away from playing this line. }
5. e4 b5 6. Be2
{ A fundamentally different approach compared to @@StartFEN@@rnbqkbnr/pp3ppp/2p1p3/8/2pP4/2N2N2/PP2PPPP/R1BQKB1R w KQkq - 0 5@@EndFEN@@  5.a4  Bb4  6.e4  b5  7.Be2  .  In this case, White, at least for now, refrains from playing a2-a4 and often pushes b2-b3 instead. That detail means the differences with 5.a4 are quite significant. I @@StartBracket@@Erwin@@EndBracket@@ was recently confronted with this move in the Wijk aan Zee tournament which alerted me to the fact that I had not yet analyzed it for the course! }
6... Nf6
{ I chose the more common  6...Bb7  7.O-O  Nf6  which is a pretty serious battleground these days. In 2019, for instance, Daniil Dubov introduced the interesting idea of  8.Rb1  intending b2-b3. Besides this modern  invention,  8.b3  ,  8.e5  ,  8.Bg5  and  8.Qc2  are moves as well. We are quite happily sidestepping all of this with the text move. }
7. O-O a5
{ It took us a while to warm up to this move, but it does make perfect sense. As White has omitted to play a2-a4, we have the opportunity to make this bold move on the queenside, which carries the positional threat of locking up the queenside with ...a5-a4. }
8. b3 { It's uncertain whether White can retain even equality with this move. }
8... Bb4
{ The most principled way to fight against White's previous move − the unstable knight is immediately attacked and we develop our bishop in the process. }
9. e5
{ A direct hit that is easy to parry, though, as we will see, not in a blitz game. }
9... Bxc3 10. exf6 gxf6
{ Simple and efficient. Instead,  10...Bxa1?  11.fxg7  Rg8  12.Bg5  f6  13.Bh6  Bc3  14.Qc2  Qe7  15.Qxh7  Qf7  16.Ne5  fxe5  17.Bh5+-  gave White a winning game in Harsha-Can, Chess.com blitz 2020. }
11. Rb1 cxb3 12. Rxb3 b4
{ White's compensation for two pawns is very vague at best. We'd like to exchange bishops on a6 next and claim a big advantage. }
