[Round "?"]
[White "1. Noteboom 4.Nc3 dxc4 − 5th Moves"]
[Black "Noteboom 4.Nc3 dxc4 5.e4 #9"]
[Result "*"]

1. d4 d5 2. c4 e6 3. Nf3 c6 4. Nc3 dxc4
{ The Noteboom Variation, named after Dutchman Daniel Noteboom. Noteboom died of pneumonia at just 21 years of age, but he lives on in chess history as his name is forever attached to this variation. He gained international fame at the Hamburg Olympiad of 1930, where he scored 11.5/15, defeating some leading players in the process. It is in this period that he started to experiment with the variation we are discussing in this course.  We capture the pawn on c4 and intend to hold on to it with all our might, with moves like ...b7-b5 and ...Bf8-b4. In the main variations, this will eventually lead to positions that are very unbalanced and of great complexity. If that isn't good enough news already; from a theoretical perspective, Black is in fine shape as well, meaning we have no reason to shy away from playing this line. }
5. e4 b5 6. Be2
{ A fundamentally different approach compared to @@StartFEN@@rnbqkbnr/pp3ppp/2p1p3/8/2pP4/2N2N2/PP2PPPP/R1BQKB1R w KQkq - 0 5@@EndFEN@@  5.a4  Bb4  6.e4  b5  7.Be2  .  In this case, White, at least for now, refrains from playing a2-a4 and often pushes b2-b3 instead. That detail means the differences with 5.a4 are quite significant. I @@StartBracket@@Erwin@@EndBracket@@ was recently confronted with this move in the Wijk aan Zee tournament which alerted me to the fact that I had not yet analyzed it for the course! }
6... Nf6
{ I chose the more common  6...Bb7  7.O-O  Nf6  which is a pretty serious battleground these days. In 2019, for instance, Daniil Dubov introduced the interesting idea of  8.Rb1  intending b2-b3. Besides this modern  invention,  8.b3  ,  8.e5  ,  8.Bg5  and  8.Qc2  are moves as well. We are quite happily sidestepping all of this with the text move. }
7. O-O a5
{ It took us a while to warm up to this move, but it does make perfect sense. As White has omitted to play a2-a4, we have the opportunity to make this bold move on the queenside, which carries the positional threat of locking up the queenside with ...a5-a4. }
8. Qc2
{ A typical move, vacating the d1-square for the rook and further supporting queenside actions like a2-a4. }
8... a4
{ Fixing the queenside. We continue ...Be7 and ...O-O with a fine game. White will have to prove compensation for the pawn deficit. }
