[White "1. Noteboom 4.Nc3 dxc4 − 5th Moves"]
[Black "Noteboom 4.Nc3 dxc4 5.g3 #2"]
[Result "*"]

1. d4 d5 2. c4 e6 3. Nf3 c6 4. Nc3 dxc4
{ The Noteboom Variation, named after Dutchman Daniel Noteboom. Noteboom died of pneumonia at just 21 years of age, but he lives on in chess history as his name is forever attached to this variation. He gained international fame at the Hamburg Olympiad of 1930, where he scored 11.5/15, defeating some leading players in the process. It is in this period that he started to experiment with the variation we are discussing in this course.  We capture the pawn on c4 and intend to hold on to it with all our might, with moves like ...b7-b5 and ...Bf8-b4. In the main variations, this will eventually lead to positions that are very unbalanced and of great complexity. If that isn't good enough news already; from a theoretical perspective, Black is in fine shape as well, meaning we have no reason to shy away from playing this line. }
5. g3
{ Taking the game into Catalan territory. This setup shouldn't worry us too much. }
5... Nd7
{ It is more common to start with  5...Nf6  , but both moves lead to the same position so why  not prevent any Nf3-e5 jumps. Dangerous  is  5...b5  6.a4!  b4  7.Ne4  with good compensation for the pawn given the lead in development. This line is special in the sense that it forces us to change our usual approach. }
6. Bg2 Ngf6 7. O-O Be7
{ We continue normal development and will worry about the c-pawn later. Another heavily debated area is the position arising after  7...b5  8.e4  Bb7  9.e5  Nd5  10.Ng5  which is a very sharp battleground. Black is likely OK here, which can be seen if for instance the top-level game Kramnik-Anand, Shamkir 2015, but we prefer the easier text move. }
8. e4 O-O 9. a4
{ Recently employed by Daniil Dubov in the Russian Championship and therefore a move we have to take seriously. }
9... b5
{ Courtesy of Dubov's opponent, Maxim Matlakov, and rarely seen in practice. I @@StartBracket@@Erwin@@EndBracket@@ never liked the solution  9...e5  10.dxe5  Ng4  11.Bf4  Qa5  which has been played in numerous games. White continues  12.e6  fxe6  13.Qe2  and structurally speaking Black's position is suspicious. A sample line is  13...Nge5  14.Nxe5  Nxe5  15.Bxe5  Qxe5  16.Kh1!?  preparing to play f2-f4 followed by e4-e5 with lasting compensation. }
10. axb5 cxb5 11. d5 { Rare, but played by Daniel King. } 11... exd5
{ That game of King continued  11...Bc5  12.dxe6  @@StartBracket@@  12.e5!  was preferable@@EndBracket@@ @@StartFEN@@r1bq1rk1/p2n1ppp/4Pn2/1pb5/2p1P3/2N2NP1/1P3PBP/R1BQ1RK1 b - - 0 12@@EndFEN@@  12...fxe6  13.e5  Ng4  14.Ne4  Bb7  15.Nfg5  Nxf2  @@StartBracket@@  15...Bxe4!  was the way to go@@EndBracket@@ @@StartFEN@@r2q1rk1/pb1n2pp/4p3/1pb1P1N1/2p1N3/6P1/1P3nBP/R1BQ1RK1 w - - 0 16@@EndFEN@@  16.Nxf2  Rxf2  17.Rxf2  Bxf2+  18.Kxf2  Qf8+  19.Bf4  Qc5+  20.Ke2  and White went on to win in King-Kotronias, Dortmund 1989. }
12. exd5 { Threatening to win a piece with d5-d6. } 12... Bc5
{ 12...Qb6  is possible as well, though  13.Nd4  would anyway oblige us to  return the b5-pawn as d5-d6 is a big threat. }
13. Nxb5 Bb7 14. Nc3 Nb6
{ Black is rounding up the d5-pawn and has a comfortable game. } *

