[White "1. Noteboom 4.Nc3 dxc4 − 5th Moves"]
[Black "Noteboom 4.Nc3 dxc4 5.g3 #7"]
[Result "*"]

1. d4 d5 2. c4 e6 3. Nf3 c6 4. Nc3 dxc4
{ The Noteboom Variation, named after Dutchman Daniel Noteboom. Noteboom died of pneumonia at just 21 years of age, but he lives on in chess history as his name is forever attached to this variation. He gained international fame at the Hamburg Olympiad of 1930, where he scored 11.5/15, defeating some leading players in the process. It is in this period that he started to experiment with the variation we are discussing in this course.  We capture the pawn on c4 and intend to hold on to it with all our might, with moves like ...b7-b5 and ...Bf8-b4. In the main variations, this will eventually lead to positions that are very unbalanced and of great complexity. If that isn't good enough news already; from a theoretical perspective, Black is in fine shape as well, meaning we have no reason to shy away from playing this line. }
5. g3
{ Taking the game into Catalan territory. This setup shouldn't worry us too much. }
5... Nd7
{ It is more common to start with  5...Nf6  , but both moves lead to the same position so why  not prevent any Nf3-e5 jumps. Dangerous  is  5...b5  6.a4!  b4  7.Ne4  with good compensation for the pawn given the lead in development. This line is special in the sense that it forces us to change our usual approach. }
6. Bg2 Ngf6 7. O-O Be7
{ We continue normal development and will worry about the c-pawn later. Another heavily debated area is the position arising after  7...b5  8.e4  Bb7  9.e5  Nd5  10.Ng5  which is a very sharp battleground. Black is likely OK here, which can be seen if for instance the top-level game Kramnik-Anand, Shamkir 2015, but we prefer the easier text move. }
8. e4 O-O 9. Bf4
{ White is still not bothered to win back the pawn on c4 and simply develops the last undeveloped piece. }
9... b5 { Not just protecting the pawn on c4, but also preparing ...Bc8-b7. }
10. d5 { White has to play it fast, before Black fully consolidates. } 10...
Qb6
{ Both  10...cxd5  and  10...e5  are valid alternatives but the text move does the job equally well. }
11. dxc6 Nc5 12. Nd2
{ Both  12.e5  Nd5  with the idea  13.Nxd5  exd5  14.Qxd5  Rd8!  trapping the queen, and @@StartFEN@@r1b2rk1/p3bppp/1qP1pn2/1pn5/2p1PB2/2N2NP1/PP3PBP/R2Q1RK1 w - - 1 12@@EndFEN@@  12.Ne5  Ba6!?  preparing queenside play, don't look too scary. }
12... Nd3
{ The classic octopus, as a knight posted on d3 @@StartBracket@@or a white knight on d6@@EndBracket@@ is called.  12...Qxc6  13.e5!  Nd5  14.Nxd5  exd5  15.Nxc4!  would backfire badly. }
13. e5 Nd5 14. a4 N5xf4
{ It takes a while for the engines to approve this way of playing, but it is in fact much more straightforward compared to the more common alternative.  14...Nxb2  15.Qc2  b4  16.Nxd5  exd5  is very messy. }
15. gxf4 Ba6
{ The first in a long sequence of forced moves. The natural  15...b4  loses to  16.Nxc4!  Qd4  17.Nb5!  Qxc4  (what else?)  18.b3  Qxf4  19.Qxd3  and the c-pawn should decide the issue. }
16. axb5 Bxb5 17. Nxb5 Qxb5 18. Qa4 Qxa4
{ Not much choice once again.  18...Qxb2?  19.Nxc4  Qd4  20.Nd6  is hopeless because of that same c-pawn. }
19. Rxa4 Nxb2 20. Ra2
{ From afar, the engine believes this endgame to be much better for White. Upon closer inspection, it changes its 'mind'. }
20... c3 21. Ne4 Nd3 { With the idea of taking on f4 or jumping to b4. } 22.
Rc2 Bb4
{ Instead,  22...Nxf4  23.Nxc3  gives White excellent compensation for the pawn. Once again, the c-pawn is the key element in the position and White has a lot of pieces to support the pawn to march onwards. }
23. Nxc3 Bxc3 24. c7
{ Slightly more venomous than  24.Rxc3  Nxf4  which would oblige White  to deal with the threat on e2 and give Black  the time, after  25.Bf3  , to play  25...Rfc8  26.c7  Nd5  , when Black is on the good side of equality. }
24... Rac8 25. Rxc3 Nxf4
{ Black is in fine shape in the endgame. Next, we will eliminate the strong bishop on g2. A sample line is  26.Re1  Nxg2  27.Kxg2  f6  with a drawish rook endgame. The c-pawn is far advanced, but won't make it much further! }
