20. Nxf5
{ White has won a piece, but it’s obvious that given the threats on the long diagonal, the game is far from over. }
20... Rfd8
{ Black can also start with  20...Nf3+  21.Kh1  Rad8  22.Nd6  Qa8!  with excellent compensation, but the rook move is equally tricky,  keeping the check on f3 in reserve. }
21. Nd6 Qc6
{ Time to end the line. White is still a piece up but the knight on d6 is far from stable and a check on f3 is in the air.   The engine proclaims the famous triple zeros, with  22.Qh5  Nf3+  23.Kh1  Rd7  , when it proposes to move the  bishop to either b4 or a3. We think this position plays much easier with Black. }
