{ Forcing White to put the cards on the table. Given time, Black will be a pawn up. Dzagnidze once played  11...a5  which also did not look bad, as  12.axb5  O-O  13.b6  Nd7  14.Na4  c5  15.dxc5  Nxc5  16.Nxc5  Bxc5  17.Bxa5  Nc6  saw many pieces disappearing from the board. The players agreed on a draw on move 43 in Kashlinskaya-Dzagnidze, Lausanne 2020. }
12. axb5 axb5 13. Nxb5
{ An attempt to solve the problems in the position in a tactical fashion. }
13... Bxd2 14. Na3
{ This is White's point. Since both bishops are hanging White will win back the piece. The problem is that in the process, too many pieces will get exchanged. }
14... Ba6 15. Bxa6 Nxa6 16. Nxd2 Qxd4 17. Nf3 Qb4
{ Black is comfortable. A possible continuation is @@StartFEN@@r3k2r/4nppp/n1p1p3/8/1q2P3/NQ3N2/5PPP/R4RK1 w kq - 2 18@@EndFEN@@  18.Qxb4  Nxb4  19.Nc2  Na6  20.Nb4  Nc7  21.Rxa8+  Nxa8  22.Ra1  O-O  with an equal endgame. }
