6. e4
{ In his excellent 2012 book The Triangle System, Scherbakov mentioned that this system may be underestimated. Indeed, it looks like one of those modern options that a creative player like for instance Daniil Dubov may easily jump on. White is not aiming at regaining the sacrificed pawn, but instead grabs the center and hopes that will prove enough compensation. }
6... b5 7. Be2 Bb7
{ The general rule is knights before bishops but this is certainly an exception! After  7...Nf6  White is ready to invest another pawn with  8.O-O!  Following  8...Bxc3  9.bxc3  Nxe4  10.Qc2  Nd6  11.Ba3  O-O  12.h4!  threatening Nf3-g5, White was doing great in Valenzuela Gomez-Bilguun, Sitges 2017. Black is missing the dark-squared bishop. }
8. O-O a6
{ Black's last two moves are aimed at safeguarding the queenside. Next up is developing the g8-knight and castling kingside. }
9. Bd2 Ne7
{ A bit safer compared to  9...Nf6  10.e5  Nd5  11.Ne4  which gives White decent compensation. Matters aren't that clear after for instance  11...Be7  12.b3!?  @@StartBracket@@  12.Bg5  O-O  13.Bxe7  Qxe7  14.Nd6  looks promising, but  14...Rd8  followed  by ...Rxd6, is excellent for Black, with two pawns for the exchange.@@EndBracket@@ }
10. b3
{ Almost universally played. Instead of trying to win back a pawn, White now exchanges a pair, in order to gain the d3-square and a tempo on the bishop. }
10... cxb3 11. Qxb3 Ba5
{ Forcing White to put the cards on the table. Given time, Black will be a pawn up. Dzagnidze once played  11...a5  which also did not look bad, as  12.axb5  O-O  13.b6  Nd7  14.Na4  c5  15.dxc5  Nxc5  16.Nxc5  Bxc5  17.Bxa5  Nc6  saw many pieces disappearing from the board. The players agreed on a draw on move 43 in Kashlinskaya-Dzagnidze, Lausanne 2020. }
12. axb5 axb5 13. Rfd1 { Aiming for the d4-d5 break. } 13... O-O
{ Getting the king out of the center is rarely a bad idea. } 14. Bg5 Nd7 15. d5
{ The expected break. It's once again important to note that White has to go for concrete actions like these in order to justify the loss of a pawn earlier on. Slow play isn't going to cut it. }
15... Nc5
{ The start of a forced sequence leading to a level game.  15...exd5  16.exd5  h6  is possible too, and largely a matter of taste. }
16. Qc2 Bxc3 17. Rxa8 Bxa8
{ Now  18.Qxc3  Nxe4  is plain bad for White, meaning there is a split between three moves with the d-pawn. }
18. d6 f6 { An excellent response, breaking the pin. } 19. Qxc3 Nxe4 20. Qe3
Nxg5 21. Nxg5 fxg5 22. Qxe6+
{ Of course much stronger than  22.dxe7  Qxe7  when Black would essentially be three pawns up. }
22... Rf7 23. dxe7 Qxe7
{ Black is in good shape as @@StartFEN@@b5k1/4qrpp/2p1Q3/1p4p1/8/8/4BPPP/3R2K1 w - - 0 24@@EndFEN@@  24.Qxe7  Rxe7  attacks the bishop on e2, meaning White has no time to pick up the bishop on a8. }
