{ Here we get to see the point behind Black's 7th move. While White has won back the sacrificed pawn, Black has managed to get connected passed pawns on the queenside. }
12. Bb2
{ The correct square for the bishop. Right now it is hiding behind the d4-pawn, but it only takes the d-pawn one move to turn that b2-bishop into a monster on the long diagonal. }
12... Nf6 13. Bd3
{ Developing the bishop and preparing to castle. The bishop is best placed on d3 where it has an influence on the important e4-square. It is this unbalanced position that has mesmerized generations for decades. }
13... O-O
{ 13...Be4  is a move we will see a lot more of, but here it comes too early. White replies  14.Bxe4  Nxe4  15.Qa4+!  Qd7  16.Qc2  with the double threat of  taking the knight on e4 and Nf3-e5. Following  16...Qb7  17.O-O  O-O  18.Ra4!  White  prepares Rfa1 with huge pressure on the queenside. }
14. Qc2
{ This move is rare in this exact position, and is usually played after 14.O-O. We, however, meet  14.O-O  with  14...Be4  , and the text move prevents that idea and forces us back into one of the traditional main lines. }
14... Nbd7 15. O-O
{ Now we are back in the main line, but there is an upside to that. White has already committed to the move Qc2, which is not considered the biggest test of the Noteboom Variation.  One can still find hundreds of games in the database with this move, and the sharp nature of the position alone should already be enough reason to take it very seriously. White intends to play e3-e4 and essentially blow Black away in the center. }
15... Qc7
{ In this day and age there is no more room for dogmatic thinking. The engine has shown us that we need to be flexible in our thinking and we are reminded of that in the line  15...Bxf3  16.gxf3  Qc7  . While we will not be advocating this line as our main recommendation, we do feel it's entirely playable.   To take on f3 would likely have been dismissed some time ago, but we have learned that when engines claim something is playable, we better have a look! Black's play is very simple, the next moves will be ...Rf8-b8 and ...Nd7-f8-g6 more or less regardless of what White is up to. Of course, White's bishops and center look promising, but White's slightly weakened king and Black's queenside passers should compensate for that. Definitely worth having a look at it! }
16. e4
{ The most principled follow-up, creating the immediate threat of e4-e5. }
16... e5
{ A typical counterthrust. We immediately try to get hold of the c5-square. }
17. c5 Rfc8
{ A fresh idea, put in practice by Russian Grandmaster Boris Savchenko. It should be said that there is nothing wrong with  17...exd4  either. }
18. Rfe1 exd4 19. e5 Qxc5
{ The tactical justification behind Black's last few moves. Instead of removing the knight from f6, Black creates a counterthreat. }
20. Qd2
{ The best try, avoiding the queen exchange and thereby keeping attacking options alive. }
20... Bxf3
{ Safest as both  20...Ne8  21.Nxd4  Nxe5  22.Nf5  and @@StartFEN@@r1r3k1/1b1n1ppp/5n2/p1q1P3/1p1p4/3B1N2/1B1Q1PPP/R3R1K1 b - - 1 20@@EndFEN@@  20...Nd5  21.Bxd4  are messier. }
21. exf6 Bc6
{ The correct square to retreat to. Instead,  21...Bb7  22.Bxd4  Qd5  23.Be4!  is problematic following  23...Qb5  24.Bxb7  Qxb7  25.Qg5  with a mating attack. }
22. Bxd4 Qd5 23. Be4 Qh5
{ Highlighting the difference with 21...Bb7. With the bishop protected on c6, the Black queen is not bound to its defense. }
*

