{ For fearless souls, pawn snatching may be an option, but we find it very hard to recommend this greedy move.   14...Qc7  looks like an interesting idea, the point being  15.O-O  a4  which is a pawn White  can't take because of ... Qc7-c6. White doesn't  need to though, as  16.d5  looks very attractive.   14...Qb6  has the upside that  15.O-O  a4  16.d5  is less dangerous, but @@StartFEN@@rn3rk1/1b3ppp/1q2pn2/p7/1pPP4/3BP3/1B1N1PPP/R2QK2R w KQ - 6 15@@EndFEN@@  15.Bc2  is fine too. Initially, engines have you make the wrong decision here, with  15...b3  before realizing  16.Bxb3  a4  17.Ba3!  axb3  18.Bxf8  Rxa1  19.Qxa1  b2  20.Qb1  Kxf8  21.O-O  is excellent for White. Qb1-c2 and Rf1-b1 are the next moves, picking up the b2-pawn. }
15. Rg1 Bb7 16. d5
{ White gets very serious compensation for the pawn. The power of the rook on g1 and the bishops staring down our king should trigger all alarm bells to go off. }
*

[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "4. Noteboom − Main Line"]
[Black "Noteboom 13.Bd3 O-O 14.Nd2 − Main Line #2"]
[Result "*"]

1. d4 d5 2. c4 e6 3. Nf3 c6 4. Nc3 dxc4
{ The Noteboom Variation, named after Dutchman Daniel Noteboom. Noteboom died of pneumonia at just 21 years of age, but he lives on in chess history as his name is forever attached to this variation. He gained international fame at the Hamburg Olympiad of 1930, where he scored 11.5/15, defeating some leading players in the process. It is in this period that he started to experiment with the variation we are discussing in this course.  We capture the pawn on c4 and intend to hold on to it with all our might, with moves like ...b7-b5 and ...Bf8-b4. In the main variations, this will eventually lead to positions that are very unbalanced and of great complexity. If that isn't good enough news already; from a theoretical perspective, Black is in fine shape as well, meaning we have no reason to shy away from playing this line. }
5. a4
{ A standard move, making it harder for Black to hold on to the c4-pawn by preempting the move ...b7-b5. }
5... Bb4
{ Pinning the knight in order to get the move ...b7-b5 back on the cards. Here we see a major difference with the Slav @@StartFEN@@rnbqkbnr/pppppppp/8/8/8/8/PPPPPPPP/RNBQKBNR w KQkq - 0 1@@EndFEN@@  1.d4  d5  2.c4  c6  3.Nf3  Nf6  4.Nc3  dxc4  5.a4  where Black also takes on c4 but is unable to hold on to that pawn for very long.  Having played ...e7-e6 instead of ...Ng8-f6 allows us to pin the knight on c3 with 5...Bb4 and follow it up with ...b7-b5, thus making it much harder for White to regain the pawn. }
6. e3
{ 6.e4  may look more logical, taking full control of the center, but it also leaves that same center more vulnerable to attack. That shows in the line  6...b5  7.Bd2  a5  8.axb5  Bxc3  9.Bxc3?!  cxb5  10.b3  Nf6!  and Black already has an advantage because  the attack on e4 is hard to counter. In this line, the e-pawn is much better placed on e3 instead of e4. That's why, as we have seen, 6.e4 is usually played with the idea of playing a gambit where White is not thinking about regaining the sacrificed pawn. }
6... b5 7. Bd2
{ Not only developing the bishop but once again pressuring the pawn on b5. }
7... a5
{ It is important to get the move orders right. For all the subtle nuances, please see the Informational dedicated to this topic. }
8. axb5 Bxc3 9. Bxc3 cxb5 10. b3
{ Winning back the pawn and slowly taking us to the main position of the Noteboom Variation. }
10... Bb7 11. bxc4
{ White can also start with  11.Bb2  transposing after  11...Nf6  12.bxc4  b4  . }
11... b4
{ Here we get to see the point behind Black's 7th move. While White has won back the sacrificed pawn, Black has managed to get connected passed pawns on the queenside. }
12. Bb2
{ The correct square for the bishop. Right now it is hiding behind the d4-pawn, but it only takes the d-pawn one move to turn that b2-bishop into a monster on the long diagonal. }
12... Nf6 13. Bd3
{ Developing the bishop and preparing to castle. The bishop is best placed on d3 where it has an influence on the important e4-square. It is this unbalanced position that has mesmerized generations for decades. }
13... O-O
{ 13...Be4  is a move we will see a lot more of, but here it comes too early. White replies  14.Bxe4  Nxe4  15.Qa4+!  Qd7  16.Qc2  with the double threat of  taking the knight on e4 and Nf3-e5. Following  16...Qb7  17.O-O  O-O  18.Ra4!  White  prepares Rfa1 with huge pressure on the queenside. }
14. Nd2
{ An extremely rare move, but maybe a very smart one! By delaying castling White prevents us from bringing the bishop to e4 and wants to transpose back to the main lines, by castling on the next move. }
14... Nbd7 { We have no real choice but to oblige. } 15. O-O Nc5
{ Another surprise, though a recent trend in correspondence chess.   15...Qc7  used to be more or less universally played when  16.f4  a4  leads to incredibly sharp play. Recent practice, however, has shown that things are not so easy for Black after the more positional @@StartFEN@@r4rk1/1bqn1ppp/4pn2/p7/1pPP4/3BP3/1B1N1PPP/R2Q1RK1 w - - 8 16@@EndFEN@@  16.Bc2  .  Our knight on d7 lacks a clear purpose and that's what brought us to the text move. By using the pin, Black immediately gets to exchange the bad knight from d7.   15...Re8  16.Bc2  Qc7  17.h3  with a better position for White. }
16. Be2
{ This looks less logical compared to the retreat to c2. Generally, the bishop is better placed on c2 where it stops the queenside pawns from coming forward and also influences the center/kingside.   16.dxc5  would be a blunder. After  16...Qxd3  Black's queenside pawns will decide the issue. }
16... Nce4 17. f3 Nxd2
{ The knight happily exchanges itself on d2. Just a few moves ago it did not have a clear future on d7. }
18. Qxd2 Qe7 19. e4 a4
{ A new move, but obviously very logical. Passed pawns must be pushed! So far we had been following Pourramezanali-Saptarshi, Pattaya 2018, where Black proceeded with  19...e5  . However, we don't like Black's position after  20.d5  @@StartBracket@@and neither does the mighty engine@@EndBracket@@. }
20. d5
{ A usual Noteboom-scenario is unfolding. Black pushes the queenside pawns while White tries to break through the center. }
20... exd5 21. cxd5 Rfb8
{ The position is very double-edged but we fancy our chances here. Our queenside pawns are going to start marching and the onus is on White to show anything in return. }
22. d6
{ White wins the b4-pawn. That, however, does run into a discovered attack. }
22... Qe6 23. Qxb4 Ba6
{ Somewhat surprisingly, we don't take on e4.  23...Bxe4  24.Qd2!  offers White some hopes for an advantage. Without our b-pawn, our queenside play is a lot less threatening. }
24. Qd2 Bxe2 25. Qxe2 Qxd6
{ The position is probably around equal but if anyone is better it's surely Black with the passed a-pawn. }
*

