{ Another surprise, though a recent trend in correspondence chess.   15...Qc7  used to be more or less universally played when  16.f4  a4  leads to incredibly sharp play. Recent practice, however, has shown that things are not so easy for Black after the more positional @@StartFEN@@r4rk1/1bqn1ppp/4pn2/p7/1pPP4/3BP3/1B1N1PPP/R2Q1RK1 w - - 8 16@@EndFEN@@  16.Bc2  .  Our knight on d7 lacks a clear purpose and that's what brought us to the text move. By using the pin, Black immediately gets to exchange the bad knight from d7.   15...Re8  16.Bc2  Qc7  17.h3  with a better position for White. }
