Bc6 { Supporting the advance of the a-pawn. } 21. e4 { Not too interesting. }
21... a4 22. d5
{ The logical follow-up of the previous move, but essentially forcing a lot of exchanges. }
22... axb3 23. dxc6 Rxa1 24. Rxa1 Qxc6 25. Qxb4
{ All the pieces are coming off fast. } 25... Nd7 26. Qxb3
{ The correspondence game Feco-Kitaev, ICCF 2019 ended in a draw after  26.Ra5  . The text move is more interesting and a nice variation on the theme of the back rank. }
26... Rb8 27. Qd1 { 27.Qc3?  Qb6+  loses on the spot. } 27... Rxb2 28. Qxd7
{ The queen is immune on d7, given the back-rank mate on a8. } 28... Qb6+
{ An excellent counter! Now White must take care. Both king moves are losing. }
29. c5 { The only move, and a good one. } 29... Qxc5+
{ After  30.Kh1  neither side threatens checkmate making the draw imminent. } *

