{ Played by Miguel Najdorf in 1973! One of the few practical examples in this line, which arose via a different move-order. }
17... Nd7 18. Nd3
{ 18.Nc6  isn't too dangerous either. We follow up  18...Qc7  19.d5  Rfe8  preparing ...Nd7-c5, when our queenside pawns are receiving good support. }
18... b3
{ We deviate from Najdorf-Szmetan, Buenos Aires 1973, which continued  18...Qe7?!  19.f3  Nef6  and now  20.c5!  gives White a  huge advantage. Rfe1 followed by a timely e3-e4 is coming, and Black doesn't have enough counterplay. }
19. Qe2
{ The tactical point is seen after  19.Qxb3  Nd2!  winning the exchange. }
19... a4
{ Pushing the queenside passers! Play could now continue  20.f3  Nef6  21.c5  , when White makes sure the knight on  d7  isn't going anywhere in the near future. We like  21...Qc8!  though, which is a very flexible queen move. We want to go ...Qa6/Qb7, next to support the queenside, and another idea is to reroute the d7-knight via b8 to c6. The engine claims triple zeros which, in human terms, means the position is unclear and all three results are on the table. Our type of scenario! }
