{ 6.e4  may look more logical, taking full control of the center, but it also leaves that same center more vulnerable to attack. That shows in the line  6...b5  7.Bd2  a5  8.axb5  Bxc3  9.Bxc3?!  cxb5  10.b3  Nf6!  and Black already has an advantage because  the attack on e4 is hard to counter. In this line, the e-pawn is much better placed on e3 instead of e4. That's why, as we have seen, 6.e4 is usually played with the idea of playing a gambit where White is not thinking about regaining the sacrificed pawn. }
6... b5 7. Bd2
{ Not only developing the bishop but once again pressuring the pawn on b5. }
7... a5
{ It is important to get the move orders right. For all the subtle nuances, please see the Informational dedicated to this topic. }
8. axb5 Bxc3 9. Bxc3 cxb5 10. b3
{ Winning back the pawn and slowly taking us to the main position of the Noteboom Variation. }
10... Bb7 11. bxc4
{ White can also start with  11.Bb2  transposing after  11...Nf6  12.bxc4  b4  . }
11... b4
{ Here we get to see the point behind Black's 7th move. While White has won back the sacrificed pawn, Black has managed to get connected passed pawns on the queenside. }
12. Bb2
{ The correct square for the bishop. Right now it is hiding behind the d4-pawn, but it only takes the d-pawn one move to turn that b2-bishop into a monster on the long diagonal. }
12... Nf6 13. Bd3
{ Developing the bishop and preparing to castle. The bishop is best placed on d3 where it has an influence on the important e4-square. It is this unbalanced position that has mesmerized generations for decades. }
13... O-O
{ 13...Be4  is a move we will see a lot more of, but here it comes too early. White replies  14.Bxe4  Nxe4  15.Qa4+!  Qd7  16.Qc2  with the double threat of  taking the knight on e4 and Nf3-e5. Following  16...Qb7  17.O-O  O-O  18.Ra4!  White  prepares Rfa1 with huge pressure on the queenside. }
14. O-O
{ The main tabiya of the Noteboom Variation. White has strong central control, the pair of bishops, and often tries to play in the center by pushing e3-e4 followed by, potentially, d4-d5 or e4-e5, giving the bishops their maximum scope.  Black though, is not empty-handed either. We are one move @@StartBracket@@...Nb8-d7@@EndBracket@@ away from harmoniously developing and, perhaps the biggest asset in the position, Black has two connected passers on the queenside. On top of that, there are no clear weaknesses in Black's camp. Decades of practice and heavy analysis have shown the various imbalances more or less cancel each other out. }
14... Be4
{ In the preparation for this course we came to the conclusion that this is a giant shortcut. The move  14...Nbd7  is played on auto-pilot generally, but here White has a wide variety of setups, of which  15.Nd2  ,  15.Re1  and  15.Qc2  are the main ones.  Thousands of over the board, correspondence, and computer games have been played in this position, making it an incredibly dense piece of opening theory. It is therefore with great joy that we present you with a much smaller alternative, that is extremely rare and not worse in any way! }
15. Bxe4
{ Stockfish strongly dislikes our last move precisely because of this capture. We will make it change its mind though! }
15... Nxe4 16. Qc2 f5
{ Fortifying our knight on e4. Of course  16...Nf6  17.e4!  is not recommended. }
17. Rfc1 { The engines like this move, meaning we should take it seriously. }
17... Nd7 18. Ne1
{ Transferring the knight to d3 is a common idea in these types of positions, simultaneously making it possible for White to expel the knight from e4 with f2-f3. }
18... Qc7 19. Nd3 Rfb8 20. f3 Nef6
{ The position is 'dynamically equal' which means both sides have their trumps and we have a very sharp battle ahead. We like our queenside pawns! }
*

