17... Qe7
{ A multipurpose move, protecting e6, covering the important c5-square and helping the queenside pawns to march forward.   The complications after  17...exd5  18.Rfd1  Qc7  19.Rxd5  Nd7  20.Nd4  aren't too clear either. For instance  20...Ndf6  21.Rxf5  Nd6  with sharp play. And even @@StartFEN@@rn1q1rk1/6pp/4p3/p2P1p2/1pP1n3/4PN2/1BQ2PPP/R4RK1 b - - 0 17@@EndFEN@@  17...Nc5  18.Bd4  Nba6  19.Qb2  a4!  is very unclear after  20.Bxg7  a3  21.Qd4  Nb3  . }
18. Nd4
{ Less critical is  18.dxe6  , after which we have many good replies. Perhaps the most tricky response is  18...a4  , typically pushing our queenside. Note that  19.Rxa4?  runs into  19...b3!  20.Qxb3  Nc5  and White loses material. }
18... Nc5 19. dxe6 a4
{ The point. White is allowed to take e6 and f5 since it's the queenside pawns that count. }
20. Nxf5 Qxe6 21. Nxg7 Qe4
{ The last few moves were all forced. Now White faces a difficult choice. First of all, it's important to note that  22.Qxe4  Nxe4  is an endgame that White is unlikely to survive. Despite being two pawns up, it will be hard to stop Black's queenside from queening. }
22. Qe2 a3 23. Bd4 { This is something White should avoid. } 23... Nb3 24. Rad1
Nc6 { White can't hold on to both the knight on g7 and bishop on d4. } *

