{ 13...Be4  is a move we will see a lot more of, but here it comes too early. White replies  14.Bxe4  Nxe4  15.Qa4+!  Qd7  16.Qc2  with the double threat of  taking the knight on e4 and Nf3-e5. Following  16...Qb7  17.O-O  O-O  18.Ra4!  White  prepares Rfa1 with huge pressure on the queenside. }
14. O-O
{ The main tabiya of the Noteboom Variation. White has strong central control, the pair of bishops, and often tries to play in the center by pushing e3-e4 followed by, potentially, d4-d5 or e4-e5, giving the bishops their maximum scope.  Black though, is not empty-handed either. We are one move @@StartBracket@@...Nb8-d7@@EndBracket@@ away from harmoniously developing and, perhaps the biggest asset in the position, Black has two connected passers on the queenside. On top of that, there are no clear weaknesses in Black's camp. Decades of practice and heavy analysis have shown the various imbalances more or less cancel each other out. }
14... Be4
{ In the preparation for this course we came to the conclusion that this is a giant shortcut. The move  14...Nbd7  is played on auto-pilot generally, but here White has a wide variety of setups, of which  15.Nd2  ,  15.Re1  and  15.Qc2  are the main ones.  Thousands of over the board, correspondence, and computer games have been played in this position, making it an incredibly dense piece of opening theory. It is therefore with great joy that we present you with a much smaller alternative, that is extremely rare and not worse in any way! }
15. Bxe4
{ Stockfish strongly dislikes our last move precisely because of this capture. We will make it change its mind though! }
15... Nxe4 16. Qc2 f5
{ Fortifying our knight on e4. Of course  16...Nf6  17.e4!  is not recommended. }
17. d5
{ This is the reason engines aren't too happy with what we have been doing. We have enough resources to hold our own though. }
17... Qe7
{ A multipurpose move, protecting e6, covering the important c5-square and helping the queenside pawns to march forward.   The complications after  17...exd5  18.Rfd1  Qc7  19.Rxd5  Nd7  20.Nd4  aren't too clear either. For instance  20...Ndf6  21.Rxf5  Nd6  with sharp play. And even @@StartFEN@@rn1q1rk1/6pp/4p3/p2P1p2/1pP1n3/4PN2/1BQ2PPP/R4RK1 b - - 0 17@@EndFEN@@  17...Nc5  18.Bd4  Nba6  19.Qb2  a4!  is very unclear after  20.Bxg7  a3  21.Qd4  Nb3  . }
18. Nd4
{ Less critical is  18.dxe6  , after which we have many good replies. Perhaps the most tricky response is  18...a4  , typically pushing our queenside. Note that  19.Rxa4?  runs into  19...b3!  20.Qxb3  Nc5  and White loses material. }
18... Nc5 19. dxe6 a4
{ The point. White is allowed to take e6 and f5 since it's the queenside pawns that count. }
20. Nxf5 Qxe6 21. Nxg7 Qe4
{ The last few moves were all forced. Now White faces a difficult choice. First of all, it's important to note that  22.Qxe4  Nxe4  is an endgame that White is unlikely to survive. Despite being two pawns up, it will be hard to stop Black's queenside from queening. }
22. Qe2 a3 23. Nh5 Qd3
{ Note that  23...Nbd7  24.Bd4  b3  is possible as well. All these lines show just how strong these passed pawns on the queenside can become in the Noteboom Variation. }
24. Qg4+ Qg6 25. Qd1 Qd3 { Offering a repetition of moves. } 26. Nf6+
{ White declines it. } 26... Rxf6 27. Bxf6 Qxd1 28. Rfxd1 Kf7
{ The endgame is one we certainly wouldn't mind playing. Black's queenside pawns are terrifying. All in all, it looks like @@StartFEN@@rn1q1rk1/1b3ppp/4pn2/p7/1pPP4/3BPN2/1B3PPP/R2Q1RK1 b - - 5 14@@EndFEN@@  14...Be4  is an excellent alternative to the more common  14...Nbd7  , and cuts down the burden on our memory as well! }
*

[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "5. Avoiding the Marshall Gambit 3.Nc3 c6 4.e4 − 6.Nc3"]
[Black "Avoiding the Marshall Gambit 3.Nc3 c6 4.e4 − 6.Nc3 #1 | Informational 6...c5"]
[Result "*"]

1. d4 d5 2. c4 e6 3. Nc3 c6 4. e4
{ Without a doubt, the most principled way of tackling our Triangle. It's good to set the stage at this point. What kind of game can we expect from here on out? We should play  4...dxe4  as it's the only way to question White's center. After  5.Nxe4  Bb4+  we then get a split.  A@@EndBracket@@  6.Nc3  is a quiet, positional, line where White aims for a small plus but we have little to worry about.  B@@EndBracket@@  6.Bd2  is the real deal. The move invites us to the complications that arise after  6...Qxd4  7.Bxb4  Qxe4+  which we will happily accept. }
4... dxe4
{ Players trying to avoid the theoretical discussion that arises after  4...dxe4  have tried to sidestep it with  4...Bb4  . It is not a great choice though, on top of the fact that it gives White additional options, after  5.Bd2  I don't think Black has anything better but to transpose back to main lines with  5...dxe4  6.Nxe4  Qxd4  . Instead @@StartFEN@@rnbqk1nr/pp3ppp/2p1p3/3p4/1bPPP3/2N5/PP1B1PPP/R2QKBNR b KQkq - 2 5@@EndFEN@@  5...dxc4  6.Bxc4  Qxd4  is a very dangerous pawn grab, as  7.Qe2  Nf6  8.Nf3  gives White a large lead in development. }
5. Nxe4 Bb4+
{ Without this check as a follow-up, White would simply be doing great, having destroyed our proud triangle structure.   In the 2018 Candidates tournament, Vladimir Kramnik shocked the chess world with the fresh  5...c5!?  which was clearly meant to be a surprise weapon. Objectively speaking, after  6.Nxc5  Nc6  7.Be3!   Caruana-Kramnik, Candidates Berlin 2018, continued  7.Nf3  Nxd4  8.Qxd4  Qxd4  9.Nxd4  Bxc5  10.Nb5  Ke7  and now  11.Nc7!  Rb8  12.Bf4  Bb4+  13.Ke2  Bd6  14.Bxd6+  Kxd6  15.Nb5+  would have given Fabiano an edge.  7...e5  8.dxe5  Qa5+  9.Qd2  Nb4  White seems to be in trouble, but there is in fact  10.Ne4!  as  10...Nc2+  11.Ke2  Qxd2+  12.Kxd2  Nxa1  13.Bd3  has the knight trapped on a1 and White already has two pawns for the exchange. That means it is actually Black who is in trouble here. }
6. Nc3
{ The positional approach, instead of the sharp pawn sacrifice  6.Bd2  . Magnus Carlsen used the text move in his World Championship match against Vishy Anand in 2013. It is often used by players who have been caught off-guard by their opponents and want to avoid the abundance of theory that arises after 6.Bd2. }
6... c5
{ The choice is between the c- and the e-pawn. We like this pawn move less.  6...Nf6  is likely to transpose to 6...c5, after  7.Nf3  @@StartBracket@@It does get interesting if White plays  7.a3  Ba5  8.b4  Bc7  when Black will play ...Nb8-d7 next and prepare the ...e6-e5 break.@@EndBracket@@  @@StartFEN@@rnbqk1nr/pp3ppp/4p3/2p5/1bPP4/2N2N2/PP3PPP/R1BQKB1R b KQkq - 1 7@@EndFEN@@  7...c5  8.Be2  . }
7. Nf3
{ 7.a3  Bxc3+  8.bxc3  Nf6  9.Nf3  Qa5  10.Bd2  Ne4  is a scenario that Black does not mind, with a lot of exchanges incoming. }
7... Nf6 8. Be2
{ It's not that clear how Black should play. Two sample lines: } 8... Nc6
{ 8...Ne4?!  9.Qd3  Qa5  10.O-O!  Nxc3  11.bxc3  Bxc3  12.Rb1  cxd4  White has given up two pawns but now gets massive compensation after  13.Rb5  . }
9. Be3 Ng4 10. Bg5 f6 11. d5
{ The main question is how should this position be evaluated. } *

