{ 10...Be6!?  is untested, but looks very reasonable. The idea is that  11.a3  Be7  12.Nf4  Nbd7  , simply allowing  13.Nxe6  , is not bad at all. After the further  13...fxe6  14.O-O-O  Bc5  the exchange of bishops leads to an equal endgame. The isolated  pawn on e6 barely plays any role as e7 will be a nice spot for the king. }
11. O-O-O Nc5 { The endgame is equal. } 12. Bxf6
{ Instead, the immediate  12.a3  allows  12...Nb3+  and the bishop  on d4 will get exchanged. }
12... gxf6 13. a3 a5
{ 13...Bxc3  14.Nxc3  Be6  is possible too, but less pretty! } 14. axb4 axb4
15. Nb1 Bf5 16. Nd4 O-O-O
{ Threatening to take on d4 followed by a knight fork on b3. } 17. Nxf5
{ Allowing perpetual check. } 17... Nb3+ 18. Kc2 Na1+ { A curious line! } *

[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "5. Avoiding the Marshall Gambit 3.Nc3 c6 4.e4 − 6.Nc3"]
[Black "Avoiding the Marshall Gambit 3.Nc3 c6 4.e4 − 6.Nc3 #7"]
[Result "*"]

1. d4 d5 2. c4 e6 3. Nc3 c6 4. e4
{ Without a doubt, the most principled way of tackling our Triangle. It's good to set the stage at this point. What kind of game can we expect from here on out? We should play  4...dxe4  as it's the only way to question White's center. After  5.Nxe4  Bb4+  we then get a split.  A@@EndBracket@@  6.Nc3  is a quiet, positional, line where White aims for a small plus but we have little to worry about.  B@@EndBracket@@  6.Bd2  is the real deal. The move invites us to the complications that arise after  6...Qxd4  7.Bxb4  Qxe4+  which we will happily accept. }
4... dxe4
{ Players trying to avoid the theoretical discussion that arises after  4...dxe4  have tried to sidestep it with  4...Bb4  . It is not a great choice though, on top of the fact that it gives White additional options, after  5.Bd2  I don't think Black has anything better but to transpose back to main lines with  5...dxe4  6.Nxe4  Qxd4  . Instead @@StartFEN@@rnbqk1nr/pp3ppp/2p1p3/3p4/1bPPP3/2N5/PP1B1PPP/R2QKBNR b KQkq - 2 5@@EndFEN@@  5...dxc4  6.Bxc4  Qxd4  is a very dangerous pawn grab, as  7.Qe2  Nf6  8.Nf3  gives White a large lead in development. }
5. Nxe4 Bb4+
{ Without this check as a follow-up, White would simply be doing great, having destroyed our proud triangle structure.   In the 2018 Candidates tournament, Vladimir Kramnik shocked the chess world with the fresh  5...c5!?  which was clearly meant to be a surprise weapon. Objectively speaking, after  6.Nxc5  Nc6  7.Be3!   Caruana-Kramnik, Candidates Berlin 2018, continued  7.Nf3  Nxd4  8.Qxd4  Qxd4  9.Nxd4  Bxc5  10.Nb5  Ke7  and now  11.Nc7!  Rb8  12.Bf4  Bb4+  13.Ke2  Bd6  14.Bxd6+  Kxd6  15.Nb5+  would have given Fabiano an edge.  7...e5  8.dxe5  Qa5+  9.Qd2  Nb4  White seems to be in trouble, but there is in fact  10.Ne4!  as  10...Nc2+  11.Ke2  Qxd2+  12.Kxd2  Nxa1  13.Bd3  has the knight trapped on a1 and White already has two pawns for the exchange. That means it is actually Black who is in trouble here. }
6. Nc3
{ The positional approach, instead of the sharp pawn sacrifice  6.Bd2  . Magnus Carlsen used the text move in his World Championship match against Vishy Anand in 2013. It is often used by players who have been caught off-guard by their opponents and want to avoid the abundance of theory that arises after 6.Bd2. }
6... e5
{ Despite being a pawn sacrifice, this is in fact the most solid reply. } 7. a3
{ The most popular and obvious move in the position, challenging the bishop on b4. I @@StartBracket@@Erwin@@EndBracket@@ have played it myself against Adhiban Baskaran in 2016. }
7... Bxc3+
{ 7...Ba5  is possible but after  8.Be3  ,  the inclusion of a3-Ba5 should favor White. }
8. bxc3 Qa5
{ Immediately asking questions. Not only is c3 hanging, but ...exd4 is also a positional threat because the c3-pawn is pinned. }
9. Qc2
{ Ignoring our second threat! This move has only been played once @@StartBracket@@in an online blitz game!@@EndBracket@@ but warrants some attention. }
9... exd4
{ Our engine also indicates  9...Bf5!?  when  10.Qxf5  Qxc3+  11.Ke2  Qxa1  12.Qc8+  Ke7  13.Bd2  are complications we'd rather avoid. The engine claims triple zeros, but with only one move,  13...Qb2  , which probably gives a hint as to how tricky this position really is. }
10. Bd2
{ White's point, as  10...dxc3?  11.Bxc3  is very dangerous now. Following  11...Qg5  12.Nf3  , White has a large lead in development. }
10... Qe5+ 11. Ne2 d3
{ The simplest. That blitz-game continued  11...Bf5  12.Qb2  d3  13.Qxb7  dxe2  14.Bxe2  Nf6  @@StartBracket@@  14...Bd3  15.O-O!  is something to avoid.@@EndBracket@@ @@StartFEN@@rn2k2r/pQ3ppp/2p2n2/4qb2/2P5/P1P5/3BBPPP/R3K2R w KQkq - 1 15@@EndFEN@@  15.Kf1  O-O  16.Qxa8  Ne4  17.Be3  Nxc3  18.Re1  Nxe2  19.Kxe2  Qc3  20.Kf3  . A heroic king!  20...Nd7  21.Qxa7  Ne5+  22.Kg3  and White seemed to be on the good side of things in Fedoseev-Mamedyarov, chess.com blitz 2020. }
12. Qxd3 Nf6
{ We want to castle next, in which case Black will have an excellent game. }
13. Bf4 Qa5 14. Bd6
{ Not the best move, but after any other move we get to castle. } 14... Na6
{ Planning to get the bishop out to e6 next, and bring the rook to d8. } 15.
Rb1 Be6 { Anyway! } 16. Rxb7 O-O-O
{ Very strong! Of course  16...Rd8  17.Re7+!  needed to be avoided. } 17. Rxa7
Nb4
{ Another flashy move. Note that there is nothing wrong with  17...Qb6  either, when there is nothing better for White than to play  18.Qe3  Qb1+  19.Qc1  Qb6  20.Qe3  with a repetition of moves. }
18. Qd4
{ 18.cxb4?!  Qxa7  19.c5  Rhe8  would be great for White if the king were castled and safely tucked away on g1. As it is, Black is for choice. }
18... Nc2+ 19. Kd1 Nxd4 20. Rxa5
{ Miraculously, White seems to hold on in this line. } 20... Nb3
{ 20...Nxe2  21.Kxe2  @@StartBracket@@of course  21.Bxe2  loses the d6-bishop  with check@@EndBracket@@ @@StartFEN@@2kr3r/5ppp/2pBbn2/R7/2P5/P1P5/4KPPP/5B1R b - - 0 21@@EndFEN@@  21...Bxc4+  22.Kf3  Bd5+  23.Kf4!  also continues. }
21. Ra8+ Kb7 22. Rxd8 Rxd8 23. Kc2
{ 23.c5  Nxc5!  doesn't help the d6-bishop much, making the text move forced. }
23... Na1+ 24. Kb2 Rxd6 25. Nd4
{ The only move, as  25.Kxa1  Rd1+  26.Kb2  Ne4  just crushes. } 25... c5 26.
Nxe6 fxe6 27. Kxa1 Rd2
{ Instead,  27...Rd1+  28.Kb2  Ne4  29.g3!  preparing a check on g2, saves the day. }
28. f3 Kb6
{ We intend to go ...Ka5-a4 next, and despite the engine showing the usual triple zeros, Black has to be preferred here in a practical game. }
