10... f5 { Threatening ...Qg6-f6, trapping the bishop on f8. } 11. Qa3 Qf6 12.
Bd6 Nh6 13. O-O-O Nf7
{ This is the point of Black's setup. The bishop has to now either leave the a3-f8 diagonal or allow itself to get exchanged. }
14. c5
{ 14.Bg3  Qe7!?  proposes the exchange of queens and looks very comfortable. Black could also play  14...Bd7  . }
14... Nxd6 15. cxd6 Nb8
{ Black is behind in development and returns the only developed minor piece to its original square! The knight is on its way to d7 though! }
16. Nf4 e5 { The position is super sharp. } 17. Re1
{ 17.Bc4!?  exf4  18.Rhe1+  Kd8  19.Re7  also deserves consideration. } 17...
Be6
{ 17...O-O  18.Bc4+  Kh8  19.Rxe5!  is a pretty tactic! Black is mated after  19...Qxe5  20.Ng6+  hxg6  21.Qh3#  . }
18. Nxe6 Qxe6 19. f4 e4 20. g4
{ Black is under serious pressure. All in all, 9...Qg6 just doesn't look appealing from Black's point of view. }
