{ 18...O-O  19.Ng3  b4  20.Bd3  b3+  is better for Black as well. However, proving this is not so easy because the position after  21.Kd2  g6  is obviously very messy. }
19. cxb5 O-O
{ Black is a piece down but the weak king on c2 is the main feature of the position! }
20. Nc3 Nf6 21. Qxc6 Bd7 22. Rxd7 Rfc8
{ This sequence reminds us somewhat of the Karjakin-Anand game from Wijk aan Zee 2006. There Anand sacrificed two pieces to get his f8-rook into the game. Here just one piece sacrifice is needed! Black is doing great.   A sample line is  23.Bd3  Rxc6  24.bxc6  Qb6  25.Bb5  Nd5  26.Rd1  h5  27.Nxd5  Qxb5  28.Nc3  Qxc6  and Black should win. }
