9. Ba5 { Threatening checkmate! Fortunately, we can stop it. } 9... Bd7
{ The old way of playing. Nowadays this line has been shelved.  9...f6  has held in correspondence chess but isn't recommendable for the practical player. After  10.Nf3  White has good compensation given his lead in development. }
10. Nf3 Nf6 11. Qd6
{ Not only preventing Black from castling kingside, but White is also intending to meet  11...c5  , with  12.Ne5  b6  13.O-O-O!  and there are devastating threats. The alternative @@StartFEN@@r3k2r/pp1b1ppp/n1p1pn2/B7/2P1q3/5N2/PP2BPPP/R2QK2R w KQkq - 6 11@@EndFEN@@  11.O-O  Qf5  12.Qe1!  O-O  13.Bc3  isn't bad either, with great compensation for the pawn. }
11... Qf5 { Stopping the knight from jumping to e5, or does it? } 12. Ne5 Qxf2+
13. Kxf2 Ne4+ 14. Kf3 Nxd6
{ The position both sides have been aiming for and one that has been played about 20 times in grandmaster practice. Black is two pawns up but will be faced with threats along the d-file. Note that White moved the king to f3, not e3, so that the knight on d6 can never move away with a check. }
15. Rhd1 Ke7
{ 15...f6  16.Rxd6  fxe5  17.Rad1  Rf8+  18.Ke3  Rf7  19.Bf3  is an unpleasant endgame for Black, but it may be tenable. }
16. Rd2
{ 16.Rxd6  Kxd6  17.Rd1+  Kxe5  18.Bc3+  Kf5  19.Rxd7  looks interesting, but  19...Kg6!  20.Bd3+  Kg5!  was clearly better for Black in Sokolov-Scherbakov, Leeuwarden 1994 which the famous Triangle expert went on to win on move  42.   16.c5  Nxc5  17.Bb4  b6  18.Rac1  Nce4  19.Bd3  used to be another direction in which this endgame could go, but it has frankly become irrelevant. The text move is much stronger. }
16... Be8 17. Rad1 Nf5 18. Rd8 Rxd8 19. Bxd8+ Kf8 20. g4
{ Powerplay by White. With every move, Black is pushed back further and further. }
20... Nh6
{ 20...Ne7  21.Nd7+  Bxd7  22.Rxd7  Ke8  23.Rxe7+  Kxd8  24.Rxf7  followed by taking on b7 or g7, is easily winning for White. }
21. Nd7+ Kg8 22. Ke3 f6
{ 22...f5  23.g5  Nf7  24.Be7!  leaves Black completely paralyzed and illustrates why  the king needed to move to e3 earlier. Otherwise Black would take on d7 now, followed by a royal fork on e5. }
23. Nxf6+ gxf6 24. Bxf6 Nf7 25. g5 Kf8 26. Bxh8 Nxh8 27. Rd8
{ Even deep into the endgame the initiative continues. } 27... Nf7 28. Ra8 Nd6
29. b3
{ White will pick up a7, leaving Black with a very grim endgame. Needless to say, this little exploration left us with little desire to advocate the move 9...Bd7. }
