Bxe5 Kb7 18. b4 Na6 19. b5 cxb5 20. cxb5 Nf7
{ Giving back the piece in order to ward off White's attack. White wanted to trade the c-pawn so that in the line  20...Nc5  21.Qc7+  Ka8  the move  22.g3  would decide at once, as the bishop will reach the long diagonal on the next move. }
21. bxa6+ Ka8
{ Now the question becomes which king is safer. With the c-file opened, the king on c1 can't feel too comfortable either. }
22. Qd3 Nxe5 23. Rxe5 Qxd3 24. Bxd3 Kb8
{ Scherbakov ends his analysis here, giving the ending as slightly worse for Black but drawish. We would go a step further and simply declare the endgame fine for Black. The pawn on a6 is a nice target in the endgame and certainly compensates for the isolated e-pawn.   For illustrative purposes we give the line @@StartFEN@@1k1r3r/p2b2pp/Pp2p3/4R3/8/3B4/P4PPP/2KR4 w - - 1 25@@EndFEN@@  25.Bc4  Bc8  26.Rde1  Rhf8  , bringing the other rook into the game,  27.f3  Rf7!  preparing ...Rf7-c7 with a fine game. }
