{ This is Black's idea. The h-file is cleared for a counter on h2. } 23. Qxh5
Rh8 24. Qg6 Qxh2+ 25. Kf1 Qh1+
{ More complicated is  25...Nc7  26.Qxg7  e5  with the idea of bringing in reinforcements with ...Nc7-e6. The line  27.Ne4  Qh1+  28.Ke2  Qh5+  29.g4  Ne8!  is forced, and gives White a few ways of bailing out. One is  30.Rd7+  Kxd7  31.Nxf6+  Ke7  32.Nxh5  Nxg7  33.Nxg7  Rh3!  with an equal endgame, as ...Bb7-f3+ is incoming. }
26. Ke2 Qxg2
{ With two pawns for the exchange, endgames are no longer something to avoid. }
27. Qxg2 Bxg2 28. Rg1 Rh2
{ The engine also has no issues returning a pawn with  28...Bc6  29.Rxg7  Nc7  ,  intending to play ...e6-e5 and ...Nc7-e6 next. Very playable as well, but we prefer to keep the g-pawn alive for now. }
29. Nf1 Bxf1+ 30. Rdxf1 g5 31. Rh1 Rxh1 32. Rxh1 e5
{ The endgame is equal as Black can't really improve while the position is untouchable. A possible continuation would be  33.Rh7  Ke6  34.Rg7  Nb8  35.Rg8  Nc6  35.f3  Nd6  when the white rook has managed to infiltrate, but can in fact do no damage on the 8th rank. }
