[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "8. Alternatives to Chapter 7"]
[Black "Introduction"]
[Result "*"]

{ This chapter consists of three alternative lines to the 9.Ba5 Marshall Gambit. Previously, we acquainted ourselves with the main variations, but in an LTR, it makes sense to be able to vary now and then.  We decided on dedicating a separate chapter to these additional options in order to keep the material manageable and preserve the overview. Clicking through the moves, we will give a quick summary of what is to come. }
1. d4 d5 2. c4 e6 3. Nc3 c6 4. e4 dxe4 5. Nxe4 Bb4+ 6. Bd2 Qxd4 7. Bxb4 Qxe4+
8. Be2 Na6 9. Ba5 b6 10. Qd6 Bd7
{ Could  10...e5  be a giant shortcut? Despite being extremely rarely played, we have yet to see the refutation of this move! Black  simply prepares to bring the c8-bishop into the game. }
11. Bc3 f6 12. Nf3 Nh6 13. Rd1 Rd8 14. Qa3 Bc8 15. Nd2 Qf4
{ 15...Qf5  is one of those moves that have only recently come to the surface, and just in correspondence chess for now. The idea is to stop the  check on h5 altogether. Black seems to be in good shape. }
16. Bh5+ Nf7 17. O-O Qd6
{ This move is also often seen, with the obvious intention of getting the king out of the center by blocking the a3-f8 diagonal. We think Black isn't doing bad here either, though the main line involves a sophisticated queen sacrifice.   17...c5  is the move we saw in the previous chapter and our recommendation, but the text move is certainly playable as well.  Do make your own choices when it comes to these alternative lines. Use them at your own discretion, either as the main line, a surprise weapon, or not at all! }
*

