12. Nf3 Nh6
{ One of those exceptions to the rule. Black needs to develop the knight to the edge of the board.   A@@EndBracket@@ Worse is  12...Ne7  13.O-O-O  as the knight is often hanging on e7, making it impossible for Black to castle queenside.   B@@EndBracket@@ A move that does warrant some attention is  12...Nc5!?  as  13.Bb4  @@StartBracket@@After  13.b4  Black has the  13...Qc2!  resource.@@EndBracket@@ @@StartFEN@@r3k1nr/p2b2pp/1ppQpp2/2n5/1BP1q3/5N2/PP2BPPP/R3K2R b KQkq - 3 13@@EndFEN@@  13...Ne7  14.Bxc5  bxc5  15.Qxc5  and now  15...e5  or  15...Ng6  , are not clear. }
13. Rd1 Rd8
{ Unfortunately,  13...O-O-O  runs into  14.Qa3  Kb7  15.c5!  Nc7  16.Nd2  when the knight aims for c4 and potentially d6,  while  16...Qxg2  17.Bf3  Qh3  18.Bxf6!  opens up the 3rd rank so that Bf3xc6 becomes a big discovered check. }
14. Qa3
{ 14.Rd4  Qb1+  15.Rd1  forces a draw,  as we have nothing better but to go back to e4. }
14... Bc8 15. Nd2 Qf5
{ One of those moves that have only recently come to the surface, and just in correspondence chess for now. The idea is to stop the check on h5 altogether. For people who like to explore variations on their own, the move  15...Qg6!?  could be attractive.  This is brand new and also stops the check on h5, and keeps an eye on g2. }
16. O-O c5 17. Qa4+ Ke7 18. Rfe1 Qf4
{ This looks like a loss of time, but Black would not normally get the knight to f5 in this line, so its a double edged sword. }
19. a3 Nf5 20. b4 Qc7
{ White was threatening to win the a7-pawn with b4-b5 thus we retreat with the queen, in order to secure our queenside. }
21. Ne4 Rxd1 22. Qxd1 Rd8 23. Qb1 Nd4
{ A recent discovery by correspondence player Dan Perry, who happens to be an expert on the Triangle!  23...Kf7  24.Bh5+  g6  25.Bxf6!  gxh5  26.b5  Nb8  27.Bxd8  Qxd8  28.Ng3  h4  29.Nxf5  exf5  30.Qc1!  still continues as Black's king is weakened. We improved on move 27 over the game Mirkowski-Hildebrand, ICCF email 2017 where 27.Be5 was played. }
24. Bxd4 cxd4 25. c5
{ I assume it is this move that made players before Perry fear going 23...Nd4. The analysis, however, runs deep here. }
25... bxc5 26. Bxa6 Bxa6 27. Nxc5 Bc8
{ The more active  27...Bc4!?  28.Rc1  d3  may work as well, temporarily sacrificing a piece to run with the d-pawn. At the very least though, White can bail out with  29.Rxc4  d2  30.Qd1  Qe5  31.Ne4  Qd5  32.Rc7+  Ke8  33.Nxd2  Qxd2  34.Qxd2  Rxd2  35.Kf1  Rd7  36.Rc6!  with the slightly better rook ending. }
28. Qxh7 Kf7
{ The knight seems comfortable on c5 but the bishop on c8 does a good job controlling it. In the meantime, Black is ready to get active play in the center by pushing the d- and e-pawn. }
29. Nd3 Bb7
{ 29...Ba6  looks more logical, challenging  the blockading piece on d3  , but  30.b5!  is strong, as  30...Bxb5  31.Qh5+!  loses the bishop. }
30. h4 Qc6 { Provoking weaknesses around White's king. } 31. f3 Qd6
{ Now ideas connected to a bishop sacrifice on f3 come into play, and the g3-square has become available for the queen. The position is even according to the engine but obviously very sharp and very much one where all three results are in play. }
*

