{ This is the tactic on which Black's entire play is based. Not only is Black now fully mobilized, but the king is also out of the center. The only question that remains is the knight on e7 that appears to be hanging. }
15. f3 { Before taking on e7, White first chases the queen. } 15... Qh4+ 16. g3
Qh3 17. Qxe7
{ 17.Bf1  Qh5  doesn't really improve White's position, and likely  18.Be2  is best. }
17... f6 { The e-file needs to be opened. } 18. Nxc6
{ This looks insane at first, but White is a piece up and captures yet another pawn, preparing to give back some material later on. }
18... Rfe8 19. Kf2
{ White’s point, after which we will see an interesting material balance of rook, piece, and pawn versus queen. }
19... Rxe7 20. Nxe7+ Kf8 21. Nd5
{ Threatening to jump to f4 followed by Rd1-d5, which would seriously embarrass our queen. }
21... Be6 22. Nf4 Qf5 23. h4
{ A sneaky attempt to trap our queen, with b2-b4 followed by Be2-d3. The immediate  23.b4  , is well met with  23...g5!  when for instance  24.Nxe6  Nxe6  25.Rd5  Qc2  26.Bxf6  Re8  or  26...a5!?  is very unclear. }
23... Re8
{ The position is dynamically equal with White having enough compensation for the missing queen but no more than that. Next up, we can play ...Be6-f7 and further contemplate kingside actions like ...g7-g5. }
*

