{ With the inclusion of 8...Na6/9.Bd6 this move has become possible. White has no immediate ways to punish this greed.   A move that has largely gone out of fashion is  9...b6  and for good reason!  10.Nf3  Bb7  11.O-O  Rd8  . This pin looks annoying for White, but it's hard for Black to up the pressure  on the d6-bishop. In the meantime, it is White who starts increasing the pressure.  12.Ng5!  Qg6  13.f4!  Threatening Be2-h5.  13...Nf6  14.Re1  Rd7  15.Bd3  Qh5  16.Bc2!   Scherbakov's suggestion of  16.Bf5  Qxd1  17.Raxd1  isn't bad either, but this is even stronger.  In the same endgame, White has f4-f5 available.  16...Qxd1  17.Raxd1  it is hard to find a  move for Black. f4-f5 is a huge threat and even without queens, the attack on the king will continue. }
10. Bf3
{ This is very rare, but we are going to take it seriously! The knight will come to e2 next and the h1-rook may come to g1 after which White's pieces take up active positions. }
10... Qg5
{ We prefer g5 over g6, as the queen is a bit more flexible on the first square. }
11. Ne2
{ Less good is  11.Nh3  Qh4!  12.Nf4  Bd7  when Black is preparing to castle. }
11... Ne7 12. Rg1 Qa5+ 13. b4
{ Very much in the spirit of White's previous play, another pawn is sacrificed. }
13... Nxb4 14. Kf1 Na6
{ This knight retreat may come as a surprise at first but is the way to go. The knight was vulnerable on b4. }
15. Nf4 { 15.Rxg7  Nf5!  is something we welcome with open arms. } 15... Ng6
{ We are three pawns up and engines like what Black is doing here. Nevertheless, we will continue our analysis somewhat as White's pieces are very active and the king is still stuck on e8. }
16. Qc1 Qd8 { Challenging the strong bishop on d6. } 17. Qa3 Nxf4 18. Bxf4 e5
{ The point behind the trade on f4. From now on, all the moves are forced. }
19. Bxe5 Bh3+ 20. Ke1 Qe7 { Using the fact that the bishop on e5 is pinned. }
21. Qxe7+ Kxe7 22. Rxg7 Nc5
{ We have given back a few pawns but still have one extra. That means White should not be enjoying this endgame. }
*

[Event "?"]
