{ This typical advance again, freeing the c8-bishop.  10...Qg6  is certainly a move,  hitting the queen on d3. Of course, an exchange of queens would be great news, being two pawns up. White should play either  11.Qe3  or  11.Qa3  , with compensation for the pawns. }
11. O-O-O Qg6
{ 11...e4  is what the engines indicate at first, but it's a mess after  12.Qc3  , while the text move is more clear-cut. }
12. Qa3 Qe4
{ The queen performs miracles! Black tries to solve the problems in a forceful manner. The direct threat, besides sometimes being able to take on h1, is ...Bc8-f5. The immediate  12...Bf5  is possible too. }
13. Qg3
{ Not convincing, but it's hard to come up with anything better. White could try  13.b4  , but rather than replying  13...Qxh1?  14.Qg3!  we play @@StartFEN@@r1b1k1nr/pp3ppp/n1pB4/4p3/1PP1q3/Q7/P3BP1P/2KR2NR b kq - 0 13@@EndFEN@@  13...Bf5  14.Bd3  Qf4+  with a big advantage as Black is two pawns up and ready to mobilize. }
13... Nf6
{ Very strong, it turns out the threat to g7 is illusory. Normally we are happy to exchange queens, but this is an exception. After  13...Qf4+  14.Qxf4  exf4  15.Nf3  White has decent compensation. }
14. Qxg7 Qf4+ 15. Kb1 Rg8 { Trapping the queen. } *

[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "9. Marshall Gambit 9.Bd6 − Main Line"]
[Black "Marshall Gambit 9.Bd6 Qxg2 10.Qd2 − Main Line #1 | Informational 10...e5"]
[Result "*"]

1. d4 d5 2. c4 e6 3. Nc3 c6 4. e4
{ Without a doubt, the most principled way of tackling our Triangle. It's good to set the stage at this point. What kind of game can we expect from here on out? We should play  4...dxe4  as it's the only way to question White's center. After  5.Nxe4  Bb4+  we then get a split.  A@@EndBracket@@  6.Nc3  is a quiet, positional, line where White aims for a small plus but we have little to worry about.  B@@EndBracket@@  6.Bd2  is the real deal. The move invites us to the complications that arise after  6...Qxd4  7.Bxb4  Qxe4+  which we will happily accept. }
4... dxe4
{ Players trying to avoid the theoretical discussion that arises after  4...dxe4  have tried to sidestep it with  4...Bb4  . It is not a great choice though, on top of the fact that it gives White additional options, after  5.Bd2  I don't think Black has anything better but to transpose back to main lines with  5...dxe4  6.Nxe4  Qxd4  . Instead @@StartFEN@@rnbqk1nr/pp3ppp/2p1p3/3p4/1bPPP3/2N5/PP1B1PPP/R2QKBNR b KQkq - 2 5@@EndFEN@@  5...dxc4  6.Bxc4  Qxd4  is a very dangerous pawn grab, as  7.Qe2  Nf6  8.Nf3  gives White a large lead in development. }
5. Nxe4 Bb4+
{ Without this check as a follow-up, White would simply be doing great, having destroyed our proud triangle structure.   In the 2018 Candidates tournament, Vladimir Kramnik shocked the chess world with the fresh  5...c5!?  which was clearly meant to be a surprise weapon. Objectively speaking, after  6.Nxc5  Nc6  7.Be3!   Caruana-Kramnik, Candidates Berlin 2018, continued  7.Nf3  Nxd4  8.Qxd4  Qxd4  9.Nxd4  Bxc5  10.Nb5  Ke7  and now  11.Nc7!  Rb8  12.Bf4  Bb4+  13.Ke2  Bd6  14.Bxd6+  Kxd6  15.Nb5+  would have given Fabiano an edge.  7...e5  8.dxe5  Qa5+  9.Qd2  Nb4  White seems to be in trouble, but there is in fact  10.Ne4!  as  10...Nc2+  11.Ke2  Qxd2+  12.Kxd2  Nxa1  13.Bd3  has the knight trapped on a1 and White already has two pawns for the exchange. That means it is actually Black who is in trouble here. }
6. Bd2
{ Obviously, the sharpest response. White is sacrificing a pawn following  6...Qxd4  7.Bxb4  Qxe4+  and as a result Black somewhat falls back in development and will be missing the dark-squared bishop.  That is especially felt when we see the mighty bishop on b4, which makes it hard for the king on e8 to find refuge.  We are a pawn up though, and while play is less straightforward compared to the Noteboom, and concrete knowledge of variations is of the essence, the Marshall Gambit stands firm from a theoretical standpoint: Black is OK in all the lines. We need to fight the bishop on b4 @@StartBracket@@usually starting with ...Nb8-a6@@EndBracket@@ and should focus on finding a safe spot for the king. If we manage those two objectives, we are usually surviving − and, with that extra pawn in the pocket, maybe even more than that! }
6... Qxd4
{ Black has to take the bait. Worse is  6...Bxd2+  7.Qxd2  Nf6  8.Nxf6+  Qxf6  9.Nf3  with a clear and easy advantage for White. }
7. Bxb4 Qxe4+
{ The starting position of the Marshall Gambit. White has given a pawn but obviously, the strong bishop on b4 gives certain compensation as outlined on move 6. }
8. Be2
{ The critical reply, it is more natural to place the bishop than the knight on e2. }
8... Na6
{ While at times we have various options, here we feel this is the only way to go, giving White the choice between three serious bishop moves.   A@@EndBracket@@ Grabbing another pawn with  8...Qxg2  is just too dangerous. White plays  9.Bf3  ,  follows up with Ng1-e2, and has massive compensation for the pawns.   B@@EndBracket@@  8...a5  has gained some followers over the last five years or so and has done well as a surprise weapon. Once the surprise is gone though, it becomes clear that  9.Bd6  Nh6  @@StartBracket@@  9...Qxg2  10.Qd2!  Qxh1  11.O-O-O  threatens not only Be2-f3, trapping the queen, but horrible things on the d-file  as well.@@EndBracket@@ @@StartFEN@@rnb1k2r/1p3ppp/2pBp2n/p7/2P1q3/8/PP2BPPP/R2QK1NR w KQkq - 2 10@@EndFEN@@  10.Qd2  Nf5  11.Ba3  is just huge for White. A quick database search will also reveal that Black's results in this position have been a disaster. }
9. Bd6
{ The most natural move in the position. On d6 the bishop is a monster that will prevent the black king from leaving the center for some time to come! This is considered the biggest test within the Marshall Gambit. }
9... Qxg2
{ With the inclusion of 8...Na6/9.Bd6 this move has become possible. White has no immediate ways to punish this greed.   A move that has largely gone out of fashion is  9...b6  and for good reason!  10.Nf3  Bb7  11.O-O  Rd8  . This pin looks annoying for White, but it's hard for Black to up the pressure  on the d6-bishop. In the meantime, it is White who starts increasing the pressure.  12.Ng5!  Qg6  13.f4!  Threatening Be2-h5.  13...Nf6  14.Re1  Rd7  15.Bd3  Qh5  16.Bc2!   Scherbakov's suggestion of  16.Bf5  Qxd1  17.Raxd1  isn't bad either, but this is even stronger.  In the same endgame, White has f4-f5 available.  16...Qxd1  17.Raxd1  it is hard to find a  move for Black. f4-f5 is a huge threat and even without queens, the attack on the king will continue. }
10. Qd2
{ A spectacular quiet move, simply preparing to castle queenside while a rook is hanging on h1. }
10... e5 { The main alternative, which may be playable. } 11. Bxe5 Bf5 12. Bf3
Qg6 13. O-O-O Nc5
{ 13...f6!?  14.Bc3  Qh6  is, as yet, untested, and worth further analysis as well. }
14. Qe3 Bb1 15. Rd2 Bxa2 16. Bd6+ Ne6 17. Be4 Qh6 18. f4
{ White does have very good compensation for the pawns. A high-level game continued: }
18... Nf6 19. Nf3 Bxc4 20. Re1
{ 20.Bf5  Nd5  21.Qa3  Ndxf4  22.Re1  Ne2+  23.Kb1  O-O-O  24.Rexe2  Bxe2  25.Rxe2  Qf6  as in Zielasko-McDermott, ICCF 2021 − this is very messy as well, though Black seems to be alright. The game was drawn on move  29. }
20... O-O-O 21. Bxc6 Ba6 { 21...bxc6  22.Qxa7  Rxd6!  was the right defense. }
22. Ng5 Nxg5 23. Bd7+ Kxd7 24. Qe7+ Kc6 25. Qc7+
{ Black resigned in Bacrot-Morozevich, Biel 2012. The jury is still out when it comes to the valuation of the move @@StartFEN@@r1b1k1nr/pp3ppp/n1pBp3/8/2P5/8/PP1QBPqP/R3K1NR b KQkq - 1 10@@EndFEN@@  10...e5  . The text move,  10...Nf6  , has done well though, so there is no need for us to look any further. }
*

