{ With the intention of meeting  11.O-O-O  with  11...Ne4  12.Qd4  Nxd6  13.Qxd6  Qg5+  and ...Qe7 next.   It is also important to note that @@StartFEN@@r1b1k1nr/pp3ppp/n1pBp3/8/2P5/8/PP1QBPqP/R3K1NR b KQkq - 1 10@@EndFEN@@  10...Qxh1?  11.O-O-O  would simply be too dangerous.  The combined threats of trapping the queen with Be2-f3 and mating on the d-file are too much to deal with. }
11. Bf3 Qg6 12. O-O-O e5 { Again this move, freeing up the bishop on c8. } 13.
Bxe5 { 13.Ne2  transposes to the 12.Ne2 move order. } 13... Be6
{ It is too dangerous to  13...O-O  at this point. White's attack quickly gets off the ground after  14.Ne2  Qf5  15.Qe3  Nb4  16.Nd4  Nxa2+  17.Kd2  Rd8  18.Ke2  and Black was in big trouble in Braun-Van der Werf, Wijk aan Zee 2008. }
14. Ne2 Qf5 { A double attack on the two bishops. } 15. Bf4 Bxc4
{ The main line − not just taking a pawn but also taking control of the d5-square. It is nice to be able to block the d-file in the future by plonking a piece on d5. }
16. Rhg1 Bxa2 17. Qe3+ { 17.Nc3  Nb4!  is just great for Black. } 17... Qe6
{ The right way to intercept the check.  17...Be6  18.Rg5  Qh3  19.Ng3  is bad news,  with Ng3-f5 incoming. Our king has no place to go. }
18. Be5 Qe7
{ So far this has been played exclusively, but it is dangerous.  18...O-O  of course loses to  19.Rxg7+! }
19. Qg5
{ 19.Rxg7!?  Nd7  20.Rxd7!?  Kxd7  21.b3  is an interesting try as well. }
19... Nd7 20. Qxe7+ Kxe7 21. Bd6+ Kf6 22. Bg3
{ Even in the endgame the king isn't safe. } 22... Ke7
{ 22...Ndc5  23.Bh4+  Ke5  was seen in Nekhaev-Evtushenko, ICCF 2011, but instead of  24.Nd4  , as that game continued, White should play  24.Rge1   24.Nd4  Nb3+  25.Nxb3  Bxb3  26.Rg5+  f5  27.Re1+  Kd6  allowed Evtushenko to survive.  24...Rhe8  25.b3!!   The idea is that after  25.Nd4+  Kf4  26.Bg3+  Kg5  27.Rg1  there is  27...Nb3+  28.Nxb3  Bxb3  exchanging off a pair of knights, the text move prevents this.  25...Bxb3  26.Nd4+  Kf4  27.Bg3+  Kg5  28.Rg1  and White is winning. A beautiful sample line is  28...Bxd1  29.Be5+  Kh4  30.Nf5+  Kh3  31.Rg3+  Kxh2  32.Rg2+  Kh1  33.Ng3#  mate! @@StartFEN@@r3r3/pp3ppp/n1p5/2n1k3/7B/1P3B2/b3NP1P/2KRR3 b - - 0 25@@EndFEN@@  25...Kf5  is the only move, but the initiative keeps raging after  26.Rg1  . }
23. Bh4+
{ An improvement over two correspondence games. Those had continued  23.Nd4  Ndc5  24.Nf5+  Kf6  25.Nxg7  Kxg7  26.Be5+  Kf8  27.Bxh8  Nb4  28.Bg7+  Ke7  29.Rge1+  Be6  and Black, with two pawns for the exchange, had no issues surviving the endgame. }
23... Ke8 24. Nd4
{ Three pawns down in a queenless middlegame, White is still very much the one in control. Black's pieces lack coordination and the king is weak. }
24... Ne5 25. Rge1 f6 26. b3
{ Making sure the bishop isn't going anywhere. We could, and have, in fact, analyzed this position deeper but believe the message is clear: this is not an attractive way of playing for Black. }
