12. gxf3 Qd4
{ An important move. It is tempting to play more ambitiously but that could backfire. }
13. c5
{ While this cements the bishop on d6, it also gives up on the d5-square. }
13... O-O-O 14. Bxa6 Qxd1+ 15. Rxd1 bxa6 16. Rg1
{ White needs to act fast in order to prove compensation. If Black is allowed to develop the knight to f6, and, potentially d5, the extra pawn will start counting. }
16... g6 17. Rg4 { Obviously  17.Bxe5  Re8!  is out of the question. } 17...
Nf6 18. Ra4 Nd5 19. Rd3
{ The best attempt, bringing in the second rook. Less testing is  19.Rxa6  Kb7  followed by, in random order, ...f7-f6, ...Rd8-d7, ...Kb7-a8 and ...Rd7-b7. }
19... Rd7 20. Rda3 Rb7 21. Rxa6 Nb4 { This resource saves the day. } 22. Rxa7
Nc2+ 23. Kf1 Nxa3 24. Ra8+ Kd7 25. Rxh8 { All forced. } 25... Nc4 26. Rxh7 Nxd6
27. cxd6 Rxb2 28. Rxf7+ Kxd6
{ In the rook endgame neither side can play for a win. } *

