10. Nf3 Bg4 11. O-O { The most obvious move, though there are alternatives. }
11... O-O-O
{ It feels great to remove the king from e8 and simultaneously pin the bishop on d6. We are not out of the woods yet though, the line very much continues! }
12. b4
{ A move that got some attention back in 2006, when Mamedyarov introduced it in tournament practice. The intention is to back up the bishop on d6 with c4-c5 while also flirting with ideas of pushing the b-pawn to get to the enemy king. }
12... Nf6
{ 12...Nxb4  highlights another important idea behind White's 11th move. White simply plays  13.c5  and is happy the b-file got  opened. Ra1-b1 is already a big threat. }
13. c5 Ne8 { The monster on d6 needs to be dealt with. } 14. Bd3 Qd5
{ A deviation from practice, though modern engines immediately indicate this queen move to be the best one in the position.  14...Qf4  15.Bxe5!  is less good. }
15. Nxe5 Bxd1 16. Bf5+
{ This is White's point. But as so often, Black has a hidden resource. } 16...
Qe6 17. Bxe6+ fxe6 18. Rfxd1 Nxd6 19. cxd6 Nxb4
{ A similar line as the one we will check next and very fine for Black as well. }
