[White "11. Stonewall 3.Nc3 c6 4.e3 f5"]
[Black "Stonewall 3.Nc3 c6 4.e3 f5 5.g4 #2"]
[Result "*"]

1. d4 d5 2. c4 e6 3. Nc3 c6 4. e3
{ We thought long and hard about what to suggest against this modest pawn push. Of course  4...Nf6  is possible, but transposing to the so-called Slow-Slav, did not seem very appealing. After all, in our LTR we aim for fighting positions, while the winning chances in the Slow-Slav are slim, and the positions, though strategically not uninteresting, are rather dry. We have therefore decided to meet all the e3-setups @@StartBracket@@including the @@StartFEN@@rnbqkbnr/ppp2ppp/4p3/3p4/2PP4/8/PP2PPPP/RNBQKBNR w KQkq - 0 3@@EndFEN@@  3.Nf3  c6  4.e3  move order@@EndBracket@@ with the Stonewall. }
4... f5
{ Without a doubt, the most ambitious way of playing. As always, when a rigorous decision is made on the chessboard, there are clear up and downsides. Let's start with the obvious downside: placing the pawn on f5 means we leave ourselves with a giant hole on e5, and we weaken the dark squares as a whole. If White also manages to exchange the dark-squared bishops, which is a common strategic idea against the Stonewall we will regret having pushed the pawn to f5 in the first place.  Another small issue is the bishop on c8, which is often the problem child in the Stonewall, hidden behind all the pawns on the light squares.  Luckily, there are upsides as well. By playing ...f7-f5 we strengthen our presence in the center by controlling the e4-square a second time and set up an impressive wall of pawns behind which we can swiftly develop our pieces. As Simen Agdestein, a big exponent of the Stonewall, mentioned in his foreword to the book Win with the Stonewall Dutch, people often think that setting up a 'stone wall' means trying to stay solid and defensive, while the modern interpretation is very different.  As in many, if not all, other openings, the engines have shown that Black can play in many different ways, some of which the inventors of this opening never could have imagined! We will try to bring you up to date on all those modern ideas. }
5. g4
{ Trying to prove that the Wall is not so impenetrable after all. This move makes use of the fact that there is no knight on f6 to push the pawn to g4, from which it can be exchanged on f5, crippling our c6-d5-e6-f5 setup. There was a time this was considered the most critical continuation in the position, but antidotes have been found and White tends to explore other avenues these days. }
5... Nf6
{ For reasons unknown to me @@StartBracket@@Erwin@@EndBracket@@, I once ventured  5...fxg4  in this position, back in 2006. After  6.Qxg4  Nf6  7.Qg2  White has a giant positional advantage and easy play as well: Bc1-d2, Ng1-f3, O-O-O, Rh1-g1 etcetera. The position plays itself! }
6. g5
{ An odd follow-up but we live in modern times and the engine, initially, likes this move best, meaning we have to get to the bottom of it! }
6... Ne4 7. f4 Be7
{ Typically, we try to meet a flank attack in the center, which is why  7...c5!?  comes to mind. It's playable, but we weren't quite sure of  8.cxd5  exd5  9.dxc5  Nxc3   9...Be6!?  with a playable endgame after  10.Nxe4  dxe4  11.Qxd8+  Kxd8  may be a better approach.  10.bxc3  Bxc5  11.Bg2  ,  when the d5-pawn is a weakness and White can play with ideas of using the b-file or bringing the g1-knight to d4.   Less good is  7...Bb4  8.Bd2  Bxc3  9.Bxc3  O-O  10.Nf3  when White has stabilized the center and, essentially, holds a big space advantage. }
8. Nf3 a5
{ Strategically a very nice move. What is important to realize is that White would love to play c4-c5 and follow it up with b2-b4 grabbing even more space. With Black's position this cramped, that would certainly be bad news. It is therefore essential that White is not allowed to close the position in this way and  8...a5  serves that exact purpose! Now  9.c5  can be met with  9...b6  , giving White no chance to consolidate.   Alternatively, setting the board on fire with  8...h6  is possible as well. The forced sequence  9.h4  hxg5  10.Nxe4  @@StartBracket@@  10.fxg5  Nxg5!  is bad for White@@EndBracket@@ @@StartFEN@@rnbqk2r/pp2b1p1/2p1p3/3p1pp1/2PPNP1P/4PN2/PP6/R1BQKB1R b KQkq - 0 10@@EndFEN@@  10...dxe4  11.Nxg5  c5  leads to very unclear play. While it's certainly possible to explore this line further, we see no reason to deviate from our main continuation. }
9. Bd3
{ A mistake, since, as paradoxical as it seems, developing the bishop on this square will make taking on e4 much harder. }
9... h6 10. h4 hxg5
{ White is in deep trouble since  11.Nxe4  , as seen in the line with 8...h6, is not possible here. }
*

