{ Without a doubt, the most ambitious way of playing. As always, when a rigorous decision is made on the chessboard, there are clear up and downsides. Let's start with the obvious downside: placing the pawn on f5 means we leave ourselves with a giant hole on e5, and we weaken the dark squares as a whole. If White also manages to exchange the dark-squared bishops, which is a common strategic idea against the Stonewall we will regret having pushed the pawn to f5 in the first place.  Another small issue is the bishop on c8, which is often the problem child in the Stonewall, hidden behind all the pawns on the light squares.  Luckily, there are upsides as well. By playing ...f7-f5 we strengthen our presence in the center by controlling the e4-square a second time and set up an impressive wall of pawns behind which we can swiftly develop our pieces. As Simen Agdestein, a big exponent of the Stonewall, mentioned in his foreword to the book Win with the Stonewall Dutch, people often think that setting up a 'stone wall' means trying to stay solid and defensive, while the modern interpretation is very different.  As in many, if not all, other openings, the engines have shown that Black can play in many different ways, some of which the inventors of this opening never could have imagined! We will try to bring you up to date on all those modern ideas. }
5. Bd3
{ White's most flexible response, not yet determining the position of the knight on g1, and keeping the option of f2-f4 open. }
5... Bd6 6. Nh3
{ A fresh move, recently introduced by Matthias Blübaum. The German GM makes the claim that on h3, the knight is better placed compared to e2. }
6... Nf6 7. O-O O-O 8. Qc2 Nbd7
{ 8...Ne4  9.f3  Nxc3  10.bxc3  e5  was a too optimistic approach by Black, in Blübaum-Krasenkow, Warsaw 2021, when the simple  11.cxd5  cxd5  12.dxe5  Bxe5  13.Ba3  Rf6  14.Rad1  already gives White a nearly winning positional advantage. }
9. f3 Qc7
{ Trying to either create a weakness in White's camp, like g2-g3 or, even worse, f3-f4. }
10. Nf4 Re8 11. h3
{ This waiting move allows us to execute a very interesting plan that is worth remembering. }
11... dxc4
{ Note that  11...a6  is even preferred by engines, and may be played as well. }
12. Bxc4 Bxf4 13. exf4
{ An enormous transition has taken place. Our once proud Wall has ceased to exist, but we did get something in return: the d5-square. Combined with queenside play that we will initiate over the next move, we seem to be doing OK. }
13... Qd6
{ Not  13...b5  14.Nxb5!  when  14...cxb5  15.Bxe6+  loses the queen to a classic discovery. }
14. Rd1 b5 15. Bb3 a5 16. a3 Kh8
{ Getting out of the a2-g8 diagonal. Interestingly enough, Stockfish is not at all impressed with our last few moves, while Leela seems to think all is well. We think Black has an easy game, where the next moves will include ...Bc8-a6, ...Nd7-b6, and, potentially, ...b5-b4.   A good illustration of how play may continue is  17.Kh2  Ba6  18.Be3  h6  ,  preparing ...Nh5 to poke around on the kingside in order to provoke some weaknesses. The position is very unclear. }
