{ Gdanski played  9...Ba6  twice, but we don't like the sequence  10.Nxd5!  Nxd5  11.cxd5  Bxd2  12.Qxd2  Bxd3  13.Qxd3  when Black fails to equalize, whichever  way we recapture on d5. By playing 9...a5 we protect the bishop on b4, preventing any Nxd5 trickery, and once again prepare ...Bc8-a6. }
10. Ne5 Ba6 11. b3
{ White's best bet, keeping light-squared bishops on the board. } 11... Qc7
{ We overrule the engines here that prefer  11...c5  . While that is certainly a fine move,  11...Qc7  keeps more tension in the position  and prepares ...Nb8-d7. }
12. Rc1 Nbd7
{ We could also have stepped out of the c-file first with  12...Qb7  but it's not strictly necessary. }
13. Be1 Ne4
{ At first sight, this seems to lead to trouble on the c-file, but no need to worry! }
14. cxd5 Bxd3 15. Qxd3 Bxc3 16. Nxc6 Ndf6 17. Bxc3 Nxd5
{ Black has great compensation for the pawn. Just look at those beautiful knights on d5 and e4! }
*

[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "11. Stonewall 3.Nc3 c6 4.e3 f5"]
[Black "Stonewall 3.Nc3 c6 4.e3 f5 5.f4 #14"]
[Result "*"]

1. d4 d5 2. c4 e6 3. Nc3 c6 4. e3
{ We thought long and hard about what to suggest against this modest pawn push. Of course  4...Nf6  is possible, but transposing to the so-called Slow-Slav, did not seem very appealing. After all, in our LTR we aim for fighting positions, while the winning chances in the Slow-Slav are slim, and the positions, though strategically not uninteresting, are rather dry. We have therefore decided to meet all the e3-setups @@StartBracket@@including the @@StartFEN@@rnbqkbnr/ppp2ppp/4p3/3p4/2PP4/8/PP2PPPP/RNBQKBNR w KQkq - 0 3@@EndFEN@@  3.Nf3  c6  4.e3  move order@@EndBracket@@ with the Stonewall. }
4... f5
{ Without a doubt, the most ambitious way of playing. As always, when a rigorous decision is made on the chessboard, there are clear up and downsides. Let's start with the obvious downside: placing the pawn on f5 means we leave ourselves with a giant hole on e5, and we weaken the dark squares as a whole. If White also manages to exchange the dark-squared bishops, which is a common strategic idea against the Stonewall we will regret having pushed the pawn to f5 in the first place.  Another small issue is the bishop on c8, which is often the problem child in the Stonewall, hidden behind all the pawns on the light squares.  Luckily, there are upsides as well. By playing ...f7-f5 we strengthen our presence in the center by controlling the e4-square a second time and set up an impressive wall of pawns behind which we can swiftly develop our pieces. As Simen Agdestein, a big exponent of the Stonewall, mentioned in his foreword to the book Win with the Stonewall Dutch, people often think that setting up a 'stone wall' means trying to stay solid and defensive, while the modern interpretation is very different.  As in many, if not all, other openings, the engines have shown that Black can play in many different ways, some of which the inventors of this opening never could have imagined! We will try to bring you up to date on all those modern ideas. }
5. f4
{ A rather annoying move to face. We are simply being copied, and on top of that, the pawn being on c4 means White is on the somewhat better side of the symmetry. On the upside, play can still get very interesting, as we found a curious method to unbalance the position. }
5... Nf6
{ 5...Qh4+!?  6.g3  Qd8  was played by Grischuk in 2001 and certainly has its merits. It could be used as a surprise weapon. }
6. Nf3 Bb4
{ A positionally well-founded move that was played three times by Gdanski in the '90s. Black intends to play ...b6, bring the bishop to a6, and, in due time, exchange on c3, thereby gaining full control of the light squares. }
7. Bd2
{ Almost universally played. Of the 14 games in the database, 12 times the bishop was moved to d2. }
7... O-O 8. Bd3 b6 9. O-O a5
{ Gdanski played  9...Ba6  twice, but we don't like the sequence  10.Nxd5!  Nxd5  11.cxd5  Bxd2  12.Qxd2  Bxd3  13.Qxd3  when Black fails to equalize, whichever  way we recapture on d5. By playing 9...a5 we protect the bishop on b4, preventing any Nxd5 trickery, and once again prepare ...Bc8-a6. }
10. Ne5 Ba6 11. b3
{ White's best bet, keeping light-squared bishops on the board. } 11... Qc7
{ We overrule the engines here that prefer  11...c5  . While that is certainly a fine move,  11...Qc7  keeps more tension in the position  and prepares ...Nb8-d7. }
12. Rc1 Nbd7
{ We could also have stepped out of the c-file first with  12...Qb7  but it's not strictly necessary. }
13. Be1 Ne4
{ At first sight, this seems to lead to trouble on the c-file, but no need to worry! }
14. cxd5 Bxd3 15. Qxd3 Bxc3 16. Nxd7 Qxd7 17. dxc6
{ This intermediate move nets White a pawn, but in the resulting position, our knight is clearly superior to the bishop. }
17... Qxc6 18. Bxc3 Qd5 { Black is in great shape. } *

[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
