5. g3 Nd7 6. Bg2 Nh6
{ We follow in the footsteps of Richard Rapport, who won a brilliant game using this setup. There are just a handful of practical examples here so the position is very fresh.   More orthodox is  6...Ngf6  7.O-O  @@StartBracket@@  7.Ng5  Qe7  followed by ...h6 and ...g5 is  also reasonable.@@EndBracket@@ @@StartFEN@@r1bqkb1r/pp1n2pp/2p1pn2/3p1p2/2PP4/5NP1/PP1NPPBP/R1BQ1RK1 b kq - 4 7@@EndFEN@@  7...Bd6  8.b3  O-O  9.Bb2  b6  followed by ...Bb7, which leads to a position that has a fine reputation. }
7. Qc2 Nf7 8. b3 { 8.cxd5  cxd5  is no issue with the knight on d2. } 8... g5
9. e3 Bd6 10. Bb2 a5 { A typical space-grabbing move on the queenside. } 11. h4
g4 12. Ng1 b5
{ With 12...b5 we deviate from Rapport’s game at this point, making sure it will be hard for White to get play on the queenside. The move is aimed against White playing a2-a4 and wanting to exchange bishops on a3. Another upside from pushing ...b7-b5 is that we can follow it up with ...Bc8-a6, bringing our light-squared bishop into the game. Black is very comfortable. We urge the student to have a look at Rapport's game since it is stunning! }
