5... Nf6
{ With the bishop on d3, we are happy to play @@StartFEN@@rnbqkbnr/pp4pp/2p1p3/3p1p2/2PP4/3BPN2/PP3PPP/RNBQK2R b KQkq - 0 5@@EndFEN@@  5...Nd7  6.O-O  Nh6  here, but with the bishop on e2, @@StartFEN@@r1bqkb1r/pp1n2pp/2p1p2n/3p1p2/2PP4/4PN2/PP2BPPP/RNBQ1RK1 w kq - 0 7@@EndFEN@@  7.b3  g5  8.e4!  is a giant difference. Though it should be mentioned that even without this direct refutation, the standard  8.Ba3  would also have led to an  improved version of the 5.Bd3 line since the bishop is better placed on e2 in this case: it is not in the way of a future Nf3-e1-d3 @@StartBracket@@after Black plays ...g5-g4@@EndBracket@@ and does a better job protecting White against Black's aggression on the kingside.   5...Bb4+!?  is a very original idea, though not new, but rather 'borrowed' from the Queen's Indian and Catalan where this maneuver is very common. The idea is to lure either the bishop or the  knight to d2, to prevent White from trading bishops on a3. The reason we aren't recommending it is  6.Bd2  Bd6  7.a3!  Threatening Bd2-b4.  7...a5  8.Ne5  Nf6  9.Nc3  O-O  10.f4  followed by castling kingside, when our position is cramped and it's hard to come up with an active plan. }
6. O-O Bd6
{ It's probably best to fall in line with common theory at this point. We tried to make  6...Ne4  7.b3  Nd7  8.Ba3  Bxa3  9.Nxa3  work,  when Black can try to go for ...g5 or even ...h5 first, but it's all rather dubious.   Not very ambitious but perhaps playable is  6...Be7  with the idea that after  7.b3  O-O  8.Ba3  , we can play  8...Bd7  and recapture  on e7 with the queen followed by ...Be8 and ...Nbd7. White is a bit better, but Black's position is certainly solid. }
7. b3 Qe7
{ It's important to make White work a little for the exchange of bishops. Instead,  7...O-O  8.Ba3  makes things too easy for White. }
8. a4
{ Of the two ways of exchanging bishops @@StartBracket@@the other one being Bc1-b2, Qd1-c1 followed by Bb2-a3@@EndBracket@@ this is the fastest one. One downside though, is that placing the pawn on a4 allows us to fix the pawn structure on the queenside in a favorable fashion. }
8... a5
{ Fixing the pawns on a4 and b3, which begs the question of how bad our c8-bishop will be in the long run. }
9. Ba3 Bxa3 10. Nxa3 O-O
{ There aren't that many practical examples that have reached this position, but the few that did give a reason for optimism. }
11. Nc2
{ White improves the worst placed piece in the position, the knight on a3. The plan is to reroute it via c2 to e1 and d3, to gain perfect control of the e5-square. }
11... b6
{ The other typical plan  11...Bd7  12.Nce1  Be8  does not work particularly well here. If White just ignores the maneuver and continues  13.Nd3  Bh5  14.Nfe5  Bxe2  15.Qxe2  Nbd7  16.Nxd7  Nxd7  17.Qb2  , the position is very unpleasant. Black is riddled with weaknesses and has little to show for it. }
12. Nce1 Na6
{ Next up: ...Bc8-b7 and ...c6-c5. Note that without the inclusion of the moves a2-a4 and ...a7-a5, Black's position would be extremely dubious from a strategic viewpoint. }
13. Nd3
{ Besides playing the obvious  13...Bb7  , which is fine, this move gives Black an additional option. }
13... dxc4 14. bxc4 c5
{ An enormous transformation! Our a6-knight will jump to b4 and the c8-bishop will have a good time on the long diagonal. Certainly, an interesting position to play. }
