{ There aren't that many practical examples that have reached this position, but the few that did give a reason for optimism. }
11. Qc2
{ Played by Vitiugov in 2016 and quite tricky. His opponent, Emre Can, did not manage in the game, but we found a clear improvement. }
11... Bd7
{ 11...Na6  12.Rfc1  Nb4  looks very desirable,  and b4 is a beautiful square for the knight indeed, yet, after  13.Qb2  followed by Na3-c2, the knight on b4 will be exchanged and a lot of tempi lost. }
12. Rfc1 Be8
{ 12...Ne4  13.Ne5  Be8  14.f3  was very pleasant for White in Vitiugov-Can, Gjakova 2016.  Can moved the knight to e4, in order to defend the f5-pawn but that turns out to be unnecessary. }
13. cxd5
{ After any other move, Black can finish development with moves like ...Nb8-d7 and ...Be8-h5 meaning the only relevant question is what happens if White goes for the pawn. }
13... exd5 14. Qxf5 Ne4 { Cutting off White's escape route back to safety. }
15. Qe5
{ The only good square, since  15.Qh3  gives Black plenty of good options. The simplest is  15...Bd7  16.Qh4  Qxh4  17.Nxh4  Rxf2  , with a comfortable endgame. }
15... Qd8
{ Of course, we have to avoid the exchange of queens. Next up is further harassment of the queen with ...Nb8-d7. }
16. Bd3 Nd7 17. Qe6+ Bf7 18. Qg4 Bg6
{ The half-open e- and f-files combined with the vulnerable positioning of White's queen, give Black excellent compensation for the pawn. }
19. Bxe4 { It makes sense to eliminate Black's powerful knight on e4. } 19...
Bxe4 20. Nd2 Bf5 21. Qe2 Qg5
{ We will play ...Ra8-e8-e6 next, with powerful compensation. } *

