{ The point! Of course, Black did not intend to suffer for the remainder of the game after  13...bxa3  14.Rxa3  Rxa3  15.Qxa3  when White holds all trumps. As Sadler points out, Stoofvlees' idea is not to fight for the a-file, but rather to use the whole queenside operation as a diversion for play on the other side of the board. }
14. Bxf5 { The critical reply. } 14... e4
{ A very playable alternative, after which White has three knight moves. } 15.
Nfd2 Nh5 { 15...Nc5!?  can be considered as well. } 16. Bg4 Ndf6
{ This leads to remarkably forced play. } 17. Bxc8
{ 17.Bxh5  Nxh5  18.axb4  Rxa1  19.Qxa1  Qg5  20.Kh1  Nf6!  is rather tricky for White. }
17... Raxc8 18. axb4
{ Trying to prevent what’s coming next with  18.h3  makes matters even worse. Black plays  18...g5!  and will tear apart White’s king in no time. }
18... Ng4 19. h3 Nxf2
{ The consequence of our previous move. There is no holding back now! } 20.
Rxf2 Rxf2 21. Kxf2 Rf8+ 22. Kg1 Qf6 23. Nxe4
{ The only move, and what is even more remarkable, it seems to allow White to stay in the game. }
23... dxe4 24. Qe2
{ 24.Nc3  Ng3  followed  by ...h5-h4, cages White's king and makes it hard for White to do anything with the extra pawn. }
24... Nf4 25. Qg4 Ng6
{ Unfortunately, we have nothing better but to retreat. Now White can repeat with  26.Qe2  or continue the game a little longer. }
26. Kh2 Qf2 27. Qe6+ Kh8 28. Qxe4 Qe1
{ Setting up counterplay with ...Rf8-f1. } 29. d5 Rf1 30. Ra8+ Nf8 31. Rxf8+
Rxf8
{ A draw is the likeliest outcome. White will start pushing the pawns after which Black will force a perpetual. }
*

[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "13. Stonewall 4.e3 f5 5.Bd3"]
[Black "Stonewall 14.Bxf5 e4 #2 | Alternative"]
[Result "*"]

1. d4 d5 2. c4 e6 3. Nf3 c6 4. e3
{ Inviting us to play a Meran type of game with  4...Nf6  , but as you probably know by now, that is not how we are going to roll in this course!  Against all the e3 setups we employ the Stonewall. }
4... f5
{ And there we go! As always, when a rigorous decision is made on the chessboard, there are clear up and downsides. Let's start with the obvious downside: placing the pawn on f5 means we leave ourselves with a giant hole on e5, and we weaken the dark squares as a whole. If White also manages to exchange the dark-squared bishops, which is a common strategic idea against the Stonewall, we will regret having pushed the pawn to f5 in the first place.   Another small issue is the bishop on c8, which is often the problem child in the Stonewall, hidden behind all the pawns on the light squares.  Luckily, there are upsides as well. By playing ...f7-f5 we strengthen our presence in the center by controlling the e4-square a second time and set up an impressive wall of pawns behind which we can swiftly develop our pieces. As Simen Agdestein, a big exponent of the Stonewall, mentioned very nicely in his foreword to the book Win with the Stonewall Dutch, people often think that setting up a 'stone wall' means trying to stay solid and defensive, while the modern interpretation is very different.  As in many other openings, the engines have shown that Black can play this opening in many different ways, some of which the inventors of this opening never could have imagined! We will try to bring you up to date on all those ideas. }
5. Bd3 { By far the main move in the position. } 5... Nf6
{ And the most usual reply. A game analyzed by Matthew Sadler in The Silicon Road to Chess Improvement recently caught our eye. In that game, the engine Stoofvlees came up with the most remarkable concept. Many of the lines that now follow are taken from the book as well. }
6. O-O Bd6 7. b3
{ We are faced with the usual plan of exchanging bishops on a3. } 7... Qe7 8.
Bb2
{ With the bishop on d3, the plan connected to  8.a4  is less attractive. The reason for that becomes apparent after  8...a5  9.Ba3  Bxa3  10.Nxa3  O-O  , when we have reached the same position as in the previous chapter,  except for the fact that White's light-squared bishop was on e2 in that line. As it is, the plan of going Na3-c2-e1-d3 is now much harder to achieve, as the bishop is in the way, making this a less favorable version for White. }
8... O-O 9. Qc1 a5
{ Surprise, surprise! Magnus Carlsen faced Black here in 2021 in the MC-tour on chess24, against Vidit, and that game continued  9...b6  10.Ba3  Bb7  11.Bxd6  Qxd6  12.Qa3  Qxa3  13.Nxa3  and Carlsen, being Carlsen, managed to win this endgame, which, objectively speaking, gave White a risk-free edge. 9...a5 is the move advocated by Stoofvlees and a whole lot more fun! }
10. Ba3 Bb4 { Agreeing to the exchange of bishops, but on our terms. } 11. Qb2
Nbd7 12. Bxb4 axb4 13. a3 e5
{ The point! Of course, Black did not intend to suffer for the remainder of the game after  13...bxa3  14.Rxa3  Rxa3  15.Qxa3  when White holds all trumps. As Sadler points out, Stoofvlees' idea is not to fight for the a-file, but rather to use the whole queenside operation as a diversion for play on the other side of the board. }
14. Bxf5 { The critical reply. } 14... e4
{ A very playable alternative, after which White has three knight moves. } 15.
Ng5 h6
{ 15...Ne8!?  is a cheeky idea, since after  16.Bxh7+  Kh8  , the bishop and knight look loose on the kingside. The line continues  17.h4  Nd6  18.axb4  Rxa1  19.Qxa1  Nf7  20.cxd5  Nxg5  21.hxg5  Kxh7  22.dxc6  bxc6  with very unclear play. }
16. Nh3 Nc5 { Another nice tactical point. } 17. dxc5 Bxf5 18. Nf4 d4 19. Qxd4
Rad8 20. Qb2 g5 21. Ne2 h5 22. axb4 Ng4
{ Preparing action against the king on g1 and, if attacked by h2-h3, the knight can jump to d3 via e5. }
*

