5. Bd3 { By far the main move in the position. } 5... Nh6
{ This is an alternative way to funk things up. We will not yet move the bishop from f8 so that the plan of b3 and Ba3 can be met with ...Bxa3, without having wasted any time on developing the f8-bishop. That means our next move will be ...Nd7 and then we start our play on the kingside with ...g5.   Starting with  5...Nd7  is bad because of  6.cxd5!  cxd5  7.Bd2  Ngf6  8.Qb3  when Bd2-b4 next promises White an enduring positional advantage. }
6. O-O
{ Certainly, White's most natural response is to castle and follow it up with b2-b3 and Bc1-a3. }
6... Nd7 7. Ne5
{ White seeks to punish Black's setup but it's bound to backfire.  7.cxd5  can now be met with  7...exd5! }
7... Nxe5 8. dxe5 Ng4
{ The endgame after  8...Nf7  9.f4  dxc4  10.Bxc4  Qxd1  11.Rxd1  is very ugly for Black, because of the cramped nature of the position. }
9. f4 g5 { Hitting White where it hurts. } 10. h3 h5
{ An important move as retreating the knight would be very sad. Black has excellent prospects and the only line of interest is one where White accepts the sacrifice. }
11. hxg4 hxg4 12. Qe1
{ Trying to prevent ...Qh4 after the inevitable capture on f4. } 12... gxf4 13.
Rxf4 dxc4 14. Bxc4 Qg5 15. Nd2 Be7 16. Nf1 Qh5
{ A fascinating position! We are a piece down and aren't exactly mating just yet. Instead, we will play ...b5, ...Bb7/a6, and castle kingside with ongoing positional pressure.   A possible continuation is  17.Kf2  Qh1  18.g3  b5  19.Be2  Ba6  20.b4  O-O-O  21.Qc3  Rh2+  22.Nxh2  Qxh2+  with perpetual check. }
