[Round "?"]
[White "13. Stonewall 4.e3 f5 5.Bd3"]
[Black "Stonewall 5.Bd3 Nh6 #6 | Alternative"]
[Result "*"]

1. d4 d5 2. c4 e6 3. Nf3 c6 4. e3
{ Inviting us to play a Meran type of game with  4...Nf6  , but as you probably know by now, that is not how we are going to roll in this course!  Against all the e3 setups we employ the Stonewall. }
4... f5
{ And there we go! As always, when a rigorous decision is made on the chessboard, there are clear up and downsides. Let's start with the obvious downside: placing the pawn on f5 means we leave ourselves with a giant hole on e5, and we weaken the dark squares as a whole. If White also manages to exchange the dark-squared bishops, which is a common strategic idea against the Stonewall, we will regret having pushed the pawn to f5 in the first place.   Another small issue is the bishop on c8, which is often the problem child in the Stonewall, hidden behind all the pawns on the light squares.  Luckily, there are upsides as well. By playing ...f7-f5 we strengthen our presence in the center by controlling the e4-square a second time and set up an impressive wall of pawns behind which we can swiftly develop our pieces. As Simen Agdestein, a big exponent of the Stonewall, mentioned very nicely in his foreword to the book Win with the Stonewall Dutch, people often think that setting up a 'stone wall' means trying to stay solid and defensive, while the modern interpretation is very different.  As in many other openings, the engines have shown that Black can play this opening in many different ways, some of which the inventors of this opening never could have imagined! We will try to bring you up to date on all those ideas. }
5. Bd3 { By far the main move in the position. } 5... Nh6
{ This is an alternative way to funk things up. We will not yet move the bishop from f8 so that the plan of b3 and Ba3 can be met with ...Bxa3, without having wasted any time on developing the f8-bishop. That means our next move will be ...Nd7 and then we start our play on the kingside with ...g5.   Starting with  5...Nd7  is bad because of  6.cxd5!  cxd5  7.Bd2  Ngf6  8.Qb3  when Bd2-b4 next promises White an enduring positional advantage. }
6. O-O
{ Certainly, White's most natural response is to castle and follow it up with b2-b3 and Bc1-a3. }
6... Nd7 7. b3 { 7.cxd5  can now be met with  7...exd5! } 7... g5
{ There we go! Officially, this is a new move, but given that both Stockfish and Leela consider this as the best move in the position, it can be introduced into practice soon. It's not like we signal a mating attack with this move, but it could very well be the start of a long-term initiative on the kingside. Furthermore, by pushing the pawn to g4 later on, kicking away the f3-knight, we are also fighting for the e5-square. }
8. Nc3 { It feels odd not to continue the plan of exchanging bishops on a3. }
8... Nf7 9. cxd5
{ This capture makes sense now that we have to recapture with the c-pawn. We have enough play on the kingside though. }
9... cxd5 10. a4 h5
{ Eventually, we will also push  10...g4  but to do it immediately gives White some extra options along the lines of  11.Ne1  h5  12.Ne2!  followed by Nf4. }
11. Ba3 Bxa3 12. Rxa3 g4 13. Ne1 h4
{ Black is fine and it's good to note that  14.Ne2  is not a very dangerous plan here, because we are in time with  14...h3!  15.g3  Nf6  which guarantees us a fine game after, for instance,  16.Nf4  Qd6  17.Ra2  Bd7  etc. }
*

