5. Bd3 { By far the main move in the position. } 5... Nh6
{ This is an alternative way to funk things up. We will not yet move the bishop from f8 so that the plan of b3 and Ba3 can be met with ...Bxa3, without having wasted any time on developing the f8-bishop. That means our next move will be ...Nd7 and then we start our play on the kingside with ...g5.   Starting with  5...Nd7  is bad because of  6.cxd5!  cxd5  7.Bd2  Ngf6  8.Qb3  when Bd2-b4 next promises White an enduring positional advantage. }
6. O-O
{ Certainly, White's most natural response is to castle and follow it up with b2-b3 and Bc1-a3. }
6... Nd7 7. b3 { 7.cxd5  can now be met with  7...exd5! } 7... g5
{ There we go! Officially, this is a new move, but given that both Stockfish and Leela consider this as the best move in the position, it can be introduced into practice soon. It's not like we signal a mating attack with this move, but it could very well be the start of a long-term initiative on the kingside. Furthermore, by pushing the pawn to g4 later on, kicking away the f3-knight, we are also fighting for the e5-square. }
8. Ba3 Bxa3
{ While we are never thrilled to get the dark-squared bishops off the board, we at least haven't lost any time in doing so, which is usually the case when the bishop is on d6. }
9. Nxa3 g4 10. Nd2
{ Or  10.Ne1  Nf6  preparing further counterplay on the kingside with ...Nf7 and ...h5-h4. }
10... Nf6
{ It's hard to analyze this position to completion, but we feel Black has fair chances here. Yes, we sorrowly miss our dark-squared bishop, but in return White's knights are somewhat derailed for the moment, not making use of the square e5. We have a clear plan of action on the kingside where we will move the h6-knight to f7 and start storming the h-pawn forward. This is anyone's game! For completeness' sake, we give the main line of the engines. }
11. Nab1 { Starting the long journey to f4. } 11... Nf7 12. Nc3 h5 13. Ne2 Qe7
{ We take some prophylactic measures as  13...h4  14.Nf4  Rh6  15.f3!  is plain bad. }
14. Nf4 Rh6 15. cxd5 Nxd5
{ Not  15...exd5  16.Qc2  Nd6  17.b4!  followed by a2-a4, with annoying queenside pressure. }
16. Nxd5 { The difference is rather stark in comparison with 15...exd5. } 16...
exd5 17. Qc2 Rf6
{ White is not nearly as fast on the queenside now, and we will start pushing our h-pawn. }
*

