1. d4 d5 2. c4 e6 3. Nf3 c6 4. g3
{ White immediately reveals the intention to go for a setup in the spirit of the Catalan @@StartFEN@@rnbqkbnr/pppppppp/8/8/8/8/PPPPPPPP/RNBQKBNR w KQkq - 0 1@@EndFEN@@  1.d4  d5  2.c4  e6  3.Nf3  Nf6  4.g3  .   There are various ways for White to play for the kingside fianchetto. In most cases, our opponents are worried about the c-pawn and first cover it with a queen or knight move  4.Qc2  ,  4.Qb3  , or  4.Nbd2  ,  but intend to play g3 soon after.   These lines are safe choices for White, but we obtain good counterplay in all cases. The move  4.g3  is a more ambitious  way for White to employ a Catalan formation. They immediately start the fianchetto but ignore the threat to the c4-pawn. Black's principled reply, and perfectly in line with the Noteboom spirit, is grabbing the c4-pawn and clinging to it with ...b5. }
4... dxc4
{ Clearly in the spirit of the Noteboom. If White fails to protect the c-pawn, we happily take it. The game takes a sharp course now, but that's what we signed up for. White usually gets enough compensation, but not more than that. We felt this suggestion promised the best chance to stir up a fight.   The alternatives at this point are  4...f5  @@StartBracket@@a less desirable Stonewall than @@StartFEN@@rnbqkbnr/pp3ppp/2p1p3/3p4/2PP4/5N2/PP2PPPP/RNBQKB1R w KQkq - 0 4@@EndFEN@@  4.Nbd2  f5  , because White's knight is not yet committed@@EndBracket@@ and @@StartFEN@@rnbqkbnr/pp3ppp/2p1p3/3p4/2PP4/5NP1/PP2PP1P/RNBQKB1R b KQkq - 0 4@@EndFEN@@  4...Nf6  , aiming for a Closed Catalan. Defending Black's side of Closed Catalan does not fit well with the energetic style of this repertoire, so we discarded this option. }
5. Bg2
{ White has no way to recoup the c4-pawn and continues with the natural move. }
5... b5
{ We support the pawn but neglect development for a while. It's important to understand that our setup is better than comparable lines in standard Catalan. There is the line @@StartFEN@@rnbqkbnr/pppppppp/8/8/8/8/PPPPPPPP/RNBQKBNR w KQkq - 0 1@@EndFEN@@  1.d4  d5  2.c4  e6  3.Nf3  Nf6  4.g3  dxc4  5.Bg2  b5?!  6.a4  c6  7.Ne5  , which gives White a strong initiative and the advantage - Black can't play  7...a6  or  7...Bb7  , which is awkward. A key difference is that White very quickly puts pressure on the queenside, even before kingside castling.  We are much better off in our 'Triangle Catalan' as we have not played the move ...Nf6 yet. This helps a lot, as it becomes clear once you look at some specific lines. Let's discuss how White continues after @@StartFEN@@rnbqkbnr/pp3ppp/2p1p3/8/2pP4/5NP1/PP2PPBP/RNBQK2R b KQkq - 1 5@@EndFEN@@  5...b5  . White wants to put pressure on our queenside.  The typical moves are Ne5, and the pawn pushes to a4 and b3, directly attacking our pawns. White can also hardly play without kingside castling, of course.  After 5...b5,  we decided to cover  6.O-O  as the main move. You'll also meet  6.a4  and  6.Ne5  frequently, but these moves don't have any significant independent value. White needs to castle and will usually play this move soon after. Therefore our coverage of  6.a4  and  6.Ne5  will consist of transpositions galore.  Move orders and transpositions are often a pain, but it is not that much of an issue for Black. Our moves after  6.a4  and  6.Ne5  are very natural and usually even forced, so you'll almost automatically transpose into the main line  6.O-O  , which is the central part of the whole chapter. }
6. Ne5
{ A popular move for White, which will still often transpose to lines that we examine using the 6.O-O move order. Castling kingside is very natural for White, after all. }
6... Bb7
{ An easy choice, covering the c6-pawn. White's popular move is  7.O-O  when  7...Nf6  transposes to @@StartFEN@@rnbqkbnr/p4ppp/2p1p3/1p6/2pP4/5NP1/PP2PPBP/RNBQK2R w KQkq - 0 6@@EndFEN@@  6.O-O  Nf6  7.Ne5  Bb7  , which is a commonly reached position. }
7. a4
{ White could also play  7.Nc3  when  7...a6  lends additional cover to b5. Now the ways for White  to transpose are  8.O-O  Nf6  or @@StartFEN@@rn1qkbnr/1b3ppp/p1p1p3/1p2N3/2pP4/2N3P1/PP2PPBP/R1BQK2R w KQkq - 0 8@@EndFEN@@  8.a4  Nf6  9.O-O  Be7  , which are examined via the 6.O-O move order. }
7... a6 8. Nc3
{ Again  8.O-O  is just a transposition after  8...Nf6  , which is covered via the 6.O-O move order. }
8... Nf6 9. axb5
{ You probably guessed right that  9.O-O  Be7  is yet another transposition to 6.O-O, as usual. }
9... axb5 10. Rxa8 Bxa8 11. O-O
{ White finally castles, allowing the transposition. } 11... Be7
{ And it's done: the current position is examined via @@StartFEN@@rnbqkbnr/p4ppp/2p1p3/1p6/2pP4/5NP1/PP2PPBP/RNBQK2R w KQkq - 0 6@@EndFEN@@  6.O-O  Nf6  7.a4  Bb7  8.Ne5  a6  9.Nc3  Be7  10.axb5  axb5  11.Rxa8  Bxa8  , which leads to about equal chances. }
