{ That's the move with some independent value. White can also play  8.axb3  , of course. This will very likely transpose to @@StartFEN@@rnbqkb1r/p4ppp/2p1pn2/1p6/2pP4/5NP1/PP2PPBP/RNBQ1RK1 w kq - 2 7@@EndFEN@@  7.Ne5  Bb7  8.b3  cxb3  9.axb3  ,  as the move Ne5 is such a vital part of White's play.  So after @@StartFEN@@rnbqkb1r/p4ppp/2p1pn2/1p6/3P4/1p3NP1/P3PPBP/RNBQ1RK1 w kq - 0 8@@EndFEN@@  8.axb3  Bb7  9.Ne5  a5  we'd immediately transpose. White could start with something like @@StartFEN@@rn1qkb1r/pb3ppp/2p1pn2/1p6/3P4/1P3NP1/4PPBP/RNBQ1RK1 w kq - 1 9@@EndFEN@@  9.Nc3  ,  but the same setup with ...a5 and ...Qb6 would work for us. }
8... Bd6
{ An unusual and surprising move. It is a novelty suggested by Stockfish and improves on the standard move  8...Bb7  . Exactly here, you'll see why we prefer the move order @@StartFEN@@rnbqkbnr/p4ppp/2p1p3/1p6/2pP4/5NP1/PP2PPBP/RNBQK2R w KQkq - 0 6@@EndFEN@@  6.O-O  Nf6  , compared to  6...Bb7  . If we'd play  6...Bb7  , almost all lines are exactly the same −  here we see the only exception! But what's the point of placing the bishop on d6? It's not easy to explain, but here we go!  We need to start our discussion  with @@StartFEN@@rnbqkb1r/p4ppp/2p1pn2/1p6/3P4/1Q3NP1/P3PPBP/RNB2RK1 b kq - 0 8@@EndFEN@@  8...Bb7  and see how the standard move unfolds. After  9.Nc3  Be7  10.Ne5  White exerts some pressure. Black has the fundamental choice between  10...b4  or a more passive setup with  10...a6  . The passive setup is complicated for Black to play as experienced in the game Nakamura-Lenderman, St. Louis 2016. After  10...a6  11.Rd1  O-O  12.Ne4  Qc7  13.Ng5  a5  14.Bh3  White had enormous pressure.  The move  10...b4  looks stronger and more active. Black's idea is to activate the bishop via a6 later, often after ...a5 is played first. Now we get to the idea of not playing 8...Bb7 to begin with. If we later want to activate the bishop on a6, we could manage this in one move instead of two. This leads to searching for an alternative  to @@StartFEN@@rnbqkb1r/p4ppp/2p1pn2/1p6/3P4/1Q3NP1/P3PPBP/RNB2RK1 b kq - 0 8@@EndFEN@@  8...Bb7  .  It makes a lot of sense to prepare kingside castling, so  8...Be7  or  8...Bd6  come to mind. Which one is better? The difference is the following line: After  8...Bd6  9.Ne5  we have the strong move  9...O-O!  , still avoiding the  move ...Bb7. We don't mind  10.Nxc6  , as this would help us to organize our position @@StartBracket@@more on that later@@EndBracket@@.  The issue with @@StartFEN@@rnbqkb1r/p4ppp/2p1pn2/1p6/3P4/1Q3NP1/P3PPBP/RNB2RK1 b kq - 0 8@@EndFEN@@  8...Be7  is that  9.Ne5  can't be answered with  9...O-O?  because  10.Bxc6!  Nxc6  11.Nxc6  Qc7  12.Nxe7+  Qxe7  13.Ba3  wins for White.  Alright, let's have a closer look at 8...Bd6 now. It's a new idea, so we don't have any game samples to use. }
9. Ne5 { This looks like the most likely and critical move. } 9... O-O
{ A key point of our move order. We don't play the bishop to b7, but rather allow White to take on c6. }
10. Nc3
{ This looks like the most logical move. White is not interested in  10.Nxc6  Nxc6  11.Bxc6  Rb8  , when Black is already significantly better. White has traded all of the active pieces and is behind in development. }
10... b4
{ This advance is part of our plan as our bishop is aiming for the a6-f1 diagonal. }
11. Na4
{ Or  11.Ne4  Nxe4  12.Bxe4  a5  ,  intending ...Ba6 as soon as possible. }
11... a5
{ The immediate  11...Ba6  also seems to work fine, but supporting the advanced pawn first looks harmonious. We want to  play ...Ba6 next, activating our worst piece. This leads to an exciting position in which White has some compensation for the pawn, but we managed to position our pieces effectively. }
