{ We support the pawn but neglect development for a while. It's important to understand that our setup is better than comparable lines in standard Catalan. There is the line @@StartFEN@@rnbqkbnr/pppppppp/8/8/8/8/PPPPPPPP/RNBQKBNR w KQkq - 0 1@@EndFEN@@  1.d4  d5  2.c4  e6  3.Nf3  Nf6  4.g3  dxc4  5.Bg2  b5?!  6.a4  c6  7.Ne5  , which gives White a strong initiative and the advantage - Black can't play  7...a6  or  7...Bb7  , which is awkward. A key difference is that White very quickly puts pressure on the queenside, even before kingside castling.  We are much better off in our 'Triangle Catalan' as we have not played the move ...Nf6 yet. This helps a lot, as it becomes clear once you look at some specific lines. Let's discuss how White continues after @@StartFEN@@rnbqkbnr/pp3ppp/2p1p3/8/2pP4/5NP1/PP2PPBP/RNBQK2R b KQkq - 1 5@@EndFEN@@  5...b5  . White wants to put pressure on our queenside.  The typical moves are Ne5, and the pawn pushes to a4 and b3, directly attacking our pawns. White can also hardly play without kingside castling, of course.  After 5...b5,  we decided to cover  6.O-O  as the main move. You'll also meet  6.a4  and  6.Ne5  frequently, but these moves don't have any significant independent value. White needs to castle and will usually play this move soon after. Therefore our coverage of  6.a4  and  6.Ne5  will consist of transpositions galore.  Move orders and transpositions are often a pain, but it is not that much of an issue for Black. Our moves after  6.a4  and  6.Ne5  are very natural and usually even forced, so you'll almost automatically transpose into the main line  6.O-O  , which is the central part of the whole chapter. }
6. O-O
{ White castles first and only later decide how to combine moves like Ne5, a4 or b3. }
6... Nf6
{ We suggest starting with this move, instead of  6...Bb7  . The difference between the two moves is small, but we believe playing  6...Nf6  is slightly more flexible due to one particular line. Please see the line  6...Nf6  7.b3  for more on this topic. After  6...Nf6  , we'll cover three moves, which are all standard ideas in White's arsenal.  A@@EndBracket@@  7.a4  is very popular and our main line.  B@@EndBracket@@  7.Ne5  is also frequently seen.  In many cases, a later a4 will transpose into lines that we cover under A, though.   C@@EndBracket@@  7.b3  is an interesting sideline. White immediately changes the queenside pawn structure and intends to play without a quick a4. }
7. Ne5
{ A standard move in White's arsenal. It does have some independent value, but transpositions to  7.a4  are still possible. }
7... Bb7
{ After this natural move, there are still options for White to play a4, which will transpose to lines that we examine via the 7.a4 move order.   A@@EndBracket@@  8.a4  a6  immediately transposes to the 7.a4 variation.   B@@EndBracket@@  8.Nc3  a6  9.a4  Be7  also transposes to the 7.a4 move order.  White's independent options involve the pawn sacrifice idea b3, which, just as a4, can be played on move eight or nine.   Let's examine  8.b3  and  8.Nc3  a6  9.b3  now. }
8. b3
{ A familiar idea. White can't make much headway without attacking our pawn chain. }
8... cxb3
{ After our capture, White has to decide whether to sacrifice a second pawn with  9.Qxb3  Qxd4  or capture with the a-pawn, which is far more common. }
9. Qxb3 { White offers the d-pawn. Should we take it? } 9... Qxd4
{ Yes, we grab the pawn. You should almost always be 'greedy' if you can take a center pawn without any obvious negative consequences. Here, two extra pawns are already a serious material advantage for us, and White needs to prove enough compensation for the material investment.   We want to mention that White follows a similar concept in the line @@StartFEN@@rnbqkb1r/p4ppp/2p1pn2/1p6/2pP4/5NP1/PP2PPBP/RNBQ1RK1 w kq - 2 7@@EndFEN@@  7.a4  Bb7  8.Ne5  a6  9.b3  cxb3  10.Qxb3  Qxd4  ,  when the additional moves a4 and ...a6 are on the board. }
10. Bf4
{ White has never tried this interesting move in practice, but it shows a difference between this line and the one with the additional moves ...a6 and a4.   After  10.Bf4  , we can't play  10...Qxa1??  due to  11.Nc3  , when our queen is trapped, and White has a crushing attack after  11...Qxf1+  12.Kxf1  .  With the two a-pawn moves inserted, we'd still have ...Qa3 to escape.   Instead of the move  10.Bf4  , White usually prefers the more natural move  10.Bb2  , when we play  10...Qb4  11.Qc2  Qc5  , using the same concept as in the line @@StartFEN@@rnbqkb1r/p4ppp/2p1pn2/1p6/2pP4/5NP1/PP2PPBP/RNBQ1RK1 w kq - 2 7@@EndFEN@@  7.a4  Bb7  8.Ne5  a6  9.b3  cxb3  10.Qxb3  Qxd4  11.Bb2  Qb4  12.Qc2  Qc5  . White has some compensation for the pawns, but it's a fair deal: two pawns are a lot. }
10... Nd5
{ As already mentioned, we need to avoid  10...Qxa1?  11.Nc3  Qxf1+  12.Kxf1  , which gives White a crushing attack. }
11. Rd1 { That's the only good move for White. } 11... Qa4
{ This is our suggestion, but  11...Qb6  is also playable. After  12.Qf3  Bc5  , White has the flashy  13.Bh6  , but  13...O-O  14.Qg4  g6  15.Bxf8  Bxf8  is a good reply. Black had to give up the exchange. but this is of minor importance, given that the two extra pawns remain on the board.   Please note that  11...Qxa1?  is still bad, this time due to  12.Bxd5  exd5  13.Nc3  , which traps the queen again. }
12. Qd3 { The only way to keep the queen on and cover the rook. } 12... Be7
{ We need to castle asap! } 13. Nc3 Qa6
{ This is much better than  13...Qa5  ,  as covering the b7-bishop is surprisingly important.  After 13...Qa5 White has the same idea as after  13...Qa6  , but it is much more effective. Let's have a look:  13...Qa5?  14.Nxd5  cxd5  15.e4  d4  16.Qxd4  O-O  17.a4  Nc6  and now  18.Qd7!  highlights the difference: our bishop is attacked and hanging, which is not the case with  the queen being on a6. }
14. Nxd5
{ White needs to open the position before we get to organize everything and start converting the extra pawns. }
14... cxd5 15. e4 d4
{ This keeps the position closed. Stockfish can determine that  15...f6  also works, but  16.Ng6!?  hxg6  17.exd5  looks very scary for a human player. Our suggestion is simpler to handle. }
16. Qxd4 O-O
{ It took a while, but we managed to castle. We still have an extra pawn, but White is active enough to claim compensation and will often regain the second pawn. }
