{ This knight jump looks attractive. White opens the diagonal for their bishop and threatens axb5 now, which more or less forces us to play 8...a6. }
8... a6
{ We support the b-pawn, there is no fully satisfactory alternative. After  8...a6  , White's most frequently played lines are  9.Nc3  Be7  10.axb5  axb5  11.Rxa8  Bxa8  or @@StartFEN@@rn1qkb1r/1b3ppp/p1p1pn2/1p2N3/P1pP4/6P1/1P2PPBP/RNBQ1RK1 w kq - 0 9@@EndFEN@@  9.axb5  axb5  10.Rxa8  Bxa8  11.Nc3  Be7  , which lead to the same position and pose no problem. More dangerous is @@StartFEN@@rn1qkb1r/1b3ppp/p1p1pn2/1p2N3/P1pP4/6P1/1P2PPBP/RNBQ1RK1 w kq - 0 9@@EndFEN@@  9.b3  , trying to open the queenside as quickly as possible. }
9. Nc3
{ By far White's most popular move, but it's not as challenging as  9.b3  , as we'll see now. }
9... Be7
{ A strong reply. We'd like to castle as soon as possible and don't mind returning a pawn to simplify our defense. }
10. axb5
{ The following sequence is forced and more or less the only sensible option for White. }
10... axb5 11. Rxa8 Bxa8 12. Nxb5 { Alright, White gets the pawn back. } 12...
cxb5 13. Bxa8 O-O 14. Bg2
{ White has lost a lot of time on the recovery mission. Now Black has more than one good move to organize. }
14... Qc7
{ Black is also fine with some other moves, like  14...Qb6  ,  14...Bd6  , or  14...h6  . You see that we are not talking about a very tactical, concrete position as Black has so many options.  Our next step is challenging the e5-knight with ...Bd6 or ...Nbd7. It's also possible to consider ...Na6-b4. White enjoys the bishop pair, but our advanced queenside pawns compensate for this deficit. }
