11. Nd2
{ This move is recommended by Narayanan. The following sequence looks like the best play from both sides. }
11... Nxe5 12. dxe5 Nd7
{ We prefer this move over  12...Nd5  . You'll see that our knight is well placed after the following moves. }
13. Ne4 { White is aiming at the weak d6-square. } 13... Be7 14. Nd6+ Bxd6 15.
exd6
{ White managed to establish a strong pawn on d6, but our knight is an excellent blockading piece. Note that  16.Qxd6?!  Qb8  leads nowhere for White. }
15... O-O 16. Qxb3
{ White finally takes the b-pawn. Narayanan concludes his analysis here and correctly assesses that White has good compensation for the pawn. We'll look closer once our suggested reply is on the board. A small side note: it's fascinating to see that @@StartFEN@@r2qkb1r/1b1n1ppp/p1p1pn2/1p2N3/P2P4/1p4P1/1B2PPBP/RN1Q1RK1 w kq - 2 11@@EndFEN@@  11.Qxb3  Nxe5  12.dxe5  Nd7  13.Nd2  Be7  14.Ne4  O-O  15.Nd6  Bxd6  16.exd6  leads to the same position. }
16... Qb6
{ A logical move. We cover the bishop and thus threaten ...c5 now. White has to address this threat, so slow development is not enough. Therefore, we don't have to examine many moves now: we'll focus on  17.a5  Qa7  18.Bxc6  , which regains the pawn, and @@StartFEN@@r4rk1/1b1n1ppp/pqpPp3/1p6/P7/1Q4P1/1B2PPBP/R4RK1 w - - 1 17@@EndFEN@@  17.Qf3  . }
17. Qf3
{ White stops ...c5 and swings the queen to the kingside. Ideas like Qg4 come to mind. }
17... b4
{ The alternative  17...Rab8  also works fine. We like  17...b4  a bit more, as it allows us to answer  18.a5  with  18...Qb5  now. }
18. h4
{ This looks best. The direct  18.Qg4?!  is worse, as  18...g6  19.Qh4  c5  shows.  We get to play ...c5 too easily in this line. White could try a different move to strengthen the attack, though.   An idea could be  18.Rfd1  , but  18...Rab8  @@StartBracket@@threatening ...c5@@EndBracket@@  19.Qg4  g6  20.h4  c5  works well for Black. White has enough attack to compensate for the pawn, but not more.   The move  18.h4  is more cunning.  White intends to play Qg4 and answer  18...g6  with the immediate  19.h5  . }
18... Rad8
{ A tough but powerful move! The idea is to answer Qg4 with ...e5!, which is now possible due to the d7-knight being covered by the rook.   If you'd play  18...Rab8?  , White has  19.Qg4  g6  20.h5  c5  21.hxg6  hxg6  and will breakthrough now.  22.Qh3  already forces the sad  22...f6  23.Qxe6+  , and according to the comp, White even has better moves than 22.Qh3. Long story short: the move 18...Rad8! is MUCH better. }
19. Qg4
{ This is a mistake, but we want to show the reason as a trainable line. White should instead try to activate the rooks, for example, like  19.a5  Qb5  20.Rab1  , looking indirectly at the b-pawn. After  20...Ba8  21.Qg4  e5  22.Bc1  h5  23.Qxb4  Qxb4  24.Rxb4  c5  we'd reach an endgame with equal chances, but there are plenty of alternatives, of course. }
19... e5
{ The huge point of the previous move. We manage to close the long diagonal and defend against the mate threat without weakening our kingside at all. Black is much better now as White does not have enough play for the pawn at all. }
