{ The first important moment. We don't mind returning a pawn to coordinate our forces. Now we'll take a closer look at  11.Nxc6  and Narayanan's suggestion  11.Nd2  . Please note that  11.Qxb3  will likely lead to the same positions as  11.Nd2  , as we'll examine shortly. }
11. Nd2
{ This move is recommended by Narayanan. The following sequence looks like the best play from both sides. }
11... Nxe5 12. dxe5 Nd7
{ We prefer this move over  12...Nd5  . You'll see that our knight is well placed after the following moves. }
13. Ne4 { White is aiming at the weak d6-square. } 13... Be7 14. Nd6+ Bxd6 15.
exd6
{ White managed to establish a strong pawn on d6, but our knight is an excellent blockading piece. Note that  16.Qxd6?!  Qb8  leads nowhere for White. }
15... O-O 16. Qxb3
{ White finally takes the b-pawn. Narayanan concludes his analysis here and correctly assesses that White has good compensation for the pawn. We'll look closer once our suggested reply is on the board. A small side note: it's fascinating to see that @@StartFEN@@r2qkb1r/1b1n1ppp/p1p1pn2/1p2N3/P2P4/1p4P1/1B2PPBP/RN1Q1RK1 w kq - 2 11@@EndFEN@@  11.Qxb3  Nxe5  12.dxe5  Nd7  13.Nd2  Be7  14.Ne4  O-O  15.Nd6  Bxd6  16.exd6  leads to the same position. }
16... Qb6
{ A logical move. We cover the bishop and thus threaten ...c5 now. White has to address this threat, so slow development is not enough. Therefore, we don't have to examine many moves now: we'll focus on  17.a5  Qa7  18.Bxc6  , which regains the pawn, and @@StartFEN@@r4rk1/1b1n1ppp/pqpPp3/1p6/P7/1Q4P1/1B2PPBP/R4RK1 w - - 1 17@@EndFEN@@  17.Qf3  . }
17. a5
{ White goes for an immediate, tactical solution. Our queen is attacked, and we only have one good reply. }
17... Qa7
{ The only good move as  17...Qc5?  18.Rfc1  Qxd6  19.Qc3  f6  20.Ba3  demonstrates. }
18. Bxc6
{ The point of 17.a5. White regains the pawn with this little tactic. } 18...
Bxc6 19. Qc3 { White regains the piece with this double-threat. } 19... e5 20.
Qxc6 Rac8
{ We think it's a good moment to take stock. We have returned the extra pawn but made some good progress. The d-pawn is safely blockaded, and we are first on the c-file. White now has to decide where to retreat the queen.   After  21.Qf3  , for example, we have a choice of good moves. The moves  21...Qb8  ,  21...Rc2  and  21...Rc4  all look fine and lead to interesting play. }
