6. Nc3
{ A rare move at this point, even though the knight move looks perfectly natural. White usually still prefers other options since the knight is often exposed to the pawn advance ...b5-b4, as we will see. It needs to be mentioned that the position after 6.Nc3 is theoretically well explored as it also arises from a different move order: @@StartFEN@@rnbqkbnr/pppppppp/8/8/8/8/PPPPPPPP/RNBQKBNR w KQkq - 0 1@@EndFEN@@  1.d4  d5  2.c4  c6  3.Nf3  Nf6  4.Nc3  e6  5.Qb3  dxc4  6.Qxc4  , which leads to the same position. }
6... b5
{ The move ...b5 makes the most sense in two scenarios: White has played g3 already, so we prepare ...Bb7 and ...c5. White has played Nc3, which gives the b-pawn a target after a later, well-timed ...b4 push. }
7. Qd3
{ This queen retreat is more popular than  7.Qb3  .  The main difference is that from d3, the queen is still covering e4, which makes the pawn advance e2-e4 easier to play. }
7... a6
{ Just as after 7.Qb3, we start with this move. After covering b5, we are ready for ...c5.   Now White has tried many moves, but the only continuations worth checking are the aggressive moves  8.e4  and the recent trend  8.g4!?  . After slow moves like  8.g3  c5  or @@StartFEN@@rnbqkb1r/5ppp/p1p1pn2/1p6/3P4/2NQ1N2/PP2PPPP/R1B1KB1R w KQkq - 0 8@@EndFEN@@  8.Bg5  c5  , Black is clearly in good shape. }
8. e4 { This aggressive central push is White's main option. } 8... c5
{ Our standard counter-punch. Now we need to examine  9.e5  and  9.dxc5  . Both moves are fine for Black but require some care. }
9. dxc5 { The capture is rather harmless if we play correctly. } 9... Bxc5
{ This is a bit better than  9...Qxd3  10.Bxd3  Bxc5  11.e5  Nfd7  12.Be4  , which is somewhat annoying. It's  no problem to allow the queen trade and lose castling rights because our king will find a good spot on e7. A similar concept is well-known in the lines of the Queen's Gambit Accepted. }
10. Qxd8+ Kxd8 11. Bd3
{ White needs to avoid  11.e5?!  Ng4  , when the e-pawn is a clear weakness. }
11... Nc6 12. O-O Nd7
{ A strong move, controlling the e5-square. It's slightly more precise than  12...Ke7  13.e5  , which we don't need to allow. }
13. Bf4 Ke7
{ Our king is on the desired spot now. Chances are objectively equal here, but the balance may easily tip in our favor. Our centralized king is an asset, and our pieces are well-placed for action in the center and on the queenside. }
