{ This queen retreat is more popular than  7.Qb3  .  The main difference is that from d3, the queen is still covering e4, which makes the pawn advance e2-e4 easier to play. }
7... a6
{ Just as after 7.Qb3, we start with this move. After covering b5, we are ready for ...c5.   Now White has tried many moves, but the only continuations worth checking are the aggressive moves  8.e4  and the recent trend  8.g4!?  . After slow moves like  8.g3  c5  or @@StartFEN@@rnbqkb1r/5ppp/p1p1pn2/1p6/3P4/2NQ1N2/PP2PPPP/R1B1KB1R w KQkq - 0 8@@EndFEN@@  8.Bg5  c5  , Black is clearly in good shape. }
8. Bg5
{ A natural development move, but it is rather slow and does not put any direct pressure on us. }
8... c5 { We attack the center immediately. } 9. Bxf6
{ That's the most popular continuation. White gives up the bishop pair but forces up to capture with the g-pawn. This is not a problem at all, though. Let's have a look. }
9... gxf6
{ That's much better than  9...Qxf6?  10.Ne4  , which gives White an advantage. In this chapter, we explore various cases  of Bxf6, when the reply ...gxf6 turns out to be fine for Black. The doubled pawn controls important squares, in particular e5. }
10. d5 Bb7
{ Again an important decision. This is much simpler to handle than  10...b4  11.Na4  , which can easily turn out ugly due to our bad development. }
11. e4
{ White's almost exclusive choice at this point, but we can be happy with Black's prospects after it.   Stockfish suggests the yet untested move  11.Rd1  , which is based on the line  11...b4  12.Na4  Qxd5  13.Qxd5  Bxd5  14.Nb6  Bxf3  15.gxf3  Ra7  16.f4  , when White has enough compensation for the pawn. Instead of  11...b4  , we'd suggest  11...Nd7  , though. It makes sense to keep the tension and rely on our bishop pair advantage. }
11... Nd7
{ We keep the tension and continue our queenside development. It's important to note that castling queenside is an important, dynamic option here. }
12. Rd1 { White lends additional support to the d-pawn. } 12... Qc7
{ Ready for castling now! } 13. Be2 O-O-O
{ It's a bit surprising to see queenside castling after the earlier expansion on this side of the board. A closer look shows that our king will actually be quite safe on b8. A key point is that White has traded away the dark-squared bishop, which makes this color complex safer for us.  The huge upside of castling queenside is the rapidly increasing pressure on the center. It's also clear that the open g-file will come in handy for our play against White's king after kingside castling. Black has the better chances here and the much easier game. }
