6... Nbd7
{ The far more popular option for Black is the more obvious  6...b5  , but it is surprisingly difficult for Black to play. Instead, the move  6...Nbd7  is less explored but looks fully satisfactory for Black.  We prepare ...c6-c5 and also get the ...Nd7xf6 option if White decides to capture on f6. }
7. e4
{ We don't mind this move as after  7...h6  , White needs to give up the bishop pair. }
7... h6
{ This move nets the bishop pair, and it is the easiest solution. A fun alternative is  7...e5!?  , based on the tactical point  8.dxe5  Nxe5  9.Nxe5  Qa5+  , which leads to equal chances too. }
8. Bxf6
{ White can't play  8.Bh4?  as  8...g5  9.Bg3  Nxe4  or @@StartFEN@@r1bqkb1r/pp1n1p2/2p1pn1p/6p1/2QPP2B/5N2/PP3PPP/RN2KB1R w KQkq - 0 9@@EndFEN@@  9.e5  gxh4  10.exf6  Qxf6  are more or less winning for Black. }
