9... Qb6 { A good move. We attack b2 and prepare ...c5 at the same time. } 10.
O-O-O
{ The sharpest move, but it is risky for White. After  10.Rb1  , we have  10...c5  11.e5  cxd4  12.Qxd4  Nd7  and Black has the bishop pair, while @@StartFEN@@r1b1kb1r/pp3pp1/1qp1pn1p/8/2QPP3/2N2N2/PP3PPP/R3KB1R w KQkq - 2 10@@EndFEN@@  10.Bd3  is a pawn sacrifice that we can accept with  10...Qxb2  or decline with  10...Qb4  , which forces a queen trade. We wouldn't mind that, hoping to use the bishop pair in the long run. }
10... a5
{ We need to avoid the premature  10...c5?  when  11.Qa4+  Bd7  12.Bb5  gives White a strong attack. Instead, the engine suggestion 10...a5 is surprisingly strong. The idea of the pawn push is revealed after a slow move, when we may even advance further. Let's have a look. }
11. Be2
{ This is slow, but  11.Bd3  Qb4  does not bother Black at all. Stockfish suggests @@StartFEN@@r1b1kb1r/1p3pp1/1qp1pn1p/p7/2QPP3/2N2N2/PP3PPP/2KR1B1R w kq - 0 11@@EndFEN@@  11.Ne5  for White, but just  11...Bd6  or  11...Be7  look fine for Black.  A later ...Nd7 will challenge the e5-knight. }
11... a4
{ The a-pawn proves to be very annoying for White. Allowing ...a3 is tough for White, and capturing the pawn has its drawbacks too. }
12. Nxa4 Qa7 13. Nc3
{ We need to examine this move to understand the point of Black's play. Better is  13.Nc5  , but Black is clearly fine after  13...Qxa2  . }
13... b5
{ That's the point! White can't capture on c6, as the queen has no squares left after  14.Qxc6+  Bd7  . White instead has to retreat, but @@StartFEN@@r1b1kb1r/q4pp1/2p1pn1p/1p6/2QPP3/2N2N2/PP2BPPP/2KR3R w kq - 0 14@@EndFEN@@  14.Qb3  b4  gives Black a crushing position. }
