{ That's even more convincing than  10...Bxc5  11.axb5  Qb6  , which also looks fine. After @@StartFEN@@rn1qkb1r/1b3ppp/p3pn2/1pP5/P7/1Q3NP1/1P2PPBP/RNB1K2R b KQkq - 0 10@@EndFEN@@  10...Nbd7  , we intend to  capture with the knight on c5. We'll now check  11.axb5  and  11.Be3  , which look most logical. }
11. Be3 Nxc5
{ Black has the comfortable choice between  11...Nxc5  ,  11...Bxc5  , and the less obvious knight jump  11...Ng4  . We felt grabbing the bishop pair with the knight capture is probably the easiest to remember, as our previous move indicated this intention. }
12. Bxc5 Bxc5 13. axb5
{ We need to check the pawn grab. After  13.O-O  Black is fine with about any reasonable move, like  13...Qb6  ,  13...b4!?  or just  13...O-O  , which offers the b-pawn for adequate compensation. }
13... Qb6
{ The easiest move to remember. Stockfish also points out the fantastic strike  13...Bxf2+!?  , which is supposed to be 0.00, obviously :-@@EndBracket@@ Jokes aside, this line continues with  14.Kxf2  Ng4+  15.Ke1  Qb6  16.Rf1  O-O  and it looks like Black's attack gives enough compensation.  However, it's rather uneconomical to learn these lines, as White has multiple moves on move  17. All are fine for us, but it's overkill to drill that deeply. Still, this is fun to explore if you are interested. }
14. O-O Ng4
{ Again, many lines are fine for Black. Even  14...O-O  15.Nc3  axb5  16.Rxa8  Bxa8  17.Qxb5  Qxb5  18.Nxb5  Rb8  works for Black @@StartBracket@@but it's a dead draw, admittedly@@EndBracket@@. Instead, we suggest @@StartFEN@@r3k2r/1b3ppp/pq2pn2/1Pb5/8/1Q3NP1/1P2PPBP/RN3RK1 b kq - 2 14@@EndFEN@@  14...Ng4  , when White must be cautious. Here are some possibilities:  A@@EndBracket@@ @@StartFEN@@r3k2r/1b3ppp/pq2p3/1Pb5/6n1/1Q3NP1/1P2PPBP/RN3RK1 w kq - 3 15@@EndFEN@@  15.e3?  Bxe3  16.fxe3  Nxe3  is great for Black.  We threaten ...Nc2+ and ...Nxf1+, which is advantageous for us even on purely materialistic considerations.   B@@EndBracket@@ @@StartFEN@@r3k2r/1b3ppp/pq2p3/1Pb5/6n1/1Q3NP1/1P2PPBP/RN3RK1 w kq - 3 15@@EndFEN@@  15.Qa4  Bxf2+  @@StartBracket@@  15...Nxf2  16.b4  Nh3+  forces a draw already@@EndBracket@@ @@StartFEN@@r3k2r/1b3ppp/pq2p3/1P6/Q5n1/5NP1/1P2PbBP/RN3RK1 w kq - 0 16@@EndFEN@@  16.Kh1  h5  17.bxa6+  Bc6  leads to a crazy position. White needs to find  18.Qa5  , which holds a draw after  18...Qxa5  19.Rxa5  Bb6  ,  followed by the checks on f2 and h3.   C@@EndBracket@@ @@StartFEN@@r3k2r/1b3ppp/pq2p3/1Pb5/6n1/1Q3NP1/1P2PPBP/RN3RK1 w kq - 3 15@@EndFEN@@  15.Nfd2  Bxf2+  16.Kh1  Bxg2+  17.Kxg2  Ne3+  18.Kxf2  Nc2+  19.e3  Nxa1  is a fun sequence that looks fine for Black, too. We aren't any material down, and White's king is insecure. Stockfish claims 0.00, but it's certainly not boring ;-@@EndBracket@@ }
