[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "15. Triangle 3.Nf3 c6 4.Qc2"]
[Black "Triangle 4.Qc2 dxc4 5.Qxc4 − 6.g3 #10"]
[Result "*"]

1. d4 d5 2. c4 e6 3. Nf3 c6
{ In this chapter, we will examine two moves that White can play after @@StartFEN@@rnbqkbnr/pppppppp/8/8/8/8/PPPPPPPP/RNBQKBNR w KQkq - 0 1@@EndFEN@@  1.d4  d5  2.c4  e6  3.Nf3  c6  . Our move  3...c6  introduces the idea of taking the c-pawn and trying to hold it with ...b5.  The Noteboom is one of the cornerstones of this course and arises after  4.Nc3  dxc4  when ...b5 is a key move for us. White often wants to avoid these complications and prefers a more strategic alternative.  One way to cover the c-pawn is by moving the queen to c2 or b3. We answer both moves with the capture on c4 so that  @@StartFEN@@rnbqkbnr/pp3ppp/2p1p3/3p4/2PP4/5N2/PP2PPPP/RNBQKB1R w KQkq - 0 4@@EndFEN@@  4.Qb3  dxc4  5.Qxc4  and  4.Qc2  dxc4  5.Qxc4  quickly merge to the same lines.  White's queen position on c4 makes the move ...b5 a tempting option, expanding on the queenside with tempo. A key concept to understand is that ...b5 is not ALWAYS a good idea. We need to be flexible and only play the move under the right circumstances. Let's have a closer look now. }
4. Qc2
{ White covers the c4-pawn with the queen but remains flexible regarding further action. In many cases, White intends to fianchetto the f1-bishop but wants to avoid the line  4.g3  dxc4  , which often amounts to a 'real' pawn sacrifice.  White is not committed to a kingside fianchetto, though. White may still develop with Bf4 or Bg5, followed by e3, when the king's bishop will be placed on e2 or d3 later. }
4... dxc4
{ The immediate capture is most in spirit with the Triangle/Noteboom. In most cases, we plan a queenside expansion with ...b5 after White has recovered the c4-pawn.   A quick word about alternatives: Black has to avoid  4...f5?  , which is a dreadful version of the Stonewall after  5.Bf4  . We only want to enter a Stonewall after White has committed to the  move e3, for example,  after @@StartFEN@@rnbqkbnr/pppppppp/8/8/8/8/PPPPPPPP/RNBQKBNR w KQkq - 0 1@@EndFEN@@  1.d4  d5  2.c4  e6  3.Nc3  c6  4.e3  Bd6  5.Nf3  f5  ,  or an early Nbd2 after  @@StartFEN@@rnbqkbnr/pppppppp/8/8/8/8/PPPPPPPP/RNBQKBNR w KQkq - 0 1@@EndFEN@@  1.d4  d5  2.c4  e6  3.Nf3  c6  4.Nbd2  f5  .  Black is in terrible shape after @@StartFEN@@rnbqkbnr/pp3ppp/2p1p3/3p4/2PP4/5N2/PPQ1PPPP/RNB1KB1R b KQkq - 1 4@@EndFEN@@  4...f5?  5.Bf4  , when  5...Nf6  6.e3  Be7  7.Nc3  O-O  8.Bd3  Ne4  9.g4  scores about 75% for White.  A much better alternative is @@StartFEN@@rnbqkbnr/pp3ppp/2p1p3/3p4/2PP4/5N2/PPQ1PPPP/RNB1KB1R b KQkq - 1 4@@EndFEN@@  4...Nf6  ,  intending to capture on c4 after  5.Bg5  dxc4  or @@StartFEN@@rnbqkb1r/pp3ppp/2p1pn2/3p4/2PP4/5N2/PPQ1PPPP/RNB1KB1R w KQkq - 2 5@@EndFEN@@  5.g3  dxc4  . These sequences would transpose to our recommendation, but @@StartFEN@@rnbqkb1r/pp3ppp/2p1pn2/3p4/2PP4/5N2/PPQ1PPPP/RNB1KB1R w KQkq - 2 5@@EndFEN@@  5.e3  or  5.Nbd2  give White additional options that we can sidestep by taking on c4 immediately.  After @@StartFEN@@rnbqkbnr/pp3ppp/2p1p3/3p4/2PP4/5N2/PP2PPPP/RNBQKB1R w KQkq - 0 4@@EndFEN@@  4.Qc2  dxc4  White's main reply is  5.Qxc4  , but we'll have a brief look at the gambit line  5.e4  . }
5. Qxc4
{ After the natural 5.Qxc4, we reach an important moment early in the game. }
5... Nf6
{ It is essential to play  5...Nf6  here and avoid the most natural move,  5...b5  . Somewhat surprisingly, the immediate pawn push is a serious inaccuracy after  6.Qc2  Bb7  7.e4  , when Black  does not manage to play ...c6-c5 under fully satisfactory circumstances.  We need to play @@StartFEN@@rnbqkbnr/pp3ppp/2p1p3/8/2QP4/5N2/PP2PPPP/RNB1KB1R b KQkq - 0 5@@EndFEN@@  5...Nf6  first and wait for a moment until White gives us more information about the intended setup. Now White has some options − here's an overview:  A@@EndBracket@@  6.g3  is the most popular move, playing in the style of the Catalan. We'll play  6...b5  , intending to oppose White's bishop on the long diagonal  after a later ...Bb7 and ...c6-c5.   B@@EndBracket@@  6.Bg5  White pins our knight and usually intends  to develop with a later e2-e3 or e2-e4. It is important NOT to play  6...b5  here, but go for  6...Nbd7!  instead. We'll discuss the reasoning in the notes to this line.   C@@EndBracket@@  6.Qc2  is a tricky move, hoping for  6...b5?!  7.e4  , when White is better @@StartBracket@@a transposition to @@StartFEN@@rnbqkbnr/pp3ppp/2p1p3/8/2QP4/5N2/PP2PPPP/RNB1KB1R b KQkq - 0 5@@EndFEN@@  5...b5?!  6.Qc2  , essentially@@EndBracket@@. The way to equalize is @@StartFEN@@rnbqkb1r/pp3ppp/2p1pn2/8/3P4/5N2/PPQ1PPPP/RNB1KB1R b KQkq - 2 6@@EndFEN@@  6...c5!  , using the fact that 6.Qc2 is relatively slow.   D@@EndBracket@@ @@StartFEN@@rnbqkb1r/pp3ppp/2p1pn2/8/2QP4/5N2/PP2PPPP/RNB1KB1R w KQkq - 1 6@@EndFEN@@  6.Nc3  is not very popular here but leads to a well-explored line that more often arises via @@StartFEN@@rnbqkbnr/pppppppp/8/8/8/8/PPPPPPPP/RNBQKBNR w KQkq - 0 1@@EndFEN@@  1.d4  d5  2.c4  c6  3.Nf3  Nf6  4.Nc3  e6  5.Qb3  @@StartBracket@@or 5.Qd3@@EndBracket@@  5...dxc4  6.Qxc4  . Black is fine after  6...b5  , but it's helpful to know some details.   As you see, we need to be very flexible here. There is no 'standard' setup that we can go for, but we need to adjust to the various subtleties. A good rule of thumb about whether to play ...b5 or not is: we play ...b5 against the fianchetto @@StartBracket@@we answer a fianchetto with an extended fianchetto, so to say@@EndBracket@@ and when White plays Nc3, giving the b-pawn a target to attack @@StartBracket@@...b5-b4@@EndBracket@@. It's not about playing ...b5 just for the tempo, but the move needs to serve a definite purpose in reply to White's decision on move six. }
6. g3 { Preparing the kingside fianchetto is White's most popular move. } 6...
b5
{ Playing ...b5 makes a lot of sense against 6.g3. We free the b7-square for our bishop and intend to play ...Bb7 and ...c5 as soon as possible. Often this pawn break needs to be supported with ...Nbd7 and ...a6, depending on White's setup.   Now  7.Qc2  is the most popular move, but it seems that  7.Qd3  or  7.Qb3  pose more problems for Black. }
7. Qb3
{ This move follows a similar logic as  7.Qd3  . White keeps an eye on the b-pawn, making it a bit more difficult for us to  play ...c5 quickly. This advance is easy to accomplish after  7.Qc2  , while we need to be more cunning after  7.Qb3  and  7.Qd3  . }
7... Bb7 8. Bg2 a6
{ We play in the same way after @@StartFEN@@rnbqkb1r/p4ppp/2p1pn2/1p6/2QP4/5NP1/PP2PP1P/RNB1KB1R w KQkq - 0 7@@EndFEN@@  7.Qd3  Bb7  8.Bg2  , when  8...a6!  covers the b-pawn and  immediately prepares ...c5. What are the replies to check now? We'll have a look at three moves:   A@@EndBracket@@ @@StartFEN@@rn1qkb1r/1b3ppp/p1p1pn2/1p6/3P4/1Q3NP1/PP2PPBP/RNB1K2R w KQkq - 0 9@@EndFEN@@  9.a4  is a logical choice, putting  some pressure on b5. We have a strong reply  9...c5!  though.  B@@EndBracket@@ @@StartFEN@@rn1qkb1r/1b3ppp/p1p1pn2/1p6/3P4/1Q3NP1/PP2PPBP/RNB1K2R w KQkq - 0 9@@EndFEN@@  9.O-O  c5!  gives Black an easy game.  C@@EndBracket@@ @@StartFEN@@rn1qkb1r/1b3ppp/p1p1pn2/1p6/3P4/1Q3NP1/PP2PPBP/RNB1K2R w KQkq - 0 9@@EndFEN@@  9.Be3  is an unpopular move but the top choice of Stockfish. It's fine for Black, but we need to be precise. }
9. a4 c5
{ We can play this desirable move anyway! The cool point is that  10.axb5  is answered with  10...c4!  as  11.Qxc4??  axb5  wins for Black. We'll now have a look at the two possible pawn captures.  If White plays @@StartFEN@@rn1qkb1r/1b3ppp/p3pn2/1pp5/P2P4/1Q3NP1/1P2PPBP/RNB1K2R w KQkq - 0 10@@EndFEN@@  10.O-O  , we are fine after  10...c4  . This is similar to @@StartFEN@@rn1qkb1r/1b3ppp/p3pn2/1pp5/P2P4/1Q3NP1/1P2PPBP/RNB1K2R w KQkq - 0 10@@EndFEN@@  10.axb5  c4  11.Qd1  axb5  12.Rxa8  Bxa8  13.O-O  Be7  and could even easily transpose to the same position, as @@StartFEN@@rn1qkb1r/1b3ppp/p3pn2/1pp5/P2P4/1Q3NP1/1P2PPBP/RNB1K2R w KQkq - 0 10@@EndFEN@@  10.O-O  c4  11.Qd1  Be7  12.axb5  axb5  13.Rxa8  Bxa8  demonstrates. }
10. axb5 { Of course, we have to examine this move. } 10... c4
{ The point! Now  11.Qxc4??  axb5  12.Qxb5+  Bc6  wins for Black. } 11. Qd1
{ Back home, to the only stable square. Otherwise, White's queen would be in constant danger of getting attacked by our minor pieces. }
11... axb5 12. Rxa8 Bxa8 13. O-O
{ All rather forced and logical after 10...c4. } 13... Be7
{ At this point, it seems that Black has many good moves, but we think that  13...Be7  makes the most sense. We need to prepare for kingside castling and don't want to decide where to place the b8-knight. In many cases, it might be well-placed on c6 later. Therefore, we'd rather start with the bishop move instead of committing to the placement of the knight with  13...Nbd7  . }
14. b3
{ The only move that White players have tried here. It's hard to come up with a different plan, indeed. If White is losing time with slow moves, we might be able to support our two vs. one majority on the queenside even better. }
14... cxb3
{ A reasonable and straightforward solution, even though  14...O-O  seems to be satisfactory, too. }
15. Qxb3 b4
{ We have reached a position that offers equal chances. Our b-pawn is passed, but it's tough to advance quickly. To further illustrate, let's look at the game between Fabiano Caruana and Levon Aronian, played in St. Louis 2018.  The game continued  16.Bb2  Nbd7  17.Nbd2  O-O  18.Ra1  Qb8  19.Ne1  Bxg2  20.Kxg2  Rc8  21.e4  and now Aronian played  21...h5!?  22.Nd3?!  h4  and even obtained the better chances. @@StartFEN@@1qr3k1/3nbpp1/4pn2/7p/1p1PP3/1Q4P1/1B1N1PKP/R3N3 w - - 0 22@@EndFEN@@  22.Qa4  ,  intending Qa7, would have kept equality, as Stockfish points out. In any case, we can be happy with Black's prospects after 10.axb5 c4!, a key point in Black's concept. }
*

