9. O-O
{ A routine move and the most frequently played one. Our reply is obvious. }
9... c5
{ Whenever Black accomplishes ...c5 in the 6.g3 line without any concrete tactical problem, it means that we have at least gained equal chances. Our bishop is activated, and we manage to attack White's central pawn on d4. }
10. Bg5
{ This is not White's most popular move, but it's useful to check because of an instructive idea. After  10.a4  b4  or @@StartFEN@@r2qkb1r/pb1n1ppp/4pn2/1pp5/3P4/5NP1/PPQ1PPBP/RNB2RK1 w kq - 0 10@@EndFEN@@  10.dxc5  Bxc5  Black  is already simpler to play. The white queen is misplaced on c2, and a quick ...Rc8 will gain a useful tempo. }
10... Rc8 11. Bxf6 gxf6
{ Black is completely fine after the other recaptures, too. However, taking with the pawn is an interesting alternative. Playing ...f5 and ...Bg7 is an attractive option, putting some pressure on the queenside. }
