1. d4 d5 2. c4 e6
{ In this chapter, we cover White's options after @@StartFEN@@rnbqkbnr/pppppppp/8/8/8/8/PPPPPPPP/RNBQKBNR w KQkq - 0 1@@EndFEN@@  1.d4  d5  2.c4  e6  that don't merit dedicated chapters. As usual, the sidelines are sidelines for a reason.  In this chapter, we'll examine some poor or dubious lines that White can play, like  3.c5?  or various versions of an  early Bf4, when White is usually struggling to equalize. Not all the lines in the current chapter are bad for White, though. Some continuations are too harmless to pose serious problems and therefore never reach 'main line' status.  The most important of these sound, but harmless lines, is the Exchange Variation, featuring the trade on d5. White can trade on moves  three @@StartFEN@@rnbqkbnr/ppp2ppp/4p3/3p4/2PP4/8/PP2PPPP/RNBQKBNR w KQkq - 0 3@@EndFEN@@  3.cxd5  exd5  , or four @@StartFEN@@rnbqkbnr/ppp2ppp/4p3/3p4/2PP4/8/PP2PPPP/RNBQKBNR w KQkq - 0 3@@EndFEN@@  3.Nc3  /  3.Nf3  c6  4.cxd5  exd5  , and create the famous Carlsbad Pawn Structure.  We'll examine this in detail, as you'll encounter it quite frequently. Alright, let's get to work and check out White's sidelines against the Triangle. }
3. g3
{ White goes for a Catalan in a slightly unusual move order. The more common way to combine d4, c4, and g3 is to play  3.Nf3  first and only continue with 4.g3 after seeing Black's third move. The early  3.g3  gives Black some additional options that White usually avoids. Let's have a look. }
3... dxc4
{ Taking the pawn in the most critical move. In the context of our repertoire, the move  3...c6  also makes a lot of sense. It will very likely continue with  4.Nf3  dxc4  or @@StartFEN@@rnbqkbnr/pp3ppp/2p1p3/3p4/2PP4/6P1/PP2PP1P/RNBQKBNR w KQkq - 0 4@@EndFEN@@  4.Bg2  dxc4  5.Nf3  , when we'd transpose to the line @@StartFEN@@rnbqkbnr/ppp2ppp/4p3/3p4/2PP4/8/PP2PPPP/RNBQKBNR w KQkq - 0 3@@EndFEN@@  3.Nf3  c6  4.g3  dxc4  5.Bg2  , which is part of our repertoire. Our suggestion @@StartFEN@@rnbqkbnr/ppp2ppp/4p3/3p4/2PP4/8/PP2PPPP/RNBQKBNR w KQkq - 0 3@@EndFEN@@  3.g3  dxc4  will also transpose to these lines most of the time but allows some interesting possible deviations. }
4. Qa4+
{ White wants to regain the sacrificed pawn quickly. We have a pleasant choice now. }
4... Qd7
{ The most exciting and ambitious move. After the more straightforward  4...c6  5.Qxc4  Qd5  , we'd instantly equalize the game, but it is less enterprising. }
5. Qxc4 b5 { The point of ...Qd7. We develop the queenside with tempo. } 6. Qc2
Bb7 7. Nf3 Nc6
{ We have reached a new position that looks promising for Black. We attack the d4-pawn, and White has to play a clumsy move like  8.Be3  to defend it. In any case, 4.Qa4+ is a very rare line for a good reason, as Black has many good options against it. }
