[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "16. Triangle Sidelines − Deviations on moves 3 and 4"]
[Black "Triangle Sidelines 3.Nf3 c6 4.Bg5 #1"]
[Result "*"]

1. d4 d5 2. c4 e6
{ In this chapter, we cover White's options after @@StartFEN@@rnbqkbnr/pppppppp/8/8/8/8/PPPPPPPP/RNBQKBNR w KQkq - 0 1@@EndFEN@@  1.d4  d5  2.c4  e6  that don't merit dedicated chapters. As usual, the sidelines are sidelines for a reason.  In this chapter, we'll examine some poor or dubious lines that White can play, like  3.c5?  or various versions of an  early Bf4, when White is usually struggling to equalize. Not all the lines in the current chapter are bad for White, though. Some continuations are too harmless to pose serious problems and therefore never reach 'main line' status.  The most important of these sound, but harmless lines, is the Exchange Variation, featuring the trade on d5. White can trade on moves  three @@StartFEN@@rnbqkbnr/ppp2ppp/4p3/3p4/2PP4/8/PP2PPPP/RNBQKBNR w KQkq - 0 3@@EndFEN@@  3.cxd5  exd5  , or four @@StartFEN@@rnbqkbnr/ppp2ppp/4p3/3p4/2PP4/8/PP2PPPP/RNBQKBNR w KQkq - 0 3@@EndFEN@@  3.Nc3  /  3.Nf3  c6  4.cxd5  exd5  , and create the famous Carlsbad Pawn Structure.  We'll examine this in detail, as you'll encounter it quite frequently. Alright, let's get to work and check out White's sidelines against the Triangle. }
3. Nf3 c6 4. Bg5
{ A rare move, but it's a solid choice. White hopes for  4...f6?!  , which weakens Black's pawn structure for no reason, or  4...Nf6  , when  5.e3  gives White some hope for a small advantage. }
4... Be7
{ We avoid the inferior options mentioned before and invite the bishop trade. }
5. Bxe7 Qxe7
{ After the trade, our queen is well-placed on e7. We have two possible pawn breaks: the moves ...c5 or ...e5, and both are well-supported by our queen. We'll continue with ...Nf6, ...O-O, and then see which pawn break to go for. }
6. e3 Nf6 7. Nc3 O-O
{ A natural sequence so far. White has some possible moves now, but our play is pretty simple to conduct. A sound approach is to take on c4, followed by ...c5. A similar idea is ...Rd8, followed by ...c5. Let's see how this unfolds after the moves 8.Rc1 and 8.Qc2, which look logical. }
8. Rc1
{ After  8.Rc1  , the idea  8...dxc4  9.Bxc4  c5  is a bit less attractive than after 8. Qc2; we have a good alternative, though. }
8... Rd8
{ We already mentioned this alternative idea to the capture on c4. We centralize the rook and try to improve on the central breaks by opposing White's queen. }
9. Qc2
{ White removes the queen from the d-file.  9.cxd5  exd5  is possible, but this is a harmless version of the Carlsbad structure. We have the  ideas ...Bg4 and ...Bf5 to activate/trade our slightly passive bishop, and White has a hard time stopping both. }
9... dxc4
{ The move  9...c5  also works well. After  10.cxd5  exd5  11.Be2  Nc6  12.dxc5  Qxc5  , Black ends up with an IQP, but all the pieces are active,  and White is not well-placed to control the d4-square. In fact, ...d5-d4 is already unstoppable. }
10. Bxc4 c5 11. dxc5 Qxc5
{ And we reach a position very similar to 8.Qc2 dxc4, when Black has no problems. We'll play ...Nc6, ...Bd7 and ...Rc8, completing our development. The position is very symmetrical, and White's slightly more active pieces don't matter at all. }
