[Black "Triangle Sidelines 3.Nf3 c6 4.b3 #1"]
[Result "*"]

1. d4 d5 2. c4 e6
{ In this chapter, we cover White's options after @@StartFEN@@rnbqkbnr/pppppppp/8/8/8/8/PPPPPPPP/RNBQKBNR w KQkq - 0 1@@EndFEN@@  1.d4  d5  2.c4  e6  that don't merit dedicated chapters. As usual, the sidelines are sidelines for a reason.  In this chapter, we'll examine some poor or dubious lines that White can play, like  3.c5?  or various versions of an  early Bf4, when White is usually struggling to equalize. Not all the lines in the current chapter are bad for White, though. Some continuations are too harmless to pose serious problems and therefore never reach 'main line' status.  The most important of these sound, but harmless lines, is the Exchange Variation, featuring the trade on d5. White can trade on moves  three @@StartFEN@@rnbqkbnr/ppp2ppp/4p3/3p4/2PP4/8/PP2PPPP/RNBQKBNR w KQkq - 0 3@@EndFEN@@  3.cxd5  exd5  , or four @@StartFEN@@rnbqkbnr/ppp2ppp/4p3/3p4/2PP4/8/PP2PPPP/RNBQKBNR w KQkq - 0 3@@EndFEN@@  3.Nc3  /  3.Nf3  c6  4.cxd5  exd5  , and create the famous Carlsbad Pawn Structure.  We'll examine this in detail, as you'll encounter it quite frequently. Alright, let's get to work and check out White's sidelines against the Triangle. }
3. Nf3 c6 4. b3
{ A very rare, but reasonable move. White covers the c-pawn and remains flexible about the development of the king's bishop. White can still play e3 or opt for a kingside fianchetto. This flexibility presents an interesting move order challenge for our repertoire approach. Let's consider some possibilities and discuss the move order implications.  A@@EndBracket@@  4...f5  sets up the Stonewall. We recommend the Stonewall after @@StartFEN@@rnbqkbnr/pp3ppp/2p1p3/3p4/2PP4/5N2/PP2PPPP/RNBQKB1R w KQkq - 0 4@@EndFEN@@  4.e3  and  4.Nbd2  when White has already decided to block the path of the c1-bishop. Answering  4.b3  with  4...f5  is a slightly less attractive version, as White can still develop the bishop freely.   B@@EndBracket@@  4...Nf6  is the most obvious move, probably. It's a fine move but after  5.e3  , we transpose into a pawn structure that we usually answer with the Stonewall. After @@StartFEN@@rnbqkbnr/pppppppp/8/8/8/8/PPPPPPPP/RNBQKBNR w KQkq - 0 1@@EndFEN@@  1.d4  d5  2.c4  e6  3.Nf3  c6  4.e3  , we play  4...f5  , so allowing @@StartFEN@@rnbqkbnr/pp3ppp/2p1p3/3p4/2PP4/5N2/PP2PPPP/RNBQKB1R w KQkq - 0 4@@EndFEN@@  4.b3  Nf6  5.e3  leaves us 'move-ordered'.   C@@EndBracket@@  4...Bd6  is our choice. We develop the bishop first and still keep the option to  play ...f5 at the right moment. }
4... Bd6
{ A flexible move. We'd like to know more about White's setup and only then decide if we want to enter a Stonewall. }
5. g3
{ This is White's most popular move.  5.e3  can also be played when  5...f5  6.Be2  Nf6  transposes into our line of choice against the e3 setups − the Stonewall. }
5... Nf6
{ It's also possible to play  5...f5  , going for a Stonewall. We slightly prefer  5...Nf6  , as White has a wide range of options against  5...f5  , while our choice seems a bit easier to handle. You'll see that we still keep the Stonewall option in mind in  some cases @@StartBracket@@...Ne4 and ...f5 is a common idea@@EndBracket@@. }
6. Bg2 O-O { You may also start with  6...Nbd7  and castle on the next move. }
7. O-O { Or  7.Bb2  Nbd7  8.O-O  Ne4  , leading to the same positions. } 7...
Nbd7
{ We develop and add more control to the e5-square. White now needs to worry about the pawn push ...e5, which would liberate our c8-bishop. White's most common move is the logical  8.Bb2  ,  which prevents ...e5. We'll also take a look  at  8.Nc3  , which allows  8...e5  and leads to interesting complications. }
8. Nc3
{ White ignores the idea ...e5, but also prevents the knight jump to e4. We can't play  8...Ne4??  , as  9.Nxe4  dxe4  10.Ng5  wins the e4-pawn for nothing.  Against @@StartFEN@@r1bq1rk1/pp1n1ppp/2pbpn2/3p4/2PP4/1P3NP1/P3PPBP/RNBQ1RK1 w - - 5 8@@EndFEN@@  8.Bb2  , we play  8...Ne4  − it's  important to not play the knight to e4 on 'autopilot'. }
8... e5
{ An important move! As mentioned  8...Ne4??  is a blunder due to  9.Nxe4  dxe4  10.Ng5  . It's one thing to avoid this mistake, but it's also crucial to understand that we need to liberate our bishop as soon as possible.   Playing a slow move, like  8...b6  does not cut it. After  9.Bb2  Bb7  10.Nd2  White will manage  the move e2-e4 and is significantly better. Our whole setup only makes sense if we either accomplish ...e5 or manage to fight the pawn push to e4 successfully.  The two lines @@StartFEN@@r1bq1rk1/pp1n1ppp/2pbpn2/3p4/2PP4/1P3NP1/P3PPBP/RNBQ1RK1 w - - 5 8@@EndFEN@@  8.Nc3  e5!  and @@StartFEN@@r1bq1rk1/pp1n1ppp/2pbpn2/3p4/2PP4/1P3NP1/P3PPBP/RNBQ1RK1 w - - 5 8@@EndFEN@@  8.Bb2  Ne4  underline these principles. }
9. dxe5
{ This is the best. After  9.cxd5?!  we have the strong reply  9...e4!  10.Ne1  cxd5  , when only Black can be better. }
9... Nxe5 10. cxd5
{ At first sight, it looks like we are losing the d-pawn. We have a good tactical solution, though. }
10... Nxf3+ 11. Bxf3 Be5
{ This pin is saving the pawn @@StartBracket@@and the day!@@EndBracket@@. } 12.
Bb2 Nxd5
{ Mission accomplished. We have regained the pawn and managed to activate our c8-bishop. Chances are about equal in this position. }
