8. Bb2 { White increases the control of e5 and stops our pawn advance. } 8...
Ne4
{ We like this move, occupying the central square. We are ready to support the knight with ...f5, switching to a Stonewall structure after all. It's important to play with a clear plan in this position.   A slower approach, like  8...b6  9.Nc3  Bb7  10.Nd2  @@StartBracket@@with the idea e2-e4@@EndBracket@@ or @@StartFEN@@r1bq1rk1/pp1n1ppp/2pbpn2/3p4/2PP4/1P3NP1/PB2PPBP/RN1Q1RK1 b - - 6 8@@EndFEN@@  8...Qe7  9.Ne5  is too passive. Stockfish also likes the less obvious @@StartFEN@@r1bq1rk1/pp1n1ppp/2pbpn2/3p4/2PP4/1P3NP1/PB2PPBP/RN1Q1RK1 b - - 6 8@@EndFEN@@  8...a5!?  , but will often continue  with ...Ne4 on the next move. Our choice is more straightforward. }
9. Nbd2
{ That's White's most popular choice. There are many alternatives, but our setup will be rather similar in all cases. After  9.Nc3  f5  or @@StartFEN@@r1bq1rk1/pp1n1ppp/2pbp3/3p4/2PPn3/1P3NP1/PB2PPBP/RN1Q1RK1 w - - 7 9@@EndFEN@@  9.Ne5  f5  , we enter the Stonewall formation, similar to our main line @@StartFEN@@r1bq1rk1/pp1n1ppp/2pbp3/3p4/2PPn3/1P3NP1/PB2PPBP/RN1Q1RK1 w - - 7 9@@EndFEN@@  9.Nbd2  f5  . }
9... f5
{ We finally settle for the Stonewall formation. We could have committed to ...f5 earlier but preferred to wait until White has placed the pieces on relatively passive spots @@StartBracket@@Bb2 and Nbd2@@EndBracket@@.   Had we played @@StartFEN@@rnbqkbnr/pp3ppp/2p1p3/3p4/2PP4/5N2/PP2PPPP/RNBQKB1R w KQkq - 0 4@@EndFEN@@  4.b3  Bd6  5.g3  f5  , White would have had far more options,  like playing Bf4 or going for a quick Bb2&Qc1 idea, to prepare Ba3. }
10. Ne5
{ The closed nature of the position allows many possible ideas and move orders. We have chosen  10.Ne5  as the main move since it is the most popular. It is a rather forcing continuation, as we will take the knight and change the pawn structure immediately.   Instead of  10.Ne5  , White may also go for a slower setup,  often involving the maneuver Ne1-d3. The knight is well placed on d3, as it connects with the e5-square. At the same time, the move f3 is on the cards, asking our knight about its intentions and preparing the pawn push to e4.  There are many possible move orders to implement this idea, as White may always insert moves like Qc2 or Rc1. Here are some possible continuations to illustrate the play.   A@@EndBracket@@  10.Ne1  Qe7  11.Nd3  b6  12.f3  Nxd2  13.Qxd2  Bb7  14.e4  fxe4  15.fxe4  dxc4  16.bxc4  e5  , leading to equal chances.   B@@EndBracket@@  10.Qc2  Qe7  11.Ne1  Nxd2  12.Qxd2  b6  13.Nd3  a5  , with complex play.  It is important to know the ...a5 idea. We have the option to play ...a4, but also may develop the bishop to a6. These lines are not forced at all, which is an upside of the Stonewall formation. You have some room for creativity, which makes it a good weapon to play for a win. }
10... Nxe5
{ Going for concrete play. There is nothing wrong about  10...Qe7  , either.  Still, taking on e5 makes a lot of sense. A pawn on e5 is usually less annoying than a piece. }
11. dxe5 Be7
{ The other bishop moves, to c5 or b4, look reasonable too. We decided to stop the trainable line at this point. Black has obtained equal chances in this position. It's crucial to recognize that our c8-bishop looks bad, but White's bishops stare at pawn walls too.   We have the option to improve our problem piece with the maneuver ...Bd7-e8-g6 or to h5. After  12.Nxe4  fxe4  we gain the half-open f-file as well. }
