[White "16. Triangle Sidelines − Deviations on moves 3 and 4"]
[Black "Triangle Sidelines 3.Nc3 c6 4.Bf4 #1"]
[Result "*"]

1. d4 d5 2. c4 e6
{ In this chapter, we cover White's options after @@StartFEN@@rnbqkbnr/pppppppp/8/8/8/8/PPPPPPPP/RNBQKBNR w KQkq - 0 1@@EndFEN@@  1.d4  d5  2.c4  e6  that don't merit dedicated chapters. As usual, the sidelines are sidelines for a reason.  In this chapter, we'll examine some poor or dubious lines that White can play, like  3.c5?  or various versions of an  early Bf4, when White is usually struggling to equalize. Not all the lines in the current chapter are bad for White, though. Some continuations are too harmless to pose serious problems and therefore never reach 'main line' status.  The most important of these sound, but harmless lines, is the Exchange Variation, featuring the trade on d5. White can trade on moves  three @@StartFEN@@rnbqkbnr/ppp2ppp/4p3/3p4/2PP4/8/PP2PPPP/RNBQKBNR w KQkq - 0 3@@EndFEN@@  3.cxd5  exd5  , or four @@StartFEN@@rnbqkbnr/ppp2ppp/4p3/3p4/2PP4/8/PP2PPPP/RNBQKBNR w KQkq - 0 3@@EndFEN@@  3.Nc3  /  3.Nf3  c6  4.cxd5  exd5  , and create the famous Carlsbad Pawn Structure.  We'll examine this in detail, as you'll encounter it quite frequently. Alright, let's get to work and check out White's sidelines against the Triangle. }
3. Nc3 c6
{ The starting position of the Triangle. Now White's main options are covered in other chapters:  A@@EndBracket@@  4.e4  − The Marshall Gambit.   B@@EndBracket@@  4.Nf3  dxc4  − The Noteboom.   C@@EndBracket@@  4.e3  − We'll answer in Stonewall style with  4...f5  .   We'll examine White's other tries on move four in the current chapter. These lines are all objectively harmless, but there are some traps and transpositions worth knowing. The most important option that we'll examine is  4.cxd5  exd5  , leading to a Carlsbad pawn structure. You'll frequently meet this variation, as many opponents prefer this simple but objectively toothless exchange. }
4. Bf4
{ A very natural move, White wants to play Bf4 first, then continue with e3 to start development of the kingside. All the lines after 4.Bf4 are promising for White, except the one we will play! }
4... dxc4
{ Very much in the spirit of the Noteboom. We grab the c-pawn and have ...b5 ready to cover it. As we will see, White must fight for equality after  4...dxc4  . White's only move to do that is  5.a4!  Black is already much better after  5.e3  . }
5. e3
{ The question mark is a bit harsh, but Black has a clear advantage after our reply  5...b5  , which just keeps the extra pawn, and White has nothing to show for the material loss. }
5... b5 { Well, we didn't take on c4 to return the pawn! } 6. a4
{ The only move to put up a fight and by far the most popular. Black is just a clean pawn up if White plays any slow move instead. }
6... Qb6
{ It's essential to remember this move! In the Noteboom, we usually play a quick ...Bb4, but here  6...Bb4?  is a huge mistake due to  7.axb5  cxb5  8.Qf3  Qd5  9.Qg3  ,  when both g7 and the knight on b8 are attacked. White is winning! The correct move, 6...Qb6!, avoids this trap and gives Black the better chances. }
7. Qf3
{ Probably the most exciting move to check because the best reply is not at all obvious. Our opponent can't challenge us with slow moves like  7.Nf3  . We'd develop with  7...Nf6  and just enjoy the extra pawn. }
7... Nd7
{ This engine suggestion is stronger than the more natural move  7...Bb7  , when  8.Qg3  gives White at least a bit of play. But why  is 7...Nd7 strong? Can't White take on b5? }
8. axb5
{ The pawn capture on b5 is easier to refute than  8.Nxb5  . Black's next move is more or less forced and happens to be much better for Black. }
8... Bb7
{ Forced and very favorable for Black. White can't capture on c6 now, and against other moves ...cxb5 will give Black a large advantage. }
9. bxc6 { This loses, but let's have a quick look at why. } 9... Qxb2
{ Too many white pieces are hanging with check. } 10. Ra2
{ After  10.cxd7+  Kxd7  Black wins easily. } 10... Qxc3+ 11. Kd1 Qb3+ 12. Rc2
Ba3
{ The strongest move that gives Black a winning advantage, for example, after  13.cxd7+  Kxd7  14.e4  Bc6  . }
