3. Nc3 c6
{ The starting position of the Triangle. Now White's main options are covered in other chapters:  A@@EndBracket@@  4.e4  − The Marshall Gambit.   B@@EndBracket@@  4.Nf3  dxc4  − The Noteboom.   C@@EndBracket@@  4.e3  − We'll answer in Stonewall style with  4...f5  .   We'll examine White's other tries on move four in the current chapter. These lines are all objectively harmless, but there are some traps and transpositions worth knowing. The most important option that we'll examine is  4.cxd5  exd5  , leading to a Carlsbad pawn structure. You'll frequently meet this variation, as many opponents prefer this simple but objectively toothless exchange. }
4. Bf4
{ A very natural move, White wants to play Bf4 first, then continue with e3 to start development of the kingside. All the lines after 4.Bf4 are promising for White, except the one we will play! }
4... dxc4
{ Very much in the spirit of the Noteboom. We grab the c-pawn and have ...b5 ready to cover it. As we will see, White must fight for equality after  4...dxc4  . White's only move to do that is  5.a4!  Black is already much better after  5.e3  . }
5. a4
{ White's best move and the only one that fights for equality. It also sets a trap that we need to avoid. In the Noteboom, we often play a combination of the moves ...b5 and ...Bb4 to secure the b5-pawn.   Now  5...Bb4?!  6.e3  b5??  is a huge mistake due to  7.axb5  cxb5  8.Qf3  Qd5  9.Qg3  and White wins! }
5... Nf6
{ This looks best for Black. As mentioned, you need to avoid  5...Bb4?!  at this point. }
6. e3
{ White has tried  6.e4?  in some games, but  6...Bb4  puts too much pressure on White's center. Neither  7.f3  b5  nor @@StartFEN@@rnbqk2r/pp3ppp/2p1pn2/8/PbpPPB2/2N5/1P3PPP/R2QKBNR w KQkq - 1 7@@EndFEN@@  7.e5  Nd5  are desirable for White, showing that  the combination of Bf4 and e4 is ill-advised. }
6... b5
{ We like this dynamic approach. Here the move  6...Nd5?!  is quite popular, but after  7.Bxc4  Nxf4  8.exf4  White has a good game despite the weakened pawn structure. It's challenging for Black to activate  the c8-bishop in these structures. Some classic games by Alekhine and Rubinstein demonstrated Black's issues about a century ago. Our solution 6...b5! starts a forced sequence that wins Black tempi for development. }
7. axb5
{ White has to regain the pawn before we cover it with ...Qb6 or ...Bb4. } 7...
cxb5 8. Nxb5
{ Here,  8.Qf3?  is very naive and easily dispatched by  8...Nd5  9.Nxb5  Bb4+  10.Nc3  Bb7  , when Black has a winning attack. }
8... Bb4+ 9. Nc3 Nd5 { This position is more or less forced after 5.a4 Nf6. }
10. Ne2
{ White plays this move most of the time, but Black has a considerable advantage now. Understandably, White wants to cover both f4 and c3, but how to develop the kingside? }
10... O-O 11. Bg3 { White prepares the move e4. } 11... Nc6 12. e4 Nb6
{ Black is much better in this position. In the online Blitz game A. Tang - S. Nihal, the move  13.f3  was played, when  13...f5  would have been even better than Nihal's  13...Na5  . Black can start an attack on White's king in the center, exploiting its awkward position. }
