3. Nf3 c6 4. Bf4
{ The early Bf4 lines have a dubious reputation, and this one is no exception. We'll happily grab the c-pawn now, just as we would in the Noteboom. }
4... dxc4 { Tasty! } 5. Nbd2
{ Now, this move has never been tried in master practice, but it is an interesting suggestion from Stockfish. The usual continuations  5.a4  b5  6.Nc3  Bb4  or @@StartFEN@@rnbqkbnr/pp3ppp/2p1p3/8/2pP1B2/5N2/PP2PPPP/RN1QKB1R w KQkq - 0 5@@EndFEN@@  5.e3  b5  6.a4  Bb4+  lead to positions very similar to the Noteboom, but with White having played the move Bf4. This looks odd, as the bishop does not contribute much to White's cause and is vulnerable to a later ...Nf6-d5 idea. White is also just a pawn down, on top of everything. }
5... b5 6. b3
{ That's the engine's idea. After  6...cxb3  7.Qxb3  White has some compensation for the sacrificed pawn. }
6... c3
{ A good pragmatic decision, avoiding the capture on b3. The pawn grab is playable, but  6...c3  gives Black a good position that is easy to play. }
7. Ne4 Nf6
{ As the engine shows, White has quite interesting play after  7...b4  8.Ne5  . This whole line is computerish and somewhat unlikely to happen, but something an inventive opponent might come up with while preparing a surprise against the Triangle. }
8. Nxc3 Bb7
{ Black has a fine position after returning the pawn. We are ready for ...c5 at the right moment, and White is certainly not happy about the move b3 being on the board. The dark squares on the queenside are weak, which the lines  9.e3??  Bb4  and @@StartFEN@@rn1qkb1r/pb3ppp/2p1pn2/1p6/3P1B2/1PN2N2/P3PPPP/R2QKB1R w KQkq - 1 9@@EndFEN@@  9.g3  Bb4  10.Bd2  c5  11.Nxb5??  Bxd2+  12.Qxd2  Ne4  illustrate. }
*

[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "16. Triangle Sidelines − Deviations on moves 3 and 4"]
[Black "Triangle Sidelines 3.Bf4"]
[Result "*"]

1. d4 d5 2. c4 e6
{ In this chapter, we cover White's options after @@StartFEN@@rnbqkbnr/pppppppp/8/8/8/8/PPPPPPPP/RNBQKBNR w KQkq - 0 1@@EndFEN@@  1.d4  d5  2.c4  e6  that don't merit dedicated chapters. As usual, the sidelines are sidelines for a reason.  In this chapter, we'll examine some poor or dubious lines that White can play, like  3.c5?  or various versions of an  early Bf4, when White is usually struggling to equalize. Not all the lines in the current chapter are bad for White, though. Some continuations are too harmless to pose serious problems and therefore never reach 'main line' status.  The most important of these sound, but harmless lines, is the Exchange Variation, featuring the trade on d5. White can trade on moves  three @@StartFEN@@rnbqkbnr/ppp2ppp/4p3/3p4/2PP4/8/PP2PPPP/RNBQKBNR w KQkq - 0 3@@EndFEN@@  3.cxd5  exd5  , or four @@StartFEN@@rnbqkbnr/ppp2ppp/4p3/3p4/2PP4/8/PP2PPPP/RNBQKBNR w KQkq - 0 3@@EndFEN@@  3.Nc3  /  3.Nf3  c6  4.cxd5  exd5  , and create the famous Carlsbad Pawn Structure.  We'll examine this in detail, as you'll encounter it quite frequently. Alright, let's get to work and check out White's sidelines against the Triangle. }
3. Bf4
{ White rarely develops the bishop this early. If a Bf4-based setup is in mind, it's best to start with  3.Nf3  or  3.Nc3  and only  play Bf4 under the right circumstances. A popular line for White is  3.Nf3  Nf6  4.Nc3  Be7  5.Bf4  , when the bishop only comes up after Black has committed  to ...Be7. After the very early 3.Bf4, Black has not yet decided about the piece or pawn setup and, therefore, is very flexible. }
3... dxc4
{ Taking the pawn is a good move, and in the spirit of our repertoire, Black has a good alternative in  3...c5  , but we happily play in the style of the Noteboom by grabbing the c-pawn. A move to avoid is  3...c6?!  , as  4.e3  covers the c-pawn and leads to the scenario White is hoping for. The bishop can be developed outside of the pawn chain without any concession. }
4. e3
{ Here  4.Nc3  c6  would transpose to the line @@StartFEN@@rnbqkbnr/ppp2ppp/4p3/3p4/2PP4/8/PP2PPPP/RNBQKBNR w KQkq - 0 3@@EndFEN@@  3.Nc3  c6  4.Bf4  dxc4  , which is also covered in the current chapter. Over the next moves, there are plenty of these possible transpositions. }
4... b5 5. a4
{ White's best move.  5.Nc3  c6  transposes to the line @@StartFEN@@rnbqkbnr/ppp2ppp/4p3/3p4/2PP4/8/PP2PPPP/RNBQKBNR w KQkq - 0 3@@EndFEN@@  3.Nc3  c6  4.Bf4  dxc4  5.e3  b5  . }
5... c6 6. axb5
{ Again, there is a possible transposition:  6.Nc3  Qb6  leads to the line @@StartFEN@@rnbqkbnr/ppp2ppp/4p3/3p4/2PP4/8/PP2PPPP/RNBQKBNR w KQkq - 0 3@@EndFEN@@  3.Nc3  c6  4.Bf4  dxc4  5.e3  b5  6.Nc3  Qb6  , which is better for Black already. }
6... cxb5 7. Qf3
{ After  7.Nc3  , it is crucial to play  7...Qb6!  , as  7...Bb4??  8.Qf3!  Qd5  9.Qg3  wins for White. This is yet again a line that may also arise via the @@StartFEN@@rnbqkbnr/ppp2ppp/4p3/3p4/2PP4/8/PP2PPPP/RNBQKBNR w KQkq - 0 3@@EndFEN@@  3.Nc3  c6  4.Bf4  dxc4  move order. }
7... Qd5 8. Nc3 Qxf3
{ We have already seen that  8...Bb4??  9.Qg3!  is the trap to avoid. } 9. Nxf3
Bb4 10. Nd2
{ White is breaking the pin and attacking the b5-pawn. Instead,  10.Bxb8  Rxb8  11.Rxa7  Nf6  gives Black a huge advantage due to the bishop pair. }
10... Bd7
{ This is the final move to know in this rather rare line. After  11.Be2  Bc6  12.Bf3  Bxc3  13.bxc3  Nf6  14.Bxb8  Bxf3  15.gxf3  Rxb8  White seems to equalize with precise play, but we certainly have nothing to complain about. }
*

