[White "16. Triangle Sidelines − Deviations on moves 3 and 4"]
[Black "The Carlsbad Structure − Overview"]
[Result "*"]

1. d4 d5 2. c4 e6
{ In this chapter, we cover White's options after @@StartFEN@@rnbqkbnr/pppppppp/8/8/8/8/PPPPPPPP/RNBQKBNR w KQkq - 0 1@@EndFEN@@  1.d4  d5  2.c4  e6  that don't merit dedicated chapters. As usual, the sidelines are sidelines for a reason.  In this chapter, we'll examine some poor or dubious lines that White can play, like  3.c5?  or various versions of an  early Bf4, when White is usually struggling to equalize. Not all the lines in the current chapter are bad for White, though. Some continuations are too harmless to pose serious problems and therefore never reach 'main line' status.  The most important of these sound, but harmless lines, is the Exchange Variation, featuring the trade on d5. White can trade on moves  three @@StartFEN@@rnbqkbnr/ppp2ppp/4p3/3p4/2PP4/8/PP2PPPP/RNBQKBNR w KQkq - 0 3@@EndFEN@@  3.cxd5  exd5  , or four @@StartFEN@@rnbqkbnr/ppp2ppp/4p3/3p4/2PP4/8/PP2PPPP/RNBQKBNR w KQkq - 0 3@@EndFEN@@  3.Nc3  /  3.Nf3  c6  4.cxd5  exd5  , and create the famous Carlsbad Pawn Structure.  We'll examine this in detail, as you'll encounter it quite frequently. Alright, let's get to work and check out White's sidelines against the Triangle. }
3. Nc3 c6
{ The starting position of the Triangle. Now White's main options are covered in other chapters:  A@@EndBracket@@  4.e4  − The Marshall Gambit.   B@@EndBracket@@  4.Nf3  dxc4  − The Noteboom.   C@@EndBracket@@  4.e3  − We'll answer in Stonewall style with  4...f5  .   We'll examine White's other tries on move four in the current chapter. These lines are all objectively harmless, but there are some traps and transpositions worth knowing. The most important option that we'll examine is  4.cxd5  exd5  , leading to a Carlsbad pawn structure. You'll frequently meet this variation, as many opponents prefer this simple but objectively toothless exchange. }
4. cxd5
{ White captures on d5 and changes the pawn structure. We'll talk about this more after our natural reply. }
4... exd5
{ This pawn formation, characterized by White's trade of the c-pawn for the e-pawn, is a very regular scenario in various Queen's Gambit lines. We may face the exchange on d5 after @@StartFEN@@rnbqkbnr/pppppppp/8/8/8/8/PPPPPPPP/RNBQKBNR w KQkq - 0 1@@EndFEN@@  1.d4  d5  2.c4  e6  3.cxd5  exd5  , or after @@StartFEN@@rnbqkbnr/ppp2ppp/4p3/3p4/2PP4/8/PP2PPPP/RNBQKBNR w KQkq - 0 3@@EndFEN@@  3.Nc3  c6  4.cxd5  / @@StartFEN@@rnbqkbnr/ppp2ppp/4p3/3p4/2PP4/8/PP2PPPP/RNBQKBNR w KQkq - 0 3@@EndFEN@@  3.Nf3  c6  4.cxd5  .  We will reach the same positions because after @@StartFEN@@rnbqkbnr/ppp2ppp/4p3/3p4/2PP4/8/PP2PPPP/RNBQKBNR w KQkq - 0 3@@EndFEN@@  3.cxd5  exd5  , White has nothing better than  4.Nc3  or  4.Nf3  when, in both cases,  4...c6  is the best move and our suggested reply.   In the Carlsbad structure, Black's ideal development scheme involves playing the bishops to d6 and f5, going for the most active squares possible. This setup can only be reached if you play ...c6 first. Black needs to cover d5, to allow ...Bd6, and also prepares ...Bf5.  Without the move ...c6, the reply Qb3 is often a problem, hitting d5 and b7 simultaneously. Once ...c6 is on the board, the move ...Bf5 is easier to play, as Qb3 can quickly be answered with ...Qb6.  It is helpful to compare our specific version of the exchange with two similar lines.  A@@EndBracket@@ @@StartFEN@@rnbqkbnr/pppppppp/8/8/8/8/PPPPPPPP/RNBQKBNR w KQkq - 0 1@@EndFEN@@  1.d4  d5  2.c4  e6  3.cxd5  exd5  4.Nc3  c6  or @@StartFEN@@rnbqkbnr/ppp2ppp/4p3/3p4/2PP4/8/PP2PPPP/RNBQKBNR w KQkq - 0 3@@EndFEN@@  3.Nc3  c6  4.cxd5  exd5  .  B@@EndBracket@@ @@StartFEN@@rnbqkbnr/pppppppp/8/8/8/8/PPPPPPPP/RNBQKBNR w KQkq - 0 1@@EndFEN@@  1.d4  d5  2.c4  e6  3.Nc3  Nf6  4.cxd5  exd5  .  C@@EndBracket@@ @@StartFEN@@rnbqkbnr/pppppppp/8/8/8/8/PPPPPPPP/RNBQKBNR w KQkq - 0 1@@EndFEN@@  1.d4  d5  2.c4  e6  3.Nc3  Be7  4.cxd5  exd5  .  While lines B and C are considered main lines and good tries for an advantage, line A @@StartBracket@@our version@@EndBracket@@ is not. Why? In line B, White continues with @@StartFEN@@rnbqkb1r/ppp2ppp/5n2/3p4/3P4/2N5/PP2PPPP/R1BQKBNR w KQkq - 0 5@@EndFEN@@  5.Bg5  , pinning the knight @@StartBracket@@not possible in A@@EndBracket@@.  As mentioned, Black would like to employ an active piece setup with ...Bd6 and ...Bf5.  It turns out that it is impossible to achieve both moves under favorable circumstances. If Black  decides to play  5...Be7  to break the pin,  the ...Bd6-formation is off.  So  5...c6  is the best try to shoot for it. After  6.e3  Bd6  7.Bd3  ,  you won't manage ...Bf5, though. You could start  with @@StartFEN@@rnbqkb1r/pp3ppp/2p2n2/3p2B1/3P4/2N1P3/PP3PPP/R2QKBNR b KQkq - 0 6@@EndFEN@@  6...Bf5  , but this is met with the annoying move  7.Qf3!  when Black needs to accept a doubled f-pawn.  These lines are not entirely bad for Black, but they show that reaching the optimal/most active setup is not possible against best play.  In line C,  Black has already played the bishop to e7 and avoided the move ...Nf6. This way, the pin on the knight is not possible, but playing ...Be7 is not ideal if you'd like to place the bishop on d6.  One main continuation in line C  is: @@StartFEN@@rnbqk1nr/ppp1bppp/8/3p4/3P4/2N5/PP2PPPP/R1BQKBNR w KQkq - 0 5@@EndFEN@@  5.Bf4  c6  6.e3  Bd6  , when Black accepts a tempo loss with the bishop. We'll save a full tempo on this line: @@StartFEN@@rnbqkbnr/ppp2ppp/4p3/3p4/2PP4/8/PP2PPPP/RNBQKBNR w KQkq - 0 3@@EndFEN@@  3.cxd5  exd5  4.Nc3  c6  5.Bf4  Bd6  . This tempo is very relevant,  as White uses it to play Bd3 and Qc2, making our ...Bf5 move more difficult to realize. White has a small advantage in this line, while in our version, we easily play ...Bf5 soon and have no problems.  The conclusion is: of all the early exchange lines that aim for the Carlsbad, our version is the most comfortable for Black to handle. In many lines, Black even reaches a positive score.  Let's talk about plans and ideas for both sides now. We'll start with White's options. White has two main plans in the Carlsbad structure:  1. The Minority Attack on the queenside. White's idea is based on the advance of b4-b5, weakening Black's pawn structure. After b4-b5, White intends to capture c6 and create a backward pawn on the half-open c-file after Black recaptures with the pawn on b7. Alternatively, Black could take on b5 or decide to capture with a piece after White's capture on c6. In this case, the d5-pawn would be isolated.  We'll see that Black has good options against the minority attack in our version of the Carlsbad. One key argument in Black's favour is that usually we manage to trade the light-squared bishops. This exchange improves our option to answer b2-b4 with ...b7-b5! and stops the minority attack in its tracks.  This reply is less attractive with the light-squared bishops on the board. In this case, we'd be reluctant to place more pawns on light squares. After the trade, this is not a relevant point anymore. An additional idea after ...b7-b5 is the knight tour to c4, which is an attractive square. We'll examine these points in more detail later.  2. White plays for a central expansion with the moves f2-f3 and e2-e3-e4. After the trade on d5, White has an extra pawn in the center. Advancing in the center to gain more space certainly makes sense. This idea is often associated with the sixth World Champion Mikhail Botvinnik, and was later often adopted by his student, Garry Kasparov,  the 13th World Champion.  They used this plan in the line @@StartFEN@@rnbqkbnr/pppppppp/8/8/8/8/PPPPPPPP/RNBQKBNR w KQkq - 0 1@@EndFEN@@  1.d4  d5  2.c4  e6  3.Nc3  Nf6  4.cxd5  exd5  5.Bg5  c6  6.e3  Be7  7.Bd3  O-O  8.Qc2  Nbd7  9.Nge2  Re8  10.O-O  Nf8  11.f3  . A key issue for Black in this line is the lack of space. Black still has all the minor pieces on the board.  White's expansion with f3 and e4, possibly even e4-e5 next, gains a lot of ground, and Black often does not have enough space for the pieces.  In our version of the Carlsbad, this is usually not the case, as we quickly gain active positions for the bishops @@StartBracket@@compared to the bishops in the Botvinnik/Kasparov line@@EndBracket@@ and often trade them quickly @@StartBracket@@...Bd6 in response to Bf4 or ... Bf5 against a bishop on d3@@EndBracket@@.  What about Black's ideas? Our play depends to some extent on White's choice of plan. In some cases, correctly answering White's approach is perfectly fine to equalize and gain slightly better chances. This is often the case if we manage to answer the 'Minority Attack' with ...b7-b5, for example. A general idea for Black is to play for an attack on the kingside.  We can often make good use of the e4-square with a knight, supported by piece play and sometimes the advance of pawns. Pushing f5-f4 is our version of the 'Minority Attack', just on the other side of the board. Another common idea is to use a rook on the sixth rank @@StartBracket@@...Re8-e6-g6 or h6@@EndBracket@@.  We'd also like to mention that the square d6 is often an excellent spot for a knight. On d6, it has a very versatile role. It helps to address a possible White 'Minority Attack', maybe stopping it altogether or allowing ...Nc4 at an opportune moment. At the same time, it is ready to switch to the kingside @@StartBracket@@e4 and f5@@EndBracket@@. This also explains why we frequently develop our knight to e7 early on. The knight supports ...Bf5 in many cases, but it is also ready to be transferred to the ideal d6-square via f5 or c8.  Let's return to concrete moves now. What  does White play after @@StartFEN@@rnbqkbnr/pp3ppp/2p1p3/3P4/3P4/2N5/PP2PPPP/R1BQKBNR b KQkq - 0 4@@EndFEN@@  4...exd5?  They usually continue with a combination of the moves Bf4, Nf3, or Qc2. We suggest answering with ...Bd6 in all cases, making it easier to remember. }
*

