[White "16. Triangle Sidelines − Deviations on moves 3 and 4"]
[Black "Triangle Sidelines 3.Nc3 c6 4.cxd5 #1"]
[Result "*"]

1. d4 d5 2. c4 e6
{ In this chapter, we cover White's options after @@StartFEN@@rnbqkbnr/pppppppp/8/8/8/8/PPPPPPPP/RNBQKBNR w KQkq - 0 1@@EndFEN@@  1.d4  d5  2.c4  e6  that don't merit dedicated chapters. As usual, the sidelines are sidelines for a reason.  In this chapter, we'll examine some poor or dubious lines that White can play, like  3.c5?  or various versions of an  early Bf4, when White is usually struggling to equalize. Not all the lines in the current chapter are bad for White, though. Some continuations are too harmless to pose serious problems and therefore never reach 'main line' status.  The most important of these sound, but harmless lines, is the Exchange Variation, featuring the trade on d5. White can trade on moves  three @@StartFEN@@rnbqkbnr/ppp2ppp/4p3/3p4/2PP4/8/PP2PPPP/RNBQKBNR w KQkq - 0 3@@EndFEN@@  3.cxd5  exd5  , or four @@StartFEN@@rnbqkbnr/ppp2ppp/4p3/3p4/2PP4/8/PP2PPPP/RNBQKBNR w KQkq - 0 3@@EndFEN@@  3.Nc3  /  3.Nf3  c6  4.cxd5  exd5  , and create the famous Carlsbad Pawn Structure.  We'll examine this in detail, as you'll encounter it quite frequently. Alright, let's get to work and check out White's sidelines against the Triangle. }
3. Nc3 c6
{ The starting position of the Triangle. Now White's main options are covered in other chapters:  A@@EndBracket@@  4.e4  − The Marshall Gambit.   B@@EndBracket@@  4.Nf3  dxc4  − The Noteboom.   C@@EndBracket@@  4.e3  − We'll answer in Stonewall style with  4...f5  .   We'll examine White's other tries on move four in the current chapter. These lines are all objectively harmless, but there are some traps and transpositions worth knowing. The most important option that we'll examine is  4.cxd5  exd5  , leading to a Carlsbad pawn structure. You'll frequently meet this variation, as many opponents prefer this simple but objectively toothless exchange. }
4. cxd5
{ White captures on d5 and changes the pawn structure. We'll talk about this more after our natural reply. }
4... exd5
{ White has exchanged on d5 and created the famous 'Carlsbad Structure' @@StartBracket@@see the Informational for an in-depth overview@@EndBracket@@. }
5. Nf3 Bd6
{ There is nothing wrong with  5...Bf5  , either.  We want to develop the bishops to the natural squares f5 and d6, making ...Bf5 a good alternative.  The main reason for choosing  5...Bd6  is to be consistent with the concept of  playing ...Bd6 against all three moves:  @@StartFEN@@rnbqkbnr/pp3ppp/2p5/3p4/3P4/2N5/PP2PPPP/R1BQKBNR w KQkq - 0 5@@EndFEN@@  5.Bf4  ,  5.Qc2  , and  5.Nf3  . }
6. Bg5
{ White's main move. There are possible transpositions to lines that we cover via a different move order.  A@@EndBracket@@  6.Qc2  h6  is covered via @@StartFEN@@rnbqkbnr/pp3ppp/2p5/3p4/3P4/2N5/PP2PPPP/R1BQKBNR w KQkq - 0 5@@EndFEN@@  5.Qc2  Bd6  6.Nf3  h6  .   B@@EndBracket@@  6.g3  Nf6  7.Bg2  is covered via the 5.g3 move order. }
6... Ne7
{ This is better than  6...Nf6  , when the pin is rather annoying. Now @@StartFEN@@rnbqk2r/pp2nppp/2pb4/3p2B1/3P4/2N2N2/PP2PPPP/R2QKB1R w KQkq - 4 7@@EndFEN@@  7.e3  is by far White's main choice, but  7.Qc2  is worth checking. }
7. Qc2
{ A rare move, but there is an interesting point that we should be aware of. }
7... h6 { Inserting this move is useful. } 8. Bh4 Qa5
{ The interesting moment we were hinting at is this one. Here,  8...Bf5  looks perfectly normal, but White has  9.Qxf5  Nxf5  10.Bxd8  Kxd8  , which is not very attractive for Black to play. Instead, our suggestion 8...Qa5  leads to a more exciting play, as we prepare both ...Bf5 and ...Nf5. }
9. e3 Bf5
{ Here  9...Nf5  is possible too. White's best reply is  10.Bd3  , when  10...Nxh4  11.Nxh4  ,  intending ...Nh4-f5, leads to equal chances. }
10. Bd3 Bxd3 11. Qxd3 Nd7
{ After 11...Nd7, we reach a very similar position to @@StartFEN@@rnbqk2r/pp2nppp/2pb4/3p2B1/3P4/2N2N2/PP2PPPP/R2QKB1R w KQkq - 4 7@@EndFEN@@  7.e3  Bf5  8.Bd3  Bxd3  9.Qxd3  Nd7  .  The moves ...h6/Bh4 are inserted, and we have the move ...Qa5 in addition. This does not change the evaluation: chances are equal.   Besides @@StartFEN@@rn2k2r/pp2npp1/2pb3p/q2p4/3P3B/2NQPN2/PP3PPP/R3K2R b KQkq - 0 11@@EndFEN@@  11...Nd7  , Black may also play  11...Qa6  , when  12.Qxa6  Nxa6  leads to an equal endgame. If you prefer technical positions, this is a good option. }
