3. Nc3 c6
{ The starting position of the Triangle. Now White's main options are covered in other chapters:  A@@EndBracket@@  4.e4  − The Marshall Gambit.   B@@EndBracket@@  4.Nf3  dxc4  − The Noteboom.   C@@EndBracket@@  4.e3  − We'll answer in Stonewall style with  4...f5  .   We'll examine White's other tries on move four in the current chapter. These lines are all objectively harmless, but there are some traps and transpositions worth knowing. The most important option that we'll examine is  4.cxd5  exd5  , leading to a Carlsbad pawn structure. You'll frequently meet this variation, as many opponents prefer this simple but objectively toothless exchange. }
4. cxd5
{ White captures on d5 and changes the pawn structure. We'll talk about this more after our natural reply. }
4... exd5
{ White has exchanged on d5 and created the famous 'Carlsbad Structure' @@StartBracket@@see the Informational for an in-depth overview@@EndBracket@@. }
5. Nf3 Bd6
{ There is nothing wrong with  5...Bf5  , either.  We want to develop the bishops to the natural squares f5 and d6, making ...Bf5 a good alternative.  The main reason for choosing  5...Bd6  is to be consistent with the concept of  playing ...Bd6 against all three moves:  @@StartFEN@@rnbqkbnr/pp3ppp/2p5/3p4/3P4/2N5/PP2PPPP/R1BQKBNR w KQkq - 0 5@@EndFEN@@  5.Bf4  ,  5.Qc2  , and  5.Nf3  . }
6. Bg5
{ White's main move. There are possible transpositions to lines that we cover via a different move order.  A@@EndBracket@@  6.Qc2  h6  is covered via @@StartFEN@@rnbqkbnr/pp3ppp/2p5/3p4/3P4/2N5/PP2PPPP/R1BQKBNR w KQkq - 0 5@@EndFEN@@  5.Qc2  Bd6  6.Nf3  h6  .   B@@EndBracket@@  6.g3  Nf6  7.Bg2  is covered via the 5.g3 move order. }
6... Ne7
{ This is better than  6...Nf6  , when the pin is rather annoying. Now @@StartFEN@@rnbqk2r/pp2nppp/2pb4/3p2B1/3P4/2N2N2/PP2PPPP/R2QKB1R w KQkq - 4 7@@EndFEN@@  7.e3  is by far White's main choice, but  7.Qc2  is worth checking. }
7. e3 { White plays the normal move, preparing Bd3 and O-O. } 7... h6
{ We suggest inserting this move. It's also possible to play  7...Bf5  right away, of course. }
8. Bh4 Bf5
{ Mission accomplished. We managed to get the bishops to the best squares, d6 and f5. }
9. Bd3
{ White usually goes for this trade. Our bishop occupies a powerful diagonal and hinders ideas like Rb1, followed by the typical b2-b4 pawn advance − the minority attack. }
9... Bxd3 10. Qxd3 O-O 11. O-O Nd7
{ Black has equal chances in this position. We are very flexible in reacting to White's ideas, which often backfire if our opponent is too ambitious. We decided to stop the trainable here as too many reasonable continuations are possible. Instead, let's have a look at some ideas.  A@@EndBracket@@  12.Bg3  Nc8  @@StartBracket@@taking is not bad, either@@EndBracket@@  13.Rab1  Bxg3  14.hxg3  Nd6  15.b4  a6  16.a4  b5  ,  when Black has accomplished an excellent anti-minority-attack setup. The square c4 will be an excellent post for our knight.   B@@EndBracket@@  12.Rab1  a5  13.a3  Nb6  14.b4  axb4  15.axb4  Ra3  also looks good for Black. White's pawn play on the queenside has weakened squares more than anything else.  White may also strive  for the pawn push e4, but we are happy to take on e4 and give White an isolated queen pawn. White could start slow maneuvers, but we have some scope for improvement, too. Moves like ...Rfe8 come to mind next. Stockfish also suggests the idea of ...Qc8 to unpin the knight. A sample line to illustrate this idea is the following:   C@@EndBracket@@  12.Rfe1  Re8  13.Qc2  Qc8  14.a3  Ng6  15.Bg3  Bxg3  15.hxg3  and now  15...Nb6  , amongst others, looks fine for Black.  Due to the weakness of c4, we don't need to fear the minority attack. Our knight is already connected to this crucial square. }
