7. e4 { This looks like the most exciting try for White. } 7... dxe4 8. Nxe4
Nf6
{ This looks better than  8...Bb4+  .  We don't mind the capture on d6, as we retain excellent control of the light squares in exchange for the bishop pair. It's interesting to compare this approach to the following  line: @@StartFEN@@rnbqkbnr/pppppppp/8/8/8/8/PPPPPPPP/RNBQKBNR w KQkq - 0 1@@EndFEN@@  1.e4  c6  2.d4  d5  3.exd5  cxd5  4.Bd3  Nc6  5.c3  Nf6  6.h3  e5  7.dxe5  Nxe5  8.Nf3  , which leads to equal chances. White has the extra  move Qc2 in our version, which is not particularly useful, as we will see. }
