3. Nc3 c6
{ The starting position of the Triangle. Now White's main options are covered in other chapters:  A@@EndBracket@@  4.e4  − The Marshall Gambit.   B@@EndBracket@@  4.Nf3  dxc4  − The Noteboom.   C@@EndBracket@@  4.e3  − We'll answer in Stonewall style with  4...f5  .   We'll examine White's other tries on move four in the current chapter. These lines are all objectively harmless, but there are some traps and transpositions worth knowing. The most important option that we'll examine is  4.cxd5  exd5  , leading to a Carlsbad pawn structure. You'll frequently meet this variation, as many opponents prefer this simple but objectively toothless exchange. }
4. cxd5
{ White captures on d5 and changes the pawn structure. We'll talk about this more after our natural reply. }
4... exd5
{ White has exchanged on d5 and created the famous 'Carlsbad Structure' @@StartBracket@@see the Informational for an in-depth overview@@EndBracket@@. }
5. Bf4
{ White develops the bishop first, keeping some flexibility in regards to the kingside setup. }
5... Bd6
{ We suggest immediately offering the bishop trade with  5...Bd6  . The other move fitting to our concept would be  5...Bf5  . This is a popular option for Black and can't be wrong. However, we found the engine suggestion  6.f3!?  to be surprisingly tricky to handle for Black. This move is extremely rare, but it could be something a well-prepared opponent has in mind.  Long story short: we play 5...Bd6, as we usually do − we play the same move against @@StartFEN@@rnbqkbnr/pp3ppp/2p5/3p4/3P4/2N5/PP2PPPP/R1BQKBNR w KQkq - 0 5@@EndFEN@@  5.Qc2  and  5.Nf3  too. }
6. Bg3
{ White keeps the tension and hopes that we'll take on g3, opening the h-file for White. }
6... Ne7
{ A clever move! We plan ...Nf5, trying to capture the bishop with our knight. After ...Nf5, we gain the option to recapture on d6 with the knight, placing it on a great square. Of course, there are reasonable alternatives for Black at this point.   We want to mention  6...Bf5  , which looks logical but is not that easy to play after  7.Qb3  Bxg3  8.hxg3  . It should be about equal,  but the pressure on b7 is somewhat annoying to deal with. }
7. e3 Nf5 8. Bd3 { Alright, White is giving up the bishop pair. } 8... Nxg3
{ We'll take it, thank you very much! } 9. hxg3 Nd7
