8. Bd3 Bxd3 { Or  8...Ne7  , which is just as good. } 9. Qxd3 Ne7
{ Placing the knight on e7 looks very flexible. In some cases, we can still play the f-pawn if White continues with an f3&e4 idea. In many cases, the squares d6 or b6 are excellent for a knight, looking at important squares like c4 or e4. From e7, our knight has the route via c8 to d6 or b6, reaching these good posts quickly. }
10. Nf3
{ Or  10.Nge2  O-O  11.O-O  Nd7  12.f3  f5!  showing one idea of the knight placement on e7. }
10... Nd7 { Castling first is also fine, of course. } 11. O-O O-O 12. Rab1
{ White prepares the move b2-b4, starting the 'Minority Attack' on the queenside. In White's ideal world, they manage b2-b4-b5 and trade on c6, when Black would have an inferior pawn structure.   To illustrate what to avoid, please see the following move sequence. It features bad play on Black's part, basically ignoring White's intentions completely:  12...Rfe8  13.b4  a6  14.a4  Nf6  15.b5  axb5  16.axb5  Ng6  17.bxc6  bxc6  . This is White's dream scenario: the c-pawn is weak and an easy target, while Black has no counterplay.   How to counter White's 'Minority Attack'? The key idea is to stop the further advance of the b-pawn by playing ...b5. In such a pawn structure, the knight on e7 is ready to be improved via c8-b6-c4, reaching a dream square. }
12... a5
{ Stopping b4 for the moment, so White needs to invest a bit of time for the move a3. }
13. a3 Rfe8
{ A good waiting move. White now has a hard time making any headway, as the planned advance b4 leads nowhere. }
14. b4
{ White should probably play a slow waiting move instead. After such a move, like  14.h3  , we can play  14...Nc8  ,  heading towards b6. With a knight on b6, the advance b4 would also be difficult to achieve, as we'd have ...Nc4 in reply. }
14... b5
{ That's the key idea for Black. We already have better chances because of ...Nb6-c4 next. White has some weaknesses on the queenside and nothing to show for it. }
