{ In this chapter, we cover White's options after @@StartFEN@@rnbqkbnr/pppppppp/8/8/8/8/PPPPPPPP/RNBQKBNR w KQkq - 0 1@@EndFEN@@  1.d4  d5  2.c4  e6  that don't merit dedicated chapters. As usual, the sidelines are sidelines for a reason.  In this chapter, we'll examine some poor or dubious lines that White can play, like  3.c5?  or various versions of an  early Bf4, when White is usually struggling to equalize. Not all the lines in the current chapter are bad for White, though. Some continuations are too harmless to pose serious problems and therefore never reach 'main line' status.  The most important of these sound, but harmless lines, is the Exchange Variation, featuring the trade on d5. White can trade on moves  three @@StartFEN@@rnbqkbnr/ppp2ppp/4p3/3p4/2PP4/8/PP2PPPP/RNBQKBNR w KQkq - 0 3@@EndFEN@@  3.cxd5  exd5  , or four @@StartFEN@@rnbqkbnr/ppp2ppp/4p3/3p4/2PP4/8/PP2PPPP/RNBQKBNR w KQkq - 0 3@@EndFEN@@  3.Nc3  /  3.Nf3  c6  4.cxd5  exd5  , and create the famous Carlsbad Pawn Structure.  We'll examine this in detail, as you'll encounter it quite frequently. Alright, let's get to work and check out White's sidelines against the Triangle. }
3. cxd5
{ White immediately exchanges on d5, aiming for the famous 'Carlsbad Structure' that arises after our natural recapture. If White intends to go for this pawn structure, usually  3.Nc3  is played first and only trade on move four, after Black has committed in some way on move three. In the context of our repertoire, the early exchange on move two has purely transpositional value. Let's examine why. }
3... exd5
{ After this natural recapture, White has some options, but they all transpose to lines that we cover via different move orders.  A@@EndBracket@@ @@StartFEN@@rnbqkbnr/ppp2ppp/8/3p4/3P4/8/PP2PPPP/RNBQKBNR w KQkq - 0 4@@EndFEN@@  4.Nc3  c6  is the most common and covered via @@StartFEN@@rnbqkbnr/ppp2ppp/4p3/3p4/2PP4/8/PP2PPPP/RNBQKBNR w KQkq - 0 3@@EndFEN@@  3.Nc3  c6  4.cxd5  exd5  in the current chapter.  B@@EndBracket@@ @@StartFEN@@rnbqkbnr/ppp2ppp/8/3p4/3P4/8/PP2PPPP/RNBQKBNR w KQkq - 0 4@@EndFEN@@  4.Nf3  c6  transposes to the move order @@StartFEN@@rnbqkbnr/ppp2ppp/4p3/3p4/2PP4/8/PP2PPPP/RNBQKBNR w KQkq - 0 3@@EndFEN@@  3.Nf3  c6  4.cxd5  exd5  , which we cover in the current chapter too. Instead, Black may also play @@StartFEN@@rnbqkbnr/ppp2ppp/8/3p4/3P4/5N2/PP2PPPP/RNBQKB1R b KQkq - 1 4@@EndFEN@@  4...Bf5!?  , which transposes to a line we cover via @@StartFEN@@rnbqkbnr/pppppppp/8/8/8/8/PPPPPPPP/RNBQKBNR w KQkq - 0 1@@EndFEN@@  1.d4  d5  2.Nf3  Bf5  3.c4  e6  4.cxd5  exd5  .  C@@EndBracket@@ @@StartFEN@@rnbqkbnr/ppp2ppp/8/3p4/3P4/8/PP2PPPP/RNBQKBNR w KQkq - 0 4@@EndFEN@@  4.Bf4  is a very rare move with little independent value. After  4...c6  , we'll transpose to A or B quickly, as White's knight moves are very natural. }
