1. d4 d5 2. Nf3
{ After 1.d4 d5 White's main move is  2.c4  , the Queen's Gambit. Our answer to the Queen's Gambit is the Triangle Variation, @@StartFEN@@rnbqkbnr/pppppppp/8/8/8/8/PPPPPPPP/RNBQKBNR w KQkq - 0 1@@EndFEN@@  1.d4  d5  2.c4  e6  3.Nc3  c6  or  3.Nf3  c6  , which is the namesake for the course.  However, White is not obliged to play @@StartFEN@@rnbqkbnr/ppp1pppp/8/3p4/3P4/8/PPP1PPPP/RNBQKBNR w KQkq - 0 2@@EndFEN@@  2.c4  but may opt for a different path. The two most important alternatives are the flexible  2.Nf3  and  2.Bf4  , the popular London System. Black has a range of possible replies against these moves.  We play the moves ...e6 and ...c6 @@StartBracket@@the Triangle@@EndBracket@@ against  2.c4  , so why not go for the same setup against White's arguably less aggressive options? We considered this approach but wondered if Black might have a more ambitious response.  Let's go back to the basic position after @@StartFEN@@rnbqkbnr/pppppppp/8/8/8/8/PPPPPPPP/RNBQKBNR w KQkq - 0 1@@EndFEN@@  1.d4  d5  2.c4  . After  2.c4  ,  White threatens cxd5, so our options are limited if we want to keep the central pawn on d5. Black has to play  2...e6  or  2...c6  to accomplish this goal. After  2...e6  , Black's light-squared bishop is passive for the moment. Of course,  2...e6  is an excellent move and our repertoire choice, but  the c8-bishop is a cause for concern for the foreseeable future.   Now, consider if White does not play @@StartFEN@@rnbqkbnr/ppp1pppp/8/3p4/3P4/8/PPP1PPPP/RNBQKBNR w KQkq - 0 2@@EndFEN@@  2.c4  but instead goes for a slower move. We wondered if it is possible to 'punish' White for not playing  2.c4  by  developing our c8-bishop to f5 on move two, and only then playing the move ...e6.  We examined  2.Nf3  Bf5  and @@StartFEN@@rnbqkbnr/ppp1pppp/8/3p4/3P4/8/PPP1PPPP/RNBQKBNR w KQkq - 0 2@@EndFEN@@  2.Bf4  Bf5  , and concluded that Black's concept is perfectly viable.  These lines have the practical advantage of being relatively unexplored and, therefore, will likely not be prepared as thoroughly by your opponents. The coverage of @@StartFEN@@rnbqkbnr/pppppppp/8/8/8/8/PPPPPPPP/RNBQKBNR w KQkq - 0 1@@EndFEN@@  1.d4  d5  2.Nf3  Bf5  is split into two chapters.  A@@EndBracket@@ The current chapter covers all the lines after @@StartFEN@@rnbqkbnr/pppppppp/8/8/8/8/PPPPPPPP/RNBQKBNR w KQkq - 0 1@@EndFEN@@  1.d4  d5  2.Nf3  Bf5  except the main line.  B@@EndBracket@@ The main line @@StartFEN@@rnbqkbnr/pppppppp/8/8/8/8/PPPPPPPP/RNBQKBNR w KQkq - 0 1@@EndFEN@@  1.d4  d5  2.Nf3  Bf5  3.c4  e6  4.Nc3  Nf6  is examined in a dedicated chapter. }
