[Black "2.Nf3 Bf5 3.e3"]
[Result "*"]

1. d4 d5 2. Nf3
{ Developing the knight is a popular move for White. It is a flexible choice. White may still play c2-c4 on the next move, entering a Queen's Gambit, or opt for a slower development. As already discussed, we answer  2.Nf3  with  2...Bf5  , which leads to less explored and interesting positions. }
2... Bf5
{ After  2...Bf5  , the only critical move must be  3.c4  , which we will focus on. White's calmer alternatives on move three,  3.g3  and  3.e3  are rather harmless or will transpose to lines that we examine via different move orders. An important option for White is  3.Bf4  , but  3...e6  immediately leads to a position that is covered in the chapter on the London System. }
3. e3
{ A calm setup, aiming to develop the kingside quickly. If White continues with c2-c4 soon, we will transpose to lines that we cover via the move order  3.c4  e6  4.e3  , for example, after @@StartFEN@@rn1qkbnr/ppp1pppp/8/3p1b2/3P4/4PN2/PPP2PPP/RNBQKB1R b KQkq - 0 3@@EndFEN@@  3...e6  4.c4  , which is probably White's best option. }
3... e6 { As usual, we play the move ...e6 first. } 4. Bd3
{ White develops the kingside and seeks to trade our active bishop. This is a good move, but rather toothless. It's a bit more ambitious to play  4.c4  when  4...c6  leads to @@StartFEN@@rn1qkbnr/ppp1pppp/8/3p1b2/3P4/5N2/PPP1PPPP/RNBQKB1R w KQkq - 2 3@@EndFEN@@  3.c4  e6  4.e3  c6  , which is also examined in the current chapter. }
4... Bxd3 5. Qxd3 c6 { White was threatening Qb5+, which we need to stop. } 6.
O-O
{ After  6.c4  we suggest  6...f5  , which transposes to @@StartFEN@@rn1qkbnr/ppp1pppp/8/3p1b2/3P4/5N2/PPP1PPPP/RNBQKB1R w KQkq - 2 3@@EndFEN@@  3.c4  e6  4.e3  c6  5.Bd3  Bxd3  6.Qxd3  f5  . If White plays @@StartFEN@@rn1qkbnr/pp3ppp/2p1p3/3p4/3P4/3QPN2/PPP2PPP/RNB1K2R w KQkq - 0 6@@EndFEN@@  6.Nbd2  , the move  6...f5  makes an even stronger impression. The knight is quite passive  on d2, giving Black a great Stonewall. }
6... f5
{ The ambitious move, going for the Stonewall setup. Of course,  6...Nf6  is a good move and leads to equal chances, too. }
7. Qb3
