4. g3
{ White opts for the kingside fianchetto. A good and reliable setup for Black against it involves the moves ...Nf6 and ...c6, building the solid triangle of pawns in the center. An important consideration for Black is the move order. What to play first?   This is even more relevant because of White's options to play a g3-based setup one move earlier, after @@StartFEN@@rnbqkbnr/pppppppp/8/8/8/8/PPPPPPPP/RNBQKBNR w KQkq - 0 1@@EndFEN@@  1.d4  d5  2.Nf3  Bf5  3.g3  and one move later, when @@StartFEN@@rnbqkbnr/pppppppp/8/8/8/8/PPPPPPPP/RNBQKBNR w KQkq - 0 1@@EndFEN@@  1.d4  d5  2.Nf3  Bf5  3.c4  e6  4.Nc3  Nf6  5.g3  is an option for White.   We want to play a consistent move order that works in all cases. Here's the move order guideline:   A@@EndBracket@@ If ...e6 is not yet played, play this first @@StartBracket@@applies only to @@StartFEN@@rnbqkbnr/pppppppp/8/8/8/8/PPPPPPPP/RNBQKBNR w KQkq - 0 1@@EndFEN@@  1.d4  d5  2.Nf3  Bf5  3.g3  , when  3...e6  is the first move to play@@EndBracket@@.  B@@EndBracket@@ We play ...Nf6 next.  C@@EndBracket@@  If White plays a combination of g3, c4, and Nc3, we need to worry about the idea Nh4 and should play the move ...h6. Without Nc3 on the board, Nh4 can always be answered with ...Be4.   D@@EndBracket@@ If we have played ...e6 and ...Nf6 already, the next move should be ...c6, unless rule C applies. There are other ways to handle the move orders, but this approach works well and looks easiest to remember. }
4... Nf6
{ As per rule B. The moves  4...c6  or  4...h6  are not a mistake but may lead to slightly different versions of lines that we have in our repertoire. We'll see that the pawn moves are not always necessary, and sometimes we have better options.  Examples are playing ...h7-h5 in some lines or being able to answer Qb3 with ...Nc6.   After  4...Nf6  , we need to check some possible replies. A harmless option is  5.Nh4?!  , which we answer with  5...Be4  . More relevant are @@StartFEN@@rn1qkb1r/ppp2ppp/4pn2/3p1b2/2PP4/5NP1/PP2PP1P/RNBQKB1R w KQkq - 1 5@@EndFEN@@  5.Qb3  ,  5.Nc3  and the most popular move  5.Bg2  . }
5. Bg2 { White's most natural and popular move. } 5... c6
{ As per rule D. We play ...c6, after ...Nf6 and ...e6, is on the board, and White has not played Nc3.   Now, after  5...c6  , White has some options.  A common plan for White is playing Qb3 at some point. That could be played  right away or after  6.Nc3  h6  or @@StartFEN@@rn1qkb1r/pp3ppp/2p1pn2/3p1b2/2PP4/5NP1/PP2PPBP/RNBQK2R w KQkq - 0 6@@EndFEN@@  6.O-O  h6  has been inserted.   There are some subtle differences between these versions. The relatively most promising version for White seems to be  6.Nc3  h6  7.Qb3  . So what's the difference? Against @@StartFEN@@rn1qkb1r/pp3ppp/2p1pn2/3p1b2/2PP4/5NP1/PP2PPBP/RNBQK2R w KQkq - 0 6@@EndFEN@@  6.Qb3  Qb6  7.c5  Qxb3  8.axb3  we have the option to play  8...Bxb1  , which is a simple and good way to play.   We can employ the same plan after  6.O-O  h6  7.Qb3  Qb6  8.c5  Qxb3  9.axb3  Bxb1  , leading to almost the same position. Trading the bishop is surprisingly effective, as we will see.   Looking at this concept hints at why  6.Nc3  h6  7.Qb3  Qb6  8.c5  is a different story,  as we can't capture b1 anymore. In this case, we suggest avoiding the queen trade altogether and opting  for  8...Qc7  , which is more combative. Let's have a look at the details now. }
6. Nc3 { This seems to be the most challenging move order. } 6... h6
{ As discussed earlier: after Nc3, we want to play ...h6 to create a retreat square. }
7. Qb3
{ White can also play  7.O-O  Be7  , which we cover via @@StartFEN@@rn1qkb1r/pp3ppp/2p1pn2/3p1b2/2PP4/5NP1/PP2PPBP/RNBQK2R w KQkq - 0 6@@EndFEN@@  6.O-O  h6  7.Nc3  Be7  - please see this move order for details. }
7... Qb6 8. c5 Qc7
{ We suggest this combative reply, keeping the queens on the board. There is nothing wrong with  8...Qxb3  9.axb3  , but there is a practical problem. After  9...a6  10.b4  Be7  11.b5  cxb5  12.Nxb5  O-O  13.Nc7  Ra7  14.Nb5  White can force a draw if desired. The game doesn't have to end  @@StartBracket@@  11.h3  is more interesting@@EndBracket@@, but it's an annoying prospect.  There are other ways for Black, like @@StartFEN@@rn2kb1r/pp3pp1/2p1pn1p/2Pp1b2/3P4/1PN2NP1/1P2PPBP/R1B1K2R b KQkq - 0 9@@EndFEN@@  9...Na6  , but  10.Ra4  leads to complications that are tough to assess. These lines have been discussed in Christof's course Keep it Simple: 1.d4, showing that the endgame offers ideas for both sides. In the course, the move @@StartFEN@@rn2kb1r/pp3pp1/1qp1pn1p/2Pp1b2/3P4/1QN2NP1/PP2PPBP/R1B1K2R b KQkq - 0 8@@EndFEN@@  8...Qc7  is also analyzed, but here we'll have a fresh look at it from Black's perspective. }
9. Bf4 Qc8
{ We have lost time with our queen, but we can also point to the fact that c4-c5 and Qb3 are not helping White much. In the long run, we want to play ...b6, attacking our opponent's pawn chain. }
10. Nd2
{ White's main idea is playing the knight to d2 and preparing the e2-e4 advance. The knight move can be played right away or White could go for the more popular kingside castling. In both cases, we'll face the move e2-e4 soon and need to decide if we want to capture on e4 or just retreat our bishop.   It turns out that taking on e4 does not work well against  10.Nd2  , while after  10.O-O  there are possible move orders that allow the capture. We suggest retreating in both cases, as it works reliably and will likely lead to the same positions after all.  A sample line to show such a transposition is  10.O-O  Be7  11.Nd2  O-O  12.e4  Bh7  , which may also arise via @@StartFEN@@rnq1kb1r/pp3pp1/2p1pn1p/2Pp1b2/3P1B2/1QN2NP1/PP2PPBP/R3K2R w KQkq - 3 10@@EndFEN@@  10.Nd2  Be7  11.e4  Bh7  12.O-O  O-O  . Let's return to @@StartFEN@@rnq1kb1r/pp3pp1/2p1pn1p/2Pp1b2/3P1B2/1QN2NP1/PP2PPBP/R3K2R w KQkq - 3 10@@EndFEN@@  10.Nd2  now.  This idea was suggested by one of your authors, Christof Sielecki, in Keep it Simple: 1.d4. Black needs to be careful now − what's the most precise move? }
10... Be7
{ Black should play this move or  10...Bh7  , intending to answer  11.e4  with  11...Be7  , which transposes to the line that we are about to examine.   We need to avoid the natural move  10...Nbd7?!  , which leads to some problems for Black after  11.e4  , when Black has to capture. After  11...dxe4  12.Bxe4  Nxe4  13.Ndxe4  Be7  14.Nd6+  Black is under heavy pressure, as played in an online Blitz game between Christof and Alina Kashlinskaya in 2020. }
11. e4 { Or  11.O-O  O-O  12.e4  Bh7  , which leads to the same positions. }
11... Bh7 12. O-O
{ Instead,  12.e5?  is a big strategic mistake as we still have the ideal retreat square on d7. After  12...Nfd7  , we are ready to  play ...b6 soon, when White's overextended structure crumbles. }
12... O-O 13. Rfe1
{ White keeps the tension and has an 'x-ray' look at the e7-bishop. Taking twice on d5 is threatened now, for example,   13...Nbd7??  14.exd5  cxd5  15.Nxd5  Nxd5  16.Bxd5  and White wins. }
13... Rd8
{ The best square for the rook, covering d5 to prevent the mentioned tactic. We are now ready to attack the white pawn chain with ...b6. }
14. Rad1
{ After  14.exd5  cxd5  , we see an additional benefit of delaying  the move ...Nbd7. Our knight may jump to c6 next, putting pressure on the weak d4-pawn. }
14... b6
{ Much better than  14...dxe4?  15.Ndxe4  Nxe4  16.Nxe4  Bxe4  17.Bxe4  Nd7  18.Bb1  Nf6  19.Qc2  , when White has serious pressure. But what happens if White grabs the b-pawn now? }
15. cxb6 axb6 16. Qxb6 g5
{ The final key move to remember. Black has a great game now, as the following lines show.  A@@EndBracket@@  17.Be3  Na6  18.Qb3  Rb8  19.Qc2  Nb4  20.Qb1  c5  − a remarkable sequence, seeing the white queen retreating all the way. Black is more or less winning in the final position.   B@@EndBracket@@  17.Qc7  Nbd7  18.Qxc8  Rdxc8  19.Be3  Rcb8  gives Black great play for the pawn. White likely has to return it soon, when Black is better. }
*

