[Black "2.Nf3 Bf5 3.c4 e6 4.g3 #5"]
[Result "*"]

1. d4 d5 2. Nf3
{ Developing the knight is a popular move for White. It is a flexible choice. White may still play c2-c4 on the next move, entering a Queen's Gambit, or opt for a slower development. As already discussed, we answer  2.Nf3  with  2...Bf5  , which leads to less explored and interesting positions. }
2... Bf5
{ After  2...Bf5  , the only critical move must be  3.c4  , which we will focus on. White's calmer alternatives on move three,  3.g3  and  3.e3  are rather harmless or will transpose to lines that we examine via different move orders. An important option for White is  3.Bf4  , but  3...e6  immediately leads to a position that is covered in the chapter on the London System. }
3. c4
{ White's most principled and best move. It puts pressure on d5 and prepares the move Qb3 in many situations, looking at the tender b7-pawn. }
3... e6
{ We always play  3...e6  first in this line, preparing the kingside development. The move  3...c6?  is worse, as  4.cxd5  cxd5  5.Qb3  is awkward for Black. Black's resources are much better after the better choice, @@StartFEN@@rn1qkbnr/ppp1pppp/8/3p1b2/2PP4/5N2/PP2PPPP/RNBQKB1R b KQkq - 0 3@@EndFEN@@  3...e6  . In some cases, we might be able  to play ...c7-c5, fighting for the center with the c-pawn. Another common scenario is answering Qb3 with ...Nb8-c6, which leads to sharp play. Let's have a look at White's options after  3...e6  .  A@@EndBracket@@ White's main move is  4.Nc3  , when we suggest  4...Nf6!  This move is much better than the old-fashioned  4...c6?!  when Black's position is too passive. We cover this main line in a dedicated chapter.   B@@EndBracket@@ A critical option for White is  4.Qb3  , which immediately puts pressure  on b7. We have the strong  reply  4...Nc6!  , which leads to sharp play.   C@@EndBracket@@ White can play  4.e3  or  4.g3  , preparing the development of the f1-bishop.   D@@EndBracket@@ The exchange  4.cxd5  exd5  , leading to a Carlsbad pawn structure. Black is fine, but we need to examine some concrete lines,  as a quick Qb3 requires a precise response. }
4. g3
{ White opts for the kingside fianchetto. A good and reliable setup for Black against it involves the moves ...Nf6 and ...c6, building the solid triangle of pawns in the center. An important consideration for Black is the move order. What to play first?   This is even more relevant because of White's options to play a g3-based setup one move earlier, after @@StartFEN@@rnbqkbnr/pppppppp/8/8/8/8/PPPPPPPP/RNBQKBNR w KQkq - 0 1@@EndFEN@@  1.d4  d5  2.Nf3  Bf5  3.g3  and one move later, when @@StartFEN@@rnbqkbnr/pppppppp/8/8/8/8/PPPPPPPP/RNBQKBNR w KQkq - 0 1@@EndFEN@@  1.d4  d5  2.Nf3  Bf5  3.c4  e6  4.Nc3  Nf6  5.g3  is an option for White.   We want to play a consistent move order that works in all cases. Here's the move order guideline:   A@@EndBracket@@ If ...e6 is not yet played, play this first @@StartBracket@@applies only to @@StartFEN@@rnbqkbnr/pppppppp/8/8/8/8/PPPPPPPP/RNBQKBNR w KQkq - 0 1@@EndFEN@@  1.d4  d5  2.Nf3  Bf5  3.g3  , when  3...e6  is the first move to play@@EndBracket@@.  B@@EndBracket@@ We play ...Nf6 next.  C@@EndBracket@@  If White plays a combination of g3, c4, and Nc3, we need to worry about the idea Nh4 and should play the move ...h6. Without Nc3 on the board, Nh4 can always be answered with ...Be4.   D@@EndBracket@@ If we have played ...e6 and ...Nf6 already, the next move should be ...c6, unless rule C applies. There are other ways to handle the move orders, but this approach works well and looks easiest to remember. }
4... Nf6
{ As per rule B. The moves  4...c6  or  4...h6  are not a mistake but may lead to slightly different versions of lines that we have in our repertoire. We'll see that the pawn moves are not always necessary, and sometimes we have better options.  Examples are playing ...h7-h5 in some lines or being able to answer Qb3 with ...Nc6.   After  4...Nf6  , we need to check some possible replies. A harmless option is  5.Nh4?!  , which we answer with  5...Be4  . More relevant are @@StartFEN@@rn1qkb1r/ppp2ppp/4pn2/3p1b2/2PP4/5NP1/PP2PP1P/RNBQKB1R w KQkq - 1 5@@EndFEN@@  5.Qb3  ,  5.Nc3  and the most popular move  5.Bg2  . }
5. Bg2 { White's most natural and popular move. } 5... c6
{ As per rule D. We play ...c6, after ...Nf6 and ...e6, is on the board, and White has not played Nc3.   Now, after  5...c6  , White has some options.  A common plan for White is playing Qb3 at some point. That could be played  right away or after  6.Nc3  h6  or @@StartFEN@@rn1qkb1r/pp3ppp/2p1pn2/3p1b2/2PP4/5NP1/PP2PPBP/RNBQK2R w KQkq - 0 6@@EndFEN@@  6.O-O  h6  has been inserted.   There are some subtle differences between these versions. The relatively most promising version for White seems to be  6.Nc3  h6  7.Qb3  . So what's the difference? Against @@StartFEN@@rn1qkb1r/pp3ppp/2p1pn2/3p1b2/2PP4/5NP1/PP2PPBP/RNBQK2R w KQkq - 0 6@@EndFEN@@  6.Qb3  Qb6  7.c5  Qxb3  8.axb3  we have the option to play  8...Bxb1  , which is a simple and good way to play.   We can employ the same plan after  6.O-O  h6  7.Qb3  Qb6  8.c5  Qxb3  9.axb3  Bxb1  , leading to almost the same position. Trading the bishop is surprisingly effective, as we will see.   Looking at this concept hints at why  6.Nc3  h6  7.Qb3  Qb6  8.c5  is a different story,  as we can't capture b1 anymore. In this case, we suggest avoiding the queen trade altogether and opting  for  8...Qc7  , which is more combative. Let's have a look at the details now. }
6. O-O { White castles kingside, which is by far the most popular move. } 6...
h6
{ In the notes to 4.g3, we discussed move order rules for Black. Now we have gotten to the point where there is some flexibility. We don't need to play  6...h6  here, but it looks like the most flexible move. In many cases,  any earlier Nc3 would have prompted ...h6, anyway. After 6...h6, White usually chooses between 3 plans:  Playing for e2-e4 by going Nc3 and Nd2.  A quiet development with b3. Still going for the Qb3 plan that we have discussed before.  
We'll look at these lines, but they should just transpose. Having already castled rather reduces White's options, if anything. }
7. Qb3 { As mentioned, this move has relatively little independent value. }
7... Qb6 8. c5
{ White could also wait with  8.Nc3  , but  8...Be7  transposes to @@StartFEN@@rn1qkb1r/pp3pp1/2p1pn1p/3p1b2/2PP4/5NP1/PP2PPBP/RNBQ1RK1 w kq - 0 7@@EndFEN@@  7.Nc3  Be7  8.Qb3  Qb6  . }
8... Qxb3
{ We play the same plan after @@StartFEN@@rn1qkb1r/pp3ppp/2p1pn2/3p1b2/2PP4/5NP1/PP2PPBP/RNBQK2R w KQkq - 0 6@@EndFEN@@  6.Qb3  Qb6  7.c5  Qxb3  8.axb3  Bxb1  , it's a very similar case here. However, we also can go @@StartFEN@@rn2kb1r/pp3pp1/1qp1pn1p/2Pp1b2/3P4/1Q3NP1/PP2PPBP/RNB2RK1 b kq - 0 8@@EndFEN@@  8...Qc7  , as a transposition to @@StartFEN@@rn1qkb1r/pp3ppp/2p1pn2/3p1b2/2PP4/5NP1/PP2PPBP/RNBQK2R w KQkq - 0 6@@EndFEN@@  6.Nc3  h6  7.Qb3  Qb6  8.c5  Qc7  is very likely. It's always good to have choices. }
9. axb3 Bxb1
{ The same approach as in the similar position without castling and ...h6 being played. Here Black has an additional option in  9...Nbd7  10.Nc3  a6  11.b4  Rc8  or  11...Rd8  .  Black is fast enough to get in ...a6 and ...Nbd7, which stops b4-b5. This is  not as easily done after @@StartFEN@@rn1qkb1r/pp3ppp/2p1pn2/3p1b2/2PP4/5NP1/PP2PPBP/RNBQK2R w KQkq - 0 6@@EndFEN@@  6.Nc3  h6  7.Qb3  Qb6  8.c5  , as discussed in the notes to  8...Qc7  . }
10. Rxb1 a6
{ This position is very similar to @@StartFEN@@rn1qkb1r/pp3ppp/2p1pn2/3p1b2/2PP4/5NP1/PP2PPBP/RNBQK2R w KQkq - 0 6@@EndFEN@@  6.Qb3  Qb6  7.c5  Qxb3  8.axb3  Bxb1  9.Rxb1  a6  . The only difference is the addition of the  moves O-O and ...h6. Black can try to make us of ...h6 by going for a ...g5!?-based setup or play the more conventional ...g6. Our position is very solid and offers long term chances related to the break ...e5. }
