{ In the notes to 4.g3, we discussed move order rules for Black. Now we have gotten to the point where there is some flexibility. We don't need to play  6...h6  here, but it looks like the most flexible move. In many cases,  any earlier Nc3 would have prompted ...h6, anyway. After 6...h6, White usually chooses between 3 plans:  Playing for e2-e4 by going Nc3 and Nd2.  A quiet development with b3. Still going for the Qb3 plan that we have discussed before.  
We'll look at these lines, but they should just transpose. Having already castled rather reduces White's options, if anything. }
7. b3
{ A quiet move, covering the c-pawn and preparing the queenside fianchetto. }
7... Be7
{ In other lines, we start with ...Be7 as well. Here it is not move-order critical, though. White's slow setup gives Black some flexibility: you might also start with  7...Nbd7  here, followed  by ...Be7 and ...O-O. We'll eventually play all three moves to complete development. }
8. Bb2 O-O
{ Or  8...Nbd7  first, which will lead to the same positions. Now White has a choice between placing the  knight on c3 or d2.  The move  9.Nc3  is more active and better, but the positions after  9.Nbd2  are worth looking at, too. They frequently arise from other move orders, in particular, @@StartFEN@@rnbqkbnr/pppppppp/8/8/8/8/PPPPPPPP/RNBQKBNR w KQkq - 0 1@@EndFEN@@  1.d4  d5  2.Nf3  Bf5  3.g3  , when White often starts  with b3, Bb2, Nbd2 and only then plays the c-pawn. }
9. Nbd2
{ This setup is rather passive. It is unclear how White intends to make any progress, as it is difficult to open the position. One idea might be Ne5, but we'll see that it rather helps our cause. }
9... Nbd7 { Starting with  9...a5  is also perfectly fine. } 10. Ne5
{ This is White's most popular move and the only active-looking plan. It's tough to suggest anything else for White, as the pawn structure can't be changed that easily or open the position. Black should play for ...a5-a4, creating weaknesses on the queenside. }
10... a5
{ A standard plan when White plays Nbd2. This is less of an idea after @@StartFEN@@rn1q1rk1/pp2bpp1/2p1pn1p/3p1b2/2PP4/1P3NP1/PB2PPBP/RN1Q1RK1 w - - 3 9@@EndFEN@@  9.Nc3  when White controls  the a4-square. }
11. a3
{ This is White's usual reply, but it's not a good move. White should play a waiting move like  11.Re1  , but  11...a4  gives Black good play on the queenside. }
11... Nxe5 12. dxe5 Nd7
{ We now see a problem with the move a3. White has weakened the b3-pawn, and we are ready to apply some pressure with ideas like ...Nc5 and ...Qb6. }
13. e4 dxe4 14. Nxe4
{ White has managed to open the position, but we have a strong reply now. }
14... Nc5 15. Qe2
{ The only playable move. After  15.Nxc5  Bxc5  White's position is even worse than you might think at first.  The b3-pawn is incredibly weak and Black's bishops are far superior to their white counterparts, who stare at the pawns on e5 and c6. }
15... Qd3
{ This is a strong continuation. The move to avoid is  15...Nxb3?  when  16.Rad1  gives White good play for the pawn. }
16. Qxd3 Nxd3
{ Black has the better chances here, due to White's multiple pawn and square weaknesses. }
