{ We suggest starting with this move. It's the most reliable to transpose to lines discussed earlier. Playing  7...Nbd7  would not be a mistake but after  8.Qb3  Qb6  9.c5  the move  9...Qc7  is somewhat imprecise.  Being committed to ...Nbd7 is not ideal in the ...Qc7 setup, as discussed in the notes  to @@StartFEN@@rn1qkb1r/pp3ppp/2p1pn2/3p1b2/2PP4/5NP1/PP2PPBP/RNBQK2R w KQkq - 0 6@@EndFEN@@  6.Nc3  h6  7.Qb3  Qb6  8.c5  Qc7  9.Bf4  Qc8  10.Nd2  , when  10...Nbd7?!  is imprecise.  However, @@StartFEN@@r2qkb1r/pp1n1pp1/2p1pn1p/3p1b2/2PP4/1QN2NP1/PP2PPBP/R1B2RK1 b kq - 3 8@@EndFEN@@  8...Qxb3  9.axb3  a6  10.b4  Rd8  is a fine version of the endgame, just not what we usually go for. }
8. Nd2
{ White is heading for the pawn push e2-e4. There are two popular alternatives, but they just transpose elsewhere.  A@@EndBracket@@  8.b3  O-O  9.Bb2  Nbd7  is examined via @@StartFEN@@rn1qkb1r/pp3pp1/2p1pn1p/3p1b2/2PP4/5NP1/PP2PPBP/RNBQ1RK1 w kq - 0 7@@EndFEN@@  7.b3  Be7  8.Bb2  O-O  9.Nc3  Nbd7  .   B@@EndBracket@@  8.Qb3  Qb6  9.c5  Qc7  10.Bf4  Qc8  is a transposition to @@StartFEN@@rn1qkb1r/pp3ppp/2p1pn2/3p1b2/2PP4/5NP1/PP2PPBP/RNBQK2R w KQkq - 0 6@@EndFEN@@  6.Nc3  h6  7.Qb3  Qb6  8.c5  Qc7  9.Bf4  Qc8  10.O-O  Be7  . }
