{ Taking on e4 first is also possible, but completing the development of our minor pieces certainly makes sense. }
11. Be3
{ This looks best. White also frequently tries  11.Bf4  , when  11...Nxe4  12.Nxe4  Nf6  13.Nc3  Qb6  already looks a bit better for Black. White's pawns are vulnerable and promising targets for us. }
11... Nxe4 12. Nxe4 Nf6 13. Nc3
{ More ambitious than  13.Nxf6+  Bxf6  , which poses no problems at all. An interesting idea suggested by Stockfish is  14.Qd2  Re8  ,  intending ...Re7-d7 to increase the pressure on d4. }
13... Qb6
{ Black has a wide choice of good moves at this point. We suggest  13...Qb6  , but there is nothing wrong with  13...Qa5  ,  13...Rc8  , and some others. The queen move is a direct way of playing as we attack the  vulnerable b2-pawn. }
14. Qe2
{ This is probably best. After  14.Qb3?!  the move  14...Ng4  is even more effective than after @@StartFEN@@r4rk1/pp2bpp1/1qp1pn1p/5b2/2PP4/2N1B1P1/PP3PBP/R2Q1RK1 w - - 3 14@@EndFEN@@  14.Qe2  Ng4  , which we are about to examine. }
14... Ng4
{ An excellent way to unbalance the position. We attack the bishop, and it has no good way to retreat. If we had played @@StartFEN@@r2q1rk1/pp2bpp1/2p1pn1p/5b2/2PP4/2N1B1P1/PP3PBP/R2Q1RK1 b - - 2 13@@EndFEN@@  13...Ng4  , White still could have played  14.Bf4  .   Now, this is impossible, as the d4-pawn would just be hanging. After  14...Ng4  , White needs to accept that we'll capture the bishop.  15.Rad1  Nxe3  16.fxe3  Rad8  and Black is in good shape.  We can play for ...c5 or ...e5 later, attacking White's center.   Stockfish suggests @@StartFEN@@r4rk1/pp2bpp1/1qp1p2p/5b2/2PP2n1/2N1B1P1/PP2QPBP/R4RK1 w - - 5 15@@EndFEN@@  15.c5  instead, but after  15...Qb4  Black's chances look no worse due to the multiple weaknesses that White has created. We also managed to unbalance the position, which is not so easy to do, given White's solid setup. }
