{ After  5.Nc3  we have two good options. You can play  5...Nf6  , transposing to @@StartFEN@@rn1qkbnr/ppp2ppp/4p3/3p1b2/2PP4/5N2/PP2PPPP/RNBQKB1R w KQkq - 0 4@@EndFEN@@  4.Nc3  Nf6  5.cxd5  exd5  , but also @@StartFEN@@rn1qkbnr/ppp2ppp/8/3p1b2/3P4/2N2N2/PP2PPPP/R1BQKB1R b KQkq - 1 5@@EndFEN@@  5...c6  , which is usually reached via @@StartFEN@@rnbqkbnr/pppppppp/8/8/8/8/PPPPPPPP/RNBQKBNR w KQkq - 0 1@@EndFEN@@  1.d4  d5  2.c4  e6  3.cxd5  exd5  4.Nc3  c6  5.Nf3  Bf5  . We recommend  5...Bd6  @@StartBracket@@see the chapter on early Triangle deviations@@EndBracket@@ in this particular move order, but  5...Bf5  is just as good and easy to play.   You have no problems if you can develop your c8-bishop in the Carlsbad.  Your choice after @@StartFEN@@rn1qkbnr/ppp2ppp/8/3p1b2/3P4/5N2/PP2PPPP/RNBQKB1R w KQkq - 0 5@@EndFEN@@  5.Nc3  is mostly a matter of taste.  5...c6  is the 'cleaner' move, but  5...Nf6  might encourage White  to be more ambitious @@StartBracket@@early Qb3 ideas@@EndBracket@@ and lead to more exciting positions. }
5... Nc6
{ The typical reply to Qb3 in this chapter. We don't need to cover b7 and defend actively. Now White's most popular move is  6.Nc3  , when  6...Nf6  transposes to the line @@StartFEN@@rn1qkbnr/ppp2ppp/4p3/3p1b2/2PP4/5N2/PP2PPPP/RNBQKB1R w KQkq - 0 4@@EndFEN@@  4.Nc3  Nf6  5.cxd5  exd5  6.Qb3  Nc6  . We need to check some other options, though.  White also frequently covers b4 with  @@StartFEN@@r2qkbnr/ppp2ppp/2n5/3p1b2/3P4/1Q3N2/PP2PPPP/RNB1KB1R w KQkq - 2 6@@EndFEN@@  6.Bd2  or  6.a3  , while  6.Qxb7?  fails, but requires a precise response. }
6. Bd2
{ White's most frequently played move, besides the main continuation  6.Nc3  . }
6... Nf6
{ This looks even better than the simpler  6...Rb8  , when we transpose to @@StartFEN@@rn1qkbnr/ppp2ppp/4p3/3p1b2/2PP4/5N2/PP2PPPP/RNBQKB1R w KQkq - 0 4@@EndFEN@@  4.Qb3  Nc6  5.Bd2  Rb8  6.cxd5  exd5  . }
7. Qxb7
{ We need to check this move, of course.  7.Nc3  can be met with a range of moves. We suggest  7...Be7  , as  8.Qxb7?  Nb4  is awkward for White. }
7... Nb4 8. Bxb4
{ After  8.Na3  Rb8  9.Qxa7  Ra8  10.Qb7  Bd6  Black has a winning attack. This is rather similar to @@StartFEN@@r2qkbnr/ppp2ppp/2n5/3p1b2/3P4/1Q3N2/PP2PPPP/RNB1KB1R w KQkq - 2 6@@EndFEN@@  6.Qxb7  Nb4  7.Na3  Rb8  8.Qxa7  Ra8  9.Qb7  Bd6  , which shares the same tactical patterns. }
8... Rb8 9. Qc6+ Bd7 10. Qc1 Bxb4+ 11. Nc3 Ne4
{ Or  11...c5  , which will likely lead to the same positions. } 12. e3 c5
{ We have excellent compensation for the pawn and the much easier game. Moves like ...Qa5, ...O-O suggest themselves. }
