[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "17. 2.Nf3 Bf5 Sidelines"]
[Black "2.Nf3 Bf5 3.c4 e6 4.Qb3 #1"]
[Result "*"]

1. d4 d5 2. Nf3
{ Developing the knight is a popular move for White. It is a flexible choice. White may still play c2-c4 on the next move, entering a Queen's Gambit, or opt for a slower development. As already discussed, we answer  2.Nf3  with  2...Bf5  , which leads to less explored and interesting positions. }
2... Bf5
{ After  2...Bf5  , the only critical move must be  3.c4  , which we will focus on. White's calmer alternatives on move three,  3.g3  and  3.e3  are rather harmless or will transpose to lines that we examine via different move orders. An important option for White is  3.Bf4  , but  3...e6  immediately leads to a position that is covered in the chapter on the London System. }
3. c4
{ White's most principled and best move. It puts pressure on d5 and prepares the move Qb3 in many situations, looking at the tender b7-pawn. }
3... e6
{ We always play  3...e6  first in this line, preparing the kingside development. The move  3...c6?  is worse, as  4.cxd5  cxd5  5.Qb3  is awkward for Black. Black's resources are much better after the better choice, @@StartFEN@@rn1qkbnr/ppp1pppp/8/3p1b2/2PP4/5N2/PP2PPPP/RNBQKB1R b KQkq - 0 3@@EndFEN@@  3...e6  . In some cases, we might be able  to play ...c7-c5, fighting for the center with the c-pawn. Another common scenario is answering Qb3 with ...Nb8-c6, which leads to sharp play. Let's have a look at White's options after  3...e6  .  A@@EndBracket@@ White's main move is  4.Nc3  , when we suggest  4...Nf6!  This move is much better than the old-fashioned  4...c6?!  when Black's position is too passive. We cover this main line in a dedicated chapter.   B@@EndBracket@@ A critical option for White is  4.Qb3  , which immediately puts pressure  on b7. We have the strong  reply  4...Nc6!  , which leads to sharp play.   C@@EndBracket@@ White can play  4.e3  or  4.g3  , preparing the development of the f1-bishop.   D@@EndBracket@@ The exchange  4.cxd5  exd5  , leading to a Carlsbad pawn structure. Black is fine, but we need to examine some concrete lines,  as a quick Qb3 requires a precise response. }
4. Qb3
{ The queen sortie is a frequent guest in this chapter. Whenever Black plays ...Bf5, the pawn on b7 is undefended. Qb3 attacks the b-pawn and puts pressure on d5, making it a rather dangerous move. The real split comes after our forced reply, 4...Nc6. }
4... Nc6
{ Active defense is the only way to handle the position. The move  4...b6??  not only looks terrible but gets dispatched quickly with sequences like  5.Nc3  c6  6.cxd5  cxd5  7.e4  , and it's over. After @@StartFEN@@rn1qkbnr/ppp2ppp/4p3/3p1b2/2PP4/1Q3N2/PP2PPPP/RNB1KB1R b KQkq - 1 4@@EndFEN@@  4...Nc6  , White has a wide choice.  A@@EndBracket@@  5.Bd2  is the most popular move.  White covers the b4-square and stops any ...Nb4 ideas. We respond with  5...Rb8  , covering the b-pawn.   B@@EndBracket@@  5.a3  follows a similar idea but is less popular. This is undeserved, as Black can easily go wrong against it. We recommend  5...a6!  and explain in the notes why it is much better than the more natural  5...Rb8  .   C@@EndBracket@@  5.c5  gives Black some good options. We suggest the quirky  5...Nge7  , which invites fun complications.   D@@EndBracket@@  5.Qxb7  is unpopular because Black has a draw in hand.   E@@EndBracket@@  5.cxd5  is met by  5...Qxd5!  when Black has a good game. }
5. Qxb7
{ A rather unpopular move at this point. Black has a draw in hand, which makes it unattractive for White. }
5... Nb4 6. Na3 Rb8
{ This move forces a draw. It's possible to play differently, but White can force a draw in these lines, too. An option is  6...Nf6  , but  7.c5  pulls the plug on the game when you need to play  7...Rb8  8.Qxa7  Ra8  9.Qb7  Rb8  with a draw. }
7. Qxa7 Ra8
{ Here  7...dxc4  could be tried to avoid the draw, but  8.Bf4  Nd5  9.Qa4+  Qd7  10.Qa7  is a different way to repeat. }
8. Qb7 Rb8
{ And it's a draw. In some tournament situations, it's important to consider that Black can't avoid a draw after 5.Qxb7. If you need to win the game while your opponents want a draw, it's advisable to play differently earlier. }
*

