5. cxd5 { The capture is harmless for Black at this particular moment. } 5...
Qxd5
{ It's possible to play  5...exd5  , which transposes to a line that is part of our repertoire via @@StartFEN@@rn1qkbnr/ppp2ppp/4p3/3p1b2/2PP4/5N2/PP2PPPP/RNBQKB1R w KQkq - 0 4@@EndFEN@@  4.cxd5  exd5  5.Qb3  Nc6  . Taking with the queen, however, is stronger. }
6. Qxd5
{ The most likely move to happen. Taking on b7 is terrible, as  6.Qxb7  Nxd4  7.Qxd5  Nc2+  shows. After the better @@StartFEN@@r3kbnr/ppp2ppp/2n1p3/3q1b2/3P4/1Q3N2/PP2PPPP/RNB1KB1R w KQkq - 0 6@@EndFEN@@  6.Qa4  , we play  6...Bxb1  7.Rxb1  Bb4+  , when White has nothing better than  8.Bd2  Bxd2+  9.Kxd2  O-O-O  , which looks nice for Black. }
6... exd5 7. a3 { White needs to stop ...Nb4. } 7... Bd6 8. Nc3 Nf6 9. Nb5
{ This looks like the most interesting move to check. After  9.Bg5  , we have  9...Ne4  , which is already a bit better for Black. }
9... Ne4
{ Stockfish suggests the odd move  9...h5  here, intending to answer  10.h4  with  10...Ne4  . Inserting the h-pawn moves might benefit Black, as we managed to weaken the light squares in White's camp a bit more.  The interesting point is that @@StartFEN@@r3k2r/ppp2pp1/2nb1n2/1N1p1b1p/3P4/P4N2/1P2PPPP/R1B1KB1R w KQkq - 0 10@@EndFEN@@  10.Nxd6+  cxd6  11.Bf4  can be answered with  11...Rc8  , as  12.Bxd6  Na5  gives Black good play.  We felt that 9...h5 is tough to remember, so 9...Ne4 is our main choice. }
10. Nxd6+ Nxd6 11. Bf4 Nc4
{ That's the idea. We have given up the bishop but obtained good play on the light squares. Ideally, we'd like to play ...Kd7 and ...f6 next. }
