{ We need to compare this position to @@StartFEN@@rn1qkbnr/ppp2ppp/4p3/3p1b2/2PP4/5N2/PP2PPPP/RNBQKB1R w KQkq - 0 4@@EndFEN@@  4.Nc3  Nf6  5.cxd5  exd5  6.Qb3  Nc6  7.Bg5  , which is very similar. We have the extra  move ...Rb8, as it turns out. This is very relevant, as we will see.  7...Na5  8.Qa4+  c6  9.Bxf6  gxf6  , is similar but does not include  the move ...Rb8, which is a substantial difference. }
8... Na5 9. Qa4+ c6 10. Bxf6
{ It makes sense for White to include this move. We have to take with the pawn, after all. }
10... gxf6
{ With ...Rb8 on the board, we can't castle queenside − on the other hand, you could consider a rapid queenside offensive now. Let's have a look. }
11. e3 b5 12. Qd1 Nc4 13. Qc1 a5
{ Our idea is playing ...a4 and ...Qa5, increasing the pressure on the queenside. This initiative easily compensates for the damaged pawn structure and leads to interesting play. }
