5. a3
{ A rare move, but it is surprisingly dangerous. White stops ...Nb4 and now threatens Qxb7 'for real'. Now Black needs to be precise, as the normal-looking move  5...Rb8  is a mistake. Let's have a look at what's best. }
5... a6
{ Black has two good moves, this one and  5...Na5  . The move to avoid is  5...Rb8?!  when  6.cxd5  exd5  7.Nc3  Nf6  8.Bg5  Na5  9.Qa2!  c6  10.b4  Nc4  11.e4!  is the crushing point of White's play. After  6.cxd5  Qxd5  7.Qxd5  exd5  8.Bf4  Bd6  9.Bxd6  cxd6  10.Nc3  Nf6  Black is suffering due to the weakened pawn structure.   It's possible to play  5...Na5  , though. After  6.Qa4+  c6  7.c5  b5  8.Qd1  Black has some options, like  8...g6  . In the end, we preferred @@StartFEN@@r2qkbnr/ppp2ppp/2n1p3/3p1b2/2PP4/PQ3N2/1P2PPPP/RNB1KB1R b KQkq - 0 5@@EndFEN@@  5...a6  as it looks a bit committal to place the knight on the edge of the board this early. After  5...a6  , White can't play  6.Qxb7??  due to  6...Na5  , trapping the queen. We'll examine @@StartFEN@@r2qkbnr/1pp2ppp/p1n1p3/3p1b2/2PP4/PQ3N2/1P2PPPP/RNB1KB1R w KQkq - 0 6@@EndFEN@@  6.cxd5  and  6.e3  now. }
6. cxd5 { How to recapture now? } 6... Qxd5
{ Better than  6...exd5  7.Nc3  Nf6  8.Bg5  when the pressure  on d5 is too annoying. }
7. Qxd5 exd5 8. Bf4 Na5
{ Here we see a key difference to @@StartFEN@@r2qkbnr/ppp2ppp/2n1p3/3p1b2/2PP4/PQ3N2/1P2PPPP/RNB1KB1R b KQkq - 0 5@@EndFEN@@  5...Rb8?!  6.cxd5  Qxd5  7.Qxd5  exd5  8.Bf4  , when the knight jump is not possible. }
9. Nbd2
{ White has to develop the knight to the passive d2-square, which is a huge accomplishment for Black. }
9... Bd6
{ Let's discuss the doubled pawns once they are on the board − see you on move eleven! }
10. Bxd6 cxd6
{ Black is fine in this position. The doubled pawns don't matter at all due to the passive knight on d2. The d6-pawn is rarely a concern in such a structure, but the d5-pawn might be one. Here White has no pressure on it, as the knight is not on c3.   This is a key difference to the position after @@StartFEN@@r2qkbnr/ppp2ppp/2n1p3/3p1b2/2PP4/PQ3N2/1P2PPPP/RNB1KB1R b KQkq - 0 5@@EndFEN@@  5...Rb8?!  6.cxd5  Qxd5  7.Qxd5  exd5  8.Bf4  Bd6  9.Bxd6  cxd6  10.Nc3  , when White manages to pressurize the pawn. }
11. e3 b5
{ A crucial part of our strategy is the control of c4. If anyone, Black has an easier play here. Note how important the d6-pawn is, covering the squares e5 and c5. }
