5. c5 { White advances the pawn and prevents ...Nb4 this way. } 5... Nge7
{ Black almost always goes for  5...Rb8  in this position.  This move looks fine, but we'd like to suggest this almost unexplored possibility. We ignore the threat and sacrifice the b-pawn. It's important to note that moves other than 6.Qxb7 look lame, as we'll play ...b6 otherwise.   It's impossible to play  5...b6??  due to  6.e4!  Bxe4  7.Bb5  Nge7  8.Ne5  , which is deadly.  By covering the c6-knight, we get the ...b6 idea on the map. }
6. Bf4
{ A natural move, but not critical. We now can play the desired ...b6 move. A similar scenario would occur after  6.Nc3  b6  or @@StartFEN@@r2qkb1r/ppp1nppp/2n1p3/2Pp1b2/3P4/1Q3N2/PP2PPPP/RNB1KB1R w KQkq - 1 6@@EndFEN@@  6.e3  b6  .  In the latter case, it's important to note that  7.cxb6  axb6  8.Bb5  has to be answered with  8...f6  ,  covering the e5-square. It looks a bit odd, but it can be the first move of a later kingside initiative @@StartBracket@@...Kf7, ...g5, ...h5@@EndBracket@@. }
6... b6 7. cxb6 axb6
{ It's also fine to play  7...cxb6  here.  A later ...a6, ...b5 idea works well for Black. }
8. e3 Na5 9. Qc3 c6
{ We have reached an unconventional position. Black intends to advance further with ...b5 and possibly ...b4. But what about 10.b4 now? }
10. b4 Nc4 11. Bxc4
{ We need to check the greedy move, of course. Better is something like  11.a4  b5  , but this is hardly critical for Black. }
11... dxc4 12. Qxc4 Qd5 13. Nbd2 Qxc4 14. Nxc4 Nd5
{ Black has a great position, for example, after  15.Bd6  b5  16.Bxf8  Kxf8  17.Nd6  Bg6  18.a3  Ke7  19.Nb7  Nxb4  , when Black has regained the pawn. }
