1. d4 d5 2. Nf3
{ Developing the knight is a popular move for White. It is a flexible choice. White may still play c2-c4 on the next move, entering a Queen's Gambit, or opt for a slower development. As already discussed, we answer  2.Nf3  with  2...Bf5  , which leads to less explored and interesting positions. }
2... Bf5
{ In this chapter, we'll examine the main line of the 2.Nf3 Bf5 variation. After  3.c4  e6  , White plays the natural move  4.Nc3  most of the time, which is the topic of the current chapter. White has many alternatives, of course. These are examined in the dedicated  chapter on 2.Nf3 Bf5 Sidelines. }
3. c4
{ White's most principled and best move. It puts pressure on d5 and prepares the move Qb3 in many situations, looking at the tender b7-pawn. }
3... e6
{ We always play  3...e6  first in this line, preparing the kingside development. The move  3...c6?  is worse, as  4.cxd5  cxd5  5.Qb3  is awkward for Black. Black's resources are much better after the better choice @@StartFEN@@rn1qkbnr/ppp1pppp/8/3p1b2/2PP4/5N2/PP2PPPP/RNBQKB1R b KQkq - 0 3@@EndFEN@@  3...e6  . In some cases, we might be able  to play ...c7-c5, fighting for the center with the c-pawn. Another common scenario is answering Qb3 with ...Nb8-c6, leading to sharp play. }
4. Nc3
{ By far, White's most popular move. Developing the knight while increasing the pressure on d5 is undoubtedly a natural choice. }
4... Nf6
{ The exclamation mark is a bit strong, but it's essential to play this move instead of the old-fashioned one  4...c6  . The move  4...Nf6  is more flexible and allows much sharper play. The critical difference is that after  4...c6  , White is better in the line  5.Qb3  Qb6  6.c5  Qc7  7.Bf4!  Qc8  8.Nh4  Bg6  9.Nxg6  hxg6  10.e4  , which we avoid by playing 4...Nf6.   After  4...Nf6  , White can still play  5.Qb3  , but now we have the dynamic reply  5...Nc6!  , which is much more active. After our move @@StartFEN@@rn1qkbnr/ppp2ppp/4p3/3p1b2/2PP4/2N2N2/PP2PPPP/R1BQKB1R b KQkq - 1 4@@EndFEN@@  4...Nf6  , White has many options. Let's make an overview.  A@@EndBracket@@  5.Qb3  ,  attacking b7, always needs to be checked. We answer,  as usual, with  5...Nc6  , defending actively.   B@@EndBracket@@  5.Bg5  is the most popular line, pinning the knight. We suggest  5...c6  , which is a much better moment for this move than one move earlier.   C@@EndBracket@@  5.Nh4  attacks the bishop and is considered a critical try. We advise playing  5...Bg6  , which gives Black fair chances.   D@@EndBracket@@  5.cxd5  exd5  leads to a harmless version of a Carlsbad structure.   E@@EndBracket@@  5.e3  is a quiet continuation. Our suggestion against it is  5...Bb4  , again going for the most active choice.   F@@EndBracket@@  5.Bf4  is a healthy development move but does not pressure Black. After  5...Bb4  , we transpose to a line of the London System that we examine via a different move order. Please refer to the dedicated chapter on the London for more information.   G@@EndBracket@@  5.g3  h6!  immediately transposes to the line @@StartFEN@@rn1qkbnr/ppp2ppp/4p3/3p1b2/2PP4/5N2/PP2PPPP/RNBQKB1R w KQkq - 0 4@@EndFEN@@  4.g3  Nf6  5.Nc3  h6!  We have a lot to cover; let's check all the possibilities one by one. }
