{ White covers the c4-pawn but locks in the c1-bishop. This is a solid line for White that looks similar to 4.e3, but there is a key difference.   After @@StartFEN@@rnbqkbnr/pppppppp/8/8/8/8/PPPPPPPP/RNBQKBNR w KQkq - 0 1@@EndFEN@@  1.d4  d5  2.Nf3  Bf5  3.c4  e6  4.e3  , we suggest  4...c6  ,  when White can't play Nh4, because our queen still has an eye on this square.   Now, after @@StartFEN@@rn1qkbnr/ppp2ppp/4p3/3p1b2/2PP4/5N2/PP2PPPP/RNBQKB1R w KQkq - 0 4@@EndFEN@@  4.Nc3  Nf6  5.e3  , the situation is different, as  5...c6  6.Nh4  is possible. This would not be terrible at all because we'd just transpose to a line of the Slav Defense that usually arises after @@StartFEN@@rnbqkbnr/pppppppp/8/8/8/8/PPPPPPPP/RNBQKBNR w KQkq - 0 1@@EndFEN@@  1.d4  d5  2.c4  c6  3.Nf3  Nf6  4.e3  Bf5  5.Nc3  e6  6.Nh4  , when Black has good chances to equalize. We'd still like to suggest a different approach that is more dynamic and in the spirit of our line. }
5... Bb4
{ This move is a frequent guest in the current chapter. Black plays in the style of the Nimzo-Indian or the Ragozin Defense of the Queen's Gambit, both featuring the pinning move ...Bb4.   Now, after  5...Bb4  , White usually chooses between  6.Qb3  ,  6.Qa4  or  6.Bd2  , which is the most frequently played but rather harmless move. The whole 5...Bb4 is still rather unexplored and offers many possibilities for both sides. We, therefore, won't dig that deep and focus on some key lines and ideas. }
6. Qb3
{ As usual, we need to check the queen sortie. Generally, White plays Qb3 to attack b7, but our bishop is threatened this time. }
6... Nc6
{ We suggest  6...Nc6  , which leads to position types that are quite typical of this chapter. Black has some alternatives, though. The moves  6...a5  , or  6...Qe7  look reasonable, as well. It's crucial to avoid  6...c5?!  , which does not work well after  7.dxc5  . We can compare this to @@StartFEN@@rn1qk2r/ppp2ppp/4pn2/3p1b2/1bPP4/2N1PN2/PP3PPP/R1BQKB1R w KQkq - 1 6@@EndFEN@@  6.Bd2  O-O  7.Qb3  c5  , which is fine for Black.  In this case, our move ...O-O is much more useful than White's Bd2. }
7. Bd2
{ This move looks like the only interesting try for White. After  7.a3  Bxc3+  8.Qxc3  Ne4  9.Qb3  O-O  Black is in good shape. We have excellent development and active pieces. A notable idea is  10.Bd2  Bg4  11.Qc2  f5  , setting up a Stonewall structure. }
7... a6
{ A strong move, and far from obvious. We prepare a tactical defense of the b7-pawn, seen in the crucial line  8.a3  Be7  9.Qxb7??  Na5  , when White's queen is trapped. }
8. a3 Be7
{ The point of 8...a6. We can preserve our bishop now. White has some possible options in this yet untested position. Our opponent needs to be aware that after ...O-O the move ...Na5 is an annoying threat.   This means that after a slow move like  9.Rc1  O-O  White needs to address our idea with a defensive move, which can't trouble us.   A different idea would be  9.c5  Rb8  , but we are familiar with these structures.  We can ply ...Ne4 soon, and ...b6 is an interesting idea, as well.  Finally, there is the engine suggestion @@StartFEN@@r2qk2r/1pp1bppp/p1n1pn2/3p1b2/2PP4/PQN1PN2/1P1B1PPP/R3KB1R w KQkq - 1 9@@EndFEN@@  9.Nh4  , which we'll check briefly. }
9. Nh4 { Stockfish suggest this direct approach. } 9... dxc4 10. Bxc4 Na5 11.
Qa4+ c6 12. Nxf5
{ This looks more critical than  12.Be2  b5  13.Qd1  O-O  , when we'll play  for the ...c5 advance later. }
12... b5 { The start of a funny sequence. } 13. Nxg7+ Kd7
{ We'll win the bishop on c4, and White's g7-knight is running short of squares, too. }
14. Qd1
{ White retreats and covers the h5-square so that the stranded knight can get out. After  14.Bxb5  axb5  15.Qd1  Qg8  16.Nh5  Qxg2  Black is in good shape, too. }
14... Nxc4 15. Nh5 Nxh5 16. Qxh5 Qg8
{ A strong move. We cover f7 and attack g2 at the same time. Our knight is also ready to take the b2-pawn, which means we'll regain the temporarily sacrificed pawn. }
