10. f3
{ This looks like White's best move. It seems slow but preventing ...Ne4 is an important accomplishment for White. How to continue now? }
10... e5
{ Here we go! Let's open the position as quickly as possible, even at the cost of the material. Now White can take pawns on e5 or c6 or ignore the captures altogether − we have some ground to cover. }
11. Be2
{ This calm move is probably the most consistent with 10.f3. White avoids risky pawn captures and prepares to castle instead. }
11... exd4
{ Opening the position more looks consistent, but  11...e4  is not a bad move, either. }
12. cxd4 c5
{ All very instructive: we attack White's pawn center with all we have. } 13.
dxc5 d4
{ Very nice! We manage to breakthrough in the center. White now needs to get the king to safety. }
14. O-O { White can't play  14.e4??  , as  14...d3  is deadly. } 14... dxe3
{ We want to support our pawn on e3 next, with moves like ...Re8 and ...Qe7. Taking the pawn with  15.Bxe3  is possible for White, but after  15...Re8  16.Qa3  Qe7  17.Kf2  Qe5  White's pieces are not well coordinated.  Conclusion: @@StartFEN@@r2q1rk1/p1p2ppp/2p2n2/3ppb2/Q1PP4/2P1PP2/P5PP/R1B1KB1R w KQ - 0 11@@EndFEN@@  11.Be2  looks fine for Black, and we even have some choice, as  11...e4  is a reasonable alternative to the more direct  11...exd4  line. }
