{ The active defense. It's not just the best move, but the only one. As usual, the move  6...b6?  is a mistake and gets punished with  7.Bg5  c6  8.e4!  dxe4  9.Ne5  Be6  10.Bc4  , which is flat-out winning for White.  As a rule of thumb, we don't want to combine ...Bf5 and ...b6. This applies particularly to positions that still allow White to develop the c1-bishop actively.   Alright, back to the right move,  6...Nc6!  We'll focus on the most popular and natural move  7.Bg5  . We'll also check the wild move  7.e4!?  , which is rare but could be tricky to handle. What about  7.Qxb7?  by the way. Is that easy to refute? Well, there's the odd trick, so we'll have a closer look too. }
7. Bg5
{ White's most natural move, for sure. A quick word about  7.a3  , which is rather slow and answered with  7...Na5  . It's clear that compared to @@StartFEN@@r2qkb1r/ppp2ppp/2n2n2/3p1b2/3P4/1QN2N2/PP2PPPP/R1B1KB1R w KQkq - 2 7@@EndFEN@@  7.Bg5  Na5  , which we are about to examine, Black is better off. }
7... Na5
{ The best solution by far. White had strong pressure on b7 and d5 and  7...Na5  addresses both issues.  We cover b7 and drive the white queen away from her active post.   Playing  7...Bb4?!  is wrong,  as our d5-pawn will be too vulnerable after White consolidates with a sequence like  8.e3  O-O  9.Rc1  . Note that in the similar variation @@StartFEN@@rn1qkb1r/ppp2ppp/4pn2/3p1b2/2PP4/2N2N2/PP2PPPP/R1BQKB1R w KQkq - 2 5@@EndFEN@@  5.Qb3  Nc6  6.Bg5  the move  6...Bb4  is good because  7.cxd5  Qxd5!  works well for us. }
8. Qa4+ c6 9. Bxf6 { White has to take on f6 to make it somewhat interesting. }
9... gxf6 10. e3 Qb6
{ This looks better than  10...b5  , which weakens our already compromised structure even more. }
11. O-O-O O-O-O
{ Our king finds a safe spot on the queenside. It's also possible to play  11...Qb4  and force a queen trade. Chances should be about equal in the resulting endgame, so this is a good option if you prefer a more simplified position. }
12. Bd3 Be6
{ A vital move. We don't want to trade and weaken our control of the f5-square. }
13. Qc2
{ White's queen was misplaced and instead wants to connect to the f5-square. }
13... Nc4
{ The final move to remember. Our knight is not ideal on a5, so we maneuver it to the much better square d6.   A noteworthy idea to note is demonstrated in the following line:  14.Nd2  Nd6  15.Kb1  f5!?  with ...Ne4 to follow. All in all, this variation leads to interesting and combative play. }
