[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "18. 2.Nf3 Bf5  − Main Line 3.c4 e6 4.Nc3 Nf6"]
[Black "2.Nf3 Bf5 − Main Line 4.Nc3 Nf6 5.Nh4 #1"]
[Result "*"]

1. d4 d5 2. Nf3
{ Developing the knight is a popular move for White. It is a flexible choice. White may still play c2-c4 on the next move, entering a Queen's Gambit, or opt for a slower development. As already discussed, we answer  2.Nf3  with  2...Bf5  , which leads to less explored and interesting positions. }
2... Bf5
{ In this chapter, we'll examine the main line of the 2.Nf3 Bf5 variation. After  3.c4  e6  , White plays the natural move  4.Nc3  most of the time, which is the topic of the current chapter. White has many alternatives, of course. These are examined in the dedicated  chapter on 2.Nf3 Bf5 Sidelines. }
3. c4
{ White's most principled and best move. It puts pressure on d5 and prepares the move Qb3 in many situations, looking at the tender b7-pawn. }
3... e6
{ We always play  3...e6  first in this line, preparing the kingside development. The move  3...c6?  is worse, as  4.cxd5  cxd5  5.Qb3  is awkward for Black. Black's resources are much better after the better choice @@StartFEN@@rn1qkbnr/ppp1pppp/8/3p1b2/2PP4/5N2/PP2PPPP/RNBQKB1R b KQkq - 0 3@@EndFEN@@  3...e6  . In some cases, we might be able  to play ...c7-c5, fighting for the center with the c-pawn. Another common scenario is answering Qb3 with ...Nb8-c6, leading to sharp play. }
4. Nc3
{ By far, White's most popular move. Developing the knight while increasing the pressure on d5 is undoubtedly a natural choice. }
4... Nf6
{ The exclamation mark is a bit strong, but it's essential to play this move instead of the old-fashioned one  4...c6  . The move  4...Nf6  is more flexible and allows much sharper play.  The critical difference is that after  4...c6  , White is better in the line  5.Qb3  Qb6  6.c5  Qc7  7.Bf4!  Qc8  8.Nh4  Bg6  9.Nxg6  hxg6  10.e4  , which we avoid by playing 4...Nf6.   After  4...Nf6  , White can still play  5.Qb3  , but now we have the dynamic reply  5...Nc6!  , which is much more active. }
5. Nh4
{ White immediately attacks our bishop and tries to gain the bishop pair. It has been tested on the top GM level several times and certainly needs to be taken seriously. You probably won't meet it too often, but we need to be prepared, of course. }
5... Bg6
{ We prefer to have the bishop captured on g6. Black has an interesting alternative in  5...Bb4  . It emphasizes development at the cost of a slightly weaker pawn formation. This line is very concrete and tactical, though. These types of general evaluations are less relevant in such a scenario.   Let's focus on our move  5...Bg6  now. White usually  captures on g6 immediately, but this move can be delayed for a while. Eventually, White will almost always take on g6 and transpose to the lines we examine using  the  6.Nxg6  move order. We'll have a look at  6.Qb3  and  6.cxd5  as possible ways to avoid/delay the capture. A standard move for White is  6.Bg5  , when  6...c6  transposes to @@StartFEN@@rn1qkb1r/ppp2ppp/4pn2/3p1b2/2PP4/2N2N2/PP2PPPP/R1BQKB1R w KQkq - 2 5@@EndFEN@@  5.Bg5  c6  6.Nh4  Bg6  . }
6. Qb3 { As usual, we have to check Qb3. } 6... Nc6
{ The active defense, just as after @@StartFEN@@rn1qkbnr/ppp2ppp/4p3/3p1b2/2PP4/5N2/PP2PPPP/RNBQKB1R w KQkq - 0 4@@EndFEN@@  4.Qb3  Nc6  or @@StartFEN@@rn1qkbnr/ppp2ppp/4p3/3p1b2/2PP4/5N2/PP2PPPP/RNBQKB1R w KQkq - 0 4@@EndFEN@@  4.Nc3  Nf6  5.Qb3  Nc6  . In this particular case, we attack the d-pawn, which is undefended. }
7. e3
{ White could insert  7.Nxg6  hxg6  now, which would transpose to @@StartFEN@@rn1qkb1r/ppp2ppp/4pnb1/3p4/2PP3N/2N5/PP2PPPP/R1BQKB1R w KQkq - 4 6@@EndFEN@@  6.Nxg6  hxg6  7.Qb3  Nc6  . There is more: after @@StartFEN@@r2qkb1r/ppp2ppp/2n1pnb1/3p4/2PP3N/1QN5/PP2PPPP/R1B1KB1R w KQkq - 6 7@@EndFEN@@  7.cxd5  exd5  we'd transpose to @@StartFEN@@rn1qkb1r/ppp2ppp/4pnb1/3p4/2PP3N/2N5/PP2PPPP/R1BQKB1R w KQkq - 4 6@@EndFEN@@  6.cxd5  exd5  7.Qb3  Nc6  ,  which also has little independent significance. White will almost always take on g6 soon, which was the whole point of 5.Nh4, after all. }
7... Bb4
{ It's all about rapid development. We get the bishop out and protect b7 at the same time. }
8. Bd2
{ Again, White could play  8.Nxg6  hxg6  or @@StartFEN@@r2qk2r/ppp2ppp/2n1pnb1/3p4/1bPP3N/1QN1P3/PP3PPP/R1B1KB1R w KQkq - 1 8@@EndFEN@@  8.cxd5  exd5  , which would transpose to @@StartFEN@@rn1qkb1r/ppp2ppp/4pnb1/3p4/2PP3N/2N5/PP2PPPP/R1BQKB1R w KQkq - 4 6@@EndFEN@@  6.Nxg6  hxg6  or @@StartFEN@@rn1qkb1r/ppp2ppp/4pnb1/3p4/2PP3N/2N5/PP2PPPP/R1BQKB1R w KQkq - 4 6@@EndFEN@@  6.cxd5  exd5  . }
8... Ne4
{ A good move, trying to exploit the fact that White never captured the bishop. We could follow the same mindset with  8...Bh5  , but this looks less natural. }
9. Nxg6 Nxd2 10. Kxd2 hxg6
{ White has lost castling rights, which is obviously not ideal. Still, the king is relatively safe in the center, which means chances are about equal. }
