8. e3 Bb4 9. Bd2
{ White still delays the capture. In the 2021 online rapid game between Levon Aronian and Vladislav Artemiev, White played  9.Nxg6  hxg6  10.Bd2  , giving Black the interesting option  10...Qd6  ,  attacking the h2-pawn.  After  11.h3  Bxc3  12.Bxc3  Ne4  Black is in good shape.  Compared to @@StartFEN@@r2qk2r/ppp2pp1/2n2np1/3p4/1b1P4/1QN1P3/PP1B1PPP/R3KB1R b KQkq - 1 10@@EndFEN@@  10...O-O  , as played in the game, Black has the additional idea of queenside castling. The position after 9.Nxg6 hxg6 can also arise  after 6.Nxg6 or other earlier captures on g6, of course. }
9... O-O 10. Nxg6 hxg6
{ We have transposed to the already mentioned game Aronian-Artemiev. } 11. Bd3
Re8 12. O-O { Now we have reached a key point in the game. } 12... Rb8
{ We suggest this move, covering the b-pawn. This prepares the bishop's retreat next. Instead, Artemiev voluntarily captured on c3, which did not work well. We want to add that instead of  12...Rb8  the moves  12...a6  and even  12...Bf8  would work well, too. }
13. a3 Bd6
{ Now we can safely retreat. We'd like to go for ...Ne7 next, trying to shift the knight to the kingside. White has the bishop pair, but our position is sound, and all pieces work well. }
