{ Now we need to check some moves for White. The sequence  7.Bg5  c6  transposes to @@StartFEN@@rn1qkb1r/ppp2ppp/4pn2/3p1b2/2PP4/2N2N2/PP2PPPP/R1BQKB1R w KQkq - 2 5@@EndFEN@@  5.Bg5  c6  6.Nh4  Bg6  7.Nxg6  hxg6  . Independent options are @@StartFEN@@rn1qkb1r/ppp2pp1/4pnp1/3p4/2PP4/2N5/PP2PPPP/R1BQKB1R w KQkq - 0 7@@EndFEN@@  7.cxd5  ,  7.Qb3  and  7.e3  . }
7. cxd5 { White exchanges on d5, reaching a Carlsbad formation. } 7... exd5 8.
Qb3
{ This looks like the most challenging option. Continuations like  8.Bg5  c6  can't be dangerous for Black. We can develop quickly, and the open h-file is compensation for the loss of the bishop pair. }
8... Nc6 9. Bg5
{ Or  9.e3  Bb4  , which looks relatively harmless. We examine a similar position after @@StartFEN@@rn1qkb1r/ppp2pp1/4pnp1/3p4/2PP4/2N5/PP2PPPP/R1BQKB1R w KQkq - 0 7@@EndFEN@@  7.Qb3  Nc6  8.e3  Bb4  ,  when White has not traded on d5. This version is already fine for Black and having committed to the exchange on d5 does not help White. Instead, the move 9.Bg5 invites some tactical complications. }
9... Nxd4
{ 'Gift me the pawn!' − It's not a gift in the true sense of the word, though. White has compensation and will often regain the material quickly. }
10. Qa4+ Nc6
{ White has two attacking options now that we need to check: castling queenside and  11.e4  . After  11.e4  Black has more than one good reply, though. We like  11...Qd6  , which immediately unpins the knight. The moves  11...d4  and  11...dxe4  work as well. }
11. O-O-O Be7 { A logical way to develop and unpin. } 12. Bxf6
{ White is forcing the action. Instead,  12.e3  Nd7  13.Bxe7  Nxe7  14.Nxd5  Nxd5  15.Rxd5  Qe7  is a natural sequence that poses no problems.  Black does not need to castle in such a situation, as the h8-rook is already in play. Just playing ...Kf8 at some point might be enough to give the king a bit more safety. }
12... Bxf6 13. Nxd5 Qd6
{ We are ready to castle queenside now, for example, after  14.e4  Qc5+  15.Kb1  O-O-O  . This is not the only option, though, as kingside castling is still possible, too. Chances are equal in this position. }
