8. Bd2
{ A solid move that breaks the pin. We should attack White's center quickly now. }
8... c5
{ Using the c-pawn first, followed by ...Nc6, looks reasonable for Black. The Nf3-h4 maneuver has weakened White's control of d4, which makes an attack against this pawn more attractive. }
9. a3
{ White wants the second bishop, too! This move is more testing than  9.dxc5  Nc6  10.a3  Bxc5  or similar lines.  Black has nothing to fear in such a scenario, as all of our pieces are active, and we have good control of the d4-square. White's bishops are far from an important factor in this IQP structure. }
9... Bxc3 10. Bxc3 cxd4 { This concrete sequence of moves works well. } 11.
Qxd4
{ Or  11.Bxd4  Nc6  12.Bc3  Qc7  13.h3  O-O  , when our excellent development compensates for the loss of the bishop pair. }
11... Nc6 12. Qd3 Qc7
{ A small but important nuance. We attack the h-pawn and win an important tempo. }
13. h3 Rd8
{ Black has equalized in this position. We are ready to play ...Ne5 now, which would make sure that White has to give up one of the bishops. }
