{ The active reply, just as after @@StartFEN@@rn1qkbnr/ppp2ppp/4p3/3p1b2/2PP4/5N2/PP2PPPP/RNBQKB1R w KQkq - 0 4@@EndFEN@@  4.Qb3  Nc6  , which is quite similar. Now we have split between various tries. One of them is @@StartFEN@@r2qkb1r/ppp2ppp/2n1pn2/3p1b2/2PP4/1QN2N2/PP2PPPP/R1B1KB1R w KQkq - 4 6@@EndFEN@@  6.cxd5  exd5  , but this transposes to @@StartFEN@@rn1qkb1r/ppp2ppp/4pn2/3p1b2/2PP4/2N2N2/PP2PPPP/R1BQKB1R w KQkq - 2 5@@EndFEN@@  5.cxd5  exd5  6.Qb3  Nc6  . }
6. a3
{ A relatively rare move, but it is tricky to handle for Black. The same applies to @@StartFEN@@rn1qkbnr/ppp2ppp/4p3/3p1b2/2PP4/5N2/PP2PPPP/RNBQKB1R w KQkq - 0 4@@EndFEN@@  4.Qb3  Nc6  5.a3  , which looks harmless but is similarly challenging. }
6... Na5
{ We suggest this concrete solution. It's important and instructive to see that some alternatives lead to problems for Black.  A@@EndBracket@@  6...Rb8?!  7.cxd5  exd5  8.Bg5  Na5  9.Qa2!  is great for White, a line that is also very relevant for @@StartFEN@@rn1qkbnr/ppp2ppp/4p3/3p1b2/2PP4/5N2/PP2PPPP/RNBQKB1R w KQkq - 0 4@@EndFEN@@  4.Qb3  Nc6  5.a3  , when  5...Rb8  is dubious due to the same answer.   B@@EndBracket@@  6...a6?!  7.cxd5  exd5  8.Bg5  is annoying to face. Note that in the line @@StartFEN@@rn1qkbnr/ppp2ppp/4p3/3p1b2/2PP4/5N2/PP2PPPP/RNBQKB1R w KQkq - 0 4@@EndFEN@@  4.Qb3  Nc6  5.a3  a6  is good, as  6.cxd5  is answered with  6...Qxd5!  , a key difference.   C@@EndBracket@@  6...dxc4  is a reasonable alternative.  Black can go for ...Bd6 and ...e5 ideas after the capture. }
7. Qa4+ c6 8. c5
{ This looks best. After  8.cxd5  exd5  Black has a good position. The 'offside' knight is nicely connected with the weakened c4-square, giving Black the better chances already. }
8... b5 9. Nxb5 { A line like  9.Qd1  Ne4  can hardly be critical for Black. }
9... cxb5 10. Qxb5+ Nd7
{ You can't play  10...Ke7?  as White gets too much of an attack after  11.Bf4  or  11.Ne5  . }
11. c6 Nxc6
{ We return the piece, which leaves us a pawn down. White has lost a lot of time, though... our compensation is excellent, as the following lines demonstrate. }
12. Qxc6 Rc8 13. Qa6
{ White keeps control of the d6-square, stopping ...Bd6. After  13.Qa4  Bd6  14.e3  O-O  15.Ba6  Bc2  16.Qb5  Rc7  17.O-O  Be4  Black has great play for the pawn.  This is just a sample variation that does not need to be memorized. There are multiple possible deviations along the way, but it is clear that the play on the c-file/queenside compensates for a pawn. }
13... Rc2 14. Qxa7
{ Let's have a brief look at the 'greed is good' move. Here it's not good for White, though! It's wiser to play  14.e3  Qc7  15.Bd2  Bd6  16.Bb5  O-O  , which still gives Black nice compensation. }
14... Bd6 15. e3 O-O
{ After this move we are ready to activate the knight via f6 or b6. White is already walking a tight rope, which is nicely shown after  16.Bb5  Nf6  17.O-O  Be4!  with a decisive attack for Black! }
