[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "18. 2.Nf3 Bf5  − Main Line 3.c4 e6 4.Nc3 Nf6"]
[Black "2.Nf3 Bf5 − Main Line 4.Nc3 Nf6 5.Qb3 #2"]
[Result "*"]

1. d4 d5 2. Nf3
{ Developing the knight is a popular move for White. It is a flexible choice. White may still play c2-c4 on the next move, entering a Queen's Gambit, or opt for a slower development. As already discussed, we answer  2.Nf3  with  2...Bf5  , which leads to less explored and interesting positions. }
2... Bf5
{ In this chapter, we'll examine the main line of the 2.Nf3 Bf5 variation. After  3.c4  e6  , White plays the natural move  4.Nc3  most of the time, which is the topic of the current chapter. White has many alternatives, of course. These are examined in the dedicated  chapter on 2.Nf3 Bf5 Sidelines. }
3. c4
{ White's most principled and best move. It puts pressure on d5 and prepares the move Qb3 in many situations, looking at the tender b7-pawn. }
3... e6
{ We always play  3...e6  first in this line, preparing the kingside development. The move  3...c6?  is worse, as  4.cxd5  cxd5  5.Qb3  is awkward for Black. Black's resources are much better after the better choice @@StartFEN@@rn1qkbnr/ppp1pppp/8/3p1b2/2PP4/5N2/PP2PPPP/RNBQKB1R b KQkq - 0 3@@EndFEN@@  3...e6  . In some cases, we might be able  to play ...c7-c5, fighting for the center with the c-pawn. Another common scenario is answering Qb3 with ...Nb8-c6, leading to sharp play. }
4. Nc3
{ By far, White's most popular move. Developing the knight while increasing the pressure on d5 is undoubtedly a natural choice. }
4... Nf6
{ The exclamation mark is a bit strong, but it's essential to play this move instead of the old-fashioned one  4...c6  . The move  4...Nf6  is more flexible and allows much sharper play.  The critical difference is that after  4...c6  , White is better in the line  5.Qb3  Qb6  6.c5  Qc7  7.Bf4!  Qc8  8.Nh4  Bg6  9.Nxg6  hxg6  10.e4  , which we avoid by playing 4...Nf6.   After  4...Nf6  , White can still play  5.Qb3  , but now we have the dynamic reply  5...Nc6!  , which is much more active. }
5. Qb3 { As usual, a critical move to check. } 5... Nc6
{ The active reply, just as after @@StartFEN@@rn1qkbnr/ppp2ppp/4p3/3p1b2/2PP4/5N2/PP2PPPP/RNBQKB1R w KQkq - 0 4@@EndFEN@@  4.Qb3  Nc6  , which is quite similar. Now we have split between various tries. One of them is @@StartFEN@@r2qkb1r/ppp2ppp/2n1pn2/3p1b2/2PP4/1QN2N2/PP2PPPP/R1B1KB1R w KQkq - 4 6@@EndFEN@@  6.cxd5  exd5  , but this transposes to @@StartFEN@@rn1qkb1r/ppp2ppp/4pn2/3p1b2/2PP4/2N2N2/PP2PPPP/R1BQKB1R w KQkq - 2 5@@EndFEN@@  5.cxd5  exd5  6.Qb3  Nc6  . }
6. c5 { The pawn advance takes control of b4. } 6... Rb8
{ We need to cover b7 now. } 7. Bf4
{ A natural move. White can also play  7.Bg5  , but  7...Be7  8.e3  O-O  9.Be2  Ne4  is a logical reply that looks fine for Black. Stockfish also likes  9...h6  10.Bh4  g5!?  11.Bg3  Nh5  , which is more ambitious. }
7... Ne4
{ This is the most aggressive move. We prepare the pawn push to g5, attacking the exposed bishop. }
8. e3
{ White can stop our idea with  8.h4  , but that's not an ideal solution for our opponent, either. A good answer is the simple  8...Be7  ,  intending ...O-O and later playing for ...e5 or ...b6. }
8... g5 9. Bg3
{ After  9.Nxe4?!  gxf4  10.Ned2  fxe3  Black is already somewhat better. We have the bishop pair and good play on the dark squares. }
9... Nxg3 10. hxg3 Bg7
{ We have reached an unconventional position with about equal chances for both sides. A sample line is  11.Bb5  O-O  12.Qa4  f6  13.Bxc6  bxc6  14.O-O-O  Qd7  , but there are plenty of possibilities in this position. }
*

