6. Bg5
{ This move is not played that often but poses an interesting challenge. We'll more frequently meet the similar variation @@StartFEN@@rn1qkb1r/ppp2ppp/4pn2/3p1b2/2PP4/2N2N2/PP2PPPP/R1BQKB1R w KQkq - 2 5@@EndFEN@@  5.cxd5  exd5  6.Qb3  Nc6  7.Bg5  ,  when White has traded on d5 earlier. Black has only one good move in this line,  7...Na5  , which leads to interesting play after  8.Qa4+  c6  9.Bxf6  gxf6  .   Here, without the pawn exchange, the situation is different. White still has the option to advance the c-pawn, which is critical after  6...Na5  7.Qa4+  c6  8.c5  . This line is not easy to play for Black, as we can't play  8...b5??  due to  9.Nxb5  . Better is @@StartFEN@@r2qkb1r/pp3ppp/2p1pn2/n1Pp1bB1/Q2P4/2N2N2/PP2PPPP/R3KB1R b KQkq - 0 8@@EndFEN@@  8...Be7  , but  9.Ne5  or  9.e3  keeps some annoying pressure. It turns out that we have a more attractive solution than 6...Na5. }
6... Bb4
{ This move, in the style of the Queen's Gambit Ragozin, @@StartFEN@@rnbqkbnr/pppppppp/8/8/8/8/PPPPPPPP/RNBQKBNR w KQkq - 0 1@@EndFEN@@  1.d4  d5  2.c4  e6  3.Nf3  Nf6  4.Nc3  Bb4  , works well for Black. Again it makes sense to compare the position to @@StartFEN@@rn1qkb1r/ppp2ppp/4pn2/3p1b2/2PP4/2N2N2/PP2PPPP/R1BQKB1R w KQkq - 2 5@@EndFEN@@  5.cxd5  exd5  6.Qb3  Nc6  7.Bg5  , when  7...Bb4?!  is dubious.  The key difference is that now @@StartFEN@@r2qk2r/ppp2ppp/2n1pn2/3p1bB1/1bPP4/1QN2N2/PP2PPPP/R3KB1R w KQkq - 6 7@@EndFEN@@  7.cxd5  Qxd5!  avoids this transposition and gives Black attractive play. We'll examine this possibility and the alternatives @@StartFEN@@r2qk2r/ppp2ppp/2n1pn2/3p1bB1/1bPP4/1QN2N2/PP2PPPP/R3KB1R w KQkq - 6 7@@EndFEN@@  7.e3  and  7.a3  now. }
7. a3
{ White immediately secures the bishop pair. Taking on c3 first is also fine. }
7... dxc4 8. Qxc4 Bxc3+
{ We don't mind the loss of the bishop pair so much, as we have good central control of the light squares and easy development. There is no good alternative at this point, anyway. }
9. bxc3
{ White may also play  9.Qxc3  when  9...Qd5  , or  9...Qd7  ,  prepares queenside castling and threatens ...Ne4. This leads to an interesting position with equal chances. }
9... O-O
{ It's also interesting to consider  9...h6  10.Bh4  g5  , but castling is certainly a natural move. }
10. e3 Na5
{ The knight connects to the weak squares c4 and b3. We also need to play ...c5, which is coming next. }
11. Qa4 c5
{ Let's get some play on the c-file. It's important to note that we don't need to fear the doubled pawn in the following sequence. }
12. Bxf6 gxf6
{ Our king position is safe, and the f6-pawn is actually useful in covering the e5-square. Next, we'll play ...Qc7/...Rac8, starting some play on the c-file. }
