7. e3 { A natural move, allowing the bishop recapture on c4. } 7... a5
{ A fun reply, which immediately threatens ...a4-a3. } 8. Qa4
{ White stops the a-pawn. The line  8.Bxf6  Qxf6  9.cxd5  a4!  shows why White needs to worry about the further advance. }
8... O-O 9. a3 Bxc3+
{ Taking on c3 is more in the spirit of this line, but  9...Be7  ,  intending ...Ne4, looks reasonable too. }
10. bxc3 h6
{ The pin is annoying, and we want to address this issue immediately. } 11. Bh4
{ White can also take on f6, of course. It looks fine for us, for example after  11.Bxf6  Qxf6  12.cxd5  exd5  13.Qb5  Ne7  , which offers the b-pawn. White can't be too greedy as  14.Qxb7  Rab8  15.Qxc7  Rb2  demonstrates. We have a strong attack and more than enough compensation for the material. }
