{ The exclamation mark is a bit strong, but it's essential to play this move instead of the old-fashioned one  4...c6  . The move  4...Nf6  is more flexible and allows much sharper play.  The critical difference is that after  4...c6  , White is better in the line  5.Qb3  Qb6  6.c5  Qc7  7.Bf4!  Qc8  8.Nh4  Bg6  9.Nxg6  hxg6  10.e4  , which we avoid by playing 4...Nf6.   After  4...Nf6  , White can still play  5.Qb3  , but now we have the dynamic reply  5...Nc6!  , which is much more active. }
5. Qb3 { As usual, a critical move to check. } 5... Nc6
{ The active reply, just as after @@StartFEN@@rn1qkbnr/ppp2ppp/4p3/3p1b2/2PP4/5N2/PP2PPPP/RNBQKB1R w KQkq - 0 4@@EndFEN@@  4.Qb3  Nc6  , which is quite similar. Now we have split between various tries. One of them is @@StartFEN@@r2qkb1r/ppp2ppp/2n1pn2/3p1b2/2PP4/1QN2N2/PP2PPPP/R1B1KB1R w KQkq - 4 6@@EndFEN@@  6.cxd5  exd5  , but this transposes to @@StartFEN@@rn1qkb1r/ppp2ppp/4pn2/3p1b2/2PP4/2N2N2/PP2PPPP/R1BQKB1R w KQkq - 2 5@@EndFEN@@  5.cxd5  exd5  6.Qb3  Nc6  . }
6. Bg5
{ This move is not played that often but poses an interesting challenge. We'll more frequently meet the similar variation @@StartFEN@@rn1qkb1r/ppp2ppp/4pn2/3p1b2/2PP4/2N2N2/PP2PPPP/R1BQKB1R w KQkq - 2 5@@EndFEN@@  5.cxd5  exd5  6.Qb3  Nc6  7.Bg5  ,  when White has traded on d5 earlier. Black has only one good move in this line,  7...Na5  , which leads to interesting play after  8.Qa4+  c6  9.Bxf6  gxf6  .   Here, without the pawn exchange, the situation is different. White still has the option to advance the c-pawn, which is critical after  6...Na5  7.Qa4+  c6  8.c5  . This line is not easy to play for Black, as we can't play  8...b5??  due to  9.Nxb5  . Better is @@StartFEN@@r2qkb1r/pp3ppp/2p1pn2/n1Pp1bB1/Q2P4/2N2N2/PP2PPPP/R3KB1R b KQkq - 0 8@@EndFEN@@  8...Be7  , but  9.Ne5  or  9.e3  keeps some annoying pressure. It turns out that we have a more attractive solution than 6...Na5. }
6... Bb4
{ This move, in the style of the Queen's Gambit Ragozin, @@StartFEN@@rnbqkbnr/pppppppp/8/8/8/8/PPPPPPPP/RNBQKBNR w KQkq - 0 1@@EndFEN@@  1.d4  d5  2.c4  e6  3.Nf3  Nf6  4.Nc3  Bb4  , works well for Black. Again it makes sense to compare the position to @@StartFEN@@rn1qkb1r/ppp2ppp/4pn2/3p1b2/2PP4/2N2N2/PP2PPPP/R1BQKB1R w KQkq - 2 5@@EndFEN@@  5.cxd5  exd5  6.Qb3  Nc6  7.Bg5  , when  7...Bb4?!  is dubious.  The key difference is that now @@StartFEN@@r2qk2r/ppp2ppp/2n1pn2/3p1bB1/1bPP4/1QN2N2/PP2PPPP/R3KB1R w KQkq - 6 7@@EndFEN@@  7.cxd5  Qxd5!  avoids this transposition and gives Black attractive play. We'll examine this possibility and the alternatives @@StartFEN@@r2qk2r/ppp2ppp/2n1pn2/3p1bB1/1bPP4/1QN2N2/PP2PPPP/R3KB1R w KQkq - 6 7@@EndFEN@@  7.e3  and  7.a3  now. }
7. cxd5 Qxd5
{ As already discussed earlier,  7...exd5?  is bad for Black. The queen recapture is much better. }
8. Qxd5
{ Playing  8.Qxb4  looks fun, but  8...Nxb4  9.Nxd5  Nfxd5  is just good for Black. White has to move the king to defend against the fork threat,  which we love to see. We have good attacking chances after ...f6 and ...O-O-O. }
8... Nxd5 9. Bd2 O-O-O
{ Black is in good shape here, enjoying a considerable lead in development. It's interesting to note that often Black manages to play ...e6-e5 soon, for example, after  10.e3  Nxc3  11.bxc3  Ba3  12.Bc1  Be7  13.Be2  e5  , when  14.Nxe5  Nxe5  15.dxe5  Rd5  and @@StartFEN@@2kr3r/ppp1bppp/2n5/4pb2/3P4/2P1PN2/P3BPPP/R1B1K2R w KQ - 0 14@@EndFEN@@  14.dxe5  Be4  are fine for Black. }
