1. d4 d5 2. Nf3
{ Developing the knight is a popular move for White. It is a flexible choice. White may still play c2-c4 on the next move, entering a Queen's Gambit, or opt for a slower development. As already discussed, we answer  2.Nf3  with  2...Bf5  , which leads to less explored and interesting positions. }
2... Bf5
{ In this chapter, we'll examine the main line of the 2.Nf3 Bf5 variation. After  3.c4  e6  , White plays the natural move  4.Nc3  most of the time, which is the topic of the current chapter. White has many alternatives, of course. These are examined in the dedicated  chapter on 2.Nf3 Bf5 Sidelines. }
3. c4
{ White's most principled and best move. It puts pressure on d5 and prepares the move Qb3 in many situations, looking at the tender b7-pawn. }
3... e6
{ We always play  3...e6  first in this line, preparing the kingside development. The move  3...c6?  is worse, as  4.cxd5  cxd5  5.Qb3  is awkward for Black. Black's resources are much better after the better choice @@StartFEN@@rn1qkbnr/ppp1pppp/8/3p1b2/2PP4/5N2/PP2PPPP/RNBQKB1R b KQkq - 0 3@@EndFEN@@  3...e6  . In some cases, we might be able  to play ...c7-c5, fighting for the center with the c-pawn. Another common scenario is answering Qb3 with ...Nb8-c6, leading to sharp play. }
4. Nc3
{ By far, White's most popular move. Developing the knight while increasing the pressure on d5 is undoubtedly a natural choice. }
4... Nf6
{ The exclamation mark is a bit strong, but it's essential to play this move instead of the old-fashioned one  4...c6  . The move  4...Nf6  is more flexible and allows much sharper play.  The critical difference is that after  4...c6  , White is better in the line  5.Qb3  Qb6  6.c5  Qc7  7.Bf4!  Qc8  8.Nh4  Bg6  9.Nxg6  hxg6  10.e4  , which we avoid by playing 4...Nf6.   After  4...Nf6  , White can still play  5.Qb3  , but now we have the dynamic reply  5...Nc6!  , which is much more active. }
5. Bg5 c6
{ Here Black has two playable moves:  5...c6  and  5...Bb4  . Deciding between the two is not trivial, but  5...c6  looks slightly more reliable. The critical replies against  5...Bb4  are the lines  6.Qa4+  or  6.cxd5  exd5  7.Qa4+  , when White seems to keep a small edge.   Still, playing  5...Bb4  is certainly a good alternative if you are interested in expanding the repertoire. The move  5...c6  adds some stability to the center and prepares  the move ...Qb6 in response to White's Qb3 sortie.  An important point to recognize is that we only play ...c6 after White is committed to the move Bg5,  which is a difference to the line @@StartFEN@@rn1qkbnr/ppp2ppp/4p3/3p1b2/2PP4/2N2N2/PP2PPPP/R1BQKB1R b KQkq - 1 4@@EndFEN@@  4...c6?!  , when  5.Qb3  Qb6  6.c5  Qc7  7.Bf4!  is the critical reply. White can employ a similar idea after @@StartFEN@@rn1qkb1r/ppp2ppp/4pn2/3p1b2/2PP4/2N2N2/PP2PPPP/R1BQKB1R w KQkq - 2 5@@EndFEN@@  5.Bg5  c6  , but would lose a full tempo, as the bishop is  already on g5 − this is a substantial difference.  White has some choices after  5...c6  . Here is an overview:  A@@EndBracket@@  6.cxd5  exd5  leads to @@StartFEN@@rn1qkb1r/ppp2ppp/4pn2/3p1b2/2PP4/2N2N2/PP2PPPP/R1BQKB1R w KQkq - 2 5@@EndFEN@@  5.cxd5  exd5  6.Bg5  c6  .  B@@EndBracket@@ @@StartFEN@@rn1qkb1r/pp3ppp/2p1pn2/3p1bB1/2PP4/2N2N2/PP2PPPP/R2QKB1R w KQkq - 0 6@@EndFEN@@  6.e3  is the most frequently played move but rather harmless.  C@@EndBracket@@  6.Qb3  and  6.Nh4  are more concrete approaches and look like the most dangerous continuations. }
6. Nh4
{ White attacks our bishop, a similar idea as after 5.Nh4 − in both cases retreating to g6 is a good reply. }
6... Bg6
{ Now we'll examine  7.Nxg6  , while  7.Qb3  Qb6  8.c5  Qc7  leads to positions that are more commonly reached via @@StartFEN@@rn1qkb1r/pp3ppp/2p1pn2/3p1bB1/2PP4/2N2N2/PP2PPPP/R2QKB1R w KQkq - 0 6@@EndFEN@@  6.Qb3  Qb6  7.c5  Qc7  , a line that is fine for Black. }
7. Nxg6
{ Taking is the most obvious move, but White certainly has alternatives. They don't look scary, though. After  7.cxd5  , we have a good choice between  7...exd5  and the, maybe even more convincing,  7...cxd5  . Recapturing with the c-pawn is an option as long  as we have not played ...Nbd7. In an open c-file scenario, we need the knight on c6, its most active post. White could also go  @@StartFEN@@rn1qkb1r/pp3ppp/2p1pnb1/3p2B1/2PP3N/2N5/PP2PPPP/R2QKB1R w KQkq - 2 7@@EndFEN@@  7.e3  , but Black has some good replies, like  7...Be7  or  7...Qb6  , to name two of them. }
7... hxg6 8. cxd5
{ Or  8.e3  , when both  8...Qa5  and  8...Bb4  look good. We start counterplay  on the a5-a1 diagonal, similar to the Cambridge Springs  Variation @@StartFEN@@rnbqkbnr/pppppppp/8/8/8/8/PPPPPPPP/RNBQKBNR w KQkq - 0 1@@EndFEN@@  1.d4  d5  2.c4  e6  3.Nc3  Nf6  4.Bg5  Nbd7  5.e3  c6  6.Nf3  Qa5  , and have an easy game. Our position has no weaknesses and active pieces, a good opening result. }
8... cxd5
{ As mentioned before, this capture is a good option if ...Nc6 is still possible. }
9. Qb3 Qd7
{ We just cover the b-pawn. There are alternatives, though. The move  9...Nc6!?  is also possible, as  10.Qxb7  Nxd4  is fine for Black. }
10. O-O-O
{ This aggressive move is worth checking. A slow continuation like  10.e3  Nc6  11.Bd3  Bd6  can't trouble Black. All our pieces are well placed, and we have good prospects on the c-file. }
10... Nc6 11. e4
{ White opens up the center as quickly as possible. A similar strategy can be employed by  11.Bxf6  gxf6  12.e4  Bg7  13.exd5  exd5  14.Qxd5  Qxd5  15.Nxd5  Rd8  , when we regain the pawn with equal play. }
11... Nxe4 12. Nxe4 dxe4 13. d5
{ It looks a bit scary, but White's king position is not ideal, either. } 13...
exd5 14. Rxd5 Qc7
{ An important moment: we use the insecure position of White's king to gain a crucial tempo. }
15. Kb1 Be7
{ And finally, we are ready to castle kingside. White has some compensation for the pawn, but Black has good defensive resources and a clear plan: ...O-O, play a rook to d8, maybe ...Bf6 if White decides to avoid the bishop trade. }
