{ Most of the time, taking on b3 is undesirable, but here it makes some sense because of our next move. }
9. axb3 Ne4
{ A strong move. We hit both the g5-bishop and the c3-knight, having ...Bb4 in mind if White wants to preserve the bishop. }
10. Nxe4
{ White has a choice of some unattractive options. Lines like  10.Bf4  Bb4  or @@StartFEN@@r3kb1r/pp1n1ppp/2p1p3/3p1bB1/2PPn3/1PN1PN2/1P2BPPP/R3K2R w KQkq - 1 10@@EndFEN@@  10.c5  Nxg5  are very comfortable for Black. }
10... dxe4 { A more powerful continuation than the bishop recapture. } 11. Nd2
Bb4
{ We love to use this weakened square. We are now ready to play ...e5 soon. It would even work after  12.Bf4  , as we will see. }
12. Bf4 e5
{ Black is in great shape now after  13.dxe5  Nc5  or @@StartFEN@@r3k2r/pp1n1ppp/2p5/4pb2/1bPPpB2/1P2P3/1P1NBPPP/R3K2R w KQkq - 0 13@@EndFEN@@  13.Bxe5  Nxe5  14.dxe5  O-O-O  , when White is caught in an awkward pin. }
