2... Bf5
{ After 2...Bf5 White's main choice  is between playing the move c4 soon or avoiding the pawn break favoring kingside development. This plan often involves playing for control of the e5-square, with a quick Ne5 and Nd2-f3 ideas.   White has many move orders to choose from. If c4 is intended, White can start with  3.c4  right away, but may also begin with  3.Nf3  or  3.e3  . Similarly, play can start with the kingside development scheme following  3.Nf3  or  3.e3  .   We decided to cover all c4-setups starting with the move order  3.c4  , while the kingside development plan is covered via  3.e3  . This means that in our coverage, the move order  3.Nf3  is more or less purely transpositional. Switching to our point of view, our move orders and ideas are fairly straightforward. Our next move will be  3...e6  , preparing kingside development.   One point of the  2...Bf5  move order, compared to  2...Nf6  first, is the delay  of the move ...Nf6. Not playing ...Nf6 early gives us additional options against some of White's plans, in particular against early Ne5 ideas. }
3. Nf3
{ In our chosen way to organize the material, this move transposes to lines covered via  3.e3  or  3.c4  . Let's check some of the possible ways to transpose. }
3... e6
{ We play this move first and avoid  3...Nf6  . Of course, playing the knight first is not a mistake, but we intend to delay this move for a bit. This is relevant in lines like  3...e6  4.e3  Bd6  when  5.Ne5  is completely toothless, compared to @@StartFEN@@rn1qkbnr/ppp1pppp/8/3p1b2/3P1B2/5N2/PPP1PPPP/RN1QKB1R b KQkq - 3 3@@EndFEN@@  3...Nf6  4.e3  e6  5.Ne5  or  5.Nbd2  Bd6  6.Ne5  , which are more challenging. Now there are plenty of possible transpositions.  A@@EndBracket@@ @@StartFEN@@rn1qkbnr/ppp2ppp/4p3/3p1b2/3P1B2/5N2/PPP1PPPP/RN1QKB1R w KQkq - 0 4@@EndFEN@@  4.c4  Nf6  leads to @@StartFEN@@rn1qkbnr/ppp1pppp/8/3p1b2/3P1B2/8/PPP1PPPP/RN1QKBNR w KQkq - 2 3@@EndFEN@@  3.c4  e6  4.Nf3  Nf6  .  B@@EndBracket@@ @@StartFEN@@rn1qkbnr/ppp2ppp/4p3/3p1b2/3P1B2/5N2/PPP1PPPP/RN1QKB1R w KQkq - 0 4@@EndFEN@@  4.e3  Bd6  leads @@StartFEN@@rn1qkbnr/ppp1pppp/8/3p1b2/3P1B2/8/PPP1PPPP/RN1QKBNR w KQkq - 2 3@@EndFEN@@ to  3.e3  e6  4.Nf3  .  C@@EndBracket@@ White also has the rare and rather slow moves @@StartFEN@@rn1qkbnr/ppp2ppp/4p3/3p1b2/3P1B2/5N2/PPP1PPPP/RN1QKB1R w KQkq - 0 4@@EndFEN@@  4.c3  or  4.Nbd2  , which are answered with  4...Bd6  . This will usually transpose to the 3.e3 lines later, as White can hardly do without moving the e-pawn. }
