{ A quiet-looking move, but it has a point. After  5...Bd6  6.Ne5  White could use the same idea we employ, compared to @@StartFEN@@rn1qkb1r/ppp2ppp/4pn2/3p1b2/3P1B2/4PN2/PPP2PPP/RN1QKB1R w KQkq - 2 5@@EndFEN@@  5.Bd3  Ne4!?  , using an extra tempo. This wouldn't be fatal, but it looks like we have a simpler solution in 5...Nbd7.  Before we continue, a quick word about @@StartFEN@@rn1qkb1r/ppp2ppp/4pn2/3p1b2/3P1B2/4PN2/PPP2PPP/RN1QKB1R w KQkq - 2 5@@EndFEN@@  5.Be2  , which has a similar waiting approach in mind. Black certainly has some options against it, but we also like  5...Nbd7  against it.  Waiting with ...Bd6 defuses Ne5 ideas and looks like a good solution.  After 5.Be2 Nbd7 White quite often plays  6.Nbd2  , when we reach positions that can easily arise via @@StartFEN@@rn1qkb1r/ppp2ppp/4pn2/3p1b2/3P1B2/4PN2/PPP2PPP/RN1QKB1R w KQkq - 2 5@@EndFEN@@  5.Nbd2  Nbd7  6.Be2  − let's have a look. }
5... Nbd7
{ Delaying ...Bd6 defuses Ne5 ideas. Now  6.Ne5  is simply answered by  6...Nxe5  7.Bxe5  Bd6  , which is easy for Black to play. }
6. Be2
{ White has also tried the immediate  6.c4  , which will usually lead to some type of position that we are about to examine. We'll reply  6...Be7  and castle kingside next. After  7.Qb3  , both the solid  7...Qc8  or the more aggressive  7...O-O  are fine.  8.Qxb7?!  Rb8  9.Qxc7  Rxb2  gives Black great play for the pawn. In those lines,  White’s knight on d2 is too passive. }
6... Be7 7. O-O O-O 8. c4
{ White won't get anywhere without pushing this pawn to c4. As mentioned, this could have been played earlier, but we'd end up in the same type of position. }
8... c6
{ We suggest this move to keep some tension in the game. You could play  8...c5  and just keep the symmetry alive. This approach should equalize completely, but it is very tough to create some imbalance.  After  8...c6  ,  we avoided mass trades in the center. A good plan for Black is the advance of the a-pawn now, all the way to a4 and a3 if allowed. The goal is the creation of weaknesses. If White stops our pawn with a4, the square b4 becomes very weak. On the other hand, allowing our pawn to a3 also looks like a severe weakening.  This idea works because White's knight is on the relatively passive d2-square. If the knight was on c3, White could hope for a slight advantage. The knight would hinder our a-pawn advance, amongst other benefits. }
