{ White wants to exchange our bishop. This move is the most popular choice at this point, in particular below the master level. Black's simplest response is  5...Bxd3  , which leads to equal play without specific problems. But we want to suggest a different move, though. }
5... Ne4
{ This quirky knight jump is more fun to play than the more obvious capture on d3. Our idea is to play for the advance ...g5, usually prepared with ...Nd7 and ...Be7. This sets White players some problems that they might not even know when they opted for their quiet opening setup.   It's interesting to compare @@StartFEN@@rn1qkb1r/ppp2ppp/4pn2/3p1b2/3P1B2/4PN2/PPP2PPP/RN1QKB1R w KQkq - 2 5@@EndFEN@@  5.Bd3  Ne4  to @@StartFEN@@rn1qkb1r/ppp2ppp/4pn2/3p1b2/3P1B2/4PN2/PPP2PPP/RN1QKB1R w KQkq - 2 5@@EndFEN@@  5.Ne5  for White. A key difference is that after  5.Ne5  Nbd7  we threaten to take on e5, while White's extra tempo  after @@StartFEN@@rn1qkb1r/ppp2ppp/4pn2/3p1b2/3P1B2/4PN2/PPP2PPP/RN1QKB1R w KQkq - 2 5@@EndFEN@@  5.Bd3  Ne4  6.Nbd2  Nd7  makes the capture impossible.  We'll now have a look at the replies @@StartFEN@@rn1qkb1r/ppp2ppp/4p3/3p1b2/3PnB2/3BPN2/PPP2PPP/RN1QK2R w KQkq - 4 6@@EndFEN@@  6.Nbd2  and  6.O-O  . White should avoid  6.c4?!  when  6...Bb4+  is awkward to meet... White needs to move the king in reply. }
6. Nbd2
{ White puts some pressure on our knight immediately. There are two key differences to  6.O-O  , the second natural move that White frequently plays.  1. After  6.Nbd2  , White has a hard time playing the  c-pawn in the future, as the d3-bishop would be undefended. A sample line for this scenario  is  6.Nbd2  Nd7  7.c3??  Nxf2  , when Black wins.   2. White has the option g2-g4, which is important to consider when choosing the right move order. After  6.Nbd2  , we should avoid  6...Be7?!  as  7.g4!  is surprisingly strong. More on that later. }
6... Nd7
{ This looks best, but an interesting alternative is  6...Nc6!?  , which is  toying with the idea of ...Qd7 and a later queenside castling. Our move is more flexible and still allows us to play ...c5, attacking White's central pawn.   It's important to avoid  6...Be7?!  7.g4!  Bxg4  8.Nxe4  dxe4  9.Bxe4  c6  10.Rg1  , when White is better.  The g4 idea does not work after our move,  as @@StartFEN@@rn1qkb1r/ppp2ppp/4p3/3p1b2/3PnB2/3BPN2/PPPN1PPP/R2QK2R b KQkq - 5 6@@EndFEN@@  6...Nd7  7.g4  Bxg4  8.Nxe4  dxe4  9.Bxe4  c6  10.Rg1  Bh5  is fine for Black.  Our g-pawn is protected here, as the bishop is still on f8.   We'll investigate @@StartFEN@@r2qkb1r/pppn1ppp/4p3/3p1b2/3PnB2/3BPN2/PPPN1PPP/R2QK2R w KQkq - 6 7@@EndFEN@@  7.O-O  ,  7.Bxe4  and  7.Ne5  now. White has to avoid the blunder  7.c3?  Nxf2!  , which happens quite frequently in blitz games. }
7. Bxe4 { The start of interesting complications. } 7... dxe4
{ The only move, as  7...Bxe4?  8.Nxe4  dxe4  9.Nd2  f5  10.f3  is dreadful for Black. }
8. Ng5
{ Our e4-pawn is somewhat exposed, so White hurries to put some pressure on it. This idea is rather harmless, though. }
8... Nf6
{ The simple way, just covering the pawn. It looks like  8...e5!?  9.dxe5  Nc5  is an alternative, but it seems less reliable. }
9. Be5
{ White has to increase the pressure by tactical means. We were threatening ...h6, so concrete action was needed. }
9... Qd5
{ Instead, Black can also play  9...Nd7  10.Bf4  Nf6  or @@StartFEN@@r2qkb1r/ppp2ppp/4pn2/4BbN1/3Pp3/4P3/PPPN1PPP/R2QK2R b KQkq - 3 9@@EndFEN@@  9...Ng4  10.Bf4  Nf6  and agree to a draw. White has no good way of deviating, proving that 7.Bxe4 is not a challenging option.   We'd still like to suggest  9...Qd5  as it continues the game without taking unduly risks. We'll have a look at  10.Bxc7  now, but this is not forced, of course. If White plays  10.c4  , we have  10...Qc6  , keeping the pawns covered.  White has to worry about the g5-knight, as ...h6 would send it back to the unattractive h3-square. }
10. Bxc7
{ Wait, did we just hang a pawn? Let's see how to defuse the pawn grab. } 10...
Bg4
{ There is a cool alternative in  10...h6  11.Nh3  Bg4  12.Qc1  Qc6  , when Black has great compensation for the pawn. }
11. f3 Qxg5 12. Bf4
{ A cool sequence so far. It looks like White may end on top now, but we have a great resource. }
12... exf3 { Wow! } 13. Bxg5 fxg2
{ And we regain the material as we threaten the queen and the h1-rook with a pawn promotion on top! After  14.Rg1  Bxd1  , the position remains interesting and gives about equal chances. }
