6. Nbd2
{ White puts some pressure on our knight immediately. There are two key differences to  6.O-O  , the second natural move that White frequently plays.  1. After  6.Nbd2  , White has a hard time playing the  c-pawn in the future, as the d3-bishop would be undefended. A sample line for this scenario  is  6.Nbd2  Nd7  7.c3??  Nxf2  , when Black wins.   2. White has the option g2-g4, which is important to consider when choosing the right move order. After  6.Nbd2  , we should avoid  6...Be7?!  as  7.g4!  is surprisingly strong. More on that later. }
6... Nd7
{ This looks best, but an interesting alternative is  6...Nc6!?  , which is  toying with the idea of ...Qd7 and a later queenside castling. Our move is more flexible and still allows us to play ...c5, attacking White's central pawn.   It's important to avoid  6...Be7?!  7.g4!  Bxg4  8.Nxe4  dxe4  9.Bxe4  c6  10.Rg1  , when White is better.  The g4 idea does not work after our move,  as @@StartFEN@@rn1qkb1r/ppp2ppp/4p3/3p1b2/3PnB2/3BPN2/PPPN1PPP/R2QK2R b KQkq - 5 6@@EndFEN@@  6...Nd7  7.g4  Bxg4  8.Nxe4  dxe4  9.Bxe4  c6  10.Rg1  Bh5  is fine for Black.  Our g-pawn is protected here, as the bishop is still on f8.   We'll investigate @@StartFEN@@r2qkb1r/pppn1ppp/4p3/3p1b2/3PnB2/3BPN2/PPPN1PPP/R2QK2R w KQkq - 6 7@@EndFEN@@  7.O-O  ,  7.Bxe4  and  7.Ne5  now. White has to avoid the blunder  7.c3?  Nxf2!  , which happens quite frequently in blitz games. }
7. Ne5
{ White is going after trades but also preparing for f3 to expel our knight. }
7... Nxe5
{ We have an ambitious idea in mind, continuing with  7...Nxe5  8.Bxe5  f6  and chasing the white bishop. It's possible to play @@StartFEN@@r2qkb1r/pppn1ppp/4p3/3pNb2/3PnB2/3BP3/PPPN1PPP/R2QK2R b KQkq - 7 7@@EndFEN@@  7...Nxd2  8.Qxd2  Bxd3  and just equalize completely. In this scenario, the winning chances are minimal, though. We'd like to create a bit more tension. }
8. Bxe5 f6
{ It's still possible to go for the stale  8...Nxd2  , but our move leads to interesting play. }
9. Bf4
{ Here  9.Bg3?!  Nxg3  10.hxg3  Bxd3  11.cxd3  Qd7  looks very comfortable for Black. Our king will be safe on the queenside, and our pawn structure is much more flexible. }
9... g5
{ Moves like  9...h5  ,  9...Qd7  , or  9...Qe7  are possible too. It's good to see that there are plenty of ideas to counter the somewhat unambitious move 7.Ne5 by White. }
10. Bxe4
{ Again,  10.Bg3  Nxg3  11.hxg3  Bxd3  12.cxd3  Qd7  looks fine for Black. }
10... dxe4 11. Bg3
{ White is now ready for h2-h4, attacking our advanced pawn. } 11... Qd7
{ We are preparing for queenside castling and have reached a tense position. There are many possible options for both sides now. We'd like to show one interesting sequence. }
12. h4
{ How to answer this move? The important point to know is that  12...g4?  is a big mistake, as White could even castle kingside and have a stable position on this side of the board. }
12... Rg8
{ This is a good reply, as is  12...gxh4  . Now the position is tough to assess. The interesting point is that after both sides have castled queenside, Black might initiate an attack on this side of the board by unconventional means.  A possible line is @@StartFEN@@r3kbr1/pppq3p/4pp2/5bp1/3Pp2P/4P1B1/PPPN1PP1/R2QK2R w KQq - 1 13@@EndFEN@@  13.hxg5  Rxg5  14.Qe2  Qc6  15.O-O-O  O-O-O  , when you  can imagine ...Bg6 and a rook lift on the fifth rank. We are very deep down the rabbit hole here, but the main point was to show that we can generate chances in the 7.Ne5 line with some creative ideas. }
