{ The immediate  7...g5?  fails to  8.Bxe4  , but after the much better @@StartFEN@@r2qkb1r/pppn1ppp/4p3/3p1b2/3PnB2/3BPN2/PPPN1PPP/R2Q1RK1 b kq - 7 7@@EndFEN@@  7...Be7  , we are ready  for ...g5! next. Now White has a tough task... what to do about our threat? It's surprising to see that Stockfish regards  8.h3  as the only fully satisfactory move for White, which is a very tough move for a human to play. }
8. Ne5
{ This move was played most of the time in online games, so we use it as the main line. As mentioned, Stockfish suggests  8.h3  , but White's task after  8...g5  9.Bh2  h5  is certainly not enviable − Black has all the fun. The same applies to @@StartFEN@@r2qk2r/pppnbppp/4p3/3p1b2/3PnB2/3BPN2/PPPN1PPP/R2Q1RK1 w kq - 8 8@@EndFEN@@  8.Qe2  g5  or similar lines. }
8... g5 { Here we go! } 9. Bg3 Nxe5
{ This looks even a bit better than  9...h5  . } 10. dxe5
{ Or  10.Bxe5  f6  11.Bg3  Nxg3  12.fxg3  Bxd3  13.cxd3  h5  , which is great for Black. We will have a safe king on the queenside and an attack for free. }
10... h5
{ Black is in great shape here. We have a promising attacking setup on the kingside and no downsides in our position. }
