[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "19. London System 1.d4 d5 2.Bf4"]
[Black "London System 2.Bf4 Bf5 3.e3 #8"]
[Result "*"]

1. d4 d5 2. Bf4
{ Playing the bishop to f4 is the signature move of the London System. The London is White's most frequently played and challenging alternative to the Queen's Gambit. It's popular on all levels, from online games to classical time control games played in top GM events.  White's strategy after playing the bishop to f4 is not yet determined, but the pawn break c2-c4 or claiming control of the e5-square is still on the cards. Controlling this central square can be the start of a kingside initiative, often started by the move Ne5.  As we will see, against our answer, the symmetrical reply 2...Bf5, the first plan is the more challenging one.   A word about the move 2.Nf3: White often starts with  2.Nf3  and intends to play Bf4 on the next move. We answer  2.Nf3  with  2...Bf5  and cover this reply in two dedicated chapters. After  3.Bf4  , we'd reach a position that is covered in the current chapter. }
2... Bf5
{ After 2...Bf5 White's main choice  is between playing the move c4 soon or avoiding the pawn break favoring kingside development. This plan often involves playing for control of the e5-square, with a quick Ne5 and Nd2-f3 ideas.   White has many move orders to choose from. If c4 is intended, White can start with  3.c4  right away, but may also begin with  3.Nf3  or  3.e3  . Similarly, play can start with the kingside development scheme following  3.Nf3  or  3.e3  .   We decided to cover all c4-setups starting with the move order  3.c4  , while the kingside development plan is covered via  3.e3  . This means that in our coverage, the move order  3.Nf3  is more or less purely transpositional. Switching to our point of view, our move orders and ideas are fairly straightforward. Our next move will be  3...e6  , preparing kingside development.   One point of the  2...Bf5  move order, compared to  2...Nf6  first, is the delay  of the move ...Nf6. Not playing ...Nf6 early gives us additional options against some of White's plans, in particular against early Ne5 ideas. }
3. e3
{ The most flexible move. White can continue with c4 but also prioritize the development of the kingside. }
3... e6
{ The natural move. Of course, it's also possible to play  3...Nf6  first. It would be an almost certain transposition, as Black  needs both ...e6 and ...Nf6 to develop the kingside.  After  3...e6  , White's most active move is  4.c4  Nf6  , but this continuation transposes to lines that we examine via @@StartFEN@@rnbqkbnr/pppppppp/8/8/8/8/PPPPPPPP/RNBQKBNR w KQkq - 0 1@@EndFEN@@  1.d4  d5  2.Bf4  Bf5  3.c4  e6  4.e3  Nf6  .  This leaves the symmetrical @@StartFEN@@rn1qkbnr/ppp2ppp/4p3/3p1b2/3P1B2/4P3/PPP2PPP/RN1QKBNR w KQkq - 0 4@@EndFEN@@  4.Nf3  and  4.Bd3  to examine. In both cases, White has some very conservative options. We'll try to create some tension without taking unduly risks. }
4. Nf3
{ This position arises very frequently, as White can also start with move orders like @@StartFEN@@rnbqkbnr/pppppppp/8/8/8/8/PPPPPPPP/RNBQKBNR w KQkq - 0 1@@EndFEN@@  1.d4  d5  2.Bf4  Bf5  3.Nf3  e6  4.e3  , leading to the same position. Now we have a good choice between two moves: the symmetrical  4...Nf6  and  4...Bd6  . Please note that  4...c5?  is a rather big mistake, as  5.Bxb8!  is excellent for White.  We play the following variation: @@StartFEN@@rnbqkbnr/pppppppp/8/8/8/8/PPPPPPPP/RNBQKBNR w KQkq - 0 1@@EndFEN@@  1.d4  d5  2.Bf4  Bf5  3.c4  e6  4.e3  Nf6  5.Nf3  Bxb1  , which is fine for Black. A tempo up on this line is too much to bear, so we need to avoid @@StartFEN@@rn1qkbnr/ppp2ppp/4p3/3p1b2/3P1B2/4PN2/PPP2PPP/RN1QKB1R b KQkq - 1 4@@EndFEN@@  4...c5?  here. So what to play:  4...Bd6  or  4...Nf6  ?  We suggest  4...Nf6  , as this gives us more chances to reach a more complicated position. Still,  4...Bd6  looks perfectly fine and could be played as an alternative without any deep theoretical knowledge needed. }
4... Nf6
{ We suggest this move, completing the symmetry. The main reason for choosing  4...Nf6  is that we have exciting replies against White's most popular continuations. Let's have a look:  A@@EndBracket@@  5.Bd3  is most commonly played. We suggest the aggressive move  5...Ne4!?  , trying to unbalance the game.   B@@EndBracket@@  5.Be2  and  5.Nbd2  are super-solid options for White. We should play symmetrically against them.   C@@EndBracket@@  5.Ne5  Nbd7  can lead to fun complications after  6.g4?!  Nxg4!  , as we will see.   D@@EndBracket@@  5.c4  Bxb1!  transposes to a critical line that we examine via the move order @@StartFEN@@rn1qkbnr/ppp1pppp/8/3p1b2/3P1B2/8/PPP1PPPP/RN1QKBNR w KQkq - 2 3@@EndFEN@@  3.c4  e6  4.e3  Nf6  5.Nf3  Bxb1! }
5. Bd3
{ White wants to exchange our bishop. This move is the most popular choice at this point, in particular below the master level. Black's simplest response is  5...Bxd3  , which leads to equal play without specific problems. But we want to suggest a different move, though. }
5... Ne4
{ This quirky knight jump is more fun to play than the more obvious capture on d3. Our idea is to play for the advance ...g5, usually prepared with ...Nd7 and ...Be7. This sets White players some problems that they might not even know when they opted for their quiet opening setup.   It's interesting to compare @@StartFEN@@rn1qkb1r/ppp2ppp/4pn2/3p1b2/3P1B2/4PN2/PPP2PPP/RN1QKB1R w KQkq - 2 5@@EndFEN@@  5.Bd3  Ne4  to @@StartFEN@@rn1qkb1r/ppp2ppp/4pn2/3p1b2/3P1B2/4PN2/PPP2PPP/RN1QKB1R w KQkq - 2 5@@EndFEN@@  5.Ne5  for White. A key difference is that after  5.Ne5  Nbd7  we threaten to take on e5, while White's extra tempo  after @@StartFEN@@rn1qkb1r/ppp2ppp/4pn2/3p1b2/3P1B2/4PN2/PPP2PPP/RN1QKB1R w KQkq - 2 5@@EndFEN@@  5.Bd3  Ne4  6.Nbd2  Nd7  makes the capture impossible.  We'll now have a look at the replies @@StartFEN@@rn1qkb1r/ppp2ppp/4p3/3p1b2/3PnB2/3BPN2/PPP2PPP/RN1QK2R w KQkq - 4 6@@EndFEN@@  6.Nbd2  and  6.O-O  . White should avoid  6.c4?!  when  6...Bb4+  is awkward to meet... White needs to move the king in reply. }
6. O-O
{ White castles and keeps some flexibility regarding the queenside formation. }
6... Nd7
{ We suggest playing in the same way as after 6.Nbd2, developing the knight to d7.   Now White will often play  7.Nbd2  Be7!  when we transpose to @@StartFEN@@rn1qkb1r/ppp2ppp/4p3/3p1b2/3PnB2/3BPN2/PPP2PPP/RN1QK2R w KQkq - 4 6@@EndFEN@@  6.Nbd2  Nd7  7.O-O  Be7  , which is attractive for Black to play. Instead, we'll examine @@StartFEN@@r2qkb1r/pppn1ppp/4p3/3p1b2/3PnB2/3BPN2/PPP2PPP/RN1Q1RK1 w kq - 6 7@@EndFEN@@  7.c4  , which looks logical in connection to 6.O-O. }
7. c4 dxc4
{ This is best. After a passive move like  7...c6?  , we can't justify  the time loss involved with ...Ne4. After that,  amongst others,  8.Nc3  White is better. }
8. Bxc4 g5
{ That's the point. We need to justify the ...Ne4 sortie with concrete play against the bishop. }
9. Bg3 h5 { Here we go! Now White has a tough task: how to defend? } 10. Bd3
{ Stockfish points out this move, and it is the only good move for White! This is not at all obvious, as  10...h4  11.Be5  f6  looks awful for White at first. A closer look reveals that  12.Qc2!  is possible, showing the point of 10.Bd3 − not easy to see beforehand!  White might still find @@StartFEN@@r2qkb1r/pppn1p2/4p3/5bpp/2BPn3/4PNB1/PP3PPP/RN1Q1RK1 w kq - 0 10@@EndFEN@@  10.Bd3  with enough time available, as you could get to the move by the process of elimination. Other tries are much worse, for example,  10.h4  gxh4  11.Nxh4  Bg4  . }
10... Nxg3
{ The most straightforward move, but there are good alternatives, for example,  10...Bg7  . We suggest the capture, trying to quickly castle queenside. }
11. hxg3
{ Better than  11.fxg3  Bxd3  12.Qxd3  g4  13.Nh4  Qg5  , when Black is better. We are ready to castle queenside, as  14.Nd2  O-O-O  15.Rxf7??  Ne5!  is a neat trick. }
11... Bxd3 { One of many good moves.  11...Qf6  or  11...h4  look fine too. }
12. Qxd3 g4 13. Nh4 Qg5
{ Again, there are many good alternatives, like  13...Be7  or  13...c6  . They all lead to fun play. With  13...Qg5  , we prepare for queenside castling immediately.  White is suffering from the badly placed knight on the edge of the board, which is why we think Black has good chances. Stockfish evaluates the situation as equal, but White's job is tougher, in our opinion. }
*

