{ After 2...Bf5 White's main choice  is between playing the move c4 soon or avoiding the pawn break favoring kingside development. This plan often involves playing for control of the e5-square, with a quick Ne5 and Nd2-f3 ideas.   White has many move orders to choose from. If c4 is intended, White can start with  3.c4  right away, but may also begin with  3.Nf3  or  3.e3  . Similarly, play can start with the kingside development scheme following  3.Nf3  or  3.e3  .   We decided to cover all c4-setups starting with the move order  3.c4  , while the kingside development plan is covered via  3.e3  . This means that in our coverage, the move order  3.Nf3  is more or less purely transpositional. Switching to our point of view, our move orders and ideas are fairly straightforward. Our next move will be  3...e6  , preparing kingside development.   One point of the  2...Bf5  move order, compared to  2...Nf6  first, is the delay  of the move ...Nf6. Not playing ...Nf6 early gives us additional options against some of White's plans, in particular against early Ne5 ideas. }
3. c4
{ White plays the typical Queen's Gambit move c4, putting pressure on the d5-pawn. This approach is possible immediately or after preparing the move with  3.e3  first. We chose the move order  3.c4  , as White has some possible options to play  without the move e3. }
3... e6
{ The natural reply. We cover the d5-pawn and prepare for kingside development. }
4. Qb3 { White chooses the wrong moment for the queen sortie. } 4... Nc6
{ The active reply is best. Now we not only have ...Nb4 ideas, but we can also attack the d4-pawn! }
5. e3
{ White hurries to cover d4, but there is the other idea of ...Nc6 that White couldn't prevent at the same time. }
5... Nb4 6. Na3
{ No choice for White at this point. Now our opponent's queenside is uncoordinated. The a3-knight is tied to the defence of c2, which means that White can't quickly play a pawn to a3 to evict our annoying b4-knight. }
6... c6
{ An important move. After  6...Nf6?!  7.c5!  White has reasonable chances. After @@StartFEN@@r2qkbnr/ppp2ppp/4p3/3p1b2/1nPP1B2/NQ2P3/PP3PPP/R3KBNR b KQkq - 2 6@@EndFEN@@  6...c6!  the move  7.c5?  even loses due to  7...Qa5! }
7. Nf3 Nf6
{ Both sides continue with normal development. We continue this line to show an active option for Black on the next move. }
8. Be2 dxc4
{ Giving up the central pawn on d5 is not the most obvious choice, but we capture on c4 for a concrete reason. After White's recapture, we are ready to advance pawns on the queenside and build a nice initiative. We also gain access to the d5-square, which is useful. }
9. Bxc4 a5
{ We lend additional protection to the knight and get a5-a4 on the map. } 10.
O-O Nfd5
{ Black is in excellent shape. White can't retreat the f4-bishop because we are threatening something with 10...Nfd5. }
11. Bg3
{ White has to play a move like  11.Be2  , but Black is clearly for choice after  11...Nxf4  , amongst others. }
11... Bc2 12. Nxc2 a4 13. Qa3 Nxc2 { And Black wins! } *

