{ We develop the knight and get one move closer to kingside castling. The alternative  4...Bd6  looks less convincing after  5.Bxd6  Qxd6  6.Qb3  , when White has annoying pressure on the queenside. }
5. Qb3
{ White immediately attacks a soft spot in our camp, the b7-pawn. The moves  5.Nc3  and  5.Nf3  look logical too. These options are covered via the move order @@StartFEN@@rn1qkbnr/ppp2ppp/4p3/3p1b2/2PP1B2/8/PP2PPPP/RN1QKBNR w KQkq - 0 4@@EndFEN@@  4.Nc3  Nf6  5.e3  and @@StartFEN@@rn1qkbnr/ppp2ppp/4p3/3p1b2/2PP1B2/8/PP2PPPP/RN1QKBNR w KQkq - 0 4@@EndFEN@@  4.Nf3  Nf6  5.e3  . }
5... Nc6
{ Similar to other cases in our repertoire, this active reply is best. We should avoid passive play like  5...Qc8?!  or pawn structure concessions like  5...b6?!  After the best move  5...Nc6  ,  the pawn on b7 can't be taken, as we will see.  White should rather develop with  6.Nc3  , which we examine via a different move order: @@StartFEN@@rn1qkbnr/ppp2ppp/4p3/3p1b2/2PP1B2/8/PP2PPPP/RN1QKBNR w KQkq - 0 4@@EndFEN@@  4.Nc3  Nf6  5.Qb3  Nc6  6.e3  leads to the same position. }
6. c5
{ A mistake, but it's good to know how to exploit it. White has also tried the slow  6.a3  , when  6...Na5  7.Qa4+  c6  8.c5  b5!  is fine for Black. }
6... e5
{ Much better than the lame  6...Rb8?!  Black immediately opens the game, realizing that we can always answer the capture  on b7 with the cool reply ...Bd7! }
7. dxe5
{ White's center is falling apart after this move, but we need to check the tactical complications after the following pawn grab on b7. }
7... Ne4 8. Qxb7
{ The only move worth checking. Otherwise, we'd play ...Nxc5 next. } 8... Bd7
9. Bb5 { This is surprisingly challenging to meet. } 9... Nxc5 10. Qxc6
{ The big point of 9.Bb5. } 10... Be7
{ This is a lot stronger than taking the queen! After  10...Bxc6+  11.Bxc6+  Nd7  12.Nc3  White is still able to put up a fight.   After the amazing  10...Be7!  we threaten to take the queen under more favorable circumstances,  as the reply Bxc6+ can now be answered with ...Kf8. }
11. Qxd5
{ After  11.Nc3  Bxc6  12.Bxc6+  Kf8  13.Bxa8  Qxa8  Black is winning easily.  A key point is the knight on c5, threatening to jump to d3 with a check. }
11... Bxb5
{ Black has overwhelming compensation for the pawn. The attack on the light squares with ...Nd3+ on the horizon is unstoppable. }
