3. c4
{ White plays the typical Queen's Gambit move c4, putting pressure on the d5-pawn. This approach is possible immediately or after preparing the move with  3.e3  first. We chose the move order  3.c4  , as White has some possible options to play  without the move e3. }
3... e6
{ The natural reply. We cover the d5-pawn and prepare for kingside development. }
4. Nc3
{ White's most popular move. It increases the pressure on the d5-pawn and avoids a possible capture on b1, followed by Bb4+. This idea is relevant in lines like @@StartFEN@@rn1qkbnr/ppp2ppp/4p3/3p1b2/2PP1B2/8/PP2PPPP/RN1QKBNR w KQkq - 0 4@@EndFEN@@  4.e3  Nf6  5.Nf3  Bxb1  6.Rxb1  Bb4+  , when White needs to move the king. }
4... Nf6
{ We continue to develop and get one move closer to castling. Now White's main move is the natural  5.e3  , but  5.Nf3  and  5.Qb3  are worth checking too. }
5. Nf3
{ The position after this natural move may also arise via @@StartFEN@@rn1qkbnr/ppp2ppp/4p3/3p1b2/2PP1B2/8/PP2PPPP/RN1QKBNR w KQkq - 0 4@@EndFEN@@  4.Nf3  Nf6  5.Nc3  . }
5... Bb4
{ Our preferred way to develop is playing in the style of the Ragozin. After this move, we will focus on the reply  6.Qa4+  , followed by  6...Nc6  7.Ne5  . There are various ways to transpose to other lines.  A@@EndBracket@@ @@StartFEN@@rn1qk2r/ppp2ppp/4pn2/3p1b2/1bPP1B2/2N2N2/PP2PPPP/R2QKB1R w KQkq - 4 6@@EndFEN@@  6.Qb3  Nc6  @@StartBracket@@  6...c5!?  is reasonable too@@EndBracket@@ leads to @@StartFEN@@rn1qkb1r/ppp2ppp/4pn2/3p1b2/2PP1B2/2N5/PP2PPPP/R2QKBNR w KQkq - 2 5@@EndFEN@@  5.Qb3  Nc6  6.Nf3  Bb4  .  B@@EndBracket@@ @@StartFEN@@rn1qk2r/ppp2ppp/4pn2/3p1b2/1bPP1B2/2N2N2/PP2PPPP/R2QKB1R w KQkq - 4 6@@EndFEN@@  6.e3  O-O  is very natural and examined via @@StartFEN@@rn1qkb1r/ppp2ppp/4pn2/3p1b2/2PP1B2/2N5/PP2PPPP/R2QKBNR w KQkq - 2 5@@EndFEN@@  5.e3  Bb4  6.Nf3  O-O  . }
6. Qa4+
{ White forces our knight to c6, but we don't mind. As we will see, our development is excellent, and the concrete lines work well for Black. }
6... Nc6 7. Ne5
{ White almost always plays this move. After the rare  7.e3  Ne4  , we'd transpose to @@StartFEN@@rn1qkb1r/ppp2ppp/4pn2/3p1b2/2PP1B2/2N5/PP2PPPP/R2QKBNR w KQkq - 2 5@@EndFEN@@  5.e3  Bb4  6.Qa4+  Nc6  7.Nf3  Ne4  , when White is fighting for equality. After @@StartFEN@@r2qk2r/ppp2ppp/2n1pn2/3p1b2/QbPP1B2/2N2N2/PP2PPPP/R3KB1R w KQkq - 6 7@@EndFEN@@  7.Ne5  White threatens  on c6, we have a cunning reply. }
7... Rb8
{ A strong move and a novelty according to Mega Database 2022. After Nxc6, our b4-bishop is attacked by the white queen. Our rook provides cover for the bishop − a surprising 'x-ray move'.   White can still win a pawn with  8.Nxc6  , but we get excellent play for a minimal material investment. }
8. Nxc6
{ As mentioned, 7...Rb8! is a new move, so we don't have any game samples to refer to. Taking on c6 and winning the pawn is certainly White's most natural move.   Stockfish also suggests the surprising  8.g4!?  , which is likely not played as an over-the-board inspiration. After  8...Nxg4  9.Nxc6  bxc6  10.Qxc6+  Qd7  11.Qxd7+  Kxd7  12.f3  Nf6  we have reached a position with material equality.   White won a pawn on c6 but gave up the g-pawn to get in f3 with a tempo, controlling the e4-square. Chances are equal, but we like Black's prospects. All the pieces are active, which is always a bonus. }
8... bxc6 9. Qxc6+ Qd7 10. Qxc7
{ Gordon Gekko said, 'Greed is good!', but he certainly didn't talk about this chess position. Snatching c7 is too much. }
10... Qxc7 11. Bxc7 Rb7 12. Bf4 Ba5
{ This is the important point! We attack b2, and White has no good way to defend the pawn. Black is much better! }
