{ We have now reached a position that frequently arises via different move orders. After @@StartFEN@@rn1qkbnr/ppp2ppp/4p3/3p1b2/2PP1B2/8/PP2PPPP/RN1QKBNR w KQkq - 0 4@@EndFEN@@  4.e3  Nf6  5.Nc3  Bb4  6.Qb3  Nc6  or @@StartFEN@@rn1qkbnr/ppp2ppp/4p3/3p1b2/2PP1B2/8/PP2PPPP/RN1QKBNR w KQkq - 0 4@@EndFEN@@  4.Nc3  Nf6  5.e3  Bb4  6.Qb3  Nc6  we get the same position. }
7. a3
{ White badly wants to gain the bishop pair, but it's an awfully slow move. It turns out that White has to be very careful to avoid trouble now. }
7... Bxc3+ 8. bxc3
{ White wants to avoid ...Ne4 with a tempo, but a later ...Na5 is still on the agenda for us.   8.Qxc3  looks like the better choice, but we'll check both recaptures. }
8... O-O
{ Speeding up development. Now the threat ...Na5 is very annoying for White. }
9. Qxb7
{ That's still worth checking. After  9.cxd5  Nxd5  10.Bg3  Na5  11.Qb2  c5  12.dxc5  Qf6  Black is much better without any difficulties. This looks like the best Nimzo-Indian/Ragozin ever. }
9... e5 { Not the most obvious move, but it is powerful. } 10. Bg5
{ Even worse is  10.dxe5?  Na5  11.Qb4  c5  , which looks like a quick win for us. }
10... Qd7
{ We unpin and cover the c6-knight. White is in trouble now, being so much behind in development. }
