4... Nf6
{ We continue to develop and get one move closer to castling. Now White's main move is the natural  5.e3  , but  5.Nf3  and  5.Qb3  are worth checking too. }
5. e3 { The most flexible and natural move for White. } 5... Bb4
{ An important move! We want to play as actively as possible, in the style of the Nimzo-Indian @@StartFEN@@rnbqkbnr/pppppppp/8/8/8/8/PPPPPPPP/RNBQKBNR w KQkq - 0 1@@EndFEN@@  1.d4  Nf6  2.c4  e6  3.Nc3  Bb4  , or the Ragozin @@StartFEN@@rnbqkbnr/pppppppp/8/8/8/8/PPPPPPPP/RNBQKBNR w KQkq - 0 1@@EndFEN@@  1.d4  d5  2.c4  e6  3.Nf3  Nf6  4.Nc3  Bb4  , but with the  added moves Bf4 and ...Bf5. This leads to an interesting struggle that theory has not yet deeply covered.  Let's have a look at White's options.  A@@EndBracket@@ @@StartFEN@@rn1qk2r/ppp2ppp/4pn2/3p1b2/1bPP1B2/2N1P3/PP3PPP/R2QKBNR w KQkq - 1 6@@EndFEN@@  6.Qb3  is the most popular move. We suggest  6...Nc6  , which transposes to a line that we can reach via other move orders, for example, @@StartFEN@@rnbqkbnr/pppppppp/8/8/8/8/PPPPPPPP/RNBQKBNR w KQkq - 0 1@@EndFEN@@  1.d4  d5  2.Bf4  Bf5  3.c4  e6  4.Nc3  Nf6  5.Qb3  Nc6  6.e3  Bb4  , which gives Black good chances.  It also possible to answer @@StartFEN@@rn1qk2r/ppp2ppp/4pn2/3p1b2/1bPP1B2/2N1P3/PP3PPP/R2QKBNR w KQkq - 1 6@@EndFEN@@  6.Qb3  with  6...c5!?  , but it does not seem better than  6...Nc6  , so we suggest going for the transposition.  B@@EndBracket@@ @@StartFEN@@rn1qk2r/ppp2ppp/4pn2/3p1b2/1bPP1B2/2N1P3/PP3PPP/R2QKBNR w KQkq - 1 6@@EndFEN@@  6.Nf3  looks like the most natural move, besides option A. We answer  6...O-O  and stay flexible. We'll have a closer look at this line in a moment.  C@@EndBracket@@ @@StartFEN@@rn1qk2r/ppp2ppp/4pn2/3p1b2/1bPP1B2/2N1P3/PP3PPP/R2QKBNR w KQkq - 1 6@@EndFEN@@  6.a3  Bxc3+  7.bxc3  c5  is unexplored but should certainly be fine for Black. White has many pawn weaknesses that we can exploit  later with Qa5, for example.   D@@EndBracket@@ @@StartFEN@@rn1qk2r/ppp2ppp/4pn2/3p1b2/1bPP1B2/2N1P3/PP3PPP/R2QKBNR w KQkq - 1 6@@EndFEN@@  6.Qa4+  Nc6  looks like a worse version of line A,  as the queen can't be any better on a4 compared to b3. A continuation like  7.Nf3  Ne4  looks easy to play for Black. }
6. Nf3
{ This developing move looks like White's best bet, besides the popular  6.Qb3  Nc6  , which we examine via a different move order. This is discussed more in the notes to move  5.   6.Nge2  dxc4  is fine for Black. After  7.a3  Ba5  , White is already fighting for equality. }
6... O-O
{ We stay flexible. Now we'll have a look at  7.Qb3  and  7.Be2  , which both look sensible. We'd be happy about  7.a3  Bxc3+  8.bxc3  c5  , when White's queenside is weak. }
7. Be2 Ne4
{ Alternatives like  7...c5  , or  7...dxc4  8.Bxc4  c5  are fine, as well. Our choice is a bit more aggressive. }
8. Qb3
{ White can't play  8.Rc1?  as  8...Nxc3  9.bxc3  Ba3  picks up the exchange. White's rook can't escape the scope of the bishops. }
8... Nc6 { We now threaten ...Bxc3+, followed by ...Na5. } 9. O-O
{ White continues with development but allows the mentioned plan. Taking on d5 is possible, but both  9.cxd5  exd5  and @@StartFEN@@r2q1rk1/ppp2ppp/2n1p3/3p1b2/1bPPnB2/1QN1PN2/PP2BPPP/R3K2R w KQ - 7 9@@EndFEN@@  9.cxd5  Qxd5  look perfectly fine for Black. Our pieces are very active, and we have no weaknesses. }
9... Bxc3 10. bxc3 Na5 11. Qb4 Nxc4 12. Bxc4 dxc4 13. Qxc4 c5
{ Black has a slight advantage. White's queenside and the light squares are weak. }
