5. Qb3
{ White can play the move Qb3 in various versions. There are sequences like @@StartFEN@@rn1qkbnr/ppp1pppp/8/3p1b2/3P1B2/8/PPP1PPPP/RN1QKBNR w KQkq - 2 3@@EndFEN@@  3.c4  e6  4.Qb3  ,  3.c4  e6  4.Nc3  Nf6  5.Qb3  or @@StartFEN@@rn1qkbnr/ppp1pppp/8/3p1b2/3P1B2/8/PPP1PPPP/RN1QKBNR w KQkq - 2 3@@EndFEN@@  3.e3  e6  4.c4  Nf6  5.Qb3  .   In all cases, we want to avoid a passive or weakening reply like ...Qc8 or ...b6 and instead defend actively. This is usually accomplished by ignoring the threat to the b7-pawn and developing the knight on c6.  This is the way we handle the three mentioned sample sequences, and the current position is no exception. Still, it's worth mentioning that Black has a good alternative here, the capture on c4.  After @@StartFEN@@rn1qkb1r/ppp2ppp/4pn2/3p1b2/2PP1B2/1Q3N2/PP2PPPP/RN2KB1R b KQkq - 3 5@@EndFEN@@  5...dxc4  6.Qxb7  Be4  7.Qxc7  Qxc7  8.Bxc7  Bb4+  , Black is a pawn down for a while but gets reasonable compensation.   Currently, Black's chances look okay in this line, but we see a practical drawback. It requires a substantial effort to learn, but the resulting endgames will not give Black great winning chances in many cases. On the other hand, our move 5...Nc6 leads to combative and still relatively unexplored positions. }
