6. Qxb7
{ The greedy capture is not bad objectively, but White has to be very careful. We get a strong initiative − the best that White can hope for is equality with perfect play. We need to check the move in detail, as taking the pawn is certainly a principled way of playing. }
6... Nb4 7. Na3 { There is nothing else, White has to cover c2. } 7... dxc4
{ The only good move. We take the pawn but, more importantly, clear the d5-square for our pieces. Our knights and the queen might use this square, but ...Be4-d5 is also an important idea. }
8. Nb5
{ White goes for a counterattack on c7. This is the start of a long, forced sequence. }
8... Nfd5
{ We cover c7, attack f4, and still threaten ...Nc2+, leading to a crazy position. It looks like perfect play leads to equality now; let's have a look. }
9. Rc1 { The best move is getting out of the fork. } 9... Rb8
{ This forces the following trades. } 10. Nxc7+ Nxc7 11. Qxc7 Qxc7 12. Bxc7 Rb7
13. Rxc4 Nd5
{ A much better choice than  13...Nxa2?  14.Ba5  Rxb2  15.Rc8+  , when Black's coordination is severely lacking. Instead, @@StartFEN@@4kb1r/prB2ppp/4p3/5b2/1nRP4/5N2/PP2PPPP/4KB1R b Kk - 0 13@@EndFEN@@  13...Nc2+  is possible and should lead to equal chances. }
14. Ba5 Rxb2
{ And now there are some ways to a forced draw, for example,  15.Rc8+  Ke7  16.Ne5  Rb1+  17.Kd2  Rb2+  or  16.Ne5  Rb1+  17.Kd2  Rb2+  leads to repetition.  This whole line, starting with 6.Qxb7, seems very unlikely to happen, but we need to be prepared in case someone dares to grab the pawn and then proceed to find all the correct defensive moves. }
