{ The usual reply to Qb3 ideas. We need to consider two replies,  6.c5  and mostly  6.Nbd2  , which is surprisingly challenging. We'll also have a look at  6.Qxb7  , but we'll get good chances against this greedy move. It's not necessary to examine  6.e3?!  Nb4  or @@StartFEN@@r2qkb1r/ppp2ppp/2n1pn2/3p1b2/2PP1B2/1Q3N2/PP2PPPP/RN2KB1R w KQkq - 4 6@@EndFEN@@  6.a3?!  dxc4  7.Qxb7?  Na5  in any detail, as they don't pose any particular challenge. }
6. Qxb7
{ The greedy capture is not bad objectively, but White has to be very careful. We get a strong initiative − the best that White can hope for is equality with perfect play. We need to check the move in detail, as taking the pawn is certainly a principled way of playing. }
6... Nb4 7. Na3 { There is nothing else, White has to cover c2. } 7... dxc4
{ The only good move. We take the pawn but, more importantly, clear the d5-square for our pieces. Our knights and the queen might use this square, but ...Be4-d5 is also an important idea. }
8. Bxc7 { White grabs a second pawn, but this is decidedly too much. } 8... Qc8
{ That's even stronger than  8...Qd5  , which is good enough for a significant advantage. }
9. Qxc8+
{ Or  9.Qb5+  Nd7  10.Qxc4  Qb7  , when White is helpless against the  threat ...Rc8. }
9... Rxc8 10. Ba5 c3
{ The important point. Black is breaking through on the queenside. } 11. bxc3
Rxc3 12. Nb5 Rc8
{ And finally, we can conclude that White is helpless against the ...Nc2+ threat. }
