10... Bd5 11. Qc1
{ Now we need to be precise as the most obvious move fails. After  11...Nxa2?  12.Qb1  , our knight is attacked, but at the same time,  White threatens e4, trapping our bishop in the middle of the board! }
11... Rc8
{ Much better than the capture on a2. We threaten ...c5 now, opening the c-file. }
12. Qb1 { Aiming for the e4-push. Now Black has a range of exciting options. }
12... c5
{ This is probably the most logical move, but  12...Nh5  or  12...Qa5  are interesting as well. }
13. e4 Ba8
{ We suggest this move to continue the game. Why continue the game? Well, it looks like  13...cxd4!?  14.exd5  d3  leads to a forced draw after further complications. Instead, our move avoids a forced line and keeps the tension.   It is better to retreat to a8 than  13...Bc6  , as we'd like  to have the c6-square for our knight.  After  14.Nac4  White  threatens a3 when we have no good retreat.   After the much better  13...Ba8  , we reach a complicated position with multiple possibilities. In case of  14.Bb5+  we have  14...Bc6  , while after @@StartFEN@@b1rqkb1r/p4ppp/4pn2/2p5/1n1PPB2/N7/PP1N1PPP/RQ2KB1R w KQk - 1 14@@EndFEN@@  14.Nac4  we can play  14...cxd4  , amongst others.   We can conclude that White can take on b7, but it is a risky move, and often our opponent needs to dodge bullets to stay in the game afterwards. }
