{ This move is probably the most challenging at this point. The square d2 is not particularly attractive for the knight at first sight, but it covers c4 and therefore secures White's position against ...Na5 ideas. }
6... Be7
{ An important move! It is much better to avoid the slow  6...Rb8  and instead continue with development. After  6...Be7  , White can't take  on b7 anyway,  as  7.Qxb7?  Nb4  is great for Black.   A good alternative to  6...Be7  is  6...a5  , though. We will  see that ...a5 is an idea after  6...Be7  , and often both moves will be part of our setup.  Before we continue, a word about  6...Nb4?  This move falls short due to  7.Rc1  a5  8.c5  when we have no good way to justify the knight jump. After choosing @@StartFEN@@r2qkb1r/ppp2ppp/2n1pn2/3p1b2/2PP1B2/1Q3N2/PP1NPPPP/R3KB1R b KQkq - 5 6@@EndFEN@@  6...Be7  , we will examine  7.e3  and  7.cxd5  . As already mentioned,  7.Qxb7?  Nb4  is good for Black. White could play  7.c5  when  7...Rb8  leads to a position quite similar to @@StartFEN@@r2qkb1r/ppp2ppp/2n1pn2/3p1b2/2PP1B2/1Q3N2/PP2PPPP/RN2KB1R w KQkq - 4 6@@EndFEN@@  6.c5  Rb8  . }
7. cxd5 Qxd5
{ This is much more dynamic and stronger than  7...exd5  . White now has to reckon  with ...Qxb3, ...Nb4, and ...Nxd4. }
8. Rc1
{ This is the best defense. White has to avoid  8.Qxb7??  Rb8  9.Qxc7  O-O  , when White's queen is in deep trouble. White also can't play @@StartFEN@@r3k2r/ppp1bppp/2n1pn2/3q1b2/3P1B2/1Q3N2/PP1NPPPP/R3KB1R w KQkq - 0 8@@EndFEN@@  8.Qxd5?  Nxd5  9.Bg3  Ndb4  ,  as ...Nc2+ is too awkward to meet. }
8... Qxb3
{ Moves like  8...Bd6  or  8...O-O  are fine too. The queen trade has a concrete idea in mind. }
9. Nxb3 Ne4
{ That's the idea. We centralize the knight, making ...g5 possible and the ...Bb4+ ideas stronger. White can't take the c-pawn... let's check why.   After  10.Bxc7?  Bb4+  11.Nbd2  Rc8  12.Bg3  O-O  White is helpless against our attack.  The threat is ...Nxd4, which even works after  13.e3  Nxd4  − a cool line! }
10. a3 { Covering b4, but we have an aggressive reply. } 10... g5
{ More powerful than the conservative  10...Bd6  . What happens if White takes the pawn? }
11. Bxc7 Rc8 12. Ba5
{ Very odd, but  12.Bg3  O-O  13.e3  Na5  14.Rxc8  Rxc8  15.Nxa5  Rc1+  16.Ke2  Rc2+  17.Ke1  Rxb2  is already game over for White. Black has a decisive attack, even though queens are traded. }
12... O-O 13. Bc3 b5
{ Black has great initiative for the pawn, an excellent opening result. Note that White had to dodge some bullets to get here in the first place. }
