1. d4 d5 2. Bf4
{ Playing the bishop to f4 is the signature move of the London System. The London is White's most frequently played and challenging alternative to the Queen's Gambit. It's popular on all levels, from online games to classical time control games played in top GM events.  White's strategy after playing the bishop to f4 is not yet determined, but the pawn break c2-c4 or claiming control of the e5-square is still on the cards. Controlling this central square can be the start of a kingside initiative, often started by the move Ne5.  As we will see, against our answer, the symmetrical reply 2...Bf5, the first plan is the more challenging one.   A word about the move 2.Nf3: White often starts with  2.Nf3  and intends to play Bf4 on the next move. We answer  2.Nf3  with  2...Bf5  and cover this reply in two dedicated chapters. After  3.Bf4  , we'd reach a position that is covered in the current chapter. }
2... Bf5
{ After 2...Bf5 White's main choice  is between playing the move c4 soon or avoiding the pawn break favoring kingside development. This plan often involves playing for control of the e5-square, with a quick Ne5 and Nd2-f3 ideas.   White has many move orders to choose from. If c4 is intended, White can start with  3.c4  right away, but may also begin with  3.Nf3  or  3.e3  . Similarly, play can start with the kingside development scheme following  3.Nf3  or  3.e3  .   We decided to cover all c4-setups starting with the move order  3.c4  , while the kingside development plan is covered via  3.e3  . This means that in our coverage, the move order  3.Nf3  is more or less purely transpositional. Switching to our point of view, our move orders and ideas are fairly straightforward. Our next move will be  3...e6  , preparing kingside development.   One point of the  2...Bf5  move order, compared to  2...Nf6  first, is the delay  of the move ...Nf6. Not playing ...Nf6 early gives us additional options against some of White's plans, in particular against early Ne5 ideas. }
3. c4
{ White plays the typical Queen's Gambit move c4, putting pressure on the d5-pawn. This approach is possible immediately or after preparing the move with  3.e3  first. We chose the move order  3.c4  , as White has some possible options to play  without the move e3. }
3... e6
{ The natural reply. We cover the d5-pawn and prepare for kingside development. }
4. Nf3
{ This position arises frequently via @@StartFEN@@rnbqkbnr/ppp1pppp/8/3p4/3P4/8/PPP1PPPP/RNBQKBNR w KQkq - 0 2@@EndFEN@@  2.Nf3  Bf5  3.Bf4  e6  4.c4  , which makes it particularly important. }
4... Nf6
{ A healthy development, getting one move closer to castling. Here  4...dxc4!?  is a relatively unexplored alternative worth checking.  We still opted for  4...Nf6  because the position after White's reply  5.e3  needs to be covered in any case.  White can always start with the move e3 and only then play c4, which would avoid the ...dxc4 option.   A possible move order is @@StartFEN@@rn1qkbnr/ppp1pppp/8/3p1b2/3P1B2/8/PPP1PPPP/RN1QKBNR w KQkq - 2 3@@EndFEN@@  3.e3  e6  4.c4  Nf6  5.Nf3  , reaching the same position. Besides @@StartFEN@@rn1qkb1r/ppp2ppp/4pn2/3p1b2/2PP1B2/5N2/PP2PPPP/RN1QKB1R w KQkq - 2 5@@EndFEN@@  5.e3  , we will also examine  5.Qb3  , while  5.Nc3  transposes to a line that we check via @@StartFEN@@rn1qkbnr/ppp2ppp/4p3/3p1b2/2PP1B2/8/PP2PPPP/RN1QKBNR w KQkq - 0 4@@EndFEN@@  4.Nc3  Nf6  5.Nf3  . }
5. Qb3
{ White can play the move Qb3 in various versions. There are sequences like @@StartFEN@@rn1qkbnr/ppp1pppp/8/3p1b2/3P1B2/8/PPP1PPPP/RN1QKBNR w KQkq - 2 3@@EndFEN@@  3.c4  e6  4.Qb3  ,  3.c4  e6  4.Nc3  Nf6  5.Qb3  or @@StartFEN@@rn1qkbnr/ppp1pppp/8/3p1b2/3P1B2/8/PPP1PPPP/RN1QKBNR w KQkq - 2 3@@EndFEN@@  3.e3  e6  4.c4  Nf6  5.Qb3  .   In all cases, we want to avoid a passive or weakening reply like ...Qc8 or ...b6 and instead defend actively. This is usually accomplished by ignoring the threat to the b7-pawn and developing the knight on c6.  This is the way we handle the three mentioned sample sequences, and the current position is no exception. Still, it's worth mentioning that Black has a good alternative here, the capture on c4.  After @@StartFEN@@rn1qkb1r/ppp2ppp/4pn2/3p1b2/2PP1B2/1Q3N2/PP2PPPP/RN2KB1R b KQkq - 3 5@@EndFEN@@  5...dxc4  6.Qxb7  Be4  7.Qxc7  Qxc7  8.Bxc7  Bb4+  , Black is a pawn down for a while but gets reasonable compensation.   Currently, Black's chances look okay in this line, but we see a practical drawback. It requires a substantial effort to learn, but the resulting endgames will not give Black great winning chances in many cases. On the other hand, our move 5...Nc6 leads to combative and still relatively unexplored positions. }
5... Nc6
{ The usual reply to Qb3 ideas. We need to consider two replies,  6.c5  and mostly  6.Nbd2  , which is surprisingly challenging. We'll also have a look at  6.Qxb7  , but we'll get good chances against this greedy move. It's not necessary to examine  6.e3?!  Nb4  or @@StartFEN@@r2qkb1r/ppp2ppp/2n1pn2/3p1b2/2PP1B2/1Q3N2/PP2PPPP/RN2KB1R w KQkq - 4 6@@EndFEN@@  6.a3?!  dxc4  7.Qxb7?  Na5  in any detail, as they don't pose any particular challenge. }
6. Nbd2
{ This move is probably the most challenging at this point. The square d2 is not particularly attractive for the knight at first sight, but it covers c4 and therefore secures White's position against ...Na5 ideas. }
6... Be7
{ An important move! It is much better to avoid the slow  6...Rb8  and instead continue with development. After  6...Be7  , White can't take  on b7 anyway,  as  7.Qxb7?  Nb4  is great for Black.   A good alternative to  6...Be7  is  6...a5  , though. We will  see that ...a5 is an idea after  6...Be7  , and often both moves will be part of our setup.  Before we continue, a word about  6...Nb4?  This move falls short due to  7.Rc1  a5  8.c5  when we have no good way to justify the knight jump. After choosing @@StartFEN@@r2qkb1r/ppp2ppp/2n1pn2/3p1b2/2PP1B2/1Q3N2/PP1NPPPP/R3KB1R b KQkq - 5 6@@EndFEN@@  6...Be7  , we will examine  7.e3  and  7.cxd5  . As already mentioned,  7.Qxb7?  Nb4  is good for Black. White could play  7.c5  when  7...Rb8  leads to a position quite similar to @@StartFEN@@r2qkb1r/ppp2ppp/2n1pn2/3p1b2/2PP1B2/1Q3N2/PP2PPPP/RN2KB1R w KQkq - 4 6@@EndFEN@@  6.c5  Rb8  . }
7. e3
{ The most natural move for White. Our opponent is behind in kingside development and needs to catch up. }
7... O-O
{ Again, we don't need to spend time on ...Rb8 and prefer quick development. Now we are ready to play ...Na5, which is very annoying for White. }
8. c5
{ White defuses the ...Na5 idea by advancing the pawn. A continuation like  8.Rc1?!  Na5  9.Qa4  Nxc4  10.Nxc4  dxc4  11.Bxc4  c6  looks good for Black.  We threaten ...b5, but also have an annoying queen sortie to b6 or a5, if White moves the queen. }
8... a5
{ It's also possible to play the more standard  8...Rb8  , but  8...a5  is more interesting. Black's idea is  not that obvious − we'd like to play ...b6, attacking the advanced c-pawn.  Currently, playing  8...b6?  fails to  9.Qa4  , when our attacked knight has no good square to go to. The move 8...a5 takes control  of b4, so the idea of ...b6 gains in strength. }
9. Rc1
{ A good move, stopping ...b6. After  9.Be2?!  b6!  10.cxb6  cxb6  Black is already slightly better.  Our c6-knight is much better than its counterpart on d2, and we have ...a5-a4-a3 ideas too. }
9... Qc8
{ A tough call at this point as  9...Rb8  or the odd  9...Ra7  are interesting too. }
10. h3 { White likes to keep the bishop, avoiding a line like  10.Be2  Nh5  . }
10... a4 { One point of not playing ...Rb8. } 11. Qc3
{ White should avoid  11.Qa3  b6  or @@StartFEN@@r1q2rk1/1pp1bppp/2n1pn2/2Pp1b2/p2P1B2/1Q2PN1P/PP1N1PP1/2R1KB1R w K - 0 11@@EndFEN@@  11.Qd1?  a3  . }
11... Ne4 12. Nxe4 Bxe4 { Our idea is to play for the ...e5 advance now. } 13.
Bb5
{ We'll check this as the main move, but  13.Nd2  is a logical alternative for White. After  13...Bf5  14.Be2  the immediate  14...e5!?  is a fascinating option, when  15.Bxe5  Nxe5  16.dxe5  c6  17.O-O  f6  gives Black good play for the pawn. }
13... f6
{ Stockfish also suggests  13...e5!?  as an option, when  14.Bxe5  Nxe5  15.dxe5  Qe6  is the follow-up. Black wants to  play ...c6 and ...Bd8-c7, picking up the c-pawn later. The engine evaluates it as equal, but it's not a boring position, for sure. }
14. Bg3 { A prophylactic retreat, but White can't stop ...e5 this way. } 14...
e5
{ Stockfish insists that White still has about equal chances, but clearly, Black can be happy with the opening result. All in all, the lines after 5.Qb3 Nc6 are relatively unexplored and lead to fascinating play with many options for both sides.   15.Bxc6  bxc6  16.dxe5  fxe5  17.Bxe5  Rf7!?  leads to good play for Black.  We cover g7 and want to play ...Qf5 next, with very nice compensation for the pawn. }
