[White "19. London System 1.d4 d5 2.Bf4"]
[Black "London System 3.c4 e6 4.Nf3 #10"]
[Result "*"]

1. d4 d5 2. Bf4
{ Playing the bishop to f4 is the signature move of the London System. The London is White's most frequently played and challenging alternative to the Queen's Gambit. It's popular on all levels, from online games to classical time control games played in top GM events.  White's strategy after playing the bishop to f4 is not yet determined, but the pawn break c2-c4 or claiming control of the e5-square is still on the cards. Controlling this central square can be the start of a kingside initiative, often started by the move Ne5.  As we will see, against our answer, the symmetrical reply 2...Bf5, the first plan is the more challenging one.   A word about the move 2.Nf3: White often starts with  2.Nf3  and intends to play Bf4 on the next move. We answer  2.Nf3  with  2...Bf5  and cover this reply in two dedicated chapters. After  3.Bf4  , we'd reach a position that is covered in the current chapter. }
2... Bf5
{ After 2...Bf5 White's main choice  is between playing the move c4 soon or avoiding the pawn break favoring kingside development. This plan often involves playing for control of the e5-square, with a quick Ne5 and Nd2-f3 ideas.   White has many move orders to choose from. If c4 is intended, White can start with  3.c4  right away, but may also begin with  3.Nf3  or  3.e3  . Similarly, play can start with the kingside development scheme following  3.Nf3  or  3.e3  .   We decided to cover all c4-setups starting with the move order  3.c4  , while the kingside development plan is covered via  3.e3  . This means that in our coverage, the move order  3.Nf3  is more or less purely transpositional. Switching to our point of view, our move orders and ideas are fairly straightforward. Our next move will be  3...e6  , preparing kingside development.   One point of the  2...Bf5  move order, compared to  2...Nf6  first, is the delay  of the move ...Nf6. Not playing ...Nf6 early gives us additional options against some of White's plans, in particular against early Ne5 ideas. }
3. c4
{ White plays the typical Queen's Gambit move c4, putting pressure on the d5-pawn. This approach is possible immediately or after preparing the move with  3.e3  first. We chose the move order  3.c4  , as White has some possible options to play  without the move e3. }
3... e6
{ The natural reply. We cover the d5-pawn and prepare for kingside development. }
4. Nf3
{ This position arises frequently via @@StartFEN@@rnbqkbnr/ppp1pppp/8/3p4/3P4/8/PPP1PPPP/RNBQKBNR w KQkq - 0 2@@EndFEN@@  2.Nf3  Bf5  3.Bf4  e6  4.c4  , which makes it particularly important. }
4... Nf6
{ A healthy development, getting one move closer to castling. Here  4...dxc4!?  is a relatively unexplored alternative worth checking.  We still opted for  4...Nf6  because the position after White's reply  5.e3  needs to be covered in any case.  White can always start with the move e3 and only then play c4, which would avoid the ...dxc4 option.   A possible move order is @@StartFEN@@rn1qkbnr/ppp1pppp/8/3p1b2/3P1B2/8/PPP1PPPP/RN1QKBNR w KQkq - 2 3@@EndFEN@@  3.e3  e6  4.c4  Nf6  5.Nf3  , reaching the same position. Besides @@StartFEN@@rn1qkb1r/ppp2ppp/4pn2/3p1b2/2PP1B2/5N2/PP2PPPP/RN1QKB1R w KQkq - 2 5@@EndFEN@@  5.e3  , we will also examine  5.Qb3  , while  5.Nc3  transposes to a line that we check via @@StartFEN@@rn1qkbnr/ppp2ppp/4p3/3p1b2/2PP1B2/8/PP2PPPP/RN1QKBNR w KQkq - 0 4@@EndFEN@@  4.Nc3  Nf6  5.Nf3  . }
5. e3 { The natural move, covering the c-pawn. } 5... Bxb1
{ A key move in our concept. After  5...Bb4+  , White can still play  6.Nbd2  . Our idea is to take the knight first and then give the check, forcing the white king to move. White can now insert @@StartFEN@@rn1qkb1r/ppp2ppp/4pn2/3p4/2PP1B2/4PN2/PP3PPP/Rb1QKB1R w KQkq - 0 6@@EndFEN@@  6.Qa4+  or choose between  6.Rxb1  and  6.Qxb1  , when we'd reply  6...Bb4+  to force the king to move. }
6. Rxb1
{ The recaptures on move six are about equally popular. They lead to somewhat different positions, as White's concept after  6.Rxb1  involves  a quick Qa4+, which is clearly off the table  after  6.Qxb1  . }
6... Bb4+
{ We didn't give up the bishop on b1 for nothing. This check forces  7.Ke2  , as  7.Nd2??  Ne4  wins the house. }
7. Ke2 dxc4
{ That is the most direct way to play. We make sure that the position opens up quickly. Black has also fared well with  7...Bd6  , but our suggested move is clearer. }
8. Qa4+
{ The only move that makes any sense. After  8.Qa4+  Nc6  , White wants to continue with  9.Ne5  to put pressure on our minor pieces. }
8... Nc6 9. Ne5
{ White not only attacks our c6-knight but also undermines the stability of our bishop. }
9... a5
{ This move looks like the cleanest solution, but Black has also tried  9...Nd5  with good results. }
10. Nxc6
{ White can also play  10.a3  Bd6  11.Nxc6  Qd7  , which is just a transposition to the line that we will examine in a moment. }
10... Qd7
{ This fun counter-pin is saving the day for us. We will regain the knight later − White has no way of keeping the material. It's important to note that we don't even need to take the knight on the next move. We have ideas like ...Nd5-b6 or ...Ra6, which might allow us to take it without doubling pawns.   Now we'll examine White's replies  11.a3  and  11.Rc1  . White has also tried  11.g3  , but this is very similar to  11.a3  Bd6  12.g3  . }
11. a3 { White pushes our bishop back first. } 11... Bd6
{ Now we threaten to take on f4, which would damage White's pawn structure considerably if recapturing with the e-pawn is forced. This applies to a line like  12.Qxc4?!  Bxf4  12.exf4  bxc6  , when Black is much better. }
12. g3
{ This makes a lot of sense. White is now ready to recapture with the g-pawn and at the same time prepares the bishop fianchetto. White could have played this idea even one move earlier. After @@StartFEN@@r3k2r/1ppq1ppp/2N1pn2/p7/QbpP1B2/4P3/PP2KPPP/1R3B1R w kq - 1 11@@EndFEN@@  11.g3  Ra6  12.Bg2  Nd5  , we would follow a very similar path to the line we are currently examining. }
12... Bxf4
{ This looks a bit easier for Black than  12...Qxc6  , which was played in an online rapid game between Magnus Carlsen and Anish Giri @@StartBracket@@chess24 Banter Blitz Cup Final@@EndBracket@@. Our move aims to avoid the compromised pawn structure. }
13. gxf4 Ra6 { That's the point! } 14. Bg2 Nd5
{ And finally, after all the tricks, we get the piece back. } 15. Qxc4 Rxc6
{ Black is in good shape here. We have avoided any pawn structure concessions and enjoy the strong knight on d5. White has a hard time ever playing e3-e4, as the pawn advance would weaken f4 and d4 a lot. }
