1. d4 d5
{ In this chapter, we will examine the sidelines that White may play on move two. After @@StartFEN@@rnbqkbnr/pppppppp/8/8/8/8/PPPPPPPP/RNBQKBNR w KQkq - 0 1@@EndFEN@@  1.d4  d5  White's main move is  2.c4  , the Queen's Gambit. Our answer to the Queen's Gambit is the Triangle Variation  2...e6  3.Nc3  c6  or @@StartFEN@@rnbqkbnr/ppp2ppp/4p3/3p4/2PP4/8/PP2PPPP/RNBQKBNR w KQkq - 0 3@@EndFEN@@  3.Nf3  c6  , which is the namesake for the course.   However, White is not obliged to play  2.c4  but may opt for a different path. The two most important alternatives are the flexible  2.Nf3  and  2.Bf4  , the popular London System. Black has a range of possible replies against these moves.  We play the moves ...e6 and ...c6 @@StartBracket@@the Triangle@@EndBracket@@ against  2.c4  , so why not go for the same setup against White's arguably less aggressive options? We considered this approach but wondered if Black might have a more ambitious response.  Let's go back to the basic position after @@StartFEN@@rnbqkbnr/pppppppp/8/8/8/8/PPPPPPPP/RNBQKBNR w KQkq - 0 1@@EndFEN@@  1.d4  d5  2.c4  . After  2.c4  ,  White threatens cxd5, so our options are limited if we want to keep the central pawn on d5. Black has to play  2...e6  or  2...c6  to accomplish this goal. After  2...e6  , Black's light-squared bishop is passive for the moment. Of course,  2...e6  is an excellent move and our repertoire choice,  but the c8-bishop is a cause for concern for the foreseeable future.   Now, consider if White does not play @@StartFEN@@rnbqkbnr/ppp1pppp/8/3p4/3P4/8/PPP1PPPP/RNBQKBNR w KQkq - 0 2@@EndFEN@@  2.c4  but instead goes for a slower move. We wondered if it is possible to 'punish' White for not playing  2.c4  by  developing our c8-bishop to f5 on move two, and only then play the move ...e6.   We examined @@StartFEN@@rnbqkbnr/ppp1pppp/8/3p4/3P4/8/PPP1PPPP/RNBQKBNR w KQkq - 0 2@@EndFEN@@  2.Nf3  Bf5  , and @@StartFEN@@rnbqkbnr/ppp1pppp/8/3p4/3P4/8/PPP1PPPP/RNBQKBNR w KQkq - 0 2@@EndFEN@@  2.Bf4  Bf5  and concluded that Black's concept is perfectly viable. These lines have the practical advantage of being relatively unexplored and, therefore, will likely not be prepared as thoroughly by your opponents.  We decided to split the coverage of the 'Non-Queen's Gambit' lines into four chapters. The current chapter examines lines like @@StartFEN@@rnbqkbnr/ppp1pppp/8/3p4/3P4/8/PPP1PPPP/RNBQKBNR w KQkq - 0 2@@EndFEN@@  2.Bg5  ,  2.Nc3  or even rarer options. The other three chapters deal with the London System  2.Bf4  Bf5  @@StartBracket@@one chapter@@EndBracket@@ and @@StartFEN@@rnbqkbnr/ppp1pppp/8/3p4/3P4/8/PPP1PPPP/RNBQKBNR w KQkq - 0 2@@EndFEN@@  2.Nf3  Bf5  , which is covered in two chapters. You'll frequently meet both lines, in particular in online/rapid/blitz play.   Let's have a look now at White's more offbeat lines on move two. There is a wide range of possible moves, so let's have an overview.  A@@EndBracket@@  2.e4?  is the incorrect Blackmar-Diemer Gambit. We can take the pawn and are much better.   B@@EndBracket@@  2.e3  is a cautious move. We suggest  2...Bf5  , staying true to our approach against 2.Nf3. After @@StartFEN@@rnbqkbnr/ppp1pppp/8/3p4/3P4/8/PPP1PPPP/RNBQKBNR w KQkq - 0 2@@EndFEN@@  2.e3  Bf5  , the game will often transpose to lines that usually start with @@StartFEN@@rnbqkbnr/ppp1pppp/8/3p4/3P4/8/PPP1PPPP/RNBQKBNR w KQkq - 0 2@@EndFEN@@  2.Nf3  Bf5  3.e3  , as we will see.   C@@EndBracket@@  2.g3  is a similar case as 2.e3. We suggest playing  2...Bf5  , angling for a transposition to @@StartFEN@@rnbqkbnr/ppp1pppp/8/3p4/3P4/8/PPP1PPPP/RNBQKBNR w KQkq - 0 2@@EndFEN@@  2.Nf3  Bf5  3.g3  .   D@@EndBracket@@  2.Bg5  White plays in the style of the Trompowsky @@StartFEN@@rnbqkbnr/pppppppp/8/8/8/8/PPPPPPPP/RNBQKBNR w KQkq - 0 1@@EndFEN@@  1.d4  Nf6  2.Bg5  , but there is  no knight on f6 to capture or pin. Against this move, Black has better options than a ... Bf5-based setup.  We suggest @@StartFEN@@rnbqkbnr/ppp1pppp/8/3p2B1/3P4/8/PPP1PPPP/RN1QKBNR b KQkq - 1 2@@EndFEN@@  2...h6  3.Bh4  c5  , which looks excellent for Black.   E@@EndBracket@@  2.Nc3  is the most important line in the current chapter. White focuses on quick queenside development and frequently aims to castle on that side of the board. Black's most active reply is  2...c5  , which we suggest playing. Let's see how to battle White's move two sidelines − we have some ground to cover. }
