[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "20. 1.d4 d5 − 2nd Move Sidelines"]
[Black "Blackmar-Diemer Gambit 2.e4 #1"]
[Result "*"]

1. d4 d5
{ In this chapter, we will examine the sidelines that White may play on move two. }
2. e4
{ The Blackmar-Diemer Gambit. It is objectively incorrect, but knowing a good reply is helpful. The first step is easy: grab the central pawn. }
2... dxe4
{ In a significant portion of games, Black opts for  2...e6  or  2...c6  , which lets White off the hook. You should take a free central pawn! }
3. Nc3
{ White's idea is to follow up  3.Nc3  Nf6  with  4.f3  . It is worse for White to play @@StartFEN@@rnbqkbnr/ppp1pppp/8/8/3Pp3/8/PPP2PPP/RNBQKBNR w KQkq - 0 3@@EndFEN@@  3.f3?  right away, as  3...e5!  is very effective. After  4.dxe5  Qxd1+  5.Kxd1  exf3  White's king is stuck in the center,  and the e5-pawn is terminally weak. }
3... Nf6
{ We need to cover the captured pawn. We often opt for a quick ...Bf5 in our repertoire, but here  3...Bf5?  allows  4.g4  , which is helping White. We still want to develop the bishop this way but need to get the timing right.  The setup we aim for  includes ...Bf5, ...e6, and often ... c6 to stabilize the center.  Now White, most of the time, plays @@StartFEN@@rnbqkb1r/ppp1pppp/5n2/8/3Pp3/2N5/PPP2PPP/R1BQKBNR w KQkq - 2 4@@EndFEN@@  4.f3  , but we'll have a quick look at  4.Bg5  too. }
4. Bg5 Bf5 { Lending additional cover to the extra pawn. } 5. Qe2
{ White sets a trap: what about the d4-pawn now? Can we take it? Before we examine Black's best reply, a quick note about  5.f3  , which we should answer with  5...Nbd7  . After  6.Bc4  exf3  7.Nxf3  e6  , we reach positions similar to 4.f3. White does not have enough play for the pawn. }
5... Nbd7
{ Don't take on d4! After  5...Qxd4??  6.Qb5+  Bd7  7.Qxb7  Bc6  8.Bb5  White is winning on the spot. Instead, we continue with our development, and White does not have enough for the pawn. }
6. O-O-O
{ We are already a full pawn up. If White plays  6.Qb5?  , we are happy to  give up b7 for more development with  6...e6  7.Qxb7  Bd6  , when Black has a fantastic position. }
6... c6
{ The bishop on g5 makes it a bit more difficult to play ...e6, so we should start with ...c6. Our f8-bishop can be developed with ...g6 later. }
7. f3
{ Or  7.d5  Nxd5  8.Nxd5  cxd5  9.Rxd5  g6  , when Black will be the one doing all the attacking soon. The bishop  arriving on g7 will be a monster. }
7... exf3 8. Nxf3 g6
{ Black has a clear advantage. White can try the direct  9.d5  Nxd5  10.Nxd5  cxd5  11.Rxd5  Bg7  12.Nd4  , but  12...Bxd4!  13.Rxd4  Rc8  is excellent for Black. }
