{ We need to cover the captured pawn. We often opt for a quick ...Bf5 in our repertoire, but here  3...Bf5?  allows  4.g4  , which is helping White. We still want to develop the bishop this way but need to get the timing right.  The setup we aim for  includes ...Bf5, ...e6, and often ... c6 to stabilize the center.  Now White, most of the time, plays @@StartFEN@@rnbqkb1r/ppp1pppp/5n2/8/3Pp3/2N5/PPP2PPP/R1BQKBNR w KQkq - 2 4@@EndFEN@@  4.f3  , but we'll have a quick look at  4.Bg5  , too. }
4. f3 exf3
{ Playing  4...Bf5  is a good alternative. We think that taking is a bit simpler to handle, though. }
5. Nxf3
{ Occasionally White has tried  5.Qxf3?  , but we can just play  5...Qxd4  and be two pawns up. After  6.Be3  Qg4  7.Qf2  Qf5  @@StartBracket@@there are other good lines, too@@EndBracket@@ White has no compensation. }
5... Bf5
{ A natural move. We develop our bishop and will usually follow up with ...e6 and ...c6, stabilizing the center.   It's also possible to start this setup with  5...c6  , but  6.Bd3  prevents our intended bishop deployment. The move  6...Bg4  is possible, but there is some additional theoretical workload that we can avoid  by starting with the bishop move to f5 right away. }
6. Ne5 { White prepares both an assault on f7 and the pawn push g2-g4. } 6...
c6
{ It's important to play this move and avoid  6...e6  7.g4  Bg6  8.Bg2  c6  9.h4  , which gives White some play.  By going 6...c6 first, we preserve the option to retreat the bishop to e6, if needed. }
7. Bc4
{ White develops and threatens mate, a tempting move. Here  7.g4?!  Be6!  is good for Black.  We are ready to play ...Nd7 soon, challenging White's centralized knight. }
7... e6 8. g4
{ We need to be precise against this crude attack. White may also play  8.O-O  when  8...Bg6!  is the typical reply. We secure f7 with this important move, leading to positions similar/identical to the lines after 7.O-O, which is analyzed next. }
8... Nfd7
{ Very important! After  8...Bg6?  9.h4  things are not clear at all. } 9. gxf5
{ White has no good move here. We were threatening both ...Qh4+ and ...Nxe5. }
9... Nxe5 { Playing  9...Qh4+  is just as good. } 10. Be2
{ Here  10.dxe5?  Qh4+  is even more devastating for White. } 10... Qh4+ 11.
Kf1 Qh3+ 12. Ke1 Be7
{ Who's doing the attacking now? White's gambit has poorly backfired, with ...Bh4+ looming. After  13.dxe5  Qg2  14.Rf1  Bh4+  15.Kd2  Na6  Black wins quickly. }
*

[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "20. 1.d4 d5 − 2nd Move Sidelines"]
[Black "Blackmar-Diemer Gambit 2.e4 #3"]
[Result "*"]

1. d4 d5
{ In this chapter, we will examine the sidelines that White may play on move two. }
2. e4
{ The Blackmar-Diemer Gambit. It is objectively incorrect, but knowing a good reply is helpful. The first step is easy: grab the central pawn. }
2... dxe4
{ In a significant portion of games, Black opts for  2...e6  or  2...c6  , which lets White off the hook. You should take a free central pawn! }
3. Nc3
{ White's idea is to follow up  3.Nc3  Nf6  with  4.f3  . It is worse for White to play @@StartFEN@@rnbqkbnr/ppp1pppp/8/8/3Pp3/8/PPP2PPP/RNBQKBNR w KQkq - 0 3@@EndFEN@@  3.f3?  right away, as  3...e5!  is very effective. After  4.dxe5  Qxd1+  5.Kxd1  exf3  White's king is stuck in the center,  and the e5-pawn is terminally weak. }
3... Nf6
{ We need to cover the captured pawn. We often opt for a quick ...Bf5 in our repertoire, but here  3...Bf5?  allows  4.g4  , which is helping White. We still want to develop the bishop this way but need to get the timing right.  The setup we aim for  includes ...Bf5, ...e6, and often ... c6 to stabilize the center.  Now White, most of the time, plays @@StartFEN@@rnbqkb1r/ppp1pppp/5n2/8/3Pp3/2N5/PPP2PPP/R1BQKBNR w KQkq - 2 4@@EndFEN@@  4.f3  , but we'll have a quick look at  4.Bg5  , too. }
4. f3 exf3
{ Playing  4...Bf5  is a good alternative. We think that taking is a bit simpler to handle, though. }
5. Nxf3
{ Occasionally White has tried  5.Qxf3?  , but we can just play  5...Qxd4  and be two pawns up. After  6.Be3  Qg4  7.Qf2  Qf5  @@StartBracket@@there are other good lines, too@@EndBracket@@ White has no compensation. }
5... Bf5
{ A natural move. We develop our bishop and will usually follow up with ...e6 and ...c6, stabilizing the center.   It's also possible to start this setup with  5...c6  , but  6.Bd3  prevents our intended bishop deployment. The move  6...Bg4  is possible, but there is some additional theoretical workload that we can avoid  by starting with the bishop move to f5 right away. }
6. Bc4
{ This is White's most popular move, to develop the kingside quickly and put some pressure on f7. It's interesting to see that Stockfish recommends  6.Bd3  for White, a move that is almost never played. After the natural reply  6...Bxd3  7.Qxd3  c6  , White's compensation is not sufficient, but it looks like this is the lesser evil, compared to the more crude attacking schemes that we are about to examine. Still, we can be happy after 6.Bd3, as we enjoy the extra pawn in a position without any weaknesses. }
6... c6
{ It's also possible to start with  6...e6  , but the move  6...c6  will often follow anyway. It's useful to increase  the control of d5, so we'll likely need both. }
7. O-O
{ A sensible move. White wants to create some play on the opened f-file, which is the only upside of the pawn sacrifice.   An alternative for White is  7.Ne5  e6  8.g4  , when  8...Nfd7!  is a crucial reply. We analyze this line via the move order @@StartFEN@@rn1qkb1r/ppp1pppp/5n2/5b2/3P4/2N2N2/PPP3PP/R1BQKB1R w KQkq - 1 6@@EndFEN@@  6.Ne5  c6  7.Bc4  e6  8.g4  Nfd7!  Please have a look there if you'd like more information. }
7... e6 8. Ne5 { Or  8.Ng5  Bg6  , when White's attack is going nowhere. } 8...
Bg6
{ White was threatening Nxf7 and Rxf5, so this is a necessary retreat. The ...Bg6 setup is the main point to remember. Now we have the simple development scheme involving ...Be7, ...O-O, and...Nbd7. White has no compensation for the pawn. }
*

[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "20. 1.d4 d5 − 2nd Move Sidelines"]
[Black "Reversed Stonewall 2.e3 Bf5 3.f4"]
[Result "*"]

1. d4 d5
{ In this chapter, we will examine the sidelines that White may play on move two. }
2. e3
{ There are various lines in which White plays an early e3 while the queen's bishop is still at home on c1. At first, this approach looks passive, but White's concept has upsides.   One key point is to cover a pawn on c4, for example in lines like @@StartFEN@@rnbqkbnr/pppppppp/8/8/8/8/PPPPPPPP/RNBQKBNR w KQkq - 0 1@@EndFEN@@  1.d4  d5  2.c4  e6  3.Nf3  c6  4.e3  or  3.Nc3  c6  4.e3  . White is concerned about the  capture on c4 and protects the pawn in these lines. Once the center opens up, the c1-bishop will often come to life later by playing e3-e4 or maybe on the long diagonal a1-h8.   In the case of @@StartFEN@@rnbqkbnr/pppppppp/8/8/8/8/PPPPPPPP/RNBQKBNR w KQkq - 0 1@@EndFEN@@  1.d4  d5  2.e3  ,  White commits to e3 when Black has not yet revealed much about their intentions. In the two sample lines in the Triangle, we have already played ...e6 and ...c6, and only then does White go for e3.   After @@StartFEN@@rnbqkbnr/pppppppp/8/8/8/8/PPPPPPPP/RNBQKBNR w KQkq - 0 1@@EndFEN@@  1.d4  d5  2.e3  , we can equalize in multiple ways, but we suggest sticking to the general concept of  playing ...Bf5 when possible.  After  2...Bf5  White's most interesting try is  3.c4  , while  3.Nf3  would transpose to lines that we examine via @@StartFEN@@rnbqkbnr/ppp1pppp/8/3p4/3P4/8/PPP1PPPP/RNBQKBNR w KQkq - 0 2@@EndFEN@@  2.Nf3  Bf5  3.e3  in a different chapter. }
2... Bf5 3. f4
{ The reversed Stonewall is a welcome sight. Our f5-bishop is perfectly placed to exploit the light-squared weaknesses in White's camp. Note that we play the Stonewall formation with Black, but only in cases where White can't play a setup with Bf4 and e3.   We have @@StartFEN@@rnbqkbnr/pppppppp/8/8/8/8/PPPPPPPP/RNBQKBNR w KQkq - 0 1@@EndFEN@@  1.d4  d5  2.c4  e6  3.Nf3  c6  4.e3  f5  in our repertoire, but not @@StartFEN@@rnbqkbnr/pppppppp/8/8/8/8/PPPPPPPP/RNBQKBNR w KQkq - 0 1@@EndFEN@@  1.d4  d5  2.c4  e6  3.Nf3  c6  4.Qc2  f5?  , when  5.Bf4!  is excellent for White. }
3... e6
{ We aim for a setup with ...e6, ...Nf6 and ...c5. You can start with either move here, so  3...Nf6  or  3...c5  are fine too. }
4. Nf3 Nf6 { Or  4...c5  first and  next ...Nf6. } 5. Bd3 c5
{ Again, Black has some flexibility and may also start with  5...Be7  and  then ...c5. An important concept to know: please avoid taking the bishop on d3.  After @@StartFEN@@rn1qkb1r/ppp2ppp/4pn2/3p1b2/3P1P2/3BPN2/PPP3PP/RNBQK2R b KQkq - 3 5@@EndFEN@@  5...Bxd3  6.cxd3  White  plugs the hole on e4, which is undesirable for Black. The possible doubled pawn on the f-file is no problem at all, as we will see. }
6. Bxf5
{ After  6.c3  , we would be in a better position  to capture on d3, as White would be obliged to take with the queen. Keeping the tension is better, though. As long as we don't take on d3, White can't play Nbd2 or Bd2, as the queen needs to protect the d3-bishop.   We suggest a sequence like  6.c3  Bd6  7.O-O  O-O  8.Qe2  Nc6  to complete development. A good plan to know is rerouting  the c6-knight to connect to the e4-square. This is possible via e7-c8-d6 or e7-f5-d6. Black firmly controls e4 and has good chances on the queenside in the long run. White's c1-bishop remains a problem. }
6... exf5 7. O-O
{ Or  7.Qd3  Qc8  , which  defends f5 and keeps an eye on b7 and c5, so Qb5+ is no problem. }
7... Nc6
{ We have reached a favorable pawn structure. Black controls e4 forever, while the square e5 is not stable for White because of a future ...f6. We have a much better bishop and chances to play on the e-file and the queenside. }
*

