[White "20. 1.d4 d5 − 2nd Move Sidelines"]
[Black "2.e3 Bf5 3.c4 #1"]
[Result "*"]

1. d4 d5
{ In this chapter, we will examine the sidelines that White may play on move two. }
2. e3
{ There are various lines in which White plays an early e3 while the queen's bishop is still at home on c1. At first, this approach looks passive, but White's concept has upsides.   One key point is to cover a pawn on c4, for example in lines like @@StartFEN@@rnbqkbnr/pppppppp/8/8/8/8/PPPPPPPP/RNBQKBNR w KQkq - 0 1@@EndFEN@@  1.d4  d5  2.c4  e6  3.Nf3  c6  4.e3  or  3.Nc3  c6  4.e3  . White is concerned about the  capture on c4 and protects the pawn in these lines. Once the center opens up, the c1-bishop will often come to life later by playing e3-e4 or maybe on the long diagonal a1-h8.   In the case of @@StartFEN@@rnbqkbnr/pppppppp/8/8/8/8/PPPPPPPP/RNBQKBNR w KQkq - 0 1@@EndFEN@@  1.d4  d5  2.e3  ,  White commits to e3 when Black has not yet revealed much about their intentions. In the two sample lines in the Triangle, we have already played ...e6 and ...c6, and only then does White go for e3.   After @@StartFEN@@rnbqkbnr/pppppppp/8/8/8/8/PPPPPPPP/RNBQKBNR w KQkq - 0 1@@EndFEN@@  1.d4  d5  2.e3  , we can equalize in multiple ways, but we suggest sticking to the general concept of  playing ...Bf5 when possible.  After  2...Bf5  White's most interesting try is  3.c4  , while  3.Nf3  would transpose to lines that we examine via @@StartFEN@@rnbqkbnr/ppp1pppp/8/3p4/3P4/8/PPP1PPPP/RNBQKBNR w KQkq - 0 2@@EndFEN@@  2.Nf3  Bf5  3.e3  in a different chapter. }
2... Bf5 3. c4
{ White's only reply that is worth a closer look. It puts pressure on d5 and allows Qb3. Another solid choice for White would be  3.Bd3  , but this is very similar to @@StartFEN@@rnbqkbnr/ppp1pppp/8/3p4/3P4/8/PPP1PPPP/RNBQKBNR w KQkq - 0 2@@EndFEN@@  2.Nf3  Bf5  3.e3  e6  4.Bd3  , which we examine in the chapter on 2.Nf3 Bf5. }
3... e6
{ We stick to our usual approach to start with ...e6. It is perfectly possible to play  3...c6  here, but after  4.cxd5  cxd5  we'd reach a pawn structure that we usually don't aim for in our repertoire. It is not bad for Black, but we'd like to maintain a consistent approach whenever possible.   After our choice  3...e6  White can play  4.Nf3  or lines like  4.Nc3  c6  5.Nf3  , when we'd transpose to the chapter on 2.Nf3 Bf5. This is likely to happen, but we'll have a look at some independent ideas. }
4. Qb3
{ After  4.Nf3  c6  or @@StartFEN@@rn1qkbnr/ppp2ppp/4p3/3p1b2/2PP4/4P3/PP3PPP/RNBQKBNR w KQkq - 0 4@@EndFEN@@  4.Nc3  c6  5.Nf3  Nd7  , we reach lines that are examined via the 2.Nf3 Bf5 move order in a different chapter. }
4... Nc6
{ The active and correct way to defend b7. We develop a piece and don't weaken the pawn structure with an ugly move like  4...b6?!  White can't take on b7 now and should rather defend against ...Nb4 ideas. }
5. Qxb7 { A huge mistake. } 5... Nb4 6. cxd5
{ This move still requires a precise response. After  6.Na3  a6!  7.Nf3  Rb8  8.Qa7  Qc8  White's queen is trapped! }
6... a6
{ Instead,  6...Rb8!  also works, but  6...Nc2+  7.Kd1  Nxa1  8.Bb5+  Ke7  9.d6+  backfires badly! }
7. Na3
{ After  7.dxe6  Bxe6  Black  wins, as ...Nc2+ and ...Bd5 is threatened. } 7...
Rb8 8. Qa7 Qc8 { And ...Ra8 is the deadly idea, winning the queen. } *

