1. d4 d5
{ In this chapter, we will examine the sidelines that White may play on move two. }
2. g3
{ A relatively unusual move order at this point. White often combines d4 and g3, for example, in the Catalan Opening @@StartFEN@@rnbqkbnr/pppppppp/8/8/8/8/PPPPPPPP/RNBQKBNR w KQkq - 0 1@@EndFEN@@  1.d4  d5  2.c4  e6  3.Nf3  Nf6  4.g3  .   Christof's course Keep it Simple: 1.d4 also features g3-based setups, but he opted to  play @@StartFEN@@rnbqkbnr/pppppppp/8/8/8/8/PPPPPPPP/RNBQKBNR w KQkq - 0 1@@EndFEN@@  1.d4  d5  2.Nf3  first, waiting for Black to commit in some way. After  2.Nf3  Nf6  , he suggests playing  3.g3  , often leading to the same positions as 2.g3 does. }
2... Bf5
{ We recommend playing  2...Bf5  , as we'll almost certainly transpose to @@StartFEN@@rnbqkbnr/pppppppp/8/8/8/8/PPPPPPPP/RNBQKBNR w KQkq - 0 1@@EndFEN@@  1.d4  d5  2.Nf3  Bf5  3.g3  , which looks fine for Black.   A good, active alternative is  2...c5  . This move would also fit well with the spirit of our repertoire, given that we suggest @@StartFEN@@rnbqkbnr/pppppppp/8/8/8/8/PPPPPPPP/RNBQKBNR w KQkq - 0 1@@EndFEN@@  1.d4  d5  2.Nc3  c5  and @@StartFEN@@rnbqkbnr/pppppppp/8/8/8/8/PPPPPPPP/RNBQKBNR w KQkq - 0 1@@EndFEN@@  1.d4  d5  2.Bg5  h6  3.Bh4  c5  .   The practical drawback of  2...c5  is the complexity of lines like  3.Nf3  cxd4  4.Bg2  , when Black has some choice between interesting options. These are rather tricky to handle, which could prove problematic in practice. You'll meet 2.g3 very rarely, so learning a whole complex of lines seems like an uneconomic decision. }
3. Bg2
{ The natural move here. It is almost certain that we will transpose to @@StartFEN@@rnbqkbnr/pppppppp/8/8/8/8/PPPPPPPP/RNBQKBNR w KQkq - 0 1@@EndFEN@@  1.d4  d5  2.Nf3  Bf5  3.g3  soon − playing Nf3 is part of White's setup.  If White plays @@StartFEN@@rn1qkbnr/ppp1pppp/8/3p1b2/3P4/6P1/PPP1PP1P/RNBQKBNR w KQkq - 1 3@@EndFEN@@  3.Nf3  e6  , we already transpose to @@StartFEN@@rnbqkbnr/pppppppp/8/8/8/8/PPPPPPPP/RNBQKBNR w KQkq - 0 1@@EndFEN@@  1.d4  d5  2.Nf3  Bf5  3.g3  e6  .   White could also start with @@StartFEN@@rn1qkbnr/ppp1pppp/8/3p1b2/3P4/6P1/PPP1PP1P/RNBQKBNR w KQkq - 1 3@@EndFEN@@  3.c4  e6  , when  4.Bg2  Nf6  transposes to the line we are about to cover via @@StartFEN@@rn1qkbnr/ppp1pppp/8/3p1b2/3P4/6P1/PPP1PP1P/RNBQKBNR w KQkq - 1 3@@EndFEN@@  3.Bg2  e6  4.c4  Nf6  . We never have to worry about  an early Qb3, as  @@StartFEN@@rn1qkbnr/ppp1pppp/8/3p1b2/3P4/6P1/PPP1PP1P/RNBQKBNR w KQkq - 1 3@@EndFEN@@  3.c4  e6  4.Qb3  is answered by  4...Nc6!  We'll see a very similar idea after @@StartFEN@@rn1qkbnr/ppp1pppp/8/3p1b2/3P4/6P1/PPP1PP1P/RNBQKBNR w KQkq - 1 3@@EndFEN@@  3.Bg2  e6  4.c4  Nf6  5.Qb3  Nc6!  , which is nice for Black. }
3... e6
{ We use the same move order @@StartBracket@@...e6 first@@EndBracket@@ in the related line @@StartFEN@@rnbqkbnr/pppppppp/8/8/8/8/PPPPPPPP/RNBQKBNR w KQkq - 0 1@@EndFEN@@  1.d4  d5  2.Nf3  Bf5  3.g3  e6  . Playing @@StartFEN@@rn1qkbnr/ppp1pppp/8/3p1b2/3P4/6P1/PPP1PPBP/RNBQK1NR b KQkq - 2 3@@EndFEN@@  3...c6  or  3...Nf6  first will likely transpose to the same lines, though. }
4. c4
{ Here  4.Nf3  Nf6  would immediately transpose to @@StartFEN@@rnbqkbnr/pppppppp/8/8/8/8/PPPPPPPP/RNBQKBNR w KQkq - 0 1@@EndFEN@@  1.d4  d5  2.Nf3  Bf5  3.g3  e6  4.Bg2  Nf6  . This is likely to happen, as White is usually delaying the c-pawn move, considering that it has been 'refused' to be played earlier. }
4... Nf6
{ It's also possible to start with  4...c6  here. The main incentive for playing  4...Nf6  is that  5.Qb3  is now favorably answered with  5...Nc6!  , so we first set a small trap by playing the knight.  Now White's most natural move is @@StartFEN@@rn1qkb1r/ppp2ppp/4pn2/3p1b2/2PP4/6P1/PP2PPBP/RNBQK1NR w KQkq - 1 5@@EndFEN@@  5.Nf3  , when  5...c6  again leads to a transposition to @@StartFEN@@rnbqkbnr/pppppppp/8/8/8/8/PPPPPPPP/RNBQKBNR w KQkq - 0 1@@EndFEN@@  1.d4  d5  2.Nf3  Bf5  3.g3  e6  4.Bg2  Nf6  5.c4  c6  . We'll have a look at @@StartFEN@@rn1qkb1r/ppp2ppp/4pn2/3p1b2/2PP4/6P1/PP2PPBP/RNBQK1NR w KQkq - 1 5@@EndFEN@@  5.Qb3  and  5.Nc3  , which avoid this immediate transposition. }
5. Qb3 { A slightly dubious move, as we will see. } 5... Nc6
{ A strong reply, going for a counterattack on the d4-pawn. Black also intends ...Nb4, which can be extremely annoying for White. In the chapter on @@StartFEN@@rnbqkbnr/pppppppp/8/8/8/8/PPPPPPPP/RNBQKBNR w KQkq - 0 1@@EndFEN@@  1.d4  d5  2.Nf3  Bf5  , this idea is widespread. A key line in this chapter is  3.c4  e6  4.Qb3  Nc6  , which leads to an interesting play. }
6. Nf3
{ White can also play  6.cxd5  exd5  7.Nf3  , when  7...Nb4  leads to a very similar play as after @@StartFEN@@r2qkb1r/ppp2ppp/2n1pn2/3p1b2/2PP4/1Q4P1/PP2PPBP/RNB1K1NR w KQkq - 3 6@@EndFEN@@  6.Nf3  Nb4  . The potential for transposition is high, as the  capture on d5 might occur later. }
6... Nb4 7. Na3 a5
{ Black has a comfortable position due to White's misplaced pieces on the queenside. We'll continue with natural moves, like ...Be7, ...O-O, and ...c7-c6. }
*

[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "20. 1.d4 d5 − 2nd Move Sidelines"]
[Black "2.g3 #2"]
[Result "*"]

1. d4 d5
{ In this chapter, we will examine the sidelines that White may play on move two. }
2. g3
{ A relatively unusual move order at this point. White often combines d4 and g3, for example, in the Catalan Opening @@StartFEN@@rnbqkbnr/pppppppp/8/8/8/8/PPPPPPPP/RNBQKBNR w KQkq - 0 1@@EndFEN@@  1.d4  d5  2.c4  e6  3.Nf3  Nf6  4.g3  .   Christof's course Keep it Simple: 1.d4 also features g3-based setups, but he opted to  play @@StartFEN@@rnbqkbnr/pppppppp/8/8/8/8/PPPPPPPP/RNBQKBNR w KQkq - 0 1@@EndFEN@@  1.d4  d5  2.Nf3  first, waiting for Black to commit in some way. After  2.Nf3  Nf6  , he suggests playing  3.g3  , often leading to the same positions as 2.g3 does. }
2... Bf5
{ We recommend playing  2...Bf5  , as we'll almost certainly transpose to @@StartFEN@@rnbqkbnr/pppppppp/8/8/8/8/PPPPPPPP/RNBQKBNR w KQkq - 0 1@@EndFEN@@  1.d4  d5  2.Nf3  Bf5  3.g3  , which looks fine for Black.   A good, active alternative is  2...c5  . This move would also fit well with the spirit of our repertoire, given that we suggest @@StartFEN@@rnbqkbnr/pppppppp/8/8/8/8/PPPPPPPP/RNBQKBNR w KQkq - 0 1@@EndFEN@@  1.d4  d5  2.Nc3  c5  and @@StartFEN@@rnbqkbnr/pppppppp/8/8/8/8/PPPPPPPP/RNBQKBNR w KQkq - 0 1@@EndFEN@@  1.d4  d5  2.Bg5  h6  3.Bh4  c5  .   The practical drawback of  2...c5  is the complexity of lines like  3.Nf3  cxd4  4.Bg2  , when Black has some choice between interesting options. These are rather tricky to handle, which could prove problematic in practice. You'll meet 2.g3 very rarely, so learning a whole complex of lines seems like an uneconomic decision. }
3. Bg2
{ The natural move here. It is almost certain that we will transpose to @@StartFEN@@rnbqkbnr/pppppppp/8/8/8/8/PPPPPPPP/RNBQKBNR w KQkq - 0 1@@EndFEN@@  1.d4  d5  2.Nf3  Bf5  3.g3  soon − playing Nf3 is part of White's setup.  If White plays @@StartFEN@@rn1qkbnr/ppp1pppp/8/3p1b2/3P4/6P1/PPP1PP1P/RNBQKBNR w KQkq - 1 3@@EndFEN@@  3.Nf3  e6  , we already transpose to @@StartFEN@@rnbqkbnr/pppppppp/8/8/8/8/PPPPPPPP/RNBQKBNR w KQkq - 0 1@@EndFEN@@  1.d4  d5  2.Nf3  Bf5  3.g3  e6  .   White could also start with @@StartFEN@@rn1qkbnr/ppp1pppp/8/3p1b2/3P4/6P1/PPP1PP1P/RNBQKBNR w KQkq - 1 3@@EndFEN@@  3.c4  e6  , when  4.Bg2  Nf6  transposes to the line we are about to cover via @@StartFEN@@rn1qkbnr/ppp1pppp/8/3p1b2/3P4/6P1/PPP1PP1P/RNBQKBNR w KQkq - 1 3@@EndFEN@@  3.Bg2  e6  4.c4  Nf6  . We never have to worry about  an early Qb3, as  @@StartFEN@@rn1qkbnr/ppp1pppp/8/3p1b2/3P4/6P1/PPP1PP1P/RNBQKBNR w KQkq - 1 3@@EndFEN@@  3.c4  e6  4.Qb3  is answered by  4...Nc6!  We'll see a very similar idea after @@StartFEN@@rn1qkbnr/ppp1pppp/8/3p1b2/3P4/6P1/PPP1PP1P/RNBQKBNR w KQkq - 1 3@@EndFEN@@  3.Bg2  e6  4.c4  Nf6  5.Qb3  Nc6!  , which is nice for Black. }
3... e6
{ We use the same move order @@StartBracket@@...e6 first@@EndBracket@@ in the related line @@StartFEN@@rnbqkbnr/pppppppp/8/8/8/8/PPPPPPPP/RNBQKBNR w KQkq - 0 1@@EndFEN@@  1.d4  d5  2.Nf3  Bf5  3.g3  e6  . Playing @@StartFEN@@rn1qkbnr/ppp1pppp/8/3p1b2/3P4/6P1/PPP1PPBP/RNBQK1NR b KQkq - 2 3@@EndFEN@@  3...c6  or  3...Nf6  first will likely transpose to the same lines, though. }
4. c4
{ Here  4.Nf3  Nf6  would immediately transpose to @@StartFEN@@rnbqkbnr/pppppppp/8/8/8/8/PPPPPPPP/RNBQKBNR w KQkq - 0 1@@EndFEN@@  1.d4  d5  2.Nf3  Bf5  3.g3  e6  4.Bg2  Nf6  . This is likely to happen, as White is usually delaying the c-pawn move, considering that it has been 'refused' to be played earlier. }
4... Nf6
{ It's also possible to start with  4...c6  here. The main incentive for playing  4...Nf6  is that  5.Qb3  is now favorably answered with  5...Nc6!  , so we first set a small trap by playing the knight.  Now White's most natural move is @@StartFEN@@rn1qkb1r/ppp2ppp/4pn2/3p1b2/2PP4/6P1/PP2PPBP/RNBQK1NR w KQkq - 1 5@@EndFEN@@  5.Nf3  , when  5...c6  again leads to a transposition to @@StartFEN@@rnbqkbnr/pppppppp/8/8/8/8/PPPPPPPP/RNBQKBNR w KQkq - 0 1@@EndFEN@@  1.d4  d5  2.Nf3  Bf5  3.g3  e6  4.Bg2  Nf6  5.c4  c6  . We'll have a look at @@StartFEN@@rn1qkb1r/ppp2ppp/4pn2/3p1b2/2PP4/6P1/PP2PPBP/RNBQK1NR w KQkq - 1 5@@EndFEN@@  5.Qb3  and  5.Nc3  , which avoid this immediate transposition. }
5. Nc3 { White increases the pressure on d5. } 5... c6
{ Adding additional protection to d5 looks logical. It's also possible to start with  5...h6  when  6.Nf3  c6  leads to the same position as @@StartFEN@@rn1qkb1r/ppp2ppp/4pn2/3p1b2/2PP4/2N3P1/PP2PPBP/R1BQK1NR b KQkq - 2 5@@EndFEN@@  5...c6  6.Nf3  h6  .   After  5...h6  6.Qb3  Nc6  is possible, but not too attractive to allow − compared to @@StartFEN@@rn1qkb1r/ppp2ppp/4pn2/3p1b2/2PP4/6P1/PP2PPBP/RNBQK1NR w KQkq - 1 5@@EndFEN@@  5.Qb3  Nc6  , we have  inserted Nc3 and ...h6, which helps White. Playing 5...c6 is a simpler solution. }
6. Qb3
{ Here  6.Nf3  h6  is the most popular continuation, which transposes to @@StartFEN@@rnbqkbnr/pppppppp/8/8/8/8/PPPPPPPP/RNBQKBNR w KQkq - 0 1@@EndFEN@@  1.d4  d5  2.Nf3  Bf5  3.c4  e6  4.g3  Nf6  5.Bg2  c6  6.Nc3  h6  .  We play ...h6 to address White's idea Nh4. This concept is explained in more detail in the notes to the mentioned line. }
6... Qb6 7. c5 Qc7
{ 8.Nf3  h6  9.Bf4  Qc8  or @@StartFEN@@rn2kb1r/ppq2ppp/2p1pn2/2Pp1b2/3P4/1QN3P1/PP2PPBP/R1B1K1NR w KQkq - 1 8@@EndFEN@@  8.Bf4  Qc8  9.Nf3  h6  would transpose to this line.  @@StartFEN@@rn2kb1r/pp3ppp/1qp1pn2/2Pp1b2/3P4/1QN3P1/PP2PPBP/R1B1K1NR b KQkq - 0 7@@EndFEN@@  7...Qc7  is more combative than  7...Qxb3  , which would be fine too − more on that, in the 2.Nf3 Bf5 chapter @@StartBracket@@the line above@@EndBracket@@. }
*

[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "20. 1.d4 d5 − 2nd Move Sidelines"]
[Black "Hodgson Attack 2.Bg5 #1"]
[Result "*"]

1. d4 d5
{ In this chapter, we will examine the sidelines that White may play on move two. }
2. Bg5
{ White plays in the spirit of the Trompowsky @@StartFEN@@rnbqkbnr/pppppppp/8/8/8/8/PPPPPPPP/RNBQKBNR w KQkq - 0 1@@EndFEN@@  1.d4  Nf6  2.Bg5  , but there  is no knight on f6 that the bishop might capture or pin. Black has some good  replies to @@StartFEN@@rnbqkbnr/ppp1pppp/8/3p4/3P4/8/PPP1PPPP/RNBQKBNR w KQkq - 0 2@@EndFEN@@  2.Bg5  , but surprisingly our standard recipe of playing  a quick ...Bf5 does not work that well.   After  2...Bf5  or  2...h6  3.Bh4  Bf5  White has the move  4.c4  when we can't play  the desirable move ...e6. Of course,  playing  4...c6  is not the end of the world, but Black has better options against 2.Bg5. We suggest a different approach, let's have a look. }
2... h6
{ It's useful to insert this move. We create a possible retreat square h7 for our bishop, and often ...h6 helps to stop a later back rank mate. As we will see, there is even a concrete tactical idea. More on that later.   Here  2...f6!?  is a funky alternative that is worth mentioning, but our suggestion is compelling too. }
3. Bh4
{ White has played  3.Bf4  on rare occasions, reaching a London System in which Black has gained the additional  move ...h6. White argues that in some setups against the London, this extra move might have a negative effect.   While there are certainly only a few lines where this is relevant, it is entirely unproblematic for us. We suggest @@StartFEN@@rnbqkbnr/ppp1pppp/8/3p4/3P4/8/PPP1PPPP/RNBQKBNR w KQkq - 0 2@@EndFEN@@  2.Bf4  Bf5  for Black, when the  extra move ...h6 will be universally useful. So  after @@StartFEN@@rnbqkbnr/ppp1ppp1/7p/3p2B1/3P4/8/PPP1PPPP/RN1QKBNR w KQkq - 0 3@@EndFEN@@  3.Bf4  , we play  3...Bf5  and are in good shape. }
3... c5
{ Just as after @@StartFEN@@rnbqkbnr/ppp1pppp/8/3p4/3P4/8/PPP1PPPP/RNBQKBNR w KQkq - 0 2@@EndFEN@@  2.Nc3  c5  , we attack White's d-pawn.  Now White usually captures on c5, as  the replies @@StartFEN@@rnbqkbnr/pp2ppp1/7p/2pp4/3P3B/8/PPP1PPPP/RN1QKBNR w KQkq - 0 4@@EndFEN@@  4.e3  and  4.c3  are toothless. }
4. e3
{ Even less promising is  4.c3?!  when  4...Qb6  already exerts annoying pressure  on d4 and b2. White probably has nothing better than  5.Qb3  , when  5...Qxb3  6.axb3  cxd4  7.cxd4  Nc6  is already better for Black. }
4... cxd4 { The immediate  4...Qb6  is not bad, either. } 5. exd4 Qb6
{ Developing with  5...Nc6  first is fine too. The queen move is a bit more aggressive though. How should White defend the b-pawn? }
6. b3
{ A mistake, but it's by far the most popular move in online chess. White should prefer  6.Nc3  , when  6...e6  7.Rb1  Nc6  8.Nf3  Bd7  gives Black slightly better chances, but it's still a game. We have a good play on the c-file and the interesting  plan ...Ne7-f5, hunting the bishop pair.   Why is  6.b3?  so bad? It looks strategically dubious, but is there a concrete problem? }
6... e5
{ A powerful strike! Now White can't play  7.dxe5??  due to  7...Qb4+  , winning the unlucky bishop! }
7. Nf3
{ White is in terrible shape in any case. Against  7.c3  , we can play  7...exd4  8.Qxd4  Qxd4  9.cxd4  Bb4+  10.Nd2  Nc6  11.Ngf3  g5  12.Bg3  Bf5  and have a fantastic play on the weakened squares on the queenside.  White's g3-bishop is misplaced. }
7... e4 8. Ne5 Nc6 9. Nxc6 bxc6
{ We have a huge advantage, intending to play ...Ne7-f5 next. It is a bit shocking to see that Stockfish already evaluates the position as +3 for Black, but it is clear that things have gone badly wrong for White. }
