[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "20. 1.d4 d5 − 2nd Move Sidelines"]
[Black "2.Nc3 c5 3.Nf3 #1"]
[Result "*"]

1. d4 d5
{ In this chapter, we will examine the sidelines that White may play on move two. }
2. Nc3
{ In recent years, early combinations of d4 and Nc3 have become more popular. Lines like @@StartFEN@@rnbqkbnr/pppppppp/8/8/8/8/PPPPPPPP/RNBQKBNR w KQkq - 0 1@@EndFEN@@  1.d4  Nf6  2.Bf4  g6  3.Nc3  or @@StartFEN@@rnbqkbnr/pppppppp/8/8/8/8/PPPPPPPP/RNBQKBNR w KQkq - 0 1@@EndFEN@@  1.d4  Nf6  2.Nc3  d5  3.Bf4  , the so-called 'Jobava London' are interesting ways for White to get the game away from the mainstream while still being fundamentally sound.  The sequence @@StartFEN@@rnbqkbnr/pppppppp/8/8/8/8/PPPPPPPP/RNBQKBNR w KQkq - 0 1@@EndFEN@@  1.d4  d5  2.Nc3  is a bit less common because it gives Black some additional options than the lines mentioned before. The difference is that Black hasn't yet committed to  an early ...Nf6, which allows the  reply  2...c5  , our choice. }
2... c5
{ This is the most principled move. Black plays the desired pawn break right away and claims: 'Well, you failed to play 2.c4, then I'll go ahead and play 2...c5!'. Of course, this is not the only good move available.   2...Nf6  is a frequently seen alternative, while  2...Bf5  is an interesting option that is less explored. We often play an  early ...Bf5,  think of @@StartFEN@@rnbqkbnr/pppppppp/8/8/8/8/PPPPPPPP/RNBQKBNR w KQkq - 0 1@@EndFEN@@  1.d4  d5  2.Nf3  Bf5  , so this would fit quite well too. After our choice, @@StartFEN@@rnbqkbnr/ppp1pppp/8/3p4/3P4/2N5/PPP1PPPP/R1BQKBNR b KQkq - 1 2@@EndFEN@@  2...c5  , White's most popular and interesting move is  3.e4  , but we'll also investigate less critical moves like  3.Nf3  and  3.Bf4  . }
3. Nf3 Nc6
{ We increase the pressure on d4. It's a bad idea to play  3...cxd4?!  4.Qxd4  Nf6  5.e4  , when White opens up the position favorably. }
4. Bf4
{ White may also play  4.dxc5  when  4...Nf6  leads to a position that we examine via @@StartFEN@@rnbqkbnr/pp2pppp/8/2pp4/3P4/2N5/PPP1PPPP/R1BQKBNR w KQkq - 0 3@@EndFEN@@  3.dxc5  Nf6  4.Nf3  Nc6  . }
4... Nf6
{ This looks best. After  4...cxd4?!  5.Nxd4  Nf6  White has the dynamic  6.e4!  which is surprisingly strong. }
5. e3
{ White has no reasonable alternative. By now,  5.dxc5?  is flawed due to  5...d4  ,  when the c3-knight has no good square to go to.  Note that @@StartFEN@@r1bqkb1r/pp2pppp/2n2n2/2pp4/3P1B2/2N2N2/PPP1PPPP/R2QKB1R w KQkq - 4 5@@EndFEN@@  5.Nb5?  is met by  5...Qa5+  . }
5... Bg4
{ Pinning the knight is a natural move. A good alternative is  5...cxd4  , intending to continue  6.exd4  Bg4  . After @@StartFEN@@r1bqkb1r/pp2pppp/2n2n2/2pp4/3P1B2/2N1PN2/PPP2PPP/R2QKB1R b KQkq - 0 5@@EndFEN@@  5...Bg4  , we'll examine  6.Be2  and  6.Bb5  . }
6. Bb5
{ White goes for a counter-pin. Now  6...cxd4  can be answered with the interesting  7.Qxd4!?  , which we'd like to avoid. }
6... e6 7. h3
{ White has no natural way to break the pin and forces the action. } 7... Bxf3
{ We have to avoid the naive  7...Bh5?  8.g4!  Bg6  9.Ne5  , which gives White good play. }
8. Qxf3 cxd4
{ We happily enter the Carlsbad structure, as both the c3-knight and b5-bishop are not ideally placed for White. }
9. exd4 Qb6
{ Here  9...Bd6  is also very logical. The move  9...Qb6  attacks the  pawn on d4 and the b5-bishop, while at the same time putting some 'x-ray' pressure on b2. Due to these factors, White now has a hard time keeping the bishop. }
10. O-O
{ An interesting pawn sacrifice. Stockfish already suggests  10.Bxc6  for White, when  10...Qxc6  leads to a comfortable game. In the long run, we'll start the minority attack  involving ...b5-b4. }
10... Qxd4
{ There is nothing wrong about the more cautious  10...a6  when White has to play  11.Bxc6  Qxc6  . We like Black's chances, with standard minority attack play.  Still, taking the central pawn on d4 is tempting and looks objectively stronger. }
11. Rfe1
{ White threatens Nxd5 now, which we can prevent with our natural reply. }
11... Be7 { We stop Nxd5 and prepare kingside castling. } 12. Na4
{ This is the less than intuitive move that Stockfish has in mind. It wants to play c2-c4, opening the position. At the same time, our queen is now unable to retreat to c5 or b6. }
12... Qb4
{ A strong move. We attack the bishop and prepare ...Qa5-d8 if needed.   After  13.c4  O-O  14.a3  Qa5  15.b4  Qd8  , White has some compensation for the pawn, but it's probably not quite enough. All in all, Black has good chances in the 7.Bb5 line and even some choice along the way. }
*

