[Round "?"]
[White "20. 1.d4 d5 − 2nd Move Sidelines"]
[Black "2.Nc3 c5 3.Bf4 #1"]
[Result "*"]

1. d4 d5
{ In this chapter, we will examine the sidelines that White may play on move two. }
2. Nc3
{ In recent years, early combinations of d4 and Nc3 have become more popular. Lines like @@StartFEN@@rnbqkbnr/pppppppp/8/8/8/8/PPPPPPPP/RNBQKBNR w KQkq - 0 1@@EndFEN@@  1.d4  Nf6  2.Bf4  g6  3.Nc3  or @@StartFEN@@rnbqkbnr/pppppppp/8/8/8/8/PPPPPPPP/RNBQKBNR w KQkq - 0 1@@EndFEN@@  1.d4  Nf6  2.Nc3  d5  3.Bf4  , the so-called 'Jobava London' are interesting ways for White to get the game away from the mainstream while still being fundamentally sound.  The sequence @@StartFEN@@rnbqkbnr/pppppppp/8/8/8/8/PPPPPPPP/RNBQKBNR w KQkq - 0 1@@EndFEN@@  1.d4  d5  2.Nc3  is a bit less common because it gives Black some additional options than the lines mentioned before. The difference is that Black hasn't yet committed to  an early ...Nf6, which allows the  reply  2...c5  , our choice. }
2... c5
{ This is the most principled move. Black plays the desired pawn break right away and claims: 'Well, you failed to play 2.c4, then I'll go ahead and play 2...c5!'. Of course, this is not the only good move available.   2...Nf6  is a frequently seen alternative, while  2...Bf5  is an interesting option that is less explored. We often play an  early ...Bf5,  think of @@StartFEN@@rnbqkbnr/pppppppp/8/8/8/8/PPPPPPPP/RNBQKBNR w KQkq - 0 1@@EndFEN@@  1.d4  d5  2.Nf3  Bf5  , so this would fit quite well too. After our choice, @@StartFEN@@rnbqkbnr/ppp1pppp/8/3p4/3P4/2N5/PPP1PPPP/R1BQKBNR b KQkq - 1 2@@EndFEN@@  2...c5  , White's most popular and interesting move is  3.e4  , but we'll also investigate less critical moves like  3.Nf3  and  3.Bf4  . }
3. Bf4 Nc6
{ Black should play this move or  3...Nf6  but avoid  3...cxd4?!  , as  4.Qxd4  gives White too much development.   There are some small differences between the two knight moves. Our preference is  3...Nc6  , as we are sure that  it's best on c6 while staying flexible with the other knight might be useful. Now we'll examine  4.e3  and  4.e4!?  , while  4.Nf3  Nf6  would lead to @@StartFEN@@rnbqkbnr/pp2pppp/8/2pp4/3P4/2N5/PPP1PPPP/R1BQKBNR w KQkq - 0 3@@EndFEN@@  3.Nf3  Nc6  4.Bf4  Nf6  . }
4. e4 { An aggressive move, but it leads to nothing much if we are precise. }
4... cxd4
{ The most natural, but also strictly the only move you can play. Something like  4...e6??  5.exd5  exd5  6.Nb5  loses on the spot. }
5. exd5
{ That's the idea. Instead,  5.Nxd5  e5  is fine for Black. The next moves are forced. }
5... dxc3 6. dxc6 Qxd1+ 7. Rxd1 bxc6
{ This whole sequence was forced. Now White has tried  8.Bc7  most of the time.  8.bxc3  can also be played when  8...Nf6  leads to a similar position to the continuation we are about to examine. Black has the better pawn structure and a slight advantage. }
8. Bc7
{ Not exactly a 'Mr. Subtle' move, but it has more bite than it looks like at first. }
8... Bg4
{ This looks best. Black has played  8...Bb7  most of the time, but this move is quite passive. The reasoning behind this is certainly that after  8...Bd7  9.Ba6  White threatens Bb7, trapping the rook.   We'll see that our move  8...Bg4  is just a slightly improved version of  8...Bd7  , as  8...Bg4  9.f3  Bd7  is likely to happen when  10.Ba6  is the critical reply. Let's discuss why we'd be happy to face this move − some cool complications are ahead! }
9. Nf3
{ White avoids the tempo-gaining move  9.f3  , but this gives us some time. }
9... a5
{ We should avoid  9...cxb2?  10.Ba6  , which is awkward to meet.   A good alternative is  9...Rc8  , though. After  10.Be5  cxb2  11.Ba6  Rd8  12.Rxd8+  Kxd8  White has enough compensation for the pawn, but not more. This looks more difficult for Black to play than our recommendation, though. }
10. Ba6
{ This ultimately does not lead to much, but it's the most fun.  10.bxc3  Nf6  leads to equal chances, with White's activity compensating for the damaged pawn structure. }
10... Bd7 { This looks best, covering c6. } 11. Ne5
{ Or  11.Bc4  Nf6  12.Ne5  e6  13.Nxd7  Nxd7  14.bxc3  Bc5  , which leads to the same thing. }
11... Nf6 12. Bc4 e6 13. Nxd7
{ Or  13.bxc3  Nd5  14.Nxd7  Kxd7  15.Bg3  Bd6  , which looks already quite favorable for Black. }
13... Nxd7 14. bxc3 Bc5
{ Chances are about equal in this position. White has the pair of bishops but the worse pawn structure. Black should play ...Nb6-d5 next, improving the knight considerably. }
