{ Black should play this move or  3...Nf6  but avoid  3...cxd4?!  , as  4.Qxd4  gives White too much development.   There are some small differences between the two knight moves. Our preference is  3...Nc6  , as we are sure that  it's best on c6 while staying flexible with the other knight might be useful. Now we'll examine  4.e3  and  4.e4!?  , while  4.Nf3  Nf6  would lead to @@StartFEN@@rnbqkbnr/pp2pppp/8/2pp4/3P4/2N5/PPP1PPPP/R1BQKBNR w KQkq - 0 3@@EndFEN@@  3.Nf3  Nc6  4.Bf4  Nf6  . }
4. e4 { An aggressive move, but it leads to nothing much if we are precise. }
4... cxd4
{ The most natural, but also strictly the only move you can play. Something like  4...e6??  5.exd5  exd5  6.Nb5  loses on the spot. }
5. exd5
{ That's the idea. Instead,  5.Nxd5  e5  is fine for Black. The next moves are forced. }
5... dxc3 6. dxc6 Qxd1+ 7. Rxd1 bxc6
{ This whole sequence was forced. Now White has tried  8.Bc7  most of the time.  8.bxc3  can also be played when  8...Nf6  leads to a similar position to the continuation we are about to examine. Black has the better pawn structure and a slight advantage. }
8. Bc7
{ Not exactly a 'Mr. Subtle' move, but it has more bite than it looks like at first. }
8... Bg4
{ This looks best. Black has played  8...Bb7  most of the time, but this move is quite passive. The reasoning behind this is certainly that after  8...Bd7  9.Ba6  White threatens Bb7, trapping the rook.   We'll see that our move  8...Bg4  is just a slightly improved version of  8...Bd7  , as  8...Bg4  9.f3  Bd7  is likely to happen when  10.Ba6  is the critical reply. Let's discuss why we'd be happy to face this move − some cool complications are ahead! }
9. f3 { The most likely reply, as it gains a tempo... } 9... Bd7
{ We could have played 8...Bd7 immediately, but provoking the move of the f-pawn has an important point, as we will see. }
10. Ba6
{ The move that White WANTS to play, but it's dubious if we react well to it. Best for White seems to be  10.bxc3  when the simple  10...Nf6  leads to equal chances. We like Black's structure, but White's pieces are still active. }
10... Nf6
{ The great point of Black's play is that we can allow Bb7 to happen. Our rook is trapped, but we'll have excellent play for the material. }
11. Bb7
{ This must be critical. Instead,  11.bxc3  Nd5  12.Rxd5  cxd5  13.Bb7  Rc8  14.Bxc8  Bxc8  looks better for Black, with the bishop pair and the better structure. }
11... Nd5 12. Bxa8
{ Here  12.Rxd5  cxd5  13.bxc3  Rc8  leads to the same line we mentioned in the notes to move  11. Black is much better. }
12... Nxc7 13. Bb7
{ The only square, but White's bishop is still in danger: it has no squares to go to from b7. }
13... cxb2
{ Black has two pawns for the exchange and the extremely dangerous b-pawn. White needs to attack and win it immediately; otherwise, we might keep it with ...e5 and ...Ba3 ideas. In the current position, you can also spot why it was helpful to provoke the move f3. White's development is hampered, and the square e3 is weak. }
14. Rb1
{ White has to play this move.  14.Ne2  e5  ,  intending ...Ba3, is lost for White. }
14... e5 15. Rxb2 Nd5
{ We decided to cut the trainable line here. Black has the better chances in this position. We have a pawn for the exchange and great pieces, with the dark-squared bishop and the d5-knight being particularly strong. }
