{ Black should play this move or  3...Nf6  but avoid  3...cxd4?!  , as  4.Qxd4  gives White too much development.   There are some small differences between the two knight moves. Our preference is  3...Nc6  , as we are sure that  it's best on c6 while staying flexible with the other knight might be useful. Now we'll examine  4.e3  and  4.e4!?  , while  4.Nf3  Nf6  would lead to @@StartFEN@@rnbqkbnr/pp2pppp/8/2pp4/3P4/2N5/PPP1PPPP/R1BQKBNR w KQkq - 0 3@@EndFEN@@  3.Nf3  Nc6  4.Bf4  Nf6  . }
4. e3 { White's natural reply, enabling the pawn recapture. } 4... cxd4
{ The most important thing to remember is: don't play  4...Nf6??  , as  5.Nb5  wins for White. This trap happened hundreds of times@@StartBracket@@!@@EndBracket@@ and is one reason why  White is playing Nc3 and Bf4 in the first place. We suggest taking on d4 instead,  but @@StartFEN@@r1bqkbnr/pp2pppp/2n5/2pp4/3P1B2/2N1P3/PPP2PPP/R2QKBNR b KQkq - 0 4@@EndFEN@@  4...Bf5  is also looking fine. }
5. exd4 Bf5
{ Again,  5...Nf6??  6.Nb5  has to be avoided.  After 5...Bf5, we reach a good Carlsbad structure. As usual, White's knight is a bit misplaced on c3. }
6. Nf3 e6
{ An interesting point of our move order 3...Nc6 is that we have not yet played ...Nf6 and can develop with ...Nge7. This is an interesting additional option, as the following line shows. }
7. Bb5
{ White has some alternatives, but they are hardly dangerous. After  7.Bd3  , we could simply take or play the more interesting  7...Bg4  , for example. }
7... Bd6 8. Bxd6 Qxd6 9. O-O Ne7
{ The knight is well-placed on e7. One point is that we are less concerned about the e5-outpost for White's knight later in the game. We have the option to play ...f6 or challenge the knight with ...Ng6. As usual, the Carlsbad with a knight on c3 is a welcome structure for Black, leading to easy equality and chances for more. }
