{ White's most aggressive move, playing the Albin's Counter-Gambit with an extra tempo. The Albin's arises after @@StartFEN@@rnbqkbnr/pppppppp/8/8/8/8/PPPPPPPP/RNBQKBNR w KQkq - 0 1@@EndFEN@@  1.d4  d5  2.c4  e5  and has a dubious reputation.  Black does not have enough compensation after  3.dxe5  d4  4.Nf3  Nc6  5.a3  or  5.Nbd2  , which both grant White a sizeable advantage. White has an extra tempo, which changes the evaluation considerably. While the Albin's is dubious, 3.e4 can lead to interesting play and equal chances if White is precise. }
3... dxe4
{ Just as in the Albin's @@StartFEN@@rnbqkbnr/pppppppp/8/8/8/8/PPPPPPPP/RNBQKBNR w KQkq - 0 1@@EndFEN@@  1.d4  d5  2.c4  e5  3.dxe5  , taking the e-pawn is best. White's usual response is @@StartFEN@@rnbqkbnr/pp2pppp/8/2p5/3Pp3/2N5/PPP2PPP/R1BQKBNR w KQkq - 0 4@@EndFEN@@  4.d5  , but we'll briefly check the alternatives  4.Nge2  and  4.Bb5+  . }
4. Nge2
{ A rare move, but it's not bad at all. It is more or less unexplored, therefore, we can't rely on game samples. The following line provides a good overview, ensuring that we are not surprised by the move.   Another rare but less interesting option is  4.Bb5+  when  4...Bd7  5.dxc5  Nf6  6.Bg5  a6  7.Bxd7+  Nbxd7  is a natural continuation. Black will  pick up the c5-pawn and at least, enjoy easy equality. }
4... Nf6
{ We prefer this move over  4...cxd4  , which should lead to equal chances. After  4...Nf6  , White has the opportunity to play  5.d5  , which transposes to @@StartFEN@@rnbqkbnr/pp2pppp/8/2p5/3Pp3/2N5/PPP2PPP/R1BQKBNR w KQkq - 0 4@@EndFEN@@  4.d5  Nf6  5.Nge2  . }
5. Bg5 { White avoids the mentioned transposition. } 5... Nbd7
{ Again, we avoid simplifying with  5...cxd4  and prefer keeping the tension. The capture leads to about equal chances and is a good alternative, though. }
6. dxc5
{ We were hoping for  6.d5?!  , which is very favorable for Black after  6...h6  , similar to @@StartFEN@@rnbqkbnr/pp2pppp/8/2p5/3Pp3/2N5/PPP2PPP/R1BQKBNR w KQkq - 0 4@@EndFEN@@  4.d5  Nf6  5.Bg5  Nbd7  , when  6.Nge2  h6  leads to the same position.   The capture on c5 is a better option for White,  as is @@StartFEN@@r1bqkb1r/pp1npppp/5n2/2p3B1/3Pp3/2N5/PPP1NPPP/R2QKB1R w KQkq - 4 6@@EndFEN@@  6.Ng3  , when we suggest  6...g6  . These lines are all unexplored. Therefore, we don't need to dig much deeper. }
6... g6
{ There is no rush to regain the c5-pawn. It's much more convenient to take it after we have castled. }
7. Qd2 Bg7 8. O-O-O Qa5
{ This looks like a natural sequence. Chances are about equal in this exciting position. }
*

[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "20. 1.d4 d5 − 2nd Move Sidelines"]
[Black "2.Nc3 c5 3.e4 #2"]
[Result "*"]

1. d4 d5
{ In this chapter, we will examine the sidelines that White may play on move two. }
2. Nc3
{ In recent years, early combinations of d4 and Nc3 have become more popular. Lines like @@StartFEN@@rnbqkbnr/pppppppp/8/8/8/8/PPPPPPPP/RNBQKBNR w KQkq - 0 1@@EndFEN@@  1.d4  Nf6  2.Bf4  g6  3.Nc3  or @@StartFEN@@rnbqkbnr/pppppppp/8/8/8/8/PPPPPPPP/RNBQKBNR w KQkq - 0 1@@EndFEN@@  1.d4  Nf6  2.Nc3  d5  3.Bf4  , the so-called 'Jobava London' are interesting ways for White to get the game away from the mainstream while still being fundamentally sound.  The sequence @@StartFEN@@rnbqkbnr/pppppppp/8/8/8/8/PPPPPPPP/RNBQKBNR w KQkq - 0 1@@EndFEN@@  1.d4  d5  2.Nc3  is a bit less common because it gives Black some additional options than the lines mentioned before. The difference is that Black hasn't yet committed to  an early ...Nf6, which allows the  reply  2...c5  , our choice. }
2... c5
{ This is the most principled move. Black plays the desired pawn break right away and claims: 'Well, you failed to play 2.c4, then I'll go ahead and play 2...c5!'. Of course, this is not the only good move available.   2...Nf6  is a frequently seen alternative, while  2...Bf5  is an interesting option that is less explored. We often play an  early ...Bf5,  think of @@StartFEN@@rnbqkbnr/pppppppp/8/8/8/8/PPPPPPPP/RNBQKBNR w KQkq - 0 1@@EndFEN@@  1.d4  d5  2.Nf3  Bf5  , so this would fit quite well too. After our choice, @@StartFEN@@rnbqkbnr/ppp1pppp/8/3p4/3P4/2N5/PPP1PPPP/R1BQKBNR b KQkq - 1 2@@EndFEN@@  2...c5  , White's most popular and interesting move is  3.e4  , but we'll also investigate less critical moves like  3.Nf3  and  3.Bf4  . }
3. e4
{ White's most aggressive move, playing the Albin's Counter-Gambit with an extra tempo. The Albin's arises after @@StartFEN@@rnbqkbnr/pppppppp/8/8/8/8/PPPPPPPP/RNBQKBNR w KQkq - 0 1@@EndFEN@@  1.d4  d5  2.c4  e5  and has a dubious reputation.  Black does not have enough compensation after  3.dxe5  d4  4.Nf3  Nc6  5.a3  or  5.Nbd2  , which both grant White a sizeable advantage. White has an extra tempo, which changes the evaluation considerably. While the Albin's is dubious, 3.e4 can lead to interesting play and equal chances if White is precise. }
3... dxe4
{ Just as in the Albin's @@StartFEN@@rnbqkbnr/pppppppp/8/8/8/8/PPPPPPPP/RNBQKBNR w KQkq - 0 1@@EndFEN@@  1.d4  d5  2.c4  e5  3.dxe5  , taking the e-pawn is best. White's usual response is @@StartFEN@@rnbqkbnr/pp2pppp/8/2p5/3Pp3/2N5/PPP2PPP/R1BQKBNR w KQkq - 0 4@@EndFEN@@  4.d5  , but we'll briefly check the alternatives  4.Nge2  and  4.Bb5+  . }
4. Bb5+
{ A solid, but ultimately harmless, alternative for White. There are some possible tricks on the d-file that we need to avoid, though. Let's have a closer look. }
4... Bd7
{ The logical reply. It makes no sense to walk into a self-pin instead. } 5.
dxc5
{ That's White's point. After the capture on c5, we can't take the b5-bishop, as it would spoil our castling rights after  5...Bxb5?  6.Qxd8+  Kxd8  7.Nxb5  , giving White an attack for free. Instead, we should try to recoup the c-pawn under more favorable circumstances. }
5... Nf6 { Let's cover the e-pawn first. } 6. Be3
{ A sensible move. White prepares queenside castling and covers the c-pawn. }
6... e6 { We target the c5-pawn with the bishop, a logical move. } 7. Nge2
{ Continuing the piece development. After  7.Qd4?!  we have the strong reply  7...Nc6  . }
7... Qc8
{ This is a strong move and the reason why 4.dxc5 merits no coverage at all. It looks more natural to play  7...Qc7?!  , but this move is imprecise due to  8.b4  b6  9.Bf4!  , when White gains a crucial tempo to accomplish the  maneuver Bf4-d6, which is very annoying for Black. }
8. Qd4 { Now  8.b4  b6  works out fine for Black. } 8... a6
{ Black has some reasonable alternatives, like  8...Nc6  , or  8...Be7  , but the pawn move is the most forcing and convincing choice. }
9. Ba4
{ White keeps the pin above.  9.Bxd7+  can also be played,  9...Nbxd7  10.Nxe4  Nxe4  11.Qxe4  Bxc5  , leading to easy equality for Black. }
9... Bxa4 10. Qxa4+
{ After  10.Nxa4  Nbd7  , Black is more than fine.  The move ...Qc6 will cover e4 soon and coordinate our forces. }
10... Nbd7 { Natural and best. We develop and attack the c5-pawn once more. }
11. O-O-O { Against this move we still need to be precise. } 11... Bxc5
{ Finally getting the c5-pawn, but there is an important pitfall to avoid on the next move. }
12. Bxc5 b5
{ It's essential to flick in this pawn move. After  12...Qxc5??  13.Nxe4  Qc6  14.Nd6+  White is winning! }
13. Nxe4
{ This keeps equal chances for White. After  13.Qd4?  Nxc5  we are just better, keeping the pawn. }
13... Nxe4 14. Qxe4 Nxc5
{ We regain the pawn with tempo and castle on the next move. Chances are equal here, but there is still a lot to play for. The kings are on opposite sides and the pawn structure is non-symmetrical. }
*

