[White "20. 1.d4 d5 − 2nd Move Sidelines"]
[Black "2.Nc3 c5 3.e4 #3"]
[Result "*"]

1. d4 d5
{ In this chapter, we will examine the sidelines that White may play on move two. }
2. Nc3
{ In recent years, early combinations of d4 and Nc3 have become more popular. Lines like @@StartFEN@@rnbqkbnr/pppppppp/8/8/8/8/PPPPPPPP/RNBQKBNR w KQkq - 0 1@@EndFEN@@  1.d4  Nf6  2.Bf4  g6  3.Nc3  or @@StartFEN@@rnbqkbnr/pppppppp/8/8/8/8/PPPPPPPP/RNBQKBNR w KQkq - 0 1@@EndFEN@@  1.d4  Nf6  2.Nc3  d5  3.Bf4  , the so-called 'Jobava London' are interesting ways for White to get the game away from the mainstream while still being fundamentally sound.  The sequence @@StartFEN@@rnbqkbnr/pppppppp/8/8/8/8/PPPPPPPP/RNBQKBNR w KQkq - 0 1@@EndFEN@@  1.d4  d5  2.Nc3  is a bit less common because it gives Black some additional options than the lines mentioned before. The difference is that Black hasn't yet committed to  an early ...Nf6, which allows the  reply  2...c5  , our choice. }
2... c5
{ This is the most principled move. Black plays the desired pawn break right away and claims: 'Well, you failed to play 2.c4, then I'll go ahead and play 2...c5!'. Of course, this is not the only good move available.   2...Nf6  is a frequently seen alternative, while  2...Bf5  is an interesting option that is less explored. We often play an  early ...Bf5,  think of @@StartFEN@@rnbqkbnr/pppppppp/8/8/8/8/PPPPPPPP/RNBQKBNR w KQkq - 0 1@@EndFEN@@  1.d4  d5  2.Nf3  Bf5  , so this would fit quite well too. After our choice, @@StartFEN@@rnbqkbnr/ppp1pppp/8/3p4/3P4/2N5/PPP1PPPP/R1BQKBNR b KQkq - 1 2@@EndFEN@@  2...c5  , White's most popular and interesting move is  3.e4  , but we'll also investigate less critical moves like  3.Nf3  and  3.Bf4  . }
3. e4
{ White's most aggressive move, playing the Albin's Counter-Gambit with an extra tempo. The Albin's arises after @@StartFEN@@rnbqkbnr/pppppppp/8/8/8/8/PPPPPPPP/RNBQKBNR w KQkq - 0 1@@EndFEN@@  1.d4  d5  2.c4  e5  and has a dubious reputation.  Black does not have enough compensation after  3.dxe5  d4  4.Nf3  Nc6  5.a3  or  5.Nbd2  , which both grant White a sizeable advantage. White has an extra tempo, which changes the evaluation considerably. While the Albin's is dubious, 3.e4 can lead to interesting play and equal chances if White is precise. }
3... dxe4
{ Just as in the Albin's @@StartFEN@@rnbqkbnr/pppppppp/8/8/8/8/PPPPPPPP/RNBQKBNR w KQkq - 0 1@@EndFEN@@  1.d4  d5  2.c4  e5  3.dxe5  , taking the e-pawn is best. White's usual response is @@StartFEN@@rnbqkbnr/pp2pppp/8/2p5/3Pp3/2N5/PPP2PPP/R1BQKBNR w KQkq - 0 4@@EndFEN@@  4.d5  , but we'll briefly check the alternatives  4.Nge2  and  4.Bb5+  . }
4. d5 { White is gaining space and controls the important squares c6 and e6. }
4... Nf6
{ We develop the knight and cover e4, the best move for sure. Now White has some choice. To get the most out of the opening, we need to react flexibly. Here's an overview.   A@@EndBracket@@  5.Bg5  is a great practical upside for Black.  5.Bg5  happens to be the most popular and ambitious move, but it's one of the worst moves that White can play, objectively speaking. The key point is that we frequently have the option of playing ...h6, intending to answer Bh4 with ...g5 and ...Bg7, speeding up our development. White often intends queenside castling, which we are happy to answer with ...a6 and ...b5, giving Black all the fun.   B@@EndBracket@@  5.Bf4  looks better than 5.Bg5 for White. We recommend immediately starting queenside play  with ...a6 and ...b5 against it.   C@@EndBracket@@  5.f3  turns White's opening into a 'real gambit'. We'll take the f-pawn and enter the complications of being a pawn up. White's compensation is insufficient.   D@@EndBracket@@  5.Nge2  seems to be the best move for White, but it is rather unpopular. This is somewhat surprising, as in the Albin's @@StartFEN@@rnbqkbnr/pppppppp/8/8/8/8/PPPPPPPP/RNBQKBNR w KQkq - 0 1@@EndFEN@@  1.d4  d5  c4  e5  3.dxe5  d4  4.Nf3  Nc6  5.a3  Nge7  or @@StartFEN@@r1bqkbnr/ppp2ppp/2n5/4P3/2Pp4/5N2/PP2PPPP/RNBQKB1R w KQkq - 2 5@@EndFEN@@  5.g3  Nge7  are well-known lines.  White's idea is simple: playing Ng3, trying to regain the e4-pawn. }
5. Bf4
{ White prepares queenside castling but avoids the drawback of  5.Bg5  when we are happy to gain time  with ...h6 later. The position after  5.Bf4  has been seen frequently in practice, as @@StartFEN@@rnbqkbnr/pppppppp/8/8/8/8/PPPPPPPP/RNBQKBNR w KQkq - 0 1@@EndFEN@@  1.d4  d5  2.Bf4  c5  3.e4  dxe4  4.d5  Nf6  5.Nc3  is an alternative route to it. Now Black has two good options: @@StartFEN@@rnbqkb1r/pp2pppp/5n2/2pP4/4pB2/2N5/PPP2PPP/R2QKBNR b KQkq - 2 5@@EndFEN@@  5...a6  and  5...g6  . }
5... a6
{ It's a tough call between  5...a6  and  5...g6  − both moves are of about equal strength. The main difference between them is that after  5...g6  , White's usual continuation is  6.Qd2  , followed by queenside castling.   This does not work well against  5...a6  , though. After  6.Qd2?  b5  7.O-O-O  b4  Black is far too quick on the queenside. White usually  prefers 6.Qe2 to prepare queenside castling while also attacking the e4-pawn. Let's have a look at this exciting line now. }
6. Qe2
{ By far, White's most popular move. As already mentioned,  6.Qd2  b5  7.O-O-O  b4  runs right into our concept.   White sometimes goes for  6.a4  , but this more or less gives up on queenside castling. We play  6...g6  and maintain the extra pawn − White has no clear compensation for it. }
6... g6
{ This is better than  6...b5?!  7.O-O-O  ,  when White is ready to take on e4. }
7. O-O-O Bg7
{ After  7...Bg7  , we have to check two continuations:  8.Nxe4  and  8.d6  , which is aggressive but backfires against best play. }
8. d6
{ One of your authors, Christof Sielecki, faced this move in a classical time control game. FM Etienne Goossens played it in a Dutch League game, and Christof had to find the right move over the board. This proved to be too difficult, as the correct reply is far from obvious. }
8... O-O
{ Christof played  8...e6  , but this only led to an unclear situation.  8...O-O  offers an exchange, but is a lot stronger. }
9. dxe7 Qxe7 10. Bd6 Qe8
{ A remarkable concept. Black does not mind losing the exchange, as we gain fantastic play for it. }
11. f3
{ White tries to get rid of the extremely annoying e4-pawn. It's always possible for White to grab the exchange later. }
11... Nc6 { Much better than taking on f3. } 12. Bxc5
{ Taking the pawn is more about controlling the d4-square than the material gain. }
12... Be6
{ We continue developing and plan ...Nd7 next, trying to nudge White to take the exchange finally. }
13. fxe4
{ Here  13.Bxf8  Qxf8  14.fxe4  Ng4  leads to a devastating attack for Black. Our bishop is monstrous, and there are tactics all over the place. A cute point is  15.h3  Ne3!  , when  16.Re1  Nc4  is killing  White on c3/b2. }
13... Nd7 { 'Please take the exchange!' } 14. Bxf8
{ After  14.Bd6  Qd8  we  threaten ...Re8,  when  15.Bxf8  Qxf8  transposes to 14.Bxf8, after all. }
14... Qxf8 15. Qe1 Rc8
{ Black has a fantastic game for the material and is already winning by computer standards. It looks like  16.Nge2  Nb6  17.Nf4  Nb4  19.Nxe6  Nxa2+  20.Kd2  fxe6  21.Qg3  Qb4  22.Ke2  Qxb2  is the best defense, but still, White should not survive this position. }
