4... Nf6
{ We develop the knight and cover e4, the best move for sure. Now White has some choice. To get the most out of the opening, we need to react flexibly. Here's an overview.   A@@EndBracket@@  5.Bg5  is a great practical upside for Black.  5.Bg5  happens to be the most popular and ambitious move, but it's one of the worst moves that White can play, objectively speaking. The key point is that we frequently have the option of playing ...h6, intending to answer Bh4 with ...g5 and ...Bg7, speeding up our development. White often intends queenside castling, which we are happy to answer with ...a6 and ...b5, giving Black all the fun.   B@@EndBracket@@  5.Bf4  looks better than 5.Bg5 for White. We recommend immediately starting queenside play  with ...a6 and ...b5 against it.   C@@EndBracket@@  5.f3  turns White's opening into a 'real gambit'. We'll take the f-pawn and enter the complications of being a pawn up. White's compensation is insufficient.   D@@EndBracket@@  5.Nge2  seems to be the best move for White, but it is rather unpopular. This is somewhat surprising, as in the Albin's @@StartFEN@@rnbqkbnr/pppppppp/8/8/8/8/PPPPPPPP/RNBQKBNR w KQkq - 0 1@@EndFEN@@  1.d4  d5  c4  e5  3.dxe5  d4  4.Nf3  Nc6  5.a3  Nge7  or @@StartFEN@@r1bqkbnr/ppp2ppp/2n5/4P3/2Pp4/5N2/PP2PPPP/RNBQKB1R w KQkq - 2 5@@EndFEN@@  5.g3  Nge7  are well-known lines.  White's idea is simple: playing Ng3, trying to regain the e4-pawn. }
5. Nge2
{ White intends to recover the pawn with Ng3. This looks like one of White's better tries, but it is rather unpopular still. }
5... g6
{ The most combative option. You can also play  5...e6  , when  6.Nf4  exd5  7.Nfxd5  is the usual continuation. White is a pawn down but has a strong activity and will usually regain the pawn soon. It's a safe line for Black, while 5...g6 avoids early trades. }
6. Ng3 Bg7 7. Ngxe4 Nbd7
{ We'd like to castle kingside and continue with ...b6 and ...Bb7, attacking the white d-pawn. We are already on new grounds, so let's just have a look at a logical line to illustrate this concept. }
8. Be2 O-O 9. O-O b6 10. a4 Bb7
{ We have completed the described setup and reached a position that offers equal chances. It is probably not the messy type of game that White was looking for, which might explain the unpopularity of 5.Nge2. It might be a good move, but not so much in the spirit of the whole line. }
