5. f3
{ The e4-pawn is obstructing White's pieces, so White decides to remove it at the cost of a pawn. }
5... exf3 6. Nxf3 g6
{ Black has two good options here. We recommend  6...g6  , but  6...a6  is a good alternative which prepares to  play ...e6 next.   We need to avoid the typical mistake  6...e6?  7.Bb5+  Bd7  8.dxe6  , which gives White excellent play. }
7. Bg5
{ White has tried various moves at this point. It's not necessary to study them all, as Black's concept is rather similar in all cases. We'll complete kingside castling and aim for ...a6 and ...b5, trying to attack the c3-knight and undermine the d5-pawn this way. We'll follow a sample line to illustrate the setup. }
7... Bg7 8. Qd2 O-O 9. O-O-O a6
{ We start our queenside play, a standard idea that looks even stronger than usual − White has just played O-O-O, after all! To summarize: White has some compensation after 5.f3, but it is not enough to fully compensate for the pawn loss. }
